fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-052",
  description: "026.1 Q4 — external-backed stream sources (substrate). Adds eval::stream::ExternalStream Rust trait + StreamSource::External(Box<dyn ExternalStream>) variant yielding Value::Entity rows without TermStore promotion (lineage-preserving). KB.term_store_len() exposed for diagnostic assertions. Example: in-memory WorkItemRowStream in tests/eval_q4_test.rs. Acceptance: 10K-row external scan drains via splitFirst and main TermStore size is unchanged from baseline (eval_q4_test::q4_ten_thousand_row_scan_does_not_grow_term_store). Reconciles with proposal 007 §11 — see the new §11 'Q4 implementation contract (landed)'. Stage B (resolver-side routing wiring) tracked separately under WI-052b. Proposal 026.1 Q4 + §Scale: external-backed KBs.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-048"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-03T13:50:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-053",
  description: "per-operation compile caches (follow-up to M1-M3). Add memoization arenas keyed on reflect tree nodes: (a) decision tree for match_expr keyed on OccurrenceId — built on first hit, reused; (b) Symbol → (body_term, params) cache replacing the linear OperationInfo walk in eval::lookup_operation_body; (c) per-operation slot-index table so var_ref lookups become array-indexed instead of linear-scanned. Stays on the reflect tree — no separate IR, just side-tables. Revisit after M4/M5 to decide if a targeted bytecode lowering is warranted. Brainstorm discussion in conversation 2026-04-19.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-044"],
  status: PreOpened)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-054",
  description: "refactor OperationInfo lookup into shared helper. Three callers currently duplicate the walk-OperationInfo-facts pattern: kb::typing::lookup_operation_info_full (typing.rs:546), kb::typing::check_operation_bodies (typing.rs:2180, hand-inlined), eval::lookup_operation_body (eval.rs:389). Extract pub fn lookup_operation_info(kb, functor) -> Option<OpInfoRecord> returning { params, return_type, effects, body: Option<TermId> } in kb/ (new op_info.rs or typing.rs). Collapse the three callers. Non-functional refactor; acceptance is all anthill-core tests still green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-042"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T20:55:26Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-055",
  description: "eval runtime refcount wiring: Value::Closure needs to reclaim arena slots when no Value references it. Today every reduce_lambda leaks a slot until the Interpreter drops (closure.rs retain/release are #[allow(dead_code)]). Approach: make ClosureHandle not Copy; on Clone increment the arena's refcount, on Drop decrement. Because Value needs Clone and Drop access to the arena, route via the Interpreter's closure arena held behind a shared cell (Rc<RefCell> or interior arena access). Generalize to Stream (M4) / Lazy (M5) when those land. Refcount handles acyclic cases; cycles deferred to WI-058 GC evaluation. Cycle-safety is conditional, not universal: holds while M4 streams stay lazy+non-memoized and Native stream sources respect a no-self-ref invariant. SharedStream memoization (proposal 026 post-v1) or Native sources that cache back-refs would need cycle detection at the insert site, same shape as proposal 026 §v2 Modify-store cycle checks.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-043"],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-04-19T19:36:15Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-056",
  description: "share frame locals via Rc to eliminate per-sub-expression clones. eval_nested (eval.rs:~487) clones the parent's locals SmallVec every sub-expression; apply_closure clones captured env every call; reduce_lambda captures full parent locals (not free vars). Fix path: wrap locals in Rc<SmallVec<...>> so clone is a refcount bump. A principled follow-up is free-variable analysis on lambda body to capture only what's used, but the Rc fix is the cheaper first win. Benchmark driven — land after WI-053 compile-caches.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-053"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-057",
  description: "Value::Entity.named field: change Vec<(Symbol, Value)> to SmallVec<[(Symbol, Value); 2]>. cons cells have exactly 2 named args (head, tail); entity constructors typically fit in 2-4. Saves a heap alloc per Entity value — significant on list-heavy workloads. Cross-cutting: eval.rs build_list_value + reduce_constructor + pattern.rs unify_constructor all allocate Vec today. Same rationale applies to Value::Tuple.named and Value::Entity.pos. Benchmark-driven; WI-053 companion.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-053"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-058",
  description: "prototype gc_arena vs concrete tracer for eval-time cycle handling. Spike in a branch between M4 and M5 — measure 'gc-lifetime pollution cost against the actually-built eval + resolver code (Substitution<Value> from 026.1 Q1 + LogicalStream from M4 are in scope by then). Cycles don't arise until M5 Modify[store] with store cells closing over closures; v1 refcount (WI-055) is correct until then. Decide based on: (a) ripple of 'gc into Interpreter/Substitution/Frame signatures; (b) derive(Collect) coverage on held types (SmallVec, SearchStream, persistence types); (c) mutator-threading ergonomics for builtins + host embedding; (d) safepoint discipline cost. Outcome is a decision + write-up in docs/proposals/, not a shipped implementation.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-048"],
  status: PreOpened)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-059",
  description: "cache stdlib KB across integration tests. load_kb_with re-parses + re-loads the full stdlib (~50 files) per test. With ~25 eval tests × ~400ms this dominates test run time. Fix: Lazy<Arc<KB>> in tests/common that loads stdlib once per test binary, with a cheap 'clone or fork' path that user sources extend. Requires either KB::clone (potentially expensive if hash-consed term store is deep-cloned — prefer Arc-sharing of immutable parts) or a 'fresh copy extending a read-only base' API. Needs a design sketch; profile first to confirm savings.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: PreOpened)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-060",
  description: "Convert eval to true continuation-passing so deep recursion hits EvalError::DepthExceeded instead of native SIGABRT. Proposal 026 §Activation stack mandates 'no native recursion', but today eval_nested / enter_operation / apply_closure each call run_until recursively — so the Rust call stack grows in lockstep with the activation stack and overflows first. Fix: expand Continuation enum to cover every mid-state (ApplyArg { buffered, remaining }, ApplyArgsComplete { target }, LetBind, MatchScrutinee, IfCond, ClosureResult, …). reduce_* pushes a child frame and returns StepOutcome::Continue; the outer run() loop delivers child results to the parent's Continuation. Prerequisite for honest DepthExceeded semantics and for future Suspension/Branch (VM-style resumption needs a saveable stack). Test: a zero-arg infinite recursion should return DepthExceeded at the configured cap, not SIGABRT.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-044"],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-04-19T19:40:08Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-061",
  description: "Tail-call optimization for operation/closure dispatch + bump activation-stack cap. Follow-on to WI-060. At dispatch_call time the current frame has nothing left to do (its expr has been fully consumed by the time we dispatch), so replacing it with the body frame is always safe — no static tail-position analysis needed. Change: enter_operation / enter_closure replace the top frame instead of push + awaiting=OperationResult. Also bump DEFAULT_DEPTH_CAP from 1024 to 1_000_000 (activation frames are heap-allocated; cap is a safety valve not a memory bound). Update m1_infinite_recursion_hits_depth_cap to use non-tail form (let _ = f() \n 0) since tail infinite recursion is a correct constant-time loop under TCO. Preserve original op on replacement so error messages stay readable. Acceptance: existing tests green; new test m1_tail_recursion_runs_deep showing O(1) stack over 10000 levels.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-060"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-19T17:35:22Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-062",
  description: "Interpreter resource config (EvalConfig struct). Replace ad-hoc set_stack_depth_cap with a coherent config object: pub struct EvalConfig { depth_cap: Option<usize>, step_cap: Option<u64> }. depth_cap catches non-tail recursion; step_cap catches infinite tail loops (TCO means no stack growth, so depth_cap alone can't catch them). Add EvalError::StepsExhausted. Thread through Interpreter::with_config / config / config_mut. Default: depth_cap=Some(1_000_000), step_cap=None. Deprecate set_stack_depth_cap in favor of config mutation. Test: infinite tail recursion (loop() = loop()) with step_cap=1000 surfaces StepsExhausted cleanly. value_weight_cap (memory-weight tracking) is filed separately — add when embedding / untrusted input is a concrete use case.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-061"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-19T17:52:09Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-063",
  description: "EvalConfig: add value_weight_cap. Sum per-Value weight (scalars=1, Str ~= len/16, Entity/Tuple = 2 + children) across frame locals + closure arena. Catches memory-blowup programs where stack stays shallow but values grow (e.g., recursive cons-ing of big strings). Not needed for typical CLI / test usage; useful when embedding anthill in a host (untrusted input) or for spec-level budget contracts. Tag as 'embedding prerequisite'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-062"],
  status: PreOpened)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-064",
  description: "Add fold / reduce / map / filter combinators to stdlib. Currently anthill.prelude.Iteration only has split; Collection has insert + empty. No higher-order combinators. Blocks ergonomic list processing — every user program that wants to sum a list has to hand-roll recursion. Add: fold_left(xs, init, f), fold_right(xs, init, f), map(xs, f), filter(xs, pred), for_each(xs, f) in anthill.prelude.Iteration (polymorphic over Iterator[T]). Definitions via rules over Iteration.split. Acceptance: a reduce-the-list-to-sum integration test passes end-to-end.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-275"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-06T19:42:56Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-065",
  description: "Add div to stdlib + register builtin.  parses as infix → desugars to div(a, b) functor (parse/pratt.rs:58), but no Numeric.div / Int.div / Float.div operation is declared in stdlib, so using  in anthill source fails with UnknownOperation at runtime. Declare div in Numeric (or Int + Float specifically) and register the builtin. Decide semantics: for Int, is  == divExact (truncate) or error on non-exact? Proposal needed before implementation.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-19T18:42:59Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-068",
  description: "Make Int's machine-boundedness explicit via an alias, not a rename. BigInt already exists for arbitrary-precision; most real programs want bounded arithmetic (fast, i64-sized). Keep Int as the user-facing default, but introduce `sort BoundedInt` with the current contents of Int and declare `sort Int = BoundedInt` as an alias. Users keep writing `Int`; the spec-level name BoundedInt clarifies what it actually is; the alias prevents churn across existing code. Interacts with WI-066: Error[Overflow] effect lives on BoundedInt arithmetic (inherited by Int via alias). Does NOT promote BigInt to be the literal default — bounded ints remain the pragmatic path. BigInt stays an explicit opt-in for crypto, financial, or values exceeding i64. Scope: stdlib int.anthill rename-and-alias, Error[Overflow] effect on BoundedInt.add/sub/mul/neg/abs, fact Numeric[BoundedInt] (Int inherits via alias). Proposal doc lightweight: this is cosmetic + effect addition, no runtime changes.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T16:10:59Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-069",
  description: "Implement Suspension effect: first-class continuations on the activation stack. WI-050 stubs Suspension as UnhandledEffect. Real implementation: (1) SuspensionHandle wraps a saved snapshot of the activation stack + locals + in-flight AwaitStates. (2) operation suspend(k: Function[T, U]) -> U effects Suspension — when invoked, snapshot current stack up to the suspend site, return SuspensionHandle to user code, bail out of run(). (3) operation resume(handle: SuspensionHandle, value: T) -> U — restore saved stack, deliver value to the saved continuation, resume run(). Uses the heap-allocated activation stack from WI-060 (CPS eval) directly — no VM/bytecode needed. The ClosureHandle Rc refcount (WI-055) already makes snapshot+restore safe. Scope: save/restore protocol, suspend/resume builtins, test of continuation capture and round-trip. Separate from Branch (WI-TODO) — Branch is SLD-value-level non-determinism, different shape.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-050", "WI-060"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-070",
  description: "Implement Branch effect: SLD-style value-level non-determinism. WI-050 stubs Branch as UnhandledEffect. Real implementation: (1) operation fail() effects Branch — signals 'this computation branch is infeasible, backtrack'. (2) Under Branch, an operation returning multiple values pushes alternative frames; the activation stack forks. (3) At resolution points (e.g. pattern match or constraint discharge), one branch proceeds; on fail() the saved alternative resumes. Relationship to LogicalStream (M4): LogicalStream is the external interface for non-deterministic computation (stream of values); Branch is the internal mechanism. A stream-returning operation uses Branch to represent multiple yields. Scope: snapshot of activation stack at choice points (same machinery as Suspension's save/restore), branch / fail builtins, test of backtracking through a non-deterministic operation.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-050", "WI-060"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-072",
  description: "M5 follow-up: Modify[T] runtime effect handler with arena-backed cells. WI-050 landed the effect-handler framework (register_effect_handler, invoke_effect_handler, EffectRegistry) plus Console. Modify[T] needs its own handler: ModifyArena<StoreCell> holding per-resource state keyed by resource symbol, get/set dispatched via op_sym, cycle detection on Rc reference chains surfacing as EvalError::CyclicReference. Register a default handler for Modify[?] that owns the arena. Acceptance: counter test — anthill operation that calls set(store, n) repeatedly and verifies get returns the latest value; cycle-detection test where two cells reference each other triggers CyclicReference. Depends on WI-050.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-20T06:46:45Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-073",
  description: "M5 follow-up: Error[T]::raise runtime propagation. WI-050 did not register a handler for Error[?]. Implement: default handler that unwraps args[0] as the error payload and surfaces it as EvalError::Raised { payload: Value }. Downstream catch/handle constructs (future) inspect the payload. Until catch lands, a raised Error aborts evaluation with the payload in the EvalError. Acceptance: integration test calls raise(my_error_value) and asserts the EvalError matches Raised with the expected payload. Depends on WI-050.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-389"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T10:46:34Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-074",
  description: "Reflect operations parity test: ensure sorts/operations/rules in anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs return the same results as the equivalent execute(LogicalQuery) path (per proposal 026.1 §Q3). Add integration tests that build a LogicalQuery via pattern_query/conjunction/sort_query and compare results to the direct Rust impl. No rewrite needed - the Rust impls exist, only equivalence verification. See docs/status/wi-047.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
