fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-162",
  description: "scaland resync — parser gaps blocking full stdlib load. Six stdlib files fail to parse with scaland's fastparse front end. Add support for: (1) `effects EffectExpr` clause on operation declarations — used by stdlib/anthill/prelude/iteration.anthill, collection.anthill, reflect/reflect.anthill; (2) `forall(?n)` quantifier syntax in rule bodies — used by stdlib/anthill/prelude/int.anthill (induction principle); (3) tuple type expressions like `Option[(A, B)]` — used by iteration.anthill (split returns Option[(Element, Iterator)]); (4) empty set literal `{}` in fact bindings — used by stdlib/anthill/prelude/list.anthill (`fact Collection[Element = T, Effect = {}]`); (5) investigate bool.anthill parse error at line 27 col 28 — possibly nested var-on-var pattern. Mirror references: rustland/anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs handles all of these via tree-sitter. Files: scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/parse/AnthillParser.scala, parse/IR.scala. Acceptance: sbt test green; new ParserTest cases parse each of the 6 stdlib files (bool, int, iteration, collection, list, reflect/reflect) without error; EmbeddedStdlib can extend its path list to include them.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-03T07:23:17Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-163",
  description: "scaland resync — structural-op vs typeclass-op disambiguation. Prelude.registerStructuralOps in scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/load/Prelude.scala registers bare functor names (eq, neq, neg, and, or, not, lt, lte, gt, gte, div, mod, pow, arrow) as Operations under anthill.prelude — these are the names the Pratt parser produces from infix operators (`?a + ?b` → Fn(\"add\", ...)). When typeclass files load (eq.anthill defines anthill.prelude.Eq.eq, ordered.anthill defines Ordered.lt, etc.), every reference to `eq` in a rule body resolves ambiguously to BOTH anthill.prelude.eq AND anthill.prelude.Eq.eq, producing AmbiguousSymbol cascades during load. Same for neg (Float.neg vs prelude.neg). Fix must be a real disambiguation — downgrading Ambiguous to a warning is NOT acceptable. Design options: (a) drop registerStructuralOps entirely — let the parser emit functor names that resolve via the typeclass under the value's sort; (b) register structural ops as a distinct SymbolKind (e.g. SymbolKind.StructuralPlaceholder) that's filtered out during sort-method lookup and only consulted as a last-resort fallback; (d) wire structural ops to dispatch through fact-witness lookup at resolve time — eq(?a, ?b) where ?a: T resolves through Eq[T] fact to T's eq operation. Investigate how rustland handles this in rustland/anthill-core/src/intern.rs and resolve.rs — it does not produce AmbiguousSymbol on the same inputs. Mirror its mechanism. Acceptance: sbt test green; ParserIntegrationTest can load EmbeddedStdlib expanded with eq.anthill + ordered.anthill + numeric.anthill without AmbiguousSymbol(eq, ...) cascade.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-02T10:31:41Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-164",
  description: "realization profile `rust+anthill` — hybrid bundle of Rust shim + embedded anthill spec. Sibling to `rust_std` (full codegen) and `cpp_std`. Captures the anthill→(Rust shim + embedded spec) realization where the program is interpreted at runtime by a thin Rust host that bakes the .anthill files via include_str! and dispatches `main(args)` through the WI-051 interpreter. Composable with `rust_std` at sort granularity: some sorts realize to native Rust, others stay interpreted in the same binary. Schema delta: the realization layer today says \"spec X is replaced by host code Y\" (rust_std/cpp_std are substitution profiles); rust+anthill needs an *embedding* profile shape — a new `runtime_form` discriminator on LanguageMapping (or equivalent) distinguishing substitution from embedding, plus an AnthillBundle entity (files: List[String], entry: Symbol, effect_handlers: List[T = HandlerBinding]) naming what to bake in and how to wire effects. Includes: stdlib/anthill/realization/rust_anthill.anthill — LanguageMapping fact + supporting entities; codegen knob in anthill-rust-gen (proposal 029) to honour the embed shape — emit a thin shim crate that builds KB from include_str!d files at startup, registers stdlib + project handlers, calls interp.call(entry_qname, args). Driver / acceptance: anthill-todo (WI-009) is the first consumer — its WorkItem entities + workflow rules realize via rust+anthill, the resulting `cargo install` ships one static binary with no .anthill files on disk; integration test asserts `target/release/anthill-todo list` works in a fresh tempdir without runtime stdlib lookup. Migration story: rust+anthill is the bridge from WI-009a (interpret everything, ship now) to WI-009b (rust_std for hot sorts, no interpreter): per-sort profile flip, no rewrite, identical user-facing binary. Out of scope for v1: full anthill-rust-gen (proposal 029); per-effect codegen knobs beyond Console/Modify/Error; no_std bundle variant.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-02T10:13:31Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-165",
  description: "Publish anthill workspace crates to crates.io. Anthill is now meaningfully usable end-to-end (parser, KB, SLD, interpreter via WI-051, stdlib argparse via WI-159, rust+anthill bundling via WI-164) — time to make it discoverable. Sweep all workspace crates: anthill-core (foundation), anthill-cli (the `anthill` binary), anthill-stl (codegen runtime), anthill-todo (work-item CLI), anthill-cpp-gen / anthill-rust-gen / anthill-smt-gen (codegen). Per crate add: license = \"MIT OR Apache-2.0\" (or Apache-2.0 alone if preferred), repository (github), readme, expanded description (one-line), keywords, categories. Add a `version = \"...\"` clause alongside every `path = \"..\"` inter-crate dep so consumers from the registry resolve correctly while local dev still uses path. Verify name availability on crates.io for all seven names — if any is taken, propose an alternative now (e.g. `anthill-lang-core`). Decide initial version: probably 0.1.0 to signal pre-stable; add CHANGELOG.md per crate or a single workspace-level one. Acceptance: cargo publish --dry-run --allow-dirty succeeds for every crate in dependency order (anthill-core first, leaf crates last); a RELEASE.md runbook lives in the repo root documenting the publish order, version-bump checklist, and yank policy; CI gate that runs `cargo publish --dry-run` for changed crates on PR. Out of scope for v1: cargo-release / release-please automation; signed releases; private mirror. Driver: WI-009 (the anthill-todo port) ships as `cargo install anthill-todo` once this lands. Sibling track: a follow-up Path-B git-rev mode for `anthill codegen bundle` lands first as a stopgap so iterations on WI-009 can keep moving without polluting the registry; that work is captured separately.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
