fact Feedback(content: "From WI-387 delivery + /code-review (3 forward-looking findings for the broader producer rewrite): (S1) Once a concrete carrier WRITES E (List provides Stream[E={}]), a PRIMITIVE Stream op consumed on that carrier with carrier=Some but E omitted from the goal now dispatches NoCandidates (was Unique pre-WI-387). This is by design: the carrier-less effect-row skip in collect_provides_candidates is gated on goal.carrier.is_none() to preserve WI-357 element threading (making carrier=Some match -> the Unique arm re-derives and clobbers the WI-357 re-walk -> ?_ element). BENIGN now (List's Stream ops are body-less specs / List.splitFirst resolves at RUNTIME: eval wi343 + wi362 green), but when WI-380 writes E on producers WITH bodies, re-check the lost static dispatch; the deeper fix is making the Unique arm not clobber the element re-walk. (S2) FIX 2's subtype None-arm REJECTS an OPEN-E provider (fact Stream[T], no E binding -- LogicalStream's shape) against a written Stream[E={}] expectation (provider supplies no E -> reject) instead of absorbing the open row to {}. Conservative-sound; so a carrier kept on bare fact Stream[T] won't satisfy Stream[E={}]. WI-380 should either write E explicitly on each producer or add open-row->{} absorption (WI-307). (E2 altitude) FIX 2 (subtype), FIX 3 (abstract-coverage) and the dispatch None-arm each independently re-derive 'is this provider binding ground/non-discriminating' because bind_spec_params_from_carrier threads only type-param-REF provider bindings into the subst (drops ground rows like E={}); consider threading ground bindings, or a shared provider_binding_for_short helper, when WI-380 touches this.", at: "2026-06-04T18:45:35Z", workitem: "WI-380", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "WI-387 (delivered) concretely hit this WI's unfinished scope: the fact-vs-provides DIFFERENCE is 'term loses fact' (user). A 'fact Spec[...]' head lowers via the TERM path (convert_term) which is LOSSY -- a '{}'/effect-row binding value degrades to Term::Ref('{}') -> remap_symbol_strict -> UnresolvedName (the row is DROPPED), so a written effect row cannot ride on a fact head; a 'provides' clause lowers via the type-aware path (sort_inst_to_value -> type_expr_to_value/lower_effect_row) and KEEPS it. WI-387 ROUTED AROUND it (used 'provides Stream[T=T, E={}]' for List) and fixed the type-param-shape half: sort_inst_to_value now lowers a type-param binding to Ref(param) matching the fact-head convert_term shape, so the two emit the SAME dispatch wildcard (impl_param_ref only recognizes Ref/Ident, not the nullary Fn name_to_sort_term used to build -- that divergence broke wi210). The REMAINING difference is exactly this WI's step (1): make the fact-head / SortView / provides emission a VALUE FACT (build a Value::Node head when any binding is structured/denoted). PRINCIPLE (user): fact and provides must be NO different -- both declare ONE SortProvidesInfo capability; the term representation must not lose the fact. Finishing WI-366 (unify the fact-head term-path emission with the provides type-aware path -> byte-identical SortProvidesInfo) eliminates the difference; the WI-387 wi210/wi357 dispatch canaries must stay green either way. Sub-note: the EMPTY-row {} case is ground (lowers to a ground effects_rows term, not a Node), so it is a smaller convert-level recognition gap (term path must route a {} EffectRow TypeExpr to lower_effect_row instead of stringifying) that could land independently of the denoted-row Value::Node migration this WI is gated on (045/046 effect-expressions-as-types).", at: "2026-06-04T20:58:50Z", workitem: "WI-366", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "SCOPE ADD (user): migrate OperationInfo.requires and OperationInfo.ensures (op_info.rs OperationRecord, lines 61/64) from Vec<TermId> to Vec<Value> -- the LAST term-only fields on OperationInfo; params/return_type/effects already moved to Value (WI-341/348, 'read carrier-faithfully, never materialized to a term'). WHY: a denoted-bearing precondition (requires Modify[c] -- a value-in-type SortView) cannot ride as a hash-consed TermId, so the term-level readers SILENTLY SKIP the value-fact OperationInfo head (the 'let Some(head_named)=kb.fact_head_named_args(rid) else continue' pattern) -- a wi348-boundary-no-value-to-termid violation + 'term loses fact' at the requires/ensures level. Migrating to Value closes it. CAVEAT: requires/ensures are precondition/postcondition GOAL terms (WI-347), consumed by SLD-style goal handling (check_override_refinement filters the auto-inferred EffectsRuntime[Effects=E] requires; req_insertion::run; the resolver) -- so the struct-field change must land WITH carrier-agnostic (TermView) consumer reads, not alone (overlaps WI-348 consumer migration). SIBLING narrowing (migrate together for a uniform Value requires surface): the SORT-level RequiresEntry.spec is also TermId (typing.rs:10014), held in EnclosingSort.requires: Vec<RequiresEntry>. Part of B (the fact/requires value-in-type lossless migration) for the fresh WI-366 session.", at: "2026-06-04T21:36:24Z", workitem: "WI-366", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "make_denoted FULLY DELETED 2026-06-04 (commit 244aaa3, suite green). Was already #[cfg(test)] with ZERO production callers; probe confirmed no production/reflect path builds a ground denoted term (value-in-type is always Value::Node via make_denoted_occ; unify_denoted_view is carrier-agnostic and stays). Removed the method + 7 ground-vs-Node cross-carrier tests + ground_param (typing.rs); converted region.rs modify_label to a Node label (production-faithful); carved the dead TermId-twin out of the mod.rs wi342 arrow test (kept Value-form reads). Ground-denoted TermId carrier retired. REMAINING WI-366 scope is B only (fact-head value-fact + requires/ensures Vec<TermId>->Vec<Value>, recorded in prior feedback) -- for a fresh session.", at: "2026-06-04T21:55:41Z", workitem: "WI-366", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-389",
  description: "Extract the HandlerAction carrier out of WI-082 Phase A into its own substrate WI (per proposal 027 §Outputs — the HandlerAction carrier). Define enum HandlerAction { Pure(Value), Throw(Value), Fail, Choice(Value, Vec<AltMarker>), Suspend(ContSnapshot) } in eval/effects.rs and change EffectHandler's return type from Result<Value, EvalError> to Result<HandlerAction, EvalError>. Migrate existing handlers (Console stdio/buffered/scripted, Modify) to return Pure(v). Implement dispatch-site interpretation for Pure (resume current path with the value) and Throw(payload) (abort: the DISPATCH SITE — not the handler — converts Throw into the evaluator's internal unwinding carrier, i.e. an EvalError::Raised { payload: Value } variant, propagating the opaque payload up the defunctionalized step loop). Leave Choice / Suspend / Fail arms returning an explicit 'not yet supported' EvalError until the Branch substrate lands. KEY SCOPING DECISION (the reason this is extracted): this WI does NOT depend on WI-075 — the Pure/Throw subset needs no snapshot, no push_choice, no Frame/ActivationStack Clone; only Choice/Suspend do, and those stay stubbed. So Error (WI-073) and the bundle wiring (WI-195) can build on the carrier without waiting on the Branch/resolver substrate. Design principle established in design discussion (2026-06-05): error-ness lives in the CHANNEL, not the value — the payload is an ordinary anthill Value of type T (the T of Error[T]), opaque to the runtime; nothing tags the value as an error; the handler's Throw variant (the return vocabulary) is what marks it, and the Error handler 'knows' it is an error tautologically because it is the Error handler. Replaces WI-082 Phase A step (b); WI-082 keeps its WI-075 dependency only for the Choice/Suspend/Branch portion. Acceptance: HandlerAction enum defined; EffectHandler signature changed; all existing handlers return it (Ok(v) -> Pure(v)); Pure and Throw interpreted at the dispatch site; cargo test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T08:58:11Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Phase A step (b) (define HandlerAction carrier) extracted to standalone WI-389, which intentionally does NOT depend on WI-075 — the Pure/Throw subset Error needs has no snapshot/push_choice requirement. WI-082 retains its WI-075 dependency only for the Choice/Suspend/Branch portion (steps c, e). Also: step (f) attributes the default Error handler to 'WI-070's scope' — that is a typo; the Error ticket is WI-073 (WI-070 is the Modify follow-up). Error is now tracked as WI-389 (carrier) -> WI-073 (Error Throw handler) -> WI-195 (bundle wiring).", at: "2026-06-05T05:28:26Z", workitem: "WI-082", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-390",
  description: "Represent denoted faithfully in the Term world: make occurrence<->term LOSSLESS (admit temporary/scoped items in the hash-consed term-store). PRINCIPLE (user): prefer a SINGLE representation (no permanent Term-vs-Value::Node carrier split for denoted); but WHERE a second representation is transitionally needed, it MUST be CORRECT (lossless), never a lossy projection -- 'from an evolution point of view both are right: better to have no double representation, but if needed it should be correct'. PROBLEM: value-in-type denoted currently rides ONLY as Value::Node (WI-342/348/366 retired the term-based make_denoted), so the Term world is LOSSY for denoted -- which breeds a whole CLASS OF BUGS: 'term loses fact' (reify/materialize drop the denoted; value-fact heads silently skipped via 'fact_head_named_args(rid) else continue'), Value-needs-Hash/Eq-for-keys (the resolve_cache + RequiresEntry.spec blocker that surfaced this), and dual carrier-agnostic TermView paths threaded everywhere. KEY ENABLER (user): 'we can represent occurrence as term' -- make occurrence_to_term (node_occurrence.rs:2173) + the denoted lowering FAITHFUL so a Value::Node round-trips to a Term without loss. MECHANISM: a faithful denoted Term form (un-retire make_denoted in a COMPLETE form that the old ground-only one couldn't be); the hash-consed term-store ADMITS TEMPORARY/scoped items -- the PRICE: a binder-bearing denoted (an arrow type's bound effect/row var) doesn't dedup by structure, so it rides as a refcounted/transient store entry, not a persistent shared one (needs a lifecycle: refcount/GC + binder alpha-equivalence handling). PAYOFF: the Term world becomes faithful -> RequiresEntry.spec stays a faithful TermId, resolve_cache stays TermId-keyed (no Value:Hash+Eq needed), the carrier-split readers for denoted collapse back to term reads, and the bug class dies; evolves toward a single (term) representation while Value::Node stays correct transitionally. RE-SCOPES WI-366 B2: RequiresEntry.spec->Value and the requires/ensures Value migration become unnecessary (denoted requires carried faithfully via TermId) -- B2b is superseded by this. CAUTION: foundational pivot touching unification (denoted-term special-casing + preserving the value-in-type-vs-regular-term marker), the term-store (temporary-item lifecycle + binder alpha-equivalence correctness), and the carrier-agnostic code that existed ONLY for denoted. Acceptance: occurrence_to_term lossless for denoted (Value::Node round-trips byte-faithful); 'requires Foo[Int, 3]' rides as a faithful TermId RequiresEntry.spec (no silent skip, no Value); resolve_cache keys on it correctly; suite green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T09:34:56Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "SYNC + PIVOT 2026-06-05: rebased onto origin/main (which gained WI-087 + the remote's WI-389/HandlerAction). B1 DELIVERED (commit dbc8a7e, was 3389fdd): written effect-row {} rides the term path byte-identical to provides. B2a DELIVERED (commit f7b439b, was fb3026e): OperationInfo.requires/ensures -> Vec<Value> (op_info.rs merged with WI-087's new meta field; override tests green). B2b (RequiresEntry.spec -> Value) SUPERSEDED by new WI-390 (now a dependency of WI-366): attempting B2b hit the resolve_cache, keyed by (SortGoal, Vec<RequiresEntry>), which needs RequiresEntry: Hash+Eq -- and Value isn't Hash/Eq because a TermId is LOSSY for denoted, so a term-projection hash would be incorrect (user). That surfaced the real fork: option A (make Value a first-class key via structural_eq + a cached structural hash) vs option B (represent denoted FAITHFULLY in the Term world, admitting temporary/scoped term-store items). User chose B (WI-390): 'we can represent occurrence as term'; principle = prefer a single representation, but any second representation must be CORRECT (lossless), not a lossy projection. With WI-390, RequiresEntry.spec stays a faithful TermId, the cache stays TermId-keyed, and the carrier-split bug class dies -- so B2b's Value migration is dropped in favor of WI-390. WI-366's remaining 'carry denoted requires' goal now lands via WI-390.", at: "2026-06-05T05:58:45Z", workitem: "WI-366", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "SUPPORTING RATIONALE (the sharpest 'why', from the 'why does Value have no Hash?' thread): the ABSENCE of Value: Hash/Eq is itself evidence that type-structure does not belong in the runtime union -- the SAME signal as the resolve_cache blocker. Value is a UNION of two worlds: (1) KB-structural data (scalars, Tuple, Entity, Term(TermId), Var, Node) which has a structural identity, and (2) INTERPRETER runtime handles (Closure, Stream, Lazy, Substitution, Map, Cell, Requirement) which are arena-refcounted u32 handles with NO lawful Eq/Hash -- a Cell is MUTABLE (identity = slot index, value mutated in place -> any structural hash is unstable), Closure/Stream/Lazy are suspended computations. That is why structural_eq is a METHOD, not impl PartialEq: it treats opaque handles as 'conservatively unequal' (structural_eq(closure,closure)==false) -> non-reflexive -> not a lawful Eq -> no Hash (plus Float(f64) raw NaN, which Term wraps in OrderedFloat and Value does not). KEY POINT: the cache key / RequiresEntry.spec / any type-or-spec position only ever holds the STRUCTURAL subset (Term/Node/Entity) -- never a Cell/Closure. So routing type-structure through the runtime Value union was the carrier-split's root. THE HASH STORY UNDER THIS WI: do NOT invent a separate Value structural hash. Once Term<->Value is total+lossless (this WI), DEFINE identity by the mapping: Hash(value) = Hash(its canonical Term), so a Value and its Term share ONE identity (same hash, equal across carriers) -- the single-representation ideal at the identity level. Precondition is exactly the opaque-free subset (no Cell/Closure/Stream -> they have no Term; a mutable cell cannot have a stable canonical term), which the type/spec/cache context satisfies by construction. END-STATE: Value::Node-for-denoted FOLDS INTO Value::Term -- Node existed ONLY because Term could not hold the occurrence; make Term faithful and the carrier collapses, leaving identity = TermId everywhere on the structural subset. resolve_cache/RequiresEntry then key on plain TermIds and 'hash' is never a separate concern; the opaque runtime handles are simply the part of Value that is not KB-structural (and never needs a key). MECHANICAL WALL this resolves: std::hash::Hash cannot take kb, so a hashable value must already CARRY its canonical TermId -- Value::Term does, and this WI makes denoted a Value::Term, so there is no kb-at-hash-time.", at: "2026-06-05T06:05:42Z", workitem: "WI-390", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN REFINEMENTS (user 2026-06-05): (1) The Term<->Value conversion is TOTAL and HONEST via Result, not panic/lossy: value_to_term(v) -> Result<TermId, NotRepresentable>. Ok(term) for the structural subset; Err for a Value carrying a non-representable element (the opaque runtime handles Closure/Stream/Lazy/Map/Cell/Substitution/Requirement). This REPLACES today's panic/silent-loss at the boundary (reify / materialize / build_expr_leaf panic / 'fact_head_named_args else continue'): the Err is a real signal ('this is a runtime value, not type-structure'), so a Cell-in-a-spec/key position surfaces as a typed Err the caller handles, never a panic and never a lossy term. This is the 'if a second representation is needed it must be CORRECT' principle applied to the conversion itself. (2) Occurrences and SPANS fold INTO terms -- 'we will write terms with positions as terms': the term representation gains POSITION, so an occurrence (positioned structure + span) IS a term, and a span is term-representable. This is the lossless mechanism for occurrence_to_term (the span an occurrence carries survives because the term carries it) AND it UNIFIES the two-ish representations that exist today -- (term + side-table span: term_spans/create_occurrence) AND (NodeOccurrence with inline span) -- into ONE: positioned terms. OPEN DESIGN QUESTION to nail in this WI: is the position part of term IDENTITY (hash/eq) or PROVENANCE (carried, ignored for identity)? For the resolve_cache / dispatch, structural identity must IGNORE position (a 'requires' is the same regardless of source location), so position is most likely provenance (the term dedups structurally; the span rides alongside) -- which means the genuinely NON-dedup 'temporary items' are specifically the binder-bearing denoted (scope/alpha-equivalence), not positioned terms in general. Decide this explicitly: it determines whether positioned terms hash-cons (provenance) or stay temporary (identity).", at: "2026-06-05T06:08:22Z", workitem: "WI-390", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RESOLVED — position is IDENTITY, not provenance (user): 'Position should be stored in Term, otherwise Modify[c] will be same for different c in different places.' This is a CORRECTNESS argument that overrides the earlier dedup-sharing lean: with position as mere provenance, Modify[a] bound by one callback and Modify[a] bound by another hash-cons to the SAME term despite different binders -> they wrongly unify AND wrongly share a resolve_cache entry. So the term MUST carry it. PRECISE FORM: the load-bearing discriminator is the BINDER IDENTITY the denoted reference resolves to (which c / which binding site), with source position as its carrier -- so two references to the SAME binder stay EQUAL (unify/dedup) regardless of where they appear, and two references to DIFFERENT binders (same surface name, different scope) DIFFER. NATURAL SCOPING that keeps ground dedup intact: a denoted BINDER REFERENCE carries its binder's identity/position -> binder-bearing denoteds are SCOPED (the 'temporary/scoped' store items that don't share the global ground dedup -- exactly the CLAUDE.md 'hash-consing inappropriate for binders' case), while a pure-GROUND term (Foo[Int, 3], no binder) stays position-free and hash-conses globally as before. So 'position in Term' is specifically the binder-reference's binder-identity, not a blanket source-span on every node (a blanket span would over-distinguish same-binder reuse and break unification of two uses of the same a). IMPLEMENTATION CHOICE to pin in this WI: encode the binder identity as the binder's binding-site (position/uid) vs a globally-unique per-binder symbol -- either disambiguates; the binding-site-uid is the 'position' framing.", at: "2026-06-05T06:13:35Z", workitem: "WI-390", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "CONCRETE ENCODING (user): a special term anthill.reflect.Positioned(pos, internal) -- a Term::Fn, NOT a new Term enum variant, so it reuses hash-consing (two Positioned differ iff pos or internal differ -> different binders/sites -> different terms; internal is the recoverable structure) and is special-cased by the typer/unifier like the other anthill.reflect.* forms (SortView/OperationInfo/TypeExtractor). Realizes the prior points: an occurrence IS Positioned(span_term, structure_term) -> 'occurrence and span become terms'; value_to_term builds it (Err only for opaque runtime handles); the resolve_cache then keys on plain TermIds again. ONE THING TO PIN: what exactly is pos? (a) the BINDER-SCOPE IDENTITY the denoted reference resolves to -> two refs to the SAME binder stay EQUAL (same pos) regardless of source location, different binders differ. This is the CORRECTNESS discriminator for Modify[c]. OR (b) the raw SOURCE SPAN -> over-distinguishes (same binder used twice = two terms -> their unification/dedup breaks), good for provenance/diagnostics but WRONG as the binder discriminator. These can be BOTH carried but only ONE is identity-bearing: pos-for-identity must be the binder-scope (a); the source span rides as provenance. Equivalent framing: if a binder were resolved to a globally-UNIQUE symbol per binding-site, then 'internal' alone distinguishes binders and Positioned's pos is pure provenance; the user's 'pos in identity' assertion means binders are SCOPED (non-unique surface), so pos=binder-scope is the identity. DECIDE in this WI: pos = binder-scope-uid (identity) with source-span as separate provenance, vs unique-binder-symbol (pos -> provenance). Also: granularity -- Positioned wraps the binder-bearing/denoted node (keeping pure-ground terms unwrapped + globally deduped), not every node.", at: "2026-06-05T06:15:14Z", workitem: "WI-390", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "CORRECTION to the prior note's (a)/(b) framing (it was wrong): binder-scope identity is NOT an alternative to pos -- it CONTAINS pos / is GIVEN BY pos (user: 'binder-scope identity contains pos'). A binder is identified by WHERE it is bound, so pos = the BINDING-SITE position of c, and that position IS the binder identity. There is no 'binder-scope-id vs source-span' choice to make. This also dissolves the over-distinguish worry: pos is the binder's binding-site, NOT the reference's location, so every Modify[c] resolving to the same c carries the SAME pos -> the SAME Positioned(pos, internal) term -> they unify/dedup; only a DIFFERENT binder (different binding site -> different pos) yields a different term. So anthill.reflect.Positioned(pos, internal) with pos = binding-site position is the complete answer; a reference's own source span (for diagnostics) is unrelated provenance, not this pos.", at: "2026-06-05T06:17:46Z", workitem: "WI-390", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-392",
  description: "Typer: the unconstrained-type-param check must EXEMPT an operation's OWN type parameters when checking that operation's body. An op f[Elem,Eff](s: S[T=Elem,E=Eff]) -> ... = body whose body calls a type-parameterized op (incl. itself, e.g. Stream.collect/takeN -> splitFirst + recursion) on an arg of type S[T=Elem,...] makes the inner call's type param resolve to the enclosing op's OWN (legitimately-unbound, caller-instantiated) Global var; check_unconstrained_type_params (typing.rs:4214) wrongly flags it 'unconstrained'. FIX: thread the enclosing op's type-param vids from check_operation_bodies through TypingEnv into the check; a param resolving to one of them is CONSTRAINED. Use global logical vars, NOT Var::Rigid (bind_row_tail rejects rigid effect-row tails; rigid only unifies w/ itself, but Elem genuinely unifies w/ inner fresh params). Min repro: rewrap[A](b: Box[T=A]) -> Box[T=A] = idbox(b). Blocks WI-380.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T11:44:31Z"))

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-392")
fact Feedback(content: "Design settled via dialogue 2026-06-05 (supersedes the ticket's initial 'exempt enclosing op params' framing). NOT rigid; use ordinary Global logical vars. ROOT CAUSE: extract_type_params (op_info.rs:240) returns STORED type-param vars (no per-call freshening). A SELF-recursive call (collect->collect, takeN->takeN) therefore reuses the ENCLOSING op's var -> ONE var, not two -> the no-op unify (?E =?= ?E) leaves NO substitution entry, and check_unconstrained_type_params (typing.rs:4214) walk_type_deep's it to the free ?E and flags 'unconstrained'. Cross-op calls (collect->splitFirst) already have distinct vars, so they don't alias (and splitFirst is a bodyless spec op dispatched separately, so it never hit this check) -- which is exactly why only collect/takeN errored. FIX (2 parts): (1) FRESHEN the callee's type params per call in check_apply_iter so the call-side var is DISTINCT from the enclosing op's (yields a real entry call_side := enclosing ?E); (2) the unconstrained check verifies the call-side param HAS A SUBSTITUTION ENTRY (subst.lookup(param).is_some() -- bound by THIS call) instead of walk_type_deep-to-ground. A genuine leak (empty[E]() with nothing to bind E) gets NO entry -> still flagged. RIGID rejected: bind_row_tail (typing.rs:8676, WI-336) refuses a Var::Rigid effect-row tail, so rigidifying the effect param Eff would break effects-row threading (Elem would be fine; Eff would not). Min repro: rewrap[A](b: Box[T=A]) -> Box[T=A] = idbox(b); plus a self-recursive drain[A](s: Box[T=A]) -> Box[T=A] = drain(s).", at: "2026-06-05T10:52:20Z", workitem: "WI-392", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN CORRECTED 2026-06-05 (SUPERSEDES the prior 'freshen + check substitution-entry' note — that is UNSOUND). FINAL design = RIGID (Skolemize the op's OWN type params while checking its body). RATIONALE (soundness): checking collect[Elem,Eff]'s body means checking it for ALL Elem,Eff, so the body may CONSUME the param (it flows outward into the fresh call-side globals: rigid=>global, via resolved_var matching only Global so the flexible side binds TO the rigid) but must NEVER DETERMINE it (no global=>rigid: a rigid is never solved). Fresh-two-globals is UNSOUND: with both as Globals the link is bindable either way, so a body doing e.g. add(h,1) on h:Elem would unify Elem:=Int and typecheck under a forall-Elem signature. Rigid forbids that (Rigid(E)=?=Int fails). IMPL: in check_operation_bodies, before type_check_node, substitute each op type-param Global(vid)->Rigid(fresh) across op.params types + return_type + declared_effects (fresh rigid ids to avoid occurs-check). Then: the unconstrained check (typing.rs:4214) needs NO CHANGE (it flags only Global; callee globals resolve to rigids -> pass); NO callee freshening needed (callee flexible global solves to enclosing rigid). EFFECT-ROW caveat now mostly moot: bind_row_tail (typing.rs:8676) rejects a Rigid tail only when DECOMPOSING a row with present labels over the tail; collect/takeN bodies are pure so Eff is only unified as a bare row var (var fast-path, no decomposition). VERIFY no effectful body decomposes over a rigid tail; if one does, that is the WI-336 polymorphic-row handling (rejecting is sound meanwhile). Min repro still: rewrap[A](b:Box[T=A])->Box[T=A]=idbox(b) + self-recursive drain.", at: "2026-06-05T10:56:49Z", workitem: "WI-392", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "FINAL LOCKED DESIGN (consolidates the two notes above). (1) RIGID because DECLARED: collect[Elem,Eff] declares its params, so we are in CHECK mode -> Skolemize (rigidify) Elem,Eff while checking the body. If params were INFERRED from the body they'd have to be flexible (can't infer a rigid); since declared, rigid. Inner calls keep their OWN params FLEXIBLE (inferred from their args), solving TO the enclosing rigids (rigid=>global; resolved_var matches only Global so the flexible side binds). (2) ROWS CHECKED NOT BOUND: a rigid in an effect-row tail is CHECKED structurally (tail identity + present-label coverage), never solved -> bind_row_tail (the binding path, typing.rs:8676) is NOT on the checking path, so its rigid-tail rejection doesn't bite. collect/takeN pure -> tails match by identity, no extra labels. (3) NO CALLEE FRESHENING NEEDED given per-call Substitution::new() isolation (check_apply_iter typing.rs:2892) PLUS the invariant: no call's resolved output (return/effects/written-back type-args) may leave a SHARED STORED type-param var in the enclosing scope. Upheld by: pinned param resolves to ground-or-rigid (no stored var in output), un-pinned param caught by the unconstrained check (errors, doesn't leak). If that invariant is ever violated, ADD call-side freshening (instantiate the callee scheme with fresh vars per call) as the structural safeguard. IMPL: in check_operation_bodies, before type_check_node, substitute op type-param Global(vid)->Rigid(fresh) across op.params types + return_type + declared_effects. Unconstrained check (typing.rs:4214) needs NO change (passes non-Global). VERIFY: no effectful body decomposes a row over a rigid tail (else WI-336 territory); no resolved_ret leaks a stored type-param var. Min repro: rewrap[A](b:Box[T=A])->Box[T=A]=idbox(b) + self-recursive drain[A](s:Box[T=A])->Box[T=A]=drain(s).", at: "2026-06-05T11:05:41Z", workitem: "WI-392", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED a46ed9e. Two-part fix: (1) rigidify the op's OWN type params (Global->Rigid) in check_operation_bodies before the body check; (2) views_structurally_equal (term_view.rs) compares rigid/DeBruijn vars by full Var identity (was Opaque->unequal) so a rigidified effects-row param matches itself. VERIFIED: value/element param (rewrap, self-recursive drain) AND effect param (peel: the collect shape, Eff carried in Strm[E=Eff]) thread; soundness guard (ill-typed return stays rejected). Full anthill-core green (no regression; the views_structurally_equal branch only fires for rigid/DeBruijn, which the typer never produced pre-WI-392). CAVEAT for WI-380: bind_row_tail still rejects a Rigid effect-row TAIL when DECOMPOSING a row with present labels over it (subtype_effect_rows path) -- only bites a NON-PURE body that ADDS an effect label over the threaded rigid tail; collect/takeN default bodies are PURE so they don't hit it. If WI-380 adds effectful Stream ops with bodies, that path needs rigid-tail handling (WI-336 polymorphic-row territory).", at: "2026-06-05T11:44:31Z", workitem: "WI-392", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-393",
  description: "Typer (CONSUMPTION side): thread a cross-sort carrier's provider bindings into the CONSUMING operation's OWN type parameters when the op uses [Elem,Eff] (042) mapped via its param type Spec[P = OpParam]. WI-380's rewrite (Stream ops: sort-params -> own [Elem,Eff]) makes the stdlib LOAD (WI-392) and same-sort consumption work (collect of an iterator result = real Stream[T=Int,E={}]; wi368 green), but breaks cross-sort DIRECT consumption (List[Int] used AS a Stream: collect(xs), splitFirst(xs)). Root cause: the carrier machinery binds the SPEC SORT's params (bind_spec_params_from_carrier, typing.rs:6291, via type_param_vid_in_sort(Stream, Stream.T/E)) -- which the rewritten ops NO LONGER use -- not the op's [Elem,Eff]; AND it SKIPS ground provider rows (carrier_value not a type-param ref ->  at ~6338), so E={} from  never reaches the op's Eff. TWO facets: (1) body-ful collect/takeN -> 'Eff unconstrained' (ground row E={} not threaded into Eff; the E2 finding); (2) dispatched bodyless splitFirst/head -> element ?_ (cross-sort WI-357 re-walk keys the spec sort's T, not the op's Elem; the S1 finding, whose 'deeper fix' WI-387 already flagged). FIX: at the cross-sort consumption boundary bind the OP's type params (found via the param type's Spec[T=Elem,E=Eff] mapping) from the carrier's provider view INCLUDING ground rows; preserve the WI-357 dispatched-element re-walk for bodyless ops. Consumption-side analog of WI-392 (body side). ACCEPTANCE: with WI-380's [Elem,Eff] rewrite re-applied, wi357 + wi365 + wi368 + full anthill-core green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-392"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T14:36:56Z"))

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-393")
fact Feedback(content: "(typo patch: two phrases the shell ate from the description) -- the skip site is the early-continue at bind_spec_params_from_carrier ~typing.rs:6338 where carrier_value is not a type-param ref; and the dropped ground row is E={} from the provider clause 'List provides Stream[T = T, E = {}]' (list.anthill).", at: "2026-06-05T11:56:03Z", workitem: "WI-393", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "PARTIAL + EXPANDED SCOPE (2026-06-05). Eff must thread at THREE distinct consumption forms; the WI-380 [Elem,Eff] rewrite exercises all three. (1) List PARAMETER (xs: List[T=Int], cross-sort) -- SOLVED. Fix in bind_spec_params_from_carrier (typing.rs:6291): bind the CONSUMING op own type param (found via the self-receiver param type Stream[T=Elem,E=Eff] mapping) AND, for a type-param-ref provider binding, the spec sort own param too (so the WI-325 abstract-coverage check on a dispatched bodyless splitFirst/head stays satisfied -- it inspects the spec sort param); handle GROUND provider rows (the {} written row) by binding the value directly (was continue-skipped). Made all 13 wi357+wi365+wi368 pass. (2) List LITERAL (collect of [1,2,3], cross-sort) -- NOT solved (wi362 eval). bind_spec_params_from_carrier does not fire for a literal receiver (its inferred type is not a clean parameterized List[T=Int]); the element threads via the cross-sort ARG UNIFICATION (unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref ~typing.rs:8178) but the ground E={} does not -> Eff unconstrained. (3) SAME-SORT effectful (isEmpty(eff_stream(p)) where eff_stream returns Stream[E={Modify[p]}]) -- NOT solved (wi375). The denoted-row Eff does not bind via the same-sort unify (unify_parameterized_view) -> Eff unconstrained. UNIFYING OBSERVATION: a written/ground effect row carried in the RECEIVER type must bind the consuming op Eff param, for every receiver form (param/literal/effectful) and carrier relation (cross-sort/same-sort). The likely-cleaner UNIFIED fix is in the ARG UNIFICATION (both unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref cross-sort and unify_parameterized_view same-sort) to thread the effect row into Eff -- which would SUBSUME the bind_spec_params_from_carrier path-1 fix. NEXT: investigate the two arg-unify paths. Reverted to green (rewrite + path-1 fix both backed out) pending the full multi-path implementation.", at: "2026-06-05T12:15:48Z", workitem: "WI-393", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RESEQUENCED after WI-376 (projection types) 2026-06-05 (user). WI-374 (bare-ref expansion) is the 'write shorter' convenience; its payoff only lands once type PROJECTION (WI-376: s.T/s.Sort) exists, so it now depends_on WI-376 (was the reverse: WI-376 wrongly depended on WI-374 -- corrected per this WI's own re-root note + design doc sec.8). The motivating WI-368 leak is already resolved by WI-380 (delivered; wi368 green). PLAN: after WI-376 + WI-374 land, REVERT the stdlib from the explicit [Elem,Eff] forms (WI-380) BACK to the short bare forms (bare Stream params + projections), with WI-376 projection + WI-374 expansion doing the threading. Implementation note for whoever picks it up: needs the OQ1 fresh-var-per-application path (sec.2) since the typer uses the sort's canonical param vars; (sort_ref,sort_ref) equal-base currently hits the identity fast-path and binds nothing.", at: "2026-06-05T14:51:19Z", workitem: "WI-374", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "ACCEPTANCE MET by delivered work, no new code. length(collect(List.iterator(xs))) typechecks pure (no undeclared ?_) and the element threads to List[Int] -- achieved by WI-379 (bidirectional inference) + WI-380 (stdlib [Elem,Eff] rewrite, written E={}) + WI-393 (consumption-side carrier->op-param threading). wi368_iterator_threading_test (collect_iterator_list_is_pure + collect_iterator_threads_element_int) green; full anthill-core green. Dep re-rooted WI-374->WI-379 per design sec.8.", at: "2026-06-05T14:58:52Z", workitem: "WI-368", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "IMPLEMENTATION PLAN (investigated 2026-06-05; code map). Parse IR ALREADY preserves dotted segments: Name{segments: SmallVec} (ir.rs:119); a field_access type name -> TypeExpr::Simple(Name) with multi-segment (convert.rs:346-426). NO grammar/parse change. SCOPE THIS WI to the EXPRESSION-CARRIED half (s.T/s.Sort/s.E) -- the load-bearing fluent threading; SORT-CARRIED X.L (desugar [Ti]+requires X[L=Ti]) is the follow-on seam, overlaps WI-383, defer. SLICES (green checkpoints): (1) SUBSTRATE -- add TypeNode::ExprCarried{value: Rc<NodeOccurrence>, member: Symbol} (node_occurrence.rs:787) + occ builder make_expr_carried_occ + term builder/functor anthill.prelude.TypeExtractor.ExprCarried; add TypeExtractor::ExprCarried{value,member} + TypeHead::ExprCarried + arms in type_head/extract_type/type_dispatch_name_view (typing.rs:10628-10775). Purely additive -> suite stays green (nothing emits it yet). (2) LOADER CLASSIFY (load.rs type_expr_to_child ~6088, the WI-302 is_value SymbolKind site) -- for a MULTI-SEGMENT Simple/Parameterized name, branch on the HEAD segment's SymbolKind: value head (Param/Field/LocalLet/OpResult/...) -> ExprCarried(head-value-occ, last-segment member); CRITICAL do NOT misclassify a QUALIFIED SORT REF (anthill.prelude.List, head=namespace) -- only projection when head resolves to a value (or a parametric sort for the deferred X.L). Verify FULL suite green (qualified refs unbroken). (3) ELIMINATION (the synthesis-time constraint, discharged when s is synthesized -- WI-379 bidirectional): in check_apply_iter, resolve ExprCarried(s,M) by finding the arg bound to param s (param_to_arg_sym/pos_results), take its inferred type, project member M via extract_type_param(kb,&argty,M) (s.Sort = the whole arg type), substitute into the return/effect position; mint fresh Ti + unify if needed. ABSTRACT receiver (c: C) -> project against C's declared interface member, stays polymorphic. MISSING member -> loud TypeError (project principle), never silent fresh var. (4) STRICTNESS -- param-projection dep graph (edge p->q when q's type projects p), topological/synthesis order, REJECT cycles at load, missing-member/no-such-interface loud. (5) TESTS wi376: collect(s: Stream[T=A,E=Ef]) -> List[T = s.T] effects s.E threads element+effect; splitFirst(s) -> Option[Pair[A=s.T, B=s.Sort]]; s.Sort captures all params; concrete (List[Int]->Int) vs abstract (c:C stays poly); NEGATIVE missing-member + cycle rejected. Hooks: unify_view_structural arms (typing.rs:7697) hold &mut subst for fresh-var mint (make_type_var). Deps: WI-379 (done), 042 (done). Docs: 042 sec.Type projections; type-parameter-scoping.md sec.1; expansion-during-unification.md sec.4 case 2.", at: "2026-06-05T15:07:13Z", workitem: "WI-376", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "PROGRESS 2026-06-05 (delivered the sound CONCRETE half; pushed 862d0a2/9f6b12a/2ea5252, full anthill-core green 1203). DELIVERED: expression-carried type projections s.T / s.Sort threaded through call-site composition — substrate (TypeExtractor::ExprCarried + make_expr_carried, ground-ref term form), loader classify (multi-segment value-head name -> ExprCarried, gated on the design CAPITALIZATION rule: member must be Capitalized, so Modify[result.a] stays a denoted place), eliminator in check_apply_iter (project the member off the ARGUMENT inferred type; one mechanism covers iterator(l:List)->Stream[l.T] and collect(s:Stream[T=A,E=Ef])->List[s.T]). Concrete member -> projected type; missing member -> loud error; s.Sort -> whole arg type. 8 wi376 tests incl headline gather(to_stream(xs)). /code-review fixed 2 confirmed bugs (Modify[result.a] regression via capitalization; Value::Node projection leak -> loud error) + a SOUNDNESS hole (bare/abstract receiver minted a flexible ?proj var absorbing any demand -> peek(l) usable as both Int and String; now loud error). REMAINING (acceptance 'concrete/abstract split via ONE signature' only HALF met — abstract side ERRORS soundly, not stays-poly): (1) ABSTRACT-RECEIVER stays-poly via the receiver DECLARED-INTERFACE member = rigid type tied to receiver (WI-393 carrier/provider machinery; semantic-model change); (2) cross-PARAMETER projection f(a:List,b:a.T) + load-time cycle/topological graph (slice4 strictness); (3) effects s.E does NOT load (effect names route through a separate lowering, never classified ExprCarried); (4) compound receiver a.b.T / (expr).T = TypeNode::ExprCarried Node carrier; (5) cross-sort provider DIVERGENT member name (project off declared param sort+provider, not arg raw sort); (6) ALTITUDE: eliminate at unify_types projection arms (let/rule/HO sites), not only check_apply_iter.", at: "2026-06-05T16:31:37Z", workitem: "WI-376", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-396",
  description: "Typer: expression-carried projection in EFFECT-row position (effects s.E). The element projection s.T loads and eliminates (WI-376 concrete half), but an s.E in effects syntax never reaches the ExprCarried classifier -- effect names route through a SEPARATE lowering path (effect-expression to effects_rows, not type_expr_to_child / try_expr_carried_projection in load.rs). Classify a multi-segment value-head capitalized-member name in effect position as ExprCarried, then eliminate it in the check_apply_iter effect loop (typing.rs:3001-3004 already calls eliminate_type_projections per effect e, but op.effects never contains an ExprCarried today so the loop is a no-op -- see the comment at typing.rs:2996). Project the E member off the receiver arg inferred type (the Stream E row) and substitute into the effect position. Headline: collect(s: Stream[T=A,E=Ef]) -> List[T = s.T] effects s.E threads BOTH element and effect. Missing effect member (e.g. l.E where l:List has no effect member) is a loud error per the loud-error principle (design sec.5: List has no effect member to project; the written row is the route there, not projection). Spun out of WI-376. Rust-only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-379"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-05T17:19:47Z"))

