fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-403",
  description: "Codegen/realization: lower an UNGROUNDED (rigid) path-dependent generic to the host language (docs/design/path-dependent-types.md sec.5.2). An ungrounded s.K means the operation is POLYMORPHIC over the member (an intentional type parameter induced by an abstract receiver; 011 well-typed/intentional ?, maps to a host generic). RULE DECIDED 2026-06-09 (normative: docs/rust-forward-mapping.md sec.2.14): spec-sort members surviving Self-collapse lower to Rust ASSOCIATED TYPES; within-sort s.K -> Self::K; cross-sort ungrounded -> the receiver lifts to a named generic, fn check[S: KVStore](s: S, k: S::K) (the induced host generic IS the receiver, so 'receiver in scope => nameable' = the lifted S); partial manifest -> equality bound S: KVStore[K = String]; the LIFT form fn merge[K, A: KVStore[K = K], B: KVStore[K = K]] is reserved for constraining two receivers to SHARE a member; data sorts keep generics. REMAINING SCOPE: the emitter -- implement sec.2.14 inside the WI-002 KB-driven full mapper (anthill-rust-gen; NOT the frozen bootstrap parse-IR codegen, where a projection must fail loudly instead). Rust-only (codegen).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-376", "WI-002", "WI-429"],
  status: Open)

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-403")
fact Feedback(content: "IMPL: sigma-equality = the term ALPHA-EQUALITY routine modulo the substitution equivalence classes -- the routine ACCEPTS the set of equality classes (sigma as a union-find): two terms equal at a variable iff in the SAME class; a substitution x->y (from let x=y, or a unification) puts x,y in one class, so comparing x.T and y.T succeeds; alpha-renaming at binders. NOT a bespoke check -- the SAME routine serves binder alpha-equivalence (arrow / dependent types, the deferred Positioned reading). E-graph / union-find view (equality modulo the congruence). Check, never a binding.", at: "2026-06-05T22:26:04Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "RE-SCOPED 2026-06-05 (user): implement in the RUST typer's unify_types (a sigma-equality arm at the ExprCarried head, over the Substitution -- resolve both receivers through sigma, structural compare, alpha-rename at binders), NOT via the WI-370 discrim-node custom-unification feature. WI-370 is the SELF-HOSTED-typer realization of the same idea (anthill typing rules run by the SLD resolver, WI-010, checked equal to the Rust typer, WI-079); that track is downstream of a bootstrapped typer (circular as a prereq), so it cannot gate WI-400. Dependency re-pointed WI-370 -> WI-399 (the unify-boundary is where the sigma-equality check lives). See docs/design/path-dependent-types.md sec.4 'Rust now, anthill later'.", at: "2026-06-05T22:48:51Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "REMOVED from the 'typing' build set 2026-06-05 (user): WI-370 = custom unification at a DISCRIM-TREE node, which only the SELF-HOSTED (anthill-rules) typer needs (WI-010/WI-079). The current Rust typer unifies via its own unify_types (kb/typing.rs), separate from the discrim tree, so path-dependent identity (WI-400) is a Rust unify_types arm with no trie dependency. Self-hosting is downstream of a bootstrapped typer, so WI-370 cannot gate the Rust typing work. Stays on the everything-is-facts/self-hosting track with its driver WI-371 (op-body-as-fact collapse).", at: "2026-06-05T22:48:52Z", workitem: "WI-370", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-05 (commit 5732db3): resolve a defined-type/alias to its GROUND shape before projection + comparison. resolve_alias_shape (chain-following, visited-set cycle guard, type_value_is_ground guard) wired at project_type_member (projection s.T), unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref (unify, both carriers), and the (sort_ref,parameterized) subtype arms on BOTH carriers (types_compatible_term_dispatch + types_compatible_view_structural). 7 tests; full suite green 1214. /code-review (3 finder agents + this triage) findings — DEFERRED, all SOUND (incompleteness, not soundness holes):\n(1) PARAMETRIC aliases (Pair[?X1,?X2] w/ open ? leaves) stay OPAQUE — the ground guard declines them; per-use fresh-leaf instantiation is WI-374's per-call scheme machinery (design §6 OQ6/§7 Layer-1), so this is WI-374 scope, not a WI-381 gap.\n(2) (sort_ref,sort_ref) arms (alias-vs-alias IntList vs IntList2, alias-vs-bare) NOT wired — only sort_ref<->parameterized is. False-REJECT (sound). Follow-on.\n(3) ALTITUDE: resolution wired at multiple dispatch arms; a CENTRAL resolution at the type-normalization layer (extract_type/walk) would cover all arms uniformly, but no single walk point covers types_compatible's term path (it doesn't walk at entry), and central has broad blast radius — deliberately localized. Possible future refactor.\n(4) PERF: resolve_sort_alias is an O(#SortAlias) 2-pass scan now on the bare<->parameterized subtype path; a symbol-keyed alias index would restore O(1). Pre-existing helper; no measurable regression at current scale (suite 18s unchanged). Possible optimization ticket.\n(5) View-path alias arms mirror the tested term arms but lack DEDICATED coverage — needs a denoted-bearing-alias test vehicle, blocked by a SEPARATE pre-existing denoted round-trip bug (Vec3[N=3] renders N=? in parameterized_compatible_view, rejecting a denoted type against itself; reproduces with NO alias — out of WI-381 scope).\n(6) Diagnostic prints the original alias name ('got IntList') not the resolved shape — cosmetic, rejection fires correctly.\nARG-side enforcement is WI-385-gated (args not type-checked); unify-boundary fix is in place for it.", at: "2026-06-05T23:35:11Z", workitem: "WI-381", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-06 (commit 8b6a929): args-before-expected inference for the constructor path. Two parts: (1) build-from-subst includes an unbound param as a type_var WILDCARD (not dropped) so arity is preserved (must be type_var, not bare Var — a bare Var reads as an incompatible head in the subtype dispatch); (2) expected-seed moved below the field loops (above the empty-bindings early-return). Use-site return-conformance rejects the contradiction. Un-#[ignore]'d constructor_wrong_return_rejected; suite green 1215. /code-review (2 agents) hardening applied: reverted a release-only over-acceptance in the denoted Phase-C arm; added a .-boundary check to the SortAlias prefix-walk (sibling-prefix bug Modify<->ModifyRuntime). DEFERRED (latent, not triggered):\n(1) PROVIDER-ADMISSIBILITY: a constructor result now S[T=?_] (parameterized) instead of bare S loses sort_provides_admissibly against a BARE spec, because that check is confined to the (sort_ref,sort_ref) subtype arm (not the parameterized<->sort_ref arms). Not triggered: the only stdlib provider (List) is single-param so never produces a partial ?_. Same 'confined to bare<->bare' subtype-relation gap the WI-381 review noted.\n(2) ALTITUDE: the build-from-subst hand-rolls param-short-name->Var mapping by string-slicing qualified SortAlias names (the source of the sibling-prefix bug) — a lower-altitude reimplementation of type_param_vid_in_sort; the apply path instead builds via walk_type_deep_value(subst, return_type). Refactor opportunity: enumerate the sort's declared params + type_param_vid_in_sort per param (would delete ~40 lines and subsume the boundary fix).\n(3) WI-385 boundary (confirmed, not worsened): a constructor result used as an op ARGUMENT (or a fact/constructor FIELD value) still silently accepts a contradiction (f(some(42)) with f: Option[String]->...) — the fix routes through RETURN/let conformance only (check_operation_bodies), since arg/field unify booleans are discarded (WI-385).", at: "2026-06-06T04:16:39Z", workitem: "WI-384", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-406",
  description: "Typer + stdlib: make the value<->Term reflect boundary EXPLICIT via a limited conversion API (precursor to WI-189 staging brackets). Term (anthill.reflect, sort Term = ?) is the representation-specific reflected-term sort, NOT a top type; value<->Term is a CONVERSION, not subtyping (user decision 2026-06-06). THREE pieces: (1) Add the missing TOTAL reflect op as_term[E](e: E) -> Term (entity->Term); runtime routes through the existing Value::Entity->Term::Fn lowering (alloc_from_value, kb/execute.rs; documented by WI-268). (2) The partial reify op term_as_entity[E](t: Term) -> Option[E] (Term->entity) already exists -- no change. (3) Retype fresh_var(name: String) -> Term to fresh_var[T](name: String) -> T so a query-pattern HOLE is a T-kinded logic var (WI-109), not a raw Term: Person(name: fresh_var[String](\"n\"), role: \"admin\") builds a TYPED entity, reflected to Term via as_term exactly where handed to pattern_query/execute. Rewrite the implicit value->Term sites to call as_term: rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/store.anthill commit/commit_feedback/replace -> persist_through/persist_buffer; query-construction fixtures (kb_query_test, wi182_fresh_var_test) to typed fresh_var + as_term. RESULT: every value<->Term crossing is ONE explicit conversion call, so WI-385 arg/field validation enforces the boundary with ZERO Term carve-outs. CORRELATES: WI-189 (full staging-bracket up/down reify/reflect surface -- the cosmetics/parser version this precedes and that later SUGARS these calls; WI-189 should depend on / subsume this); WI-268 (entity<->term runtime-mapping doc -- the 5 lowering rules as_term/term_as_entity sit on). Builds on proposal 042 (explicit op type-params, delivered) for the [E]/[T] forms. ACCEPTANCE: as_term loads + callable; fresh_var[T] typed; persist + query-construction sites rewritten to explicit conversions; full anthill-core green (additive -- old implicit path still tolerated until WI-385 enforces). Rust (builtin + typer) + stdlib + fixtures.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-06T05:29:02Z"))

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-406")
fact Feedback(content: "WI-406 (explicit value<->Term boundary) delivered as the prerequisite. Recon for WI-385 (investigated this session, probe stashed + design in memory anthill-typing-build-sequence): the naive types_compatible-after-unify validation produces 174 FALSE POSITIVES (polymorphic positions T/?_); a GROUNDNESS GATE (walk both sides through subst, validate only when BOTH resolved types are type_value_is_ground -- skips spec-op T params, inference ?_, free params) collapses that to 11, all in wi_tests. Those 11 had TWO root causes: (a) value<->Term reflect-boundary crossings -- NOW FIXED by WI-406 (explicit as_term / typed fresh_var, so persist+query sites type-check ground-vs-ground); (b) PROVIDER-TRANSITIVITY: IndexedFileStore provides QueryableStore/BulkStore which provide Store, so IndexedFileStore<:Store is a 2-hop provider chain, but sort_provides (typing.rs:11977) is SINGLE-HOP, so types_compatible(IndexedFileStore, Store)=false and retract(b,..)/flush(b,..) in store.anthill false-positive. (b) is the REMAINING blocker, a separate types_compatible gap unrelated to the reflect boundary -- either make sort_provides/sort_provides_admissibly transitive (recursion + cycle guard; cascades into all provider-subtyping callers = a core-relation change, stop+ask) or have WI-385 validation conservatively skip when a transitive provider path exists. IMPLEMENTATION: arg-validation in check_apply_iter after the two unify loops (~2987); field-validation in check_constructor_iter after the field-unify loops (~7073); shared helper validate_arg_against_param (walk_view both sides -> resolved_type_is_ground gate -> types_compatible) + new TypeErrorContext::OperationArgument{op_name,param}; EntityField already exists. PRE-EXISTING (unrelated): anthill-todo bundle is RED on main -- 'type mismatch in match.rule: List[String] vs List[List[String]]' at a non-reflect op; reproduces on baseline; NOT in the -p anthill-core gate; worth its own ticket.", at: "2026-06-06T05:29:03Z", workitem: "WI-385", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "CORRECTED DIAGNOSIS (supersedes the provider-transitivity feedback) — the prior premise was WRONG. Applied the stashed validation on current HEAD (post WI-406): exactly 9 failures remain, ALL 'expected Store, got IndexedFileStore' on persist/retract/flush(b) in rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/store.anthill, where b:IndexedFileStore (from 'entity wis(backend: IndexedFileStore,..)' matched as wis(b,_)) is passed to ops declared 'store: Store'. WI-406 fully fixed the reflect-boundary root cause (a). The remaining blocker is NOT transitivity: instrumented sort_provides to dump the live SortProvidesInfo edge set + probe every subtype channel. RESULT: IndexedFileStore provides ONLY Modifiable. There is NO IndexedFileStore->BulkStore, NO BulkStore->Store, NO QueryableStore->Store edge anywhere. All three channels return false for the whole hierarchy: IndexedFileStore->BulkStore = sort_provides=F sort_sym_compatible=F sort_refines=F; BulkStore->Store = F/F/F; QueryableStore->Store = F/F/F. IndexedFileStore is an Entity with parent_sort=None; Store/BulkStore/QueryableStore are Sorts with parent_sort=None. ROOT CAUSE: Store/BulkStore/QueryableStore are NON-PARAMETRIC spec sorts. The is-a is declared via 'sort QueryableStore { fact Store }' and top-level 'fact BulkStore[IndexedFileStore]', but maybe_emit_fact_provides_info (load.rs ~7276) early-returns on spec_params.is_empty(), so NON-parametric specs emit NO SortProvidesInfo at all. So the declared is-a is invisible to subtyping; it was never checked pre-WI-385 (arg-unify booleans discarded). This is the 'wave of pre-existing latent mismatches the silent path masked' the ticket predicted. The user chose 'transitive everywhere' (implemented: sort_provides recursion+cycle guard) but it has no edges to chase. WIP stash@{0} = validation + transitive sort_provides (compiles; 9 red). DECISION NEEDED (stop+ask): (A) fix provider-representation = emit zero-binding SortProvidesInfo for non-parametric 'fact <Spec>' [sort-body carrier=enclosing sort; top-level carrier=the positional] + the transitive sort_provides -> makes the declared is-a real; BIG blast radius (every non-parametric fact X across stdlib becomes a provider edge, affects dispatch/requires-coverage); likely its OWN inserted prerequisite ticket since it's a pre-existing gap not WI-385 scope. (B) warning-first per the ticket: route WI-385 mismatches through the now-DELIVERED LoadWarning channel (WI-345); suite stays green, sizes blast radius, promote to error after the gap is fixed (typer doesn't emit warnings yet, needs wiring). (C) fix the stdlib modeling to express Store is-a via a recognized mechanism. (D) narrow WI-385: hard-error ground primitive/structural mismatches now (catches the proven String-in-Int holes), skip nominal-sort-vs-nominal-sort pending the provider-repr fix.", at: "2026-06-06T06:52:17Z", workitem: "WI-385", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-407",
  description: "Loader: emit SortProvidesInfo for NON-PARAMETRIC spec 'fact <Spec>' declarations (provider-representation gap surfaced by WI-385). maybe_emit_fact_provides_info (load.rs ~7276) early-returns on spec_params.is_empty(), so 'sort QueryableStore { fact Store }' (sort-body) and top-level 'fact BulkStore[IndexedFileStore]' / 'fact QueryableStore[IndexedFileStore]' produce NO SortProvidesInfo. Probed result: IndexedFileStore provides ONLY Modifiable; sort_provides/sort_sym_compatible/sort_refines ALL false for IndexedFileStore->BulkStore, BulkStore->Store, QueryableStore->Store, so the declared Store is-a hierarchy is invisible to subtyping (never checked pre-WI-385). FIX: emit a zero-binding SortProvidesInfo for the non-parametric case -- sort-body form carrier=enclosing sort, spec=the named fact sort; top-level form carrier=the leading positional ('fact BulkStore[IFS]' => carrier IFS, spec BulkStore). PLUS the user-approved 'transitive everywhere' sort_provides (recursion+cycle guard) so IndexedFileStore->{BulkStore,QueryableStore}->Store chains. RISK/SCOPE: big blast radius -- every non-parametric 'fact X' across the stdlib becomes a real provider edge, affecting dispatch, requires-coverage, subtyping; run the FULL workspace suite and triage. ACCEPTANCE: sort_provides/types_compatible(IndexedFileStore, Store)=true via a focused test; full workspace green. WI-385's arg/field validation then lands on top and the 9 wi204/wi236 IndexedFileStore<:Store failures pass. Rust-only (loader+typer).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-06T07:25:06Z"))

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-407")
fact Feedback(content: "PREREQUISITE WI-407 DELIVERED (4154382, pushed): non-parametric spec 'fact <Spec>' now emits SortProvidesInfo + sort_provides is transitive, so IndexedFileStore<:Store (and the whole non-parametric Store hierarchy) is recognized. VERIFIED: applying this validation on top of WI-407 turns the original 9 anthill-core IndexedFileStore<:Store failures GREEN; full anthill-core suite (298 wi_tests) passes WITH the validation. Validation WIP now in stash@{0} (validation-only, applies cleanly on WI-407 HEAD, NO sort_provides conflict). REMAINING SCOPE = the anthill-todo blast radius the ticket predicted (full workspace: 6 anthill-todo targets fail with validation on; anthill-todo is GREEN without it, so this is WI-385's own scope, not WI-407). Categorized mismatches: (1) value<->Term REFLECT BOUNDARY false-positives -- 'Feedback.content: expected Term, got String', 'WorkItem.description: expected Option[T=Term], got String'. Per memory term-not-top-reflect-reify-conversion, WI-385 MUST treat value<->Term as a CONVERSION (total reflect / partial reify), NOT a mismatch. validate_arg_against_param currently does naive types_compatible -> flags String-vs-Term. NOT YET IMPLEMENTED -- this is the main remaining WI-385 work. (2) OPTION-WRAPPING: 'WorkItem.depends_on: expected Option[T=List[String]], got List[String]', 'WorkItem.description: expected Option[T=Term], got String' -- on-disk facts store a bare T where the field is Option[T] (the unwrapped-on-disk representation, cf. 5e4b635 normalize_deps). Validation must accept bare T where Option[T] declared (some()-coercion / on-disk-unwrap), OR loader wraps. DESIGN CHOICE. (3) 'walk_solutions.stream: expected LogicalStream, got Stream[T=Substitution,E=Error]' -- LogicalStream PROVIDES Stream, so passing a Stream where LogicalStream is expected is a DOWNCAST (abstract->concrete); triage whether the param is declared too-concrete (real bug) or a variance/binding gap. (4) 'match.rule: expected String got ?_' / 'expected ?_ got String' -- OperationMatch context (compute_branch_join_type), NOT the WI-385 arg/field check; triage whether pre-existing-masked or an interaction. IMPLEMENTATION PLAN for next session: (a) apply stash@{0}; (b) make validate_arg_against_param treat the Term boundary as conversion (String/any-value vs reflect Term = OK) and accept bare T vs Option[T]; (c) re-run full workspace, triage (3)/(4) -- likely a stop+ask if (3) is a real downcast bug or (4) is an interaction; (d) /code-review the validation (soundness-sensitive); deliver. Ticket's staged-rollout note (warning-first via WI-345) remains a fallback if the blast radius can't be cleanly resolved.", at: "2026-06-06T11:13:19Z", workitem: "WI-385", author: "user")
fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-408")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-06 (978d7c8, pushed). validate_arg_against_param in check_apply_iter (op args, strict) + check_constructor_iter (fields). Gated on resolved_type_is_ground. Accepts 3 boundary conversions: (1) value->Term reflection (total, both positions; Term is NOT top, so in the validation not types_compatible); (2) bare-T-vs-Option[T] FIELD INTERIM (peel + re-check element; bare Option accepts any) -- value stays bare, normalize_deps launder KEPT, on-disk unchanged; the SOUND some-insertion is WI-408 (user decision: typer inserts some, on-disk migrates to some()/none(), general implicit-conversion/into framework deferred); (3) provider admissibility -- a concrete carrier conforms to a BARE spec it provides (List->Stream param/field), found by /code-review (max effort, 2 agents CONFIRMED a false-reject regression: types_compatible confines provider-admissibility to its bare<->bare arm). Blast radius: walk_solutions widened from concrete LogicalStream to abstract Stream[Substitution,Error] (what execute returns; runtime value is a LogicalStream which provides Stream so splitFirst dispatches) + declared the Error effect. Tests: anthill-core/tests/include/wi385_arg_field_validation_test.rs (8). Full workspace green. KNOWN BOUNDARY (pre-existing pass-reach, NOT a logic gap): free-standing namespace-level entity top-level facts are not visited by type_check_sorts, so their fields stay unvalidated -- op-args, op-body constructors, and IN-SORT-entity facts ARE validated.", at: "2026-06-06T13:17:18Z", workitem: "WI-385", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-409",
  description: "Stdlib+cli: implement map (+ the find/fold combinators ParseArgs uses) on Stream/Iterable over the WI-380 splitFirst substrate, and REWRITE stdlib/anthill/cli/parse.anthill ParseArgs (parse_argv/parse_args/find_spec/find_param/next_positional/check_required) to use them INSTEAD of hand-rolled match-nil/cons recursion. THIS IS THE ORIGINAL DRIVER behind the whole type-threading effort (WI-379->380->393->...): the element threading map needs (Stream[T=A]->Stream[T=B]) is DELIVERED (WI-380/393, explicit [Elem,Eff]); the remaining blocker is HOF (WI-275 -- probe-confirmed: applying a function-typed param / passing a lambda does NOT type-check today). The PROJECTION / path-dependent cluster (WI-376/397/398/399/400) is the write-shorter FLUENCY layer (bare s.T instead of explicit [Elem,Eff]) and is NOT required for this goal. Acceptance: parse.anthill's recursive list ops expressed via map/find/fold; cargo-test green (anthill-todo CLI parse tests stay green).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-275", "WI-064"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T00:10:17Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "REFRESH NEEDED + re-rooted 2026-06-06: this is the combinator layer under WI-409 (the real driver — map/find/fold used in cli/parse.anthill ParseArgs instead of recursion). (1) The original 'definitions via rules over Iteration.split' approach is superseded by the WI-380 substrate — Stream ops (splitFirst/collect/takeN) are now OPERATIONS with default bodies over splitFirst[Elem,Eff], so map/fold/filter/find should follow that style (explicit [Elem,Eff] element threading, DELIVERED), on Stream/Iterable, not 'rules over split'. (2) Now depends_on WI-275 — the combinators take a Function param and apply it (HOF), which is the proven blocker (probe: applying a function-typed param / lambda arg does not type-check). (3) The element-type CHANGE map needs (Stream[T=A]->Stream[T=B]) is the explicit-type-param style WI-380/393 delivered; the projection/path-dependent cluster (WI-376/397...) is NOT required.", at: "2026-06-06T16:02:48Z", workitem: "WI-064", author: "user")
fact Tag(name: "first-real-map", workitem: "WI-275")
fact Tag(name: "first-real-map", workitem: "WI-064")
fact Tag(name: "first-real-map", workitem: "WI-409")
fact Feedback(content: "first-real-map surfaced this CONCRETELY 2026-06-06. Building the abstract 'map' combinator (a lazy mapped(source,fn) carrier that PROVIDES Stream — the right structure per library/002) compiles internally with direct fn(h) application, BUT 'map(s,fn) -> Stream[T=D,E=Ef] = mapped(s,fn)' fails RETURN-conformance: MappedStream[Src=S,Dst=D,Eff=Ef] does not conform to Stream[T=D,E=Ef] (nor even bare Stream) despite 'provides Stream[T=Dst,E=Eff]'. types_compatible's (parameterized,sort_ref) + (parameterized,parameterized) arms do not admit a parameterized PROVIDER; WI-385's provider-admissibility fix only patched the ARG/FIELD path (validate_arg_against_param), so CONSUMPTION (collect(map(...))) works via arg-position admissibility but PRODUCTION (map's return) does NOT. THIS is the real typer blocker for the abstract combinator (NOT HOF — checking works via direct fn(h); NOT projection — that's fluency). Right-altitude fix = provider-admissibility UNIFORMLY in types_compatible, subsuming the WI-385 arg-patch. Now on first-real-map; WI-064 depends_on it. Repro: /tmp/mapped2.anthill shape.", at: "2026-06-06T16:27:22Z", workitem: "WI-405", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "HOF CHECKING confirmed WORKING 2026-06-06 — my earlier 'broken' verdict was a SYNTAX error (wrong Function param names + missing 'lambda' keyword). Passing eval tests prove it: m2_higher_order (apply_twice(f: Function[Int,Int],x)=f(f(x)) + 'lambda n->n' → 5) and m2_user_defined_reduce_on_list_and_set (f((acc,h)) + 'lambda (a,b)->a+b' → 70). DIRECT application of a Function-typed param/field 'fn(h)' type-checks+evals; 'apply(f,x)' via Function.apply is the form that did NOT resolve. So enablement (a)+(b) is DONE. Remaining: (1) ergonomic call-site INFERENCE of a polymorphic function param's RESULT type from a lambda ('map([1,2,3], lambda x->x)' → 'D unconstrained, use map[D=…]') — a refinement (explicit type-args work); (2) the 'add stdlib List.map/fold' deliverable (c) = WI-064, blocked by WI-405 (provider-admissibility so the lazy carrier can RETURN Stream). WI-275 enablement done; combinator-acceptance folds into WI-064/WI-405.", at: "2026-06-06T16:28:16Z", workitem: "WI-275", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "NOT the map blocker (verified 2026-06-06). The MappedStream->Stream return-conformance failure was MY carrier-design error: output param named Dst/Eff (divergent from Stream's T/E) forced parameterized_compatible_view's None-arm (cross-sort provider view, which reads the provider's raw param ref WITHOUT substituting the actual's bindings). Naming the carrier's output param T and effect E (matching Stream — exactly as List provides Stream[T=T,E={}]) hits the Some-arm (direct binding) and conforms, no typer change. So the abstract lazy map combinator type-checks today. WI-405's FACET A (provider-admissibility in the parameterized<->bare-spec arm) + FACET B (alias in sort_ref<->sort_ref) remain REAL latent gaps (per the ticket / WI-381/384 reviews) but are OFF the map critical path. Untagged from first-real-map; un-claiming.", at: "2026-06-06T17:34:57Z", workitem: "WI-405", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Verified 2026-06-06: HOF args work with NAMED ops — map[...](intList, inc) with inc(n:Int)->Int loads clean. Remaining gap = BIDIRECTIONAL LAMBDA INFERENCE: inline 'lambda x -> add(x,1)' fails ('add multiple impls', x untyped) because the lambda's param type isn't pushed from the expected Function[A=…]; 'lambda x -> 0' (x unused) works; no lambda-param annotation syntax (parse error). So map/find/fold are USABLE NOW with named transform/predicate ops; lambda-ergonomics (push expected Function param/result into the lambda) is WI-275's remaining inference — a refinement, NOT a hard blocker for WI-064/WI-409.", at: "2026-06-06T17:34:57Z", workitem: "WI-275", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-06 (b0c01a9): bidirectional HOF-arg inference. Typer pushes the declared Function param type into lambda/op-ref args (hof_arg_hint in Expr::Apply); check_bare_ref eta-lifts a MONOMORPHIC, BODY-having op to its arrow type (operation_as_function_value). Runtime: new Value::OpRef + spread_eta_args (single-tuple-arg spread for multi-param). Inline lambda (lambda x->add(x,1)), bare named op (inc/lt_int), and lambda/named 2-param comparators ALL work typecheck+eval (eval test m2_hof_inference_sort_and_map asserts sort order). SOUNDNESS: typer eta gated as SUBSET-of runtime (op_has_runnable_body + type_params.is_empty) so a body-less builtin or generic op is a LOUD type error, never a runtime crash — /code-review max-effort empirically caught a builtin (as_term) that typechecked-then-crashed before the gate was added. DEFERRED (beyond stated scope; all currently loud type errors, NOT crashes): (1) builtin-as-function-value eta (needs runtime OpRef->builtin-registry routing + arity via OperationInfo); (2) generic-op eta (needs per-use type-var freshening + type_args threading through OpRef); (3) review EFFICIENCY note: Expr::Apply does a 2nd lookup_operation_info_full (1st is in check_apply_iter) on most HOF-arg applies — could thread op.params through the Build::Apply frame; no measured suite-time regression so not done. first-real-map: WI-064/WI-409 now usable with named OR inline-lambda transforms/predicates.", at: "2026-06-06T19:12:08Z", workitem: "WI-275", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-410",
  description: "Stdlib: filter combinator (lazy FilteredStream carrier that provides Stream). BLOCKED on WI-356: a kept element is returned verbatim (unlike map's fn(h), whose output type comes from the transform's return), so the source head's element type must thread through splitFirst's destructured Pair — which the typer does not yet do; a head/tail workaround hits a related 'op type-param unconstrained on an abstract carrier' wall (even an explicit abstract sort-param as the type-arg reads unconstrained). Off the WI-409 critical path (WI-409 needs map+find+fold, not filter). Acceptance: filter on a List typechecks + evals; collect(filter(xs, pred)) keeps only matching elements.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-413"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T01:43:20Z"))

fact Tag(name: "first-real-map", workitem: "WI-410")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-06 (990c4d0): fold_left/fold_right/find (eager, on Stream over splitFirst, alongside collect/takeN) + map (lazy MappedStream carrier providing Stream) in stdlib. All work typecheck+EVAL (eval_test::wi064_stdlib_combinators_fold_map_find: reduce-to-sum=10 acceptance; direction-sensitive folds via subtraction -6 vs 2; map collect 234 / map+fold 9 / empty 0; find first/head/none). Usable with NAMED transform/predicate ops (WI-275 eta); a List is the receiver via List-provides-Stream. Fn params carry E=Eff (effectful-transform soundness, /code-review). DEFERRED, all tracked: (1) FILTER -> WI-410 (blocked WI-356: a kept element returned verbatim needs the source head's element type threaded through splitFirst's Pair destructure; off WI-409 critical path); (2) map's recursive splitFirst self-dispatched to MappedStream.splitFirst when UNqualified -> latent typer bug WI-411, worked around with qualified Stream.splitFirst(src) (the user's original fragment was typecheck-only, never eval'd, so this was newly surfaced — VERIFY EVAL, not just typecheck); (3) map needs explicit [Dst,Eff] (output element/effect not inferred from transform/source — WI-275-class refinement; user accepted explicit-args interim). WI-409 (map+find+fold in ParseArgs) is now UNBLOCKED.", at: "2026-06-06T19:42:56Z", workitem: "WI-064", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-06 (04f1ba4): the 5 recursive list SEARCHES in stdlib/anthill/cli/parse.anthill (find_spec/find_param/has_binding/next_positional/check_required) rewritten via Stream.find (WI-064) — a List is the receiver via List-provides-Stream. Each predicate closes over a runtime value (target name / current acc), so it is a CURRIED builder op returning a closure typed against its OWN concrete Function[..] return (the lambda checked at a concrete element type — the workaround for WI-275's inline-lambda-on-generic-combinator gap; a bare op can't capture, an inline lambda on a generic combinator can't type). The argv walk parse_args stays direct recursion (lookahead state machine — a flag consumes the NEXT argv element — not a per-element fold). map/fold not used: parse has no list-transform/reduce-shaped op, only searches → find is the fit. Behavior IDENTICAL (head-first first-match, same predicates/error construction): cli_parse tests + full anthill-todo suite green (1538 workspace). /code-review: semantic-equivalence agent found NO behavioral diff; net +5 builder ops is the intended combinator demonstration (the whole point of WI-409). FOLLOW-UP: WI-412 (anthill-todo embedded-stdlib hand-list drifts — 7 files missing; migrate to build.rs auto-collect like anthill-cli; combinators.anthill added by hand here as interim). first-real-map GOAL REACHED: the type-threading effort (WI-379->380->393->275->064->409) now demonstrably powers real CLI code via stdlib combinators.", at: "2026-06-07T00:10:17Z", workitem: "WI-409", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-413",
  description: "Typer: effect-row threading through a CARRIER-IMPL SELF-RECURSION (the effect dual of WI-357's element threading). A provider's own splitFirst impl that self-recurses on a RECONSTRUCTED carrier value leaves the recursive call's incurred effect an unbound ??_ that won't close to the declared effect row. MINIMAL REPRO: sort Rec { sort T=?; effects E=?; entity recw(source: Stream[T=T,E=E]); provides Stream[T=T,E=E]; operation splitFirst(r: Rec) -> Option[T=Pair[A=T,B=Rec]] effects E = match r case recw(src) -> match Stream.splitFirst(src) case none()->none case some(pair(h,rest)) -> splitFirst(recw(rest)) } -> 'splitFirst.effects: expected declared [E], got undeclared effect: ??_'. WITHOUT the self-recursion (else->none) it is 0 errors; the element T threads fine (post-WI-357); ONLY the effect leaks. Parameterizing splitFirst[Elem,Eff](r: Rec[T=Elem,E=Eff]) does NOT fix it. DIAGNOSIS: the WI-357/WI-365 effect-CLOSE (typing.rs ~3302-3320, bind_spec_params_from_carrier + filter effect_is_unresolved_var) applies to a SPEC op (Stream.collect) consumed on a concrete carrier (List), but NOT to a carrier's OWN impl (Rec.splitFirst) self-recursing on a constructed carrier value — Rec is not a spec sort so self_receiver_spec_sort returns None and the close never runs. Contrast: the eager combinators (fold_left/find) recurse on a Stream 'rest' directly typed Stream[E=Eff] and DO thread the effect. FIX DIRECTION: extend the effect-close/threading to a carrier-impl self-recursion whose receiver is a constructed carrier (thread/close E like the body-less self-receiver path). This BLOCKS WI-410 (lazy filter). An EAGER filter (Stream op -> List, like find) works TODAY without this. TEST: the minimal Rec repro typechecks; the lazy FilteredStream filter typechecks+evals; WI-357/365 + full stdlib stay green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T01:42:53Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "ATTEMPTED 2026-06-07 — traced to a MULTI-LAYER gap, not a single-point fix. Debug instrumentation (WI413_DBG in the typing.rs effect-close block) on the minimal Rec repro showed: at the self-recursion splitFirst(recw(rest)), the RECEIVER recw(rest) types as Rec[T=??_, E=??_] (BOTH params unbound, not just the effect), and receiver_carrier returns Abstract because base(Rec)==spec_sort(Rec) — the 'base != spec_canon' guard at typing.rs:6448 treats a carrier-impl self-recursion as an abstract spec value, so the effect-close (3302-3320) never fires. But closing alone would be WRONG anyway (it drops the effect → a pure filter over an effectful stream); the effect must be BOUND to the carrier's E, not dropped. ROOT CHAIN (all must thread for the lazy carrier): (1) pattern destructure 'match r case recw(src)' on r: Rec[T=Elem,E=Eff] must bind src: Stream[T=Elem,E=Eff] (WI-357 claimed pattern threading works for the HEAD element A, but here even src/element comes out ??_ for the parameterized carrier — needs re-verification); (2) Stream.splitFirst(src) must thread T/E into the NESTED stream B of its Pair return (WI-357 fixed the HEAD A; the TAIL B threading is the extension); (3) the reconstructing constructor recw(rest) must carry T/E from rest into the built Rec type; (4) receiver_carrier must classify a carrier-impl self-recursion (base==spec_sort AND sort_has_constructors) as Concrete so the bind/close fires. Contrast: the EAGER combinators (fold_left/find) recurse on a Stream 'rest' DIRECTLY (no reconstruction) so they sidestep (1)/(3) — that is why an eager filter (Stream->List) works today. This is substantial effect+element threading work across pattern/spec-op-return/constructor/dispatch-classification in the delicate WI-357/365/393 cluster (soundness-sensitive). RECOMMEND a dedicated focused session; an EAGER filter unblocks WI-410's functionality meanwhile.", at: "2026-06-07T00:38:25Z", workitem: "WI-413", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-07 (903a238). ROOT CAUSE was NOT the effect-close/receiver_carrier (the WI's layer-4 diagnosis) but the PATTERN DESTRUCTURE (layer 1): extend_env_from_pattern read constructor field types through the SHALLOW walk_type_value, which resolves only a TOP-LEVEL type-param var — a parameterized field type (source: Stream[T=T,E=E], vars NESTED in the Fn named_args) was left unsubstituted, so 'case recw(src)' left src:Stream[?_,?_] and rest/recw(rest)/the recursive effect all followed to ??_. FIX: walk_pattern_field_type_deep (deep-walk field types into Fn children, preserving top-level Value::Node surfacing). With the carrier op declaring its OWN [Elem,Eff] params (the whole combinator library convention), the destructure threads AND the recursive call's Eff binds from its reconstructed arg by ordinary op-type-param unification -> closes to the declared row. CORRECTION: the WI's 'parameterizing splitFirst[Elem,Eff] does NOT fix it' was true ONLY before this fix; AFTER it the parameterized form WORKS and is the delivered form. The BARE self-receiver (r: Rec) stays unsupported (no op-param machinery to carry element/effect — same reason every eager combinator uses explicit params); known boundary, not a regression. Tests: wi413_effect_self_recursion_test (Rec carrier typechecks) + eval_test wi413_lazy_filter (filter typechecks+evals). Full workspace suite green (1540). /code-review high: no real findings.", at: "2026-06-07T01:42:53Z", workitem: "WI-413", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-07 (903a238) together with WI-413 (its only blocker). Lazy FilteredStream carrier added to combinators.anthill (sibling of MappedStream/map): entity filtered(source: Stream, pred: Function); provides Stream; splitFirst[Elem,Eff] advances the source to the first KEPT element and SELF-RECURSES on filtered(rest,pred) to skip a dropped one; filter[S,Eff](s: Stream, p) -> Stream. Both threadings work: the kept head is returned VERBATIM so its element type threads (WI-357 + the WI-413 deep-walk of the destructured Pair), and the skip-recursion's effect closes to the declared row (WI-413). ACCEPTANCE MET: eval_test wi413_lazy_filter_skips_via_self_recursion — collect(filter([1,2,3,4], n>2)) keeps [3,4] (=34), fold sums = 7, leading-skip [1,2,3]->[3]=3, all-dropped [1,2]->0, all-kept [3,4,5]=12. Uses explicit [S,Eff] like map[Dst,Eff] (output element = source element). The stale 'BLOCKED on WI-356' note was already corrected to WI-413 (f1a6a4f).", at: "2026-06-07T01:43:07Z", workitem: "WI-410", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-414",
  description: "BUG: a List op that uses `eq` under List's sort-level `requires Eq[T]` (e.g. `member`, `nth`) TYPECHECKS but FAILS AT RUNTIME when called from an external namespace: `DeferToRequirement: requirement param __req_eq not bound in caller frame`. ROOT: a CONCRETE-typed call inside the op body — `eq(i, 0)` with i:Int, or `eq(head, x)` at a concrete element — routes through the enclosing sort's `requires Eq[T]` (deferred to the __req_eq frame param) instead of resolving concretely to the available `fact Eq[Int]`. EXPECTED (user): it should EITHER fail to COMPILE if Eq genuinely can't be found, OR (the right behavior) resolve `Eq[Int]` concretely so the call works at runtime — NOT compile-clean then crash on a missing requirement. The concrete impl IS present (fact Eq[Int]), so concrete resolution should win. REPRO (both typecheck; run from an OUTSIDE namespace): `member(2, [1,2,3])` -> Err(__req_eq not bound); `length([1,2,3])` -> Ok(3) (length uses `add`/Numeric, no Eq requirement, so it works — isolating the gap to the requires-Eq path). PRE-EXISTING (NOT from the WI-410/413 typing work): demonstrated with `member`, which is unchanged code; the old bare `nth` had the same `eq(i,0)` and the same latent failure. IMPACT: eq-using List ops are not runtime-callable from an external namespace; the requirement-insertion pass (WI-218/231/239) over-defers a requirement whose concrete impl is statically available. FIX DIRECTION: at requirement insertion / dispatch, when a `requires Spec[T]` op is invoked with the relevant position at a CONCRETE type that has a `fact Spec[<concrete>]`, resolve it concretely (pin the impl) instead of threading __req. ACCEPTANCE: `member(2,[1,2,3])` and `nth([10,20,30],0)` eval from an external namespace (no manual requirement binding); full suite stays green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T05:56:23Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-07 (8988de9). The INTERNAL concrete-eq case (nth) — exactly the WI title 'a concrete spec-op call defers instead of resolving the concrete fact'. ROOT: entry_matches_subst (defer-to-requirement matching, typing.rs) treated a CONCRETE per-call value (Eq.T:=Int from eq(i:Int,0) inside a List op) as matching an OPEN-T requirement entry (requires Eq[T], a type-param wildcard) via the symmetric dispatch_values_match — so the call deferred to a __req_eq slot an external caller never binds. FIX: a concrete per-call value never defers to an open-T (wildcard) entry — it dispatches concretely to fact Eq[Int]; an abstract per-call value (the enclosing T) still defers; a concrete call to a CONCRETE requires (Eq[T=Int]) still defers via the non-wildcard match. Also rewrote nth/member bodies ite(...)->if/then/else (ite is rule-only with no eval body, and as a strict fn would eagerly recurse), so nth is now EVALUABLE: nth([10,20,30],i) evals from an external namespace (eval_test wi414_nth_dispatches_concrete_eq). /code-review (soundness-focused): no regressions (concrete dispatch is MORE sound than deferring a concrete call to the enclosing-T requirement; a concrete type with no fact is a genuine error, not a defer). Full workspace suite green (1541). The CALL-SITE dual (member) is a DISTINCT mechanism → split to WI-415.", at: "2026-06-07T05:56:23Z", workitem: "WI-414", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-415",
  description: "BUG (call-site dual of WI-414): a directly-called CONCRETE op whose parent sort `requires Spec[T]` and whose body DEFERS a spec op at the ABSTRACT element (e.g. `member(x:T, l:List)` body `if eq(head,x) ...`, head:T abstract) FAILS AT RUNTIME when called from a namespace with NO `requires`: `member(2,[1,2,3])` -> `DeferToRequirement: __req_eq not bound in caller frame`. member's eq is genuinely abstract so it correctly DEFERS to List's Eq[T]; the gap is the CALL SITE — at T=Int it must CONSTRUCT the Eq[Int] requirement from `fact Eq[Int]` and thread it, but the typer classifies the call CallClass::ConcreteApplyWithin with resolved_tree=None, and req_insertion's build_dispatching_dict_direct can't resolve the OPEN `Eq[T]` dep with empty caller_requires (Strategy 3 SLD on Eq[T] open). DIAGNOSIS (verified): the typer HAS the call-site subst (List.T:=Int from x:Int) and resolve(Eq[Int]) -> Resolved; but passing it as the single-node resolved_tree is SHAPE-WRONG — emit_tree_as_projection gives a bare Eq dict, whereas a concrete op's requirement must be the PARENT-BUNDLE shape build_dispatching_dict_direct emits (construct_requirement(parent, [sub-reqs])), so member's body can't read its __req_eq slot. FIX DIRECTION: thread the call-site subst (or the substituted direct-requires chain Eq[T]->Eq[Int]) into build_dispatching_dict_direct so build_dep_projection Strategy 3 resolves the CONCRETE dep in the parent-bundle shape; gate on a concrete goal (abstract caller stays None = current). REPRO + trip-wire: eval_test wi415_member_call_constructs_concrete_eq_requirement (#[ignore]). ACCEPTANCE: un-ignore it (member(2,[1,2,3])=true, member(9,..)=false eval from an external namespace); full suite green. Discovered fixing WI-414 (nth); nth's INTERNAL concrete eq was the other half (delivered 8988de9).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T06:54:46Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-416",
  description: "TYPER STACK OVERFLOW (infinite recursion at typecheck) on a cross-sort call to a requires-op typed with the CALLEE sort's own bare sort-parameter. MINIMAL REPRO (N1): `sort Coll { sort T = ?; operation contains(items: List[T], x: T) -> Bool = List.member(x, items) }` — `anthill check` overflows the stack (SIGABRT) at typecheck. NO `requires` on Coll needed. NARROWING: (a) calling `List.length` (no deferred spec op) from a sort op is FINE; (b) calling `List.member` from a FREE op with no enclosing sort (WI-415's `has2() = member(2,[1,2,3])`) is FINE; (c) calling `List.nth` (its own `[Elem]` type-param) gives a CLEAN error ('needs nth[Elem=…]'), not overflow. So the trigger is: a call FROM WITHIN A SORT's operation body, to a cross-sort op (member's parent List != caller sort) that is typed with the CALLEE sort's BARE sort-param (member's `x: T`, T=List.T) AND whose body defers a spec op (member's `eq` -> List requires Eq[T]). The bare-sort-param unifies caller-elem with List.T and something in the typer (requirement/projection/sort-alias resolution) re-enters without a cycle guard. PRE-EXISTING: overflows on 7e829bf (before WI-415); NOT caused by WI-415. ALSO (likely same/related recursion): an UNRESOLVED `requires X[T]` (X not imported into scope) ALSO stack-overflows instead of emitting a clean 'unresolved name' error. IMPACT: violates 'loud error over silent loop' — a malformed/cross-sort call should typecheck or error, never infinite-recurse. BLOCKS the WI-415 cross-sort-ABSTRACT requirement-threading gap (a sort `Coll requires Eq[T]` whose op delegates to `List.member` on its abstract element cannot even be typechecked, so that runtime gap is unreachable/untestable until this is fixed). ACCEPTANCE: N1 repro typechecks or errors cleanly (no overflow) — add cycle/depth guard; then a cross-sort-abstract eval test (Coll.contains threading its __req_eq onward to member, Strategy-1 var_ref) becomes writable.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T08:04:49Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Trip-wire test ADDED (subprocess, #[ignore]'d so the suite stays green): anthill-cli/tests/wi416_overflow_test.rs::wi416_cross_sort_member_call_does_not_overflow_typer + fixture anthill-cli/tests/fixtures/check/wi416-cross-sort-member.anthill. It runs the built `anthill check` on the repro and asserts the child exits cleanly (code().is_some()) rather than dying by signal. In-process won't work — the overflow is an uncatchable SIGABRT that aborts the whole test binary; the subprocess form observes the child crash safely (verified: --ignored run fails as a clean assertion, exit 134, parent binary not aborted). ACCEPTANCE = un-#[ignore] this test when the typer recursion is guarded.", at: "2026-06-07T07:30:39Z", workitem: "WI-416", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-417",
  description: "Harden the typer's other substitution-chain walkers against cyclic substitutions (WI-416 follow-up). WI-416 made walk_type iterative+cycle-guarded, fixing the filed cross-sort-member overflow. /code-review (high) found 3 SIBLING walkers that chase the same subst/sort-alias chain RECURSIVELY without a guard and would overflow on a cyclic subst: walk_type_value (typing.rs ~879), walk_value_to_resolved (~8795), walk_pattern_field_type_deep (~911). They are LATENT/UNREACHABLE on current inputs (verified: 0 deep recursions on the WI-416 repro — the WI-416 cycle only closes through the sort-alias hop, which these delegate to the now-guarded walk_type; and pure Var<->Var cycles don't arise because unify binds one direction only). But they share the exact pattern, so a value-carried cycle (Value::Term(Var)<->Var or Value::Var<->Var) would overflow. TWO altitude options: (a) extract ONE shared cycle-guarded chain-resolver all walkers call (also removes the walk_type intra-fn duplication of the guarded var-resolve block); (b) HIGHER altitude — prevent the cyclic binding at bind time via union-find canonicalization in bind_resolved (the subst is a plain HashMap<VarId,Value> with only opportunistic bind_compressed path-compression on Value::Term, NOT run on the typer's bind_resolved path), pointing both var-instances of one sort-param at a single representative when the second cross-binding is made — removes the cycle once so every reader is safe. Root cause of the cross-binding: typing a cross-sort call creates two distinct Var instances of one sort-param (e.g. Coll.T as var841 alias + var351 instance) that cross-bind; occurs_in doesn't resolve sort-refs so it can't catch a cycle formed from two individually-valid bindings. ACCEPTANCE: a value-carried cyclic-subst repro typechecks without overflow; ideally one shared guarded resolver or bind-time canonicalization.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T08:34:09Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-418",
  description: "Cross-sort ABSTRACT requirement forwarding (the third WI-415 gap; now reachable post-WI-416). A sort `Coll requires Eq[T]` whose op `contains(items: List[T], x: T) = List.member(x, items)` delegates to a cross-sort requires-op (member, parent List) on its OWN ABSTRACT element x:Coll.T. The OUTER call `Coll.contains([1,2,3], 2)` from a plain namespace is concrete (Coll.T:=Int) so WI-415 threads `Eq[Int]` into contains' frame as __req_eq. But the INNER contains->member call is cross-sort (member's parent List != enclosing Coll) AND abstract (x:Coll.T), so member needs contains' frame __req_eq FORWARDED to it (Strategy-1 var_ref: Coll's `requires Eq[T]` COVERS member's `Eq[List.T]` at List.T=Coll.T). TYPECHECKS post-WI-416 but FAILS AT EVAL: `DeferToRequirement: __req_eq not bound in caller frame`. CAUSE: build_concrete_dispatch_dict returns None for the abstract inner call (gated on any_concrete = a CONCRETE binding), and eval's start_apply_same_sort sees callee_parent(List) != enclosing(Coll) => inherit false => plain start_apply (no requirements). FIX DIRECTION: for a cross-sort (non-same-sort) call, build the dispatching dict even when the binding stays ABSTRACT, letting build_dep_projection Strategy 1/2 emit a var_ref into the CALLER's frame __req (the enclosing sort's requires covers the dep) — i.e. relax the any_concrete gate to 'not same-sort, try build_dispatching_dict_from_chain with require_complete'; eval then installs it (the var_ref reads the caller frame at eval time, which is correct). REPRO + trip-wire: eval_test wi418_cross_sort_abstract_call_forwards_caller_requirement (#[ignore]). ACCEPTANCE: un-ignore it (Coll.contains([1,2,3],2)=true, has9=false eval from an external namespace); suite green. depends_on WI-416.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-416"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T08:57:18Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "CORRECTION (commit 62bc6e7): the curried-builder workaround was UNNECESSARY for parse.anthill. All 5 builder ops (spec_name_is/param_name_is/binding_name_is/unbound_positional/required_missing) were removed and the predicates inlined as lambdas passed directly to find. Inline lambdas DO type on find: the element type is pinned by the concrete List receiver and the result is Bool, so WI-275's bidirectional HOF-arg inference (delivered b0c01a9) types both the lambda param and body. The delivered comment's claim 'an inline lambda cannot type on a generic combinator (element type unpinned)' over-applied the WI-064 FOLD finding to FIND. That gap is real ONLY when the element/accumulator type is unpinned at the call site, i.e. fold: VERIFIED that generic fold_left(xs, 0, lambda (acc,x)->acc+x) still fails 'cannot prove Numeric[Acc]' (the genuine remaining gap = WI-275's deferred two-phase remainder). Rewrite is behavior-identical: anthill check 66/66, cli_parse eval 4/4, full workspace suite green, /code-review (max-effort, 2 finders) clean — no external refs to the removed ops, no export, embedded copies include_str! the live path.", at: "2026-06-07T12:42:25Z", workitem: "WI-409", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-420",
  description: "Typer/eval FULL FIX: a requires-carrying operation eta-lifted to Value::OpRef (the WI-275 named-op HOF path) type-checks clean then CRASHES at eval with an unbound __req_*. Repro: use_pair(member, 2, [1,2,3]) where member is on 'List requires Eq[T]' -> Err(Internal(\"DeferToRequirement: requirement param __req_eq not bound in caller frame\")). CONTRAST: a genuine lambda is SOUND -- Closure snapshots frame.requirements at construction and enter_closure reinstalls them, DROPPING the caller's channel (proven by wi223_closure_requirements_test). The OpRef path has NO such capture: reduce_var (eval.rs:281) mints OpRef on body+arity alone; the eta gate operation_as_function_value (typing.rs:1587) checks params/type_params but NOT the parent sort's requires-chain; OpRef apply (eval.rs ~894 dispatch_call_with_requirements) forwards the caller's (empty) requirements into enter_operation. This VIOLATES WI-275's stated 'typer-accepted subset-of runtime-runnable' invariant (a non-runnable op must be a loud type error, never a crash). INTERIM CONSERVATIVE GATE already delivered separately: operation_as_function_value now rejects eta of an op whose enclosing sort has a non-empty requires_chain_flat -> loud load-time TypeError. That conservative gate ALSO over-rejects a concrete op on a requires-sort whose body never reads the dict (e.g. List.length); acceptable interim, lifted by this full fix. FULL FIX (this WI): give Value::OpRef a captured-requirements field like Closure, populated at mint from the resolved dispatch dict (same dict WI-415 build_concrete_dispatch_dict / start_apply_same_sort builds), installed into the callee frame at apply instead of forwarding the caller's; the typer must resolve/thread the op's requirement dict at the eta site (req_insertion currently has no Lambda/HoApply/OpRef handling). Then REMOVE the conservative gate. Acceptance: use_pair(member,2,[1,2,3]) evals Ok(true); a requires-carrying op passed to find/fold/sort works end-to-end; the interim conservative-gate regression test is updated from expect-loud-error to expect-success; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-275"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T15:33:21Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "CONSERVATIVE INTERIM GATE DELIVERED 1009baa (separate from this WI's full-fix scope). operation_as_function_value now returns Result<Option<Value>,TypeError>: Err (loud load error) when an eta-eligible op's enclosing sort has a non-empty requires_chain_flat; check_bare_ref propagates via ?. KEY LESSON from /code-review (read-only, sequential pass): the FIRST cut returned None for the requires case, which REGRESSED a CURRIED op on a requires-sort (return type itself a Function): None fell through to the return-type reading, which MATCHES the expected arrow -> load-clean-then-crash (var_ref(__req_eq) unbound). Fixed by returning Err (not None) so the rejection stays loud for curried AND non-curried shapes. Tests: wi420_eta_of_requires_carrying (member/non-curried) + wi420_eta_of_curried_requires (Wrap.build/curried) both assert the error carries the 'WI-420' marker (pins the gate fired, not an unrelated error); wi420_eta_of_requires_free still loads; wi420_lambda_over_requires_op_passed_to_hof_evals pins the SOUND lambda path still evals from a no-req caller. RESIDUAL (still part of THIS WI's full fix, do NOT spin off): hof_arg_hint matches only Expr::Lambda|VarRef, NOT Ref|Ident -- a bare op arriving as Ref/Ident gets no Function hint so the gate never runs. Currently UNREACHABLE via tested shapes (op-body identifiers emit as var_ref->VarRef; let-annotation sets expected directly), and the full fix (OpRef captures/threads its dict like Closure) removes the gate entirely, closing it. FULL FIX (this WI) remains: give Value::OpRef a captured-requirements field, populate at mint, install at apply; then delete the gate + flip the two rejection tests to expect-success.", at: "2026-06-07T13:54:33Z", workitem: "WI-420", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-421",
  description: "Loader/typer: an external operation cannot be referenced as a VALUE (for eta / HOF arg) inside a SORT BODY -- only as a qualified dot-CALL (WI-279 dot-dispatch). Surfaced finalizing WI-420: abstract-cross-sort eta (eta-lifting an external requires-op where the element type is ABSTRACT) requires referencing the op as a value inside a sort op (the only place the element is abstract), which does not resolve. Evidence (all in value position inside a sort body): bare 'member' with 'import anthill.prelude.List.{member}' -> 'unknown functor'/unresolved; 'List.member' as a value -> parsed as dot-access chain (List, member both unresolved); 'anthill.prelude.List.member' as a value -> parsed as a 4-ref access chain (anthill/prelude/List/member all unresolved). Contrast: the dot-CALL form 'List.member(args)' DOES resolve in a sort body (WI-418's Coll.contains test) but has no value-position equivalent for eta. The WI-420 requirement-capture mechanism is already IN PLACE and would handle abstract eta once the value reference resolves: Value::OpRef carries its dispatch dict (evaluated at mint in the eta-site frame, installed into the callee frame at apply); build_concrete_dispatch_dict forwards an abstract dep via a Strategy-1 var_ref to the enclosing frame's __req_*; entries_cover now uses same_symbol (WI-420 bug fix) so a qualified-vs-short spec symbol matches. FIX DIRECTION: (a) make sort-body bare-name resolution fall back to the namespace's imports for VALUE-position refs (today only call/dot-dispatch resolves), and/or (b) parse a fully-qualified op path in value position as a single op symbol rather than a dot-access chain. ACCEPTANCE: a sort op can pass an external requires-op as a HOF arg; the abstract-eta probe (sort Box requires Eq[T]; operation has(b: Box, x: T) -> Bool = use_pair(member, x, xs)) typechecks + evals true/false; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-420"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T15:59:25Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 0bbc5f1 (full fix). Value::OpRef now carries an Option<RequirementHandle> dict (mirrors Closure.requirements): the typer's attach_eta_dispatch_dict resolves the op's requirement dispatch dict at the eta site and attaches CallClass::EtaOpRef; eval's reduce_var evaluates it IN THE ETA-SITE FRAME at mint and the apply arm installs it (expand_dispatching_dict) into the callee frame instead of forwarding the caller's. THREE cases: (1) CONCRETE cross-sort (member(2,[1,2,3])) — unify eta-arrow PARAMS vs the expected arrow (arrow_parts, concrete-first) to pin the element, build_concrete_dispatch_dict resolves Eq[Int] from fact — WORKS end-to-end (the original crash, fixed). (2) SAME-SORT — capture the enclosing frame's __req_self via var_ref — WORKS (this was a SOUNDNESS HOLE /code-review caught: the same-sort guard first returned no dict → typecheck-clean eval crash; fixed + regression test wi420_eta_same_sort_captures_self_dict). (3) ABSTRACT cross-sort — machinery in place (dict forwards via a frame var_ref; also fixed a real entries_cover bug: it used != instead of same_symbol so a qualified-vs-short spec symbol failed to match) but UNREACHABLE today: an external op can't be referenced as a VALUE inside a sort body (only a dot-CALL) — filed WI-421. The conservative interim gate (1009baa) is removed. Tests: 3 eval (concrete/same-sort/lambda) + 3 typer (loads/curried-arrow-mismatch/requires-free). /code-review: read-only single pass, found the same-sort hole (fixed) + confirmed refcount/arity/same_symbol-no-overmatch sound. Full workspace suite green.", at: "2026-06-07T15:33:05Z", workitem: "WI-420", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RESOLVED via a2 (deliver). KEY FINDING: WI-421's blocker premise is FALSE. The abstract cross-sort requirement does NOT need the op referenced as a value -- it threads fine through the lambda idiom: use_pred(lambda e -> List.member(e, xs), x) inside sort Box requires Eq[T]. The Closure snapshots Box's dispatching dict (__req_self/__req_eq) at construction and reinstalls it at apply (the sound capture path WI-420 contrasts against bare OpRef), so member's eq(head,x) resolves against the abstract Eq[T] evidence Box supplies. VERIFIED typecheck + eval (present 2-in-[1,2,3] -> true; absent 9 -> false). CAPABILITY MATRIX: bare-op eta works for concrete + same-sort (WI-420); abstract works via lambda -- so bare-eta-for-abstract is the ONLY gap and it is PURE SUGAR, never more powerful (only terser, and only for a multi-arg op passed whole). DECISION (user, a2): accept the lambda + QUALIFIED-dot idiom as the answer; bare-op eta inside a sort body is deliberately NOT implemented. TEST: wi421_abstract_requires_op_via_lambda_idiom_evals (eval_test.rs) pins it -- guards the Closure abstract-requirement-capture path. SECONDARY FINDINGS: (1) even a bare CALL member(e,xs) (non-dot) fails inside a sort body -- import List.{member} creates a short-vs-qualified AMBIGUITY (candidates [member, anthill.prelude.List.member]) AND value-position resolution does not fall back to imports; the reliable idiom is lambda + qualified List.member, with NO import of member. (2) the WI-420 OpRef-dict machinery + entries_cover same_symbol fix stay in place and correct for the concrete/same-sort eta cases. DEFERRED to its own proposal (NOT folded here): a first-class summon-style dictionary / explicit evidence value -- cheap on the runtime side (Value::Requirement already exists) but needs an apply-with-dict companion (dict params are compiler-inserted, no source slot) + a coherence/named-impl decision.", at: "2026-06-07T15:59:25Z", workitem: "WI-421", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-422",
  description: "Loader/resolution: a selectively-imported operation referenced by BARE short name resolves AMBIGUOUSLY inside a sort scope that has `requires Spec[T]`. Surfaced (not caused) by WI-421. SYMPTOM: with `import anthill.prelude.List.{member}`, a bare `member` reference inside `sort Box requires Eq[T]` emits `warning: ambiguous symbol 'member' ... candidates [member, anthill.prelude.List.member]`; remap_symbol's Ambiguous arm (load.rs ~4405) then interns a FRESH unresolved symbol, so the bare reference cascades into a hard `expected resolved name, got unresolved` / `unknown functor` failure downstream. AmbiguousSymbol is itself non-load-blocking (load.rs is_load_blocking) but the cascade is fatal on the bare path. TRIGGER (narrowed empirically via minimal probes -- each toggle independently makes it CLEAN): the warning fires ONLY when ALL of (1) the enclosing sort declares `requires Spec[T]`, (2) the op is referenced by bare selectively-imported short name (not a qualified dot form), and (3) the reference is in a NESTED scope (sort/op body), not namespace level. Removing the `requires`, qualifying the ref as `List.member`, OR moving the ref to namespace level each independently removes the ambiguity. So a requires-induced parent-scope linkage re-surfaces a SECOND reachable `member` during the nested parent-walk (intern.rs resolve_in_scope_recursive ~300-352, which collects matches across eligible parents and reports >1 distinct symbol as Ambiguous). The bare candidate renders as `member` (candidate_names returns the bare `name` for an Unresolved symbol, qualified_name for a Resolved one); its exact identity is NOT yet root-caused (needs a debug build) -- candidates to check: List's companion `rule member` head functor, Set.member, or a globally-interned `member` key. INVESTIGATE that first. IMPACT: a user following the obvious `import List.{member}` pattern inside a requires-bearing sort hits a confusing ambiguity + failure with a non-obvious fix. WORKAROUND (the WI-421 a2 blessed idiom, already pinned by wi421_abstract_requires_op_via_lambda_idiom_evals in eval_test.rs): use the qualified dot form `List.member(...)`, wrapped in a lambda for HOF use, with NO `member` import -- loads warning-clean. NOT a blocker for WI-421 (closed via a2). FIX DIRECTION: a selective-import alias resolvable in an ancestor scope should take precedence over (or dedupe against) a symbol re-surfaced only via the requires-induced scope linkage, so a bare selectively-imported name resolves unambiguously inside a requires-bearing nested scope. ACCEPTANCE: `sort Box requires Eq[T]` with `import anthill.prelude.List.{member}` can reference bare `member` inside an op body without an ambiguity warning or an unresolved failure (resolving to List.member); a regression test pins it; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-07T16:45:54Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-07 (65da79b, rebased onto WI-068 Int->Int64; green 1556). Root cause was NOT yet-root-caused at file time: the phantom 'member' candidate is the loader-internal reflection FACT FUNCTOR 'member' (emits member(name,kind,parent) facts), registered as a degenerate-qualified GLOBAL LOCAL via define(). 'requires Eq[T]' opens Box->Eq->prelude->_global, bypassing the namespace's member->List.member import alias and resurfacing the global member as a rival. Fix: new SymbolTable::define_qualified_only (by_qualified_name only, never in any scope locals); the 3 kernel fact-functors (member/meta/SortAlias) moved to it; member additionally got the proper name anthill.reflect.member (user steer: 'if we emit in db member, do it as a fully qualified name'). Consumers query member facts by SORT (Member) + positional args, never the functor symbol, so the rename is transparent (make_name_term interns, doesn't scope-resolve). /code-review max-effort (2 finders + sweep): 0 bugs; one reverted the fix and confirmed the test fails with the exact cascade. ALTITUDE FINDING (both reviewers, NOT WI-422 scope, NOT fixed): KERNEL_META_SORTS (Sort/Entity/Fact/Rule/Operation/Namespace/Requirement/Description/Constraint/Member) remain bare GLOBAL LOCALS via define() with the structurally-identical leak — a user-defined sort whose name collides with a kernel meta-sort, selectively imported into a requires-bearing sort, hits the same ambiguity. Lower-risk (PascalCase kernel names rarely user-shadowed; trigger more contrived than the real List.member case) and possibly user/reflection-facing (delocalizing needs verifying no legit bare scope-ref; fact indexing is safe since make_name_term interns). Two closes: (a) delocalize the meta-sorts too, or (b) the DEEPER fix — make resolve_in_scope_recursive prefer a nearer/import-alias match over a requires-reached global local (changes the general 'collect-all-then-flag-ambiguous' policy). Candidate follow-up WI pending user decision.", at: "2026-06-07T16:46:21Z", workitem: "WI-422", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-424",
  description: "Stdlib: lift `map` and `find` onto `Iterable` (the shared read interface) so EVERY iterable — List, Stream, a future non-Stream Set — gets them, not only Streams. TODAY (WI-064) `map` lives on MappedStream only and `find` on Stream; both reach a List solely via List-provides-Stream. GOAL: `Iterable.find(c: C, pred) -> Option[Element] effects E` and `Iterable.map(c: C, f) -> Stream[Dst, E]` as real MEMBERS of Iterable deriving via `iterator(c)`. DESIGN (probed 2026-06-07, reverted to clean): `find` in BOTH Stream and Iterable is FINE — ops are sort-scoped, NO definition-time collision; only an UNqualified call where both names are in scope on a List (provides both) is ambiguous, avoidable by qualify/import. Intended layering: keep `Stream.find` as the direct engine (recurses on splitFirst, element/effect thread via the receiver type, WI-380); `Iterable.find` is the general one delegating `Stream.find(iterator(c), pred)`. Same for map: keep the `mapped` carrier + its splitFirst in MappedStream, expose `Iterable.map` = `mapped(iterator(c), f)`. BLOCKER (the real one, NOT the collision): the ABSTRACT-CARRIER iterator-walk. In an Iterable member body, `iterator(c)` where `c: C` returns `Stream[?_, ?_]` — it does NOT carry Iterable's own Element/E — so neither a delegating nor a recursive Iterable.find/map can be typed. Probe errors: `s.annotation: expected Stream[E=E, T=Element], got Stream[E=?_, T=?_]` (element+effect do not thread in the abstract body) and `<op>.effects: expected declared [], got undeclared effect ?_` at concrete List call sites. The CONCRETE walk IS delivered (`collect(List.iterator(xs))` -> List[Int64], wi368_iterator_threading_test, via WI-379/380/393); the ABSTRACT walk is not. THIS WI is the stdlib CONSUMER / ACCEPTANCE of the path-dependent PROJECTION cluster, which per `anthill-todo list --tag typing` (2026-06-07) is the ACTIVE FRONT of the typing sequence: WI-397 is `<- next`, then WI-398 -> WI-399 -> WI-400 -> WI-376 -> WI-374, with WI-424 sitting immediately after as the consumer (NOT parked, NOT deprioritized — that was a stale read; the live sequence is authoritative). The ELEMENT half needs WI-376 path-dependent projection types (`iterator(c) -> Stream[c.T]`; design in docs/design/path-dependent-types.md, status:design / unratified); the EFFECT half is WI-374's stated abstract-carrier-walk acceptance (`walk(c: C) ... = collect(iterator(c))` stays effect-polymorphic). NUANCE: WI-374's example op carries `where C provides Iterable` (an EXTERNAL op); here find/map are MEMBERS of Iterable (c: C is Iterable's own carrier, iterator a sibling op) — same underlying need but the member framing is not currently tested. PROBE ARTIFACTS for the implementer (all reverted): convert `fact Iterable[List[T], T]` -> `provides Iterable[C=List[T], Element=T, E={}]` (write the pure effect, like `provides Stream[T,{}]`) and `fact Iterable[C=Stream, Element=T]` -> `provides Iterable[C=Stream, Element=T, E=E]`; qualified-path + type-args (`Stream.find[Elem=...]`) does NOT parse — pin via a typed `let s: Stream[T=Element, E=E] = iterator(c)`, which then exposes `iterator(c) = Stream[?_,?_]` as the core gap. ACCEPTANCE: `Iterable.find` + `Iterable.map` defined as members deriving via iterator; an acceptance test calls find/map on a List (via List-provides-Iterable) AND ideally a non-Stream Iterable, typecheck + EVAL green; cli/parse.anthill's `find` imported from Iterable; existing wi064/wi368/wi357/wi365 + full anthill-core stay green. Rust/stdlib (acceptance) + typer behind it is WI-374/WI-376.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-376"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-10T02:08:51Z"))

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-424")

fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-425")
fact Feedback(content: "BUILT then REVERTED to green 2026-06-07 — blocked on the inserted prereq WI-425 (discrim opaque-head value-fact keying). The full Node-carrier approach was implemented and COMPILES clean; reverted only because the test panics at LOAD on WI-425's gap. RE-APPLY after WI-425 lands (the reverted diff was clean). What was built: (1) `TypeNode::ExprCarried { value: TypeChild, member: TypeChild }` variant (node_occurrence.rs) threaded through every exhaustive match — drain_type_node / map (reassemble) / collect vars / type_node_eq / type_node_to_term / substitute_ref_syms_occ, term_view type_node_head/keys/named (head \"ExprCarried\" arity 2; value→Node receiver, member→ground Ref), print write_type_node, typing occ_contains_var. (2) `KnowledgeBase::make_expr_carried_occ(receiver_occ, member, span, owner)` builder (mod.rs, the occ twin of make_expr_carried) + `constructors_of_sort(sort_sym)` (enumerates entity_parent; returned functors == entity_field_types keys — VERIFIED: name_to_sort_term builds the entity_parent key as Fn{remap_name(e.name)}, the same symbol entity_field_types is keyed by). (3) Loader (load.rs try_expr_carried_projection, the segs>2 arm): build the receiver value path segs[0..n-1] as a DotApply chain over Expr::Ref(head), wrap via make_expr_carried_occ → TypeChild::Node. (4) Eliminator (typing.rs eliminate_type_projections): a top-level Value::Node ExprCarried → resolve_compound_projection → resolve_receiver_path_type (Ref→arg_types[s]; DotApply{base,name}→resolve base then resolve_field_type) → project_type_member. resolve_field_type: sort_functor_of_view + constructors_of_sort + entity_field_types(field) + build_pattern_subst(recv_ty, sort) + walk_pattern_field_type_deep — the design §1 step-2 subst. Concrete compound projection is eliminated at the CALL site (like single-ref s.T); abstract receiver stays the existing loud error; nested-in-denoted-Node stays the existing loud error. (5) Test wi397_compound_projection_test.rs (wired in wi_tests.rs): return-type compound projection — getT(s: Wrapper) -> s.cell.T called on Wrapper[P = Inner[T = String]] resolves to String (positive); wrong declared return (Int64) rejected; missing field (s.nope.T) loud error. BLOCKER DETAIL: at load, getT's OperationInfo VALUE-fact embeds the DotApply receiver; discrim insert_walk panics on its Opaque head (\"value-fact keying unimplemented\") — exactly WI-425. The single-ref l.T avoids it (receiver = Ref, has a discrim key). NOTE: WI-397 is left Claimed-but-BLOCKED (the anthill-todo CLI can't unclaim — WI-395); the next loop run picks WI-425 (now the `next` ticket).", at: "2026-06-07T19:44:15Z", workitem: "WI-397", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RESOLVED 2026-06-07 by making DotApply STRUCTURAL (the real fix, per user) instead of the WI-425 opaque-keying / WI-370 custom-unification detour. DotApply was Opaque only by OMISSION — the `_ => ViewHead::Opaque` catch-all in occ_head; the term_view comment already anticipated the arm (WI-278). Now occ_head/occ_pos_child/occ_named_child/occ_named_keys (term_view.rs) map DotApply to its `dot_apply(name, receiver[, args])` reflect term twin, so a fact embedding a DotApply (the compound-projection receiver `s.cell`) indexes into the discrim tree like any term — NO opaque panic, NO custom unification needed. WI-425 DELETED as obsolete (its premise — handle opaque heads — was moot; the general opaque-head-in-fact case stays WI-370). Re-applied the Node carrier: TypeNode::ExprCarried variant threaded through node_occurrence/term_view/print/typing; make_expr_carried_occ + constructors_of_sort; loader builds the DotApply receiver chain; eliminator resolve_compound_projection/resolve_receiver_path_type/resolve_field_type (field type via constructors_of_sort + entity_field_types + build_pattern_subst + walk_pattern_field_type_deep). Tests: wi397_compound_projection_test (3: threads field+member to String / wrong-return rejected / missing-field loud) green; dot-dispatch wi279/281/283 (28) green — structural DotApply did not regress the typer dot engine (it runs in the typer, not match_view); full anthill-core 1255 passed / 0 failed. Dep on WI-425 removed; WI-397 depends only on WI-379 (delivered).", at: "2026-06-07T21:41:42Z", workitem: "WI-397", author: "user")
fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-425")
fact Feedback(content: "/code-review (high effort) DONE 2026-06-07: 3 fixes applied on top of the delivered code. (1) resolve_field_type (typing.rs) now collects the field type from ALL constructors and is ORDER-INDEPENDENT — was: returned the first ctor from a non-deterministic HashMap iteration, so a multi-variant sort with a same-named field of DIFFERING types resolved non-deterministically; now agreement across variants is required and a divergence is a LOUD error. (2) type_node_to_term ExprCarried arm rebuilds the Fn faithfully instead of silently dropping the member projection in release (loud-over-silent). (3) type_display_name_occ renders ExprCarried as `a.b.M` not `?`. Tests: wi397 now 5 (added uniform-multi-ctor-resolves + divergent-multi-ctor-loud-error); full anthill-core 1257 passed / 0 failed. DEFERRED (latent, per user steer): the DotApply structural view is not yet ISOMORPHIC to its dot_apply term twin (occ_head arity-2 field-form / flattened method form vs the loader-emitted arity-3 {receiver, name, args:List}) — filed as a follow-up. NUMBER NOTE: that follow-up is the CURRENT WI-425, a RECYCLED number — the EARLIER WI-425 (\"discrim opaque-head value-fact keying\") referenced in my prior feedback above was DELETED as obsolete (we made DotApply structural instead), and the tracker reused 425 for the isomorphism follow-up. The divergence is latent because nothing crosses a DotApply occurrence with a dot_apply term in the discrim tree today.", at: "2026-06-08T04:31:13Z", workitem: "WI-397", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN REALIZATION CHOSEN 2026-06-09 (user): eager let-alias, NOT sigma-tracked receiver vars. Documented in docs/design/path-dependent-types.md NEW sec.4.1: substrate has no union-find (sigma=VarId->Value; let y=z stored as y->type(z), not the alias y==z), so realize as delta-grounding at env-bearing sites (WI-399 eager elimination IS delta) + structural zeta in unify_types REPLACING the WI-399 ExprCarried guard line + receiver aliasing canonicalized eagerly at stable let (keeps unify_types env-free per WI-399). WI-400 co-delivers WI-376 abstract-stays-poly (abstract receiver in project_type_member must RETURN a rigid neutral, not the current loud error -- precondition for any neutral to exist for zeta). Base scope binder-free; union-find generality is the deferred flexible/rule-body case (resolver delay). Test matrix in sec.4.1. ALSO sec.5.1: value-position projection (let x=[1,2,3].T) is the generic-dot TypeProjection arm -- separate near-term follow-on, wire project_type_member into the DotApply frame off recv.ty -> anthill.prelude.Type value; not yet a WI.", at: "2026-06-09T06:20:43Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "user")
fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-427")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT A DELIVERED 2026-06-09 (391a8bf, green 1579): the MANIFEST body-site half. check_operation_bodies now discharges projection PARAM types (k: s.cell.T) against the OTHER params' DECLARED types before binding into the body env (peer of check_apply_iter/WI-398 which uses ARGUMENT types) -- ORDER-INDEPENDENT fixpoint (forward+reverse declaration order both work, like the call-site). A manifest receiver delta-grounds (k: String); closes BIDIR-3b. BONUS: op-type-param-through-projection bodies now work too (idElem[X](s: Wrapper[P=Inner[T=X]], k: s.cell.T) -> X = k). /code-review xhigh fixed 2 findings (order-dependence->fixpoint; removed a mis-constructed #[ignore] anchor). REMAINING CORE (the soundness-critical part, separate pass -- CHECKPOINT before starting, it CASCADES into delivered WI-376 tests): (1) project_type_member abstract receiver -> RETURN a rigid neutral instead of the loud 'not yet supported' error (= un-park WI-376 abstract-stays-poly; needs the abstract receiver's type to DECLARE the member via a bound/requires, the declared-interface-member reading); (2) the sigma-equality zeta arm in unify_types (structural equality of two neutral ExprCarried heads, REPLACING the WI-399 return-false guard); (3) eager-let-alias receiver canonicalization (the Scala let y=z divergence, the §5.1 increment). Acceptance: §4.1 test matrix (§1 typechecks / non-decomposition / let-alias / abstract-stays-poly). The abstract anchor + WI-376 test updates are written WITH that core.", at: "2026-06-09T07:25:10Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT B DELIVERED 2026-06-09 (abstract->neutral + the zeta arm; the soundness core). project_type_member now returns ProjResult::{Grounded,Neutral}: an abstract projection forms a rigid NEUTRAL instead of erroring when the member is declared on the receiver's interface -- a concrete sort's type-param (bare List l.T), OR a member lent to an abstract type-var receiver by its DECLARING SORT's requires Spec[param] bound (s.provider.K via State requires DataProvider[P]); a genuinely-missing member stays a LOUD error (co-delivers WI-376 abstract-stays-poly). The declaring sort is THREADED from resolve_field_type (the abstract type-param opens to a fresh var named '_' so its sort/requires can't be recovered from the var alone). zeta = expr_carried_zeta, shared by unify_types AND BOTH types_compatible (subtype) dispatchers (the return-type check uses types_compatible, NOT unify_types) -- replaces the WI-399 return-false guard; two neutrals equal iff same member off structurally-equal receivers; non-injective (distinct receivers stay distinct, never forced equal). occurrence_structural_eq + display gained a DotApply arm (compound receiver s.provider). Body-site loop is now a true fixpoint (binds stable neutrals). Tests: wi400 abstract_projection_path_identity_within_op / _distinct_receivers_rejected / _missing_member_is_loud; updated wi376 projection_bare_receiver_stays_poly + wi399 missing_member_off_abstract. Full workspace GREEN 1582. /code-review high: no reachable soundness hole. REMAINING (WI-400 still OPEN): (3) eager-let-alias canonicalization (increment C, the let y=z => y.T==z.T Scala divergence). DEFERRED (sound, documented in path-dependent-types.md §4.1): cross-call neutral threading (relay->l.T=peek(l) keeps callee's receiver symbol -- incompleteness not unsoundness); carrier-precise requires matching (whole-chain scan over-accepts on multi-param multi-requires sorts -- runtime-sound, uncallable signature); flexible/rule-body receiver delay. SEPARATE CONCERN (NOT WI-400): §1 full body s.provider.hasKey(k) needs abstract spec-op DISPATCH through requires -- probed: projection now forms the neutral, residual error is 'unknown functor' at the hasKey dispatch.", at: "2026-06-09T09:45:09Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT C DELIVERED 2026-06-09 (eager let-alias, the let y=z => y.M==z.M Scala divergence) -- completes WI-400's core (B+C). TypingEnv gains receiver_aliases: Symbol->Vec<Symbol> (a let-bound name -> its canonical receiver PATH); recorded at LetAfterValue via stable_receiver_path (only a STABLE var/field-access path aliases; let y=f() does not -- mints its own neutral). bind_receiver_alias de-aliases the head at record time (one hop) so transitive let w=y resolves to y's target. At the let-ANNOTATION elimination site (visit_type Let arm), canonicalize_projection_receivers rewrites a projection whose receiver head is aliased to the canonical path BEFORE elimination (build_projection_from_segs: single-seg term make_expr_carried / compound Node make_expr_carried_occ); unify_types stays env-free (WI-399 invariant) -- canonicalization at the site only. TWO enabling fixes: stable_receiver_path reads Expr::VarRef (the form a param/let reference takes, not just Ref/Ident); loader try_expr_carried_projection is now LOCAL-AWARE (consults lookup_local_name before resolve_in_scope, mirroring remap_symbol) so a projection off a let-LOCAL receiver resolves its head at all (was 'unresolved name y.K'). Tests (wi400): let_alias_canonicalizes_receiver, _distinct_receiver_rejected, let_unstable_value_does_not_alias, let_alias_cleared_on_unstable_rebind. /code-review high (2 finder pairs) found ONE CONFIRMED SOUNDNESS BUG (false accept): re-binding an aliased name to an UNSTABLE value left the stale alias (let y=p; let y=f(); let m:y.K=k wrongly accepted) -- FIXED: LetAfterValue now CLEARS the alias on an unstable rebind + bind_receiver_alias clears on self-alias; regression test added. Full workspace GREEN 1586. WI-400 CORE COMPLETE. DEFERRED follow-ons (all SOUND -- no false accept, at most over-rejection; documented path-dependent-types.md §4.1): flexible/rule-body receiver delay (the union-find-over-sigma generality, §4.1 explicitly scopes BASE WI-400 to op-signatures+immutable-let, NO union-find); nested let-alias canonicalization (top-level annotation only); value-position field access let y=s.provider (§5.1 INC-1b, separate); cross-call neutral threading; carrier-precise requires matching. SEPARATE CONCERN (NOT WI-400): §1 full body s.provider.hasKey(k) = abstract spec-op DISPATCH through requires.", at: "2026-06-09T10:33:15Z", workitem: "WI-400", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-09 (the cross-sort provider divergent-member half; abstract-stays-poly already co-delivered by WI-400 inc. B). PROBE PASS first (verify-before-coding): scoped what WI-400 left -- abstract receiver stays-poly works for BOTH the DataProvider/requires same-name shape AND the Iterable spec-member shape (an abstract carrier c:C with requires Iterable keeps c.Element a neutral); the SOLE gap was item 5: a DIVERGENT member at a CONCRETE receiver (l.Element on a List, where List provides Iterable[List[T], T] so Iterable's Element maps to List's T) errored 'List has no member Element' because project_type_member only checked List's own type-params. FIX: project_via_provided_spec in project_type_member's concrete arm (after the direct-type-param check, before the no-member error) -- enumerate the receiver sort's provided specs (provided_spec_base_syms, mirroring find_spec_op_for_provided_sort), for a spec that declares the member read the provides binding via the EXISTING provider_spec_view_bindings (Iterable.Element -> List.T term), then GROUND it against the receiver's type-args (build_pattern_subst + walk_pattern_field_type_deep, same as field-type resolution). EFFECT members EXCLUDED (WI-396: l.E stays a loud error, never silently {} via 'List provides Stream[T, {}]' -- guard skips an EffectsRows-headed binding). /code-review high (1 finder, 6 angles) confirmed the single-ref case sound; FIXED its top finding -- the Grounded/Neutral decision now uses the DEEP resolved_type_is_ground (was head-only is_type_param_value), so a structured binding still resting on an unbound carrier param (Element=Pair[A,B] on a bare receiver) stays NEUTRAL instead of a Grounded type that would absorb demand. Tests (wi376_projection_test): divergent_provider_member_grounds_concrete, _wrong_return_rejected, abstract_carrier_spec_member_stays_poly. Full workspace GREEN 1589. WI-376 acceptance MET (concrete l.T threading + concrete/abstract split via the spec interface); deps WI-379/398/399/400 all delivered; the 4 spun-out seams WI-396/397/398/399 all delivered. DEFERRED latent gaps (review, NONE triggered by current stdlib, all documented): (a) an effect PASSTHROUGH-var provides binding (provides Spec[E=E]) on a sort with no own E declaration slips the EffectsRows guard -> c.E becomes a neutral instead of the WI-396 loud error (needs effect-param classification machinery that doesn't exist); (b) first-provided-spec-wins across two specs declaring the same member with divergent mappings (left to a later disambiguation pass, per the comment); (c) provided_spec_base_syms uses same_symbol while provider_spec_view_bindings uses canonical_sort_sym -- a disagreement is a false-REJECT (sound, over-rejects), the two snapshots of the same facts should share one carrier predicate.", at: "2026-06-09T13:48:05Z", workitem: "WI-376", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-09: reject the ABSTRACTING (sealing) return -> the base model is escape-free (path-dependent-types.md §5). PROBE first confirmed the gap: seal(s: SubscriberStore) -> DataProvider = s loaded clean (admitted via WI-344 provider-admissibility at the return). FIX: abstracting_return_error(kb, body_ty, ret_ty, op_sym), called in check_operation_bodies in the SUCCESS branch of the return-conformance check (after types_compatible passes, so never fires on a plain mismatch). Flags when: (1) both sides have a base sort (sort_functor_of_view), (2) DIFFERENT base sorts (same-sort = no new abstraction, input-rooted -> allowed), (3) sort_provides_admissibly(body_sort, ret_sort) (the concrete->bare-spec provider upcast; entity bodies recurse to the parent sort), (4) the return leaves >=1 of ret_sort's type-params UNBOUND (bare OR partial manifest escapes per §5; a full manifest DataProvider[K=String] / Stream[T=Elem,E={}] binds them all -> admitted, members root at the op's inputs/type-params). Diagnostic names the unbound member(s). SUPERSEDES WI-344's provider-admissibility AT THE RETURN position (the bare form was the escape) -- WI-344 admissibility STAYS at the ARGUMENT position (the requires input dual, untouched). CASCADE: flipped typing_test::operation_return_accepts_value_whose_sort_provides_spec -> operation_return_rejects_abstracting_provider_upcast (the WI-344 test that asserted the now-forbidden acceptance; full suite confirmed ONLY that one test relied on bare-return admissibility -- no stdlib/production code does, stdlib iterator uses the manifest Stream[Elem,{}]). Tests: wi401_escape_free_return_test (abstracting_return_is_rejected + same_sort/concrete/type_param/manifest allowed). Full workspace GREEN 1594. /code-review high (1 finder, 6 angles): NO soundness hole (every escape flagged: seal, transitive multi-hop, entity-body, partial manifest; real stdlib upcasts survive via manifest returns). Fixed its top finding -- the diagnostic now names the actually-unbound members (was a misleading 'bare spec' message on a partial manifest). DEFERRED/by-design (review, all low/latent): a requires/refines-based upcast to a member-bearing spec is also gated (design-consistent -- the binding is still erased); an alias-return (sort MyProvider = DataProvider) isn't alias-resolved in abstracting_return_error but is currently masked by types_compatible also rejecting it (the two sites must stay in lockstep); extract_type_param matches members by short name (fragile under a short-name collision, no stdlib trigger). UNBLOCKS WI-402 (ensures-manifest translucent returns = the admit-form carved into this gate).", at: "2026-06-09T15:45:35Z", workitem: "WI-401", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REFRAME 2026-06-09 (design dialogue, user-steered). The original 'ensures result.K = String' form is a STRANGE form of ensures -- a static TYPE equation wearing a runtime VALUE-postcondition's clothes (ensures should relate values). DROP it. The clean design (user): 'ensures Spec[C]', SYMMETRIC TO 'requires Spec[C]'. requires Spec[C] = INPUT obligation (abstract carrier C must provide Spec; CALLER discharges via dict / req_insertion; body gets Spec's interface on C). ensures Spec[C] = OUTPUT guarantee (the result-carrier C provides Spec; the OPERATION discharges -- its body must produce such a C; the CALLER assumes it -- gets Spec's interface on the result for free; dict flows OUT, mirroring requires' dict-in). A member is pinned by BINDING it in the spec application (same vocabulary as requires): ensures Spec[C, K=String] manifests K (translucent); ensures Spec[C] leaves K abstract. KEY INSIGHT: ensures Spec[C] is an INTERFACE-ROOTED existential, so it is escape-free for the RIGHT reason -- §5's escape table middle row ('operation interface' root) NEVER escapes; the ensures clause names C in the signature (visible to the caller, usable only through Spec), so c.M is a neutral rooted at the op interface, NOT a hidden local. This means the existential return stops being §5's deferred 'deliberately-let-it-escape' opt-in -- controlled by ensures it is safe, and it IS precisely the 'made so by an ensures manifest' admit-form WI-401's rule already names. SPLIT: (a) BOUND members (ensures Spec[C, K=String]) = translucent manifest, fully concrete -- the SIMPLE case, reuses provider-admissibility + the WI-401 admit (small: needs binding-precise provider admissibility, the follow-up sort_provides_admissibly's own doc defers -- bare-value-vs-parameterized-spec); (b) UNBOUND members (ensures Spec[C]) = interface-rooted existential -- abstract C usable via Spec, the genuinely NEW capability (Rust -> impl Trait, ML abstract-type-with-signature), needs the discharge dual (op proves, caller assumes; dict-out-flow). PROBE FINDINGS (2026-06-09, before any code): the manifest return '-> DataProvider[K=String] = s' from a providing carrier does NOT typecheck today ('expected DataProvider[K=String], got SubscriberStore' -- provider-admissibility is bare<->bare only); the old 'ensures result.K = String' clause does not even load (name-resolution gap on the ensures atom); the bare '-> DataProvider' is correctly rejected by WI-401. OPEN SCOPE Qs: (1) near-term = the bound/manifest case only (binding-precise admissibility), defer the existential dict-out-flow? (2) carrier = result only, or result components (ensures Spec[result.a]) for multi-output ops? NO CODE WRITTEN YET -- design still being shaped; deps WI-401 (delivered).", at: "2026-06-09T17:03:15Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "WORKED EXAMPLE WRITTEN 2026-06-09: the KVStore factory (openStore(cfg) -> C ensures KVStore[C, K=String, V=Bytes] = if cfg.persistent then diskStore else memStore) is documented in docs/design/path-dependent-types.md §5 (new 'ensures Spec[C]' subsection), with the producer/consumer/eval typing story, the escape-freedom-via-interface-rooting argument, and the WI-287 branch-join-LUB connection (ensures Spec[C] is simultaneously the existential packaging AND the join's upper bound). DESIGNED, NOT BUILT -- no current driver (all active work is input-side requires / concrete). First real driver = the anthill-todo PLUGGABLE BACKEND (examples/github-todo/docs/pluggable-backend.md), scheduled AFTER WI-009; WI-402 implementation rides that. WI-402 stays Open (designed + deferred).", at: "2026-06-09T17:14:20Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REALIZATION RULE DECIDED 2026-06-09 (user-steered session): WI-403's target is the WI-002 KB-driven full mapper (proposal 029 anthill-rust-gen), NOT the bootstrap parse-IR codegen (frozen per 029; today it silently strips the receiver and emits s.K as bare K -- spec now declares a projection reaching bootstrap must fail loudly). Decision: spec-sort members lower to Rust ASSOCIATED TYPES (forced by path-dependence: delta projects THE manifest member off the receiver type = functional-member reading = type K; trait generics would be the multi-instantiation reading under which s.K is ambiguous). Lowering forms: within-sort s.K -> Self::K; cross-sort ungrounded -> receiver lifts to a named generic, fn check<S: KVStore>(s: &S, k: S::K); partial manifest -> equality bound S: KVStore<K = String>; member sharing -> the ticket's lift fn merge<K, A: KVStore<K = K>, B: KVStore<K = K>>; concrete receiver delta-grounds before codegen. Data sorts keep generics (enums have no associated types). provides/fact bindings become impl type K = String; items (2.13 'bindings ignored' no longer holds for spec-sort impls in the full mapper). NORMATIVE: docs/rust-forward-mapping.md sec.2.14 (+ sec.2.6 mapper split, summary table); design closure: docs/design/path-dependent-types.md sec.5.2 + seam-map row. Ticket RE-POINTED onto WI-002 and LEFT OPEN: closes when the WI-002 emitter implements sec.2.14.", at: "2026-06-09T17:58:39Z", workitem: "WI-403", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "SCOPE BREADCRUMB 2026-06-09: the full-mapper emitter must implement docs/rust-forward-mapping.md sec.2.14 (WI-403's path-dependent lowering rule, decided): spec-sort members -> Rust ASSOCIATED TYPES (data sorts keep generics); ungrounded s.K -> S::K off the receiver lifted to a named generic; manifest members -> equality bounds KVStore<K = String>; provides/fact bindings -> impl type K = ... items. WI-403 depends_on WI-002 and stays open until the emitter realizes the rule.", at: "2026-06-09T17:58:51Z", workitem: "WI-002", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-10 (daed654 + review fixes 5be108b, full workspace 1600 green). DEP EDGE WI-374 REMOVED before claiming — authoritative per expansion-during-unification.md §8 ('WI-374 is a convenience and threads nothing, so nothing load-bearing may depend on it') and proven empirically: the member framing needed NO bare-ref expansion. WHAT LANDED — Stdlib: Iterable.find (delegates qualified Stream.find(iterator(c), pred) — qualification REQUIRED, the WI-411 short-name self-dispatch hazard) + Iterable.map[Dst] (= mapped(iterator(c), f), the lazy carrier); List/Stream Iterable provisions rewritten fact→provides WRITING E ({} / E) per the ticket's probe artifacts; cli/parse.anthill imports find from Iterable (inline lambdas still type — element pinned by the provision). Typer, 3 gaps closed: (A) BODY — WI-392 rigidification EXTENDED to the enclosing sort's params + same-sort sibling-call seeding of those rigids into the call subst (check_apply_iter); the Var::Rigid asymmetry forces the binding direction (a-side Global binds first in unify, so without rigids the link dies in the call-local subst — plan (b) 'exempt the unconstrained check' was designed first and REJECTED for exactly this). (B) CONCRETE SITE — carrier-param receiver (find(c: C): receiver typed as the spec's own carrier param, which self_receiver_param_index deliberately skips): classified via provision_binds_param_to_carrier (the provision must bind THAT param to a carrier application — distinguishes carrier from element params), grounds Element/E incl. ground rows at the WI-367 early-bind site. (C) EVAL — resolve_spec_op_target_by_value falls back to carrier_param_receiver_for_values, gated on the SAME provision predicate so typer/eval classifications cannot disagree. Plus: build_dep_projection projects an EffectsRuntime kind-anchor dep as a synthetic structural leaf (construct_requirement(EffectsRuntime, [])) — without it require_complete dicts abort on the un-projectable anchor and the WI-418-forwarded var_ref(__req_effectsruntime) read dies 'unbound in requirement position' at eval (surfaced only now because Stream-internal calls are same-sort/inherit; Iterable.find→Stream.find is the first cross-sort delegating body). SEMANTIC TIGHTENING (intentional, review-verified): a member body calling a SIBLING op at a concrete element type (first(1,2) where first(a: T, b: T)) is now REJECTED — correct parametricity (Scala rejects the same; the WI-392 semantics extended to sort params); previously accepted by leniency. KNOWN DEFERRED (review findings, none triggered by current code): (1) half-rigid world — pattern destructure on a bare-typed scrutinee still yields CANONICAL flexible sort-param vars inside a body whose signature is rigid (pre-existing leniency, now coexisting; the deeper chokepoint fix belongs to the WI-374/392 follow-up space); (2) rule/law bodies on a sort don't get the sibling seeding (rule typing is its own world); (3) a third-party fact-form provision (fact Iterable[MyVec[T], T], no written E) gets a LOUD ?_ leak at an Iterable.find call site — migration = write the provides form with E; (4) EffectsRuntime synthetic leaf would need revisiting if effects ever become runtime-dispatched evidence (proposal 047 / handler discharge); (5) Iterable.map needs explicit [Dst] at call sites (the WI-275 two-phase remainder, same as MappedStream.map); (6) fact→provides drops the bare resolver-queryable Iterable fact (same WI-387 precedent as Stream's provision — reflect provides()/refines() read SortProvidesInfo, unaffected); (7) a MappedStream value passed as Iterable.find's receiver at EVAL would miss iterator (sort_ops_lookup is direct, no provider-hop) — not exercised; one-hop fallback if it surfaces.", at: "2026-06-10T02:08:51Z", workitem: "WI-424", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-428",
  description: "Typer+loader: RigidTypeProjection -- the TYPE-receiver projection (P.Key / MemStore.Key / Storage.Key sugar), the type-keyed sibling of ExprCarried. Design: path-dependent-types.md sec.5.3 (decided 2026-06-10 w/ user). FORM: RigidTypeProjection(requires, var, member) -- 'requires' = the CANONICAL bound application (named-sorted; positional application is sugar for names), NOT the bare spec symbol, so two same-spec bounds over distinct bindings stay distinct identities (type-side twin of WI-419); 'var' = the carrier's actual type-var TERM (+ source name for display), so delta-on-binding is an ordinary sigma walk -- instantiation grounds the projection through project_type_member with no bespoke machinery, and cross-call neutral threading holds for free for this head; 'member' = the spec's declared param NAME (identity by name, never position). Strictly (requires, member) is the identity; var is recoverable as the carrier binding, kept for display + the WI-403 lift. FORMATION (rigid by construction -- only the stuck case is ever stored): (1) delta at formation: a manifest receiver (MemStore.Key, a bound alias) grounds immediately, never stored; (2) delta THROUGH the bound: a member the bound application binds grounds through it (requires Storage[P, Key = String] => P.Key = String); only bound-OPEN members form the projection; (3) a member the spec does not declare = LOUD error. Well-formed by construction -- no env needed to validate (contrast ExprCarried's threaded declaring-sort). ZETA: equal iff same member + same canonical application + carrier vars in the same sigma-class -- a CHECK, never a binding (non-injectivity unchanged). BARE-SPEC SUGAR: Storage.Key is NEVER a type by itself -- desugars at classification when exactly ONE carrier of Storage is in scope (value carrier -> ExprCarried(s, Key); type-param carrier -> RigidTypeProjection; inside the declaring sort = qualified spelling of bare Key); two carriers -> loud ambiguity error. REFLECT: new TypeExtractor entity in stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill (the self-hosted typer must case over neutrals). HOST: WI-403 becomes a transliteration -- (Convert[A=X,B=Y], X, M) -> <X as Convert<B=Y>>::M (carrier param -> Self, other bindings -> equality bounds, member name -> associated-type name). INVARIANT (sec.5.3 groundedness stratification): rigid neutrals are TYPING-TIME citizens only -- interface-rooted (escape-free, WI-401), never in asserted facts; runtime Type values stay ground (eval delta-grounds off the dynamic receiver); extract stays total.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-400"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-11T06:14:42Z"))

