fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-430")
fact Feedback(content: "Type-side twin filed 2026-06-10: WI-428 (RigidTypeProjection) stores the full CANONICAL bound application (not the bare spec symbol) precisely so two same-spec requires over distinct bindings stay distinct TYPE identities -- the projection-identity counterpart of this dict-forwarding ambiguity. WI-430 promotes the carrier-precision fix for the delivered ExprCarried neutral path. A fix here should keep the disambiguation rule aligned with theirs (identity = canonical application + member, carrier var by sigma-class).", at: "2026-06-10T20:38:32Z", workitem: "WI-419", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT A IMPLEMENTATION NOTES (2026-06-10, in progress): (1) FORMATION SPLIT loader-classify / typer-validate: the loader cannot read requires bounds (source-order: an op may precede the requires clause), so try_rigid_type_projection (load.rs) only CLASSIFIES -- param-head detection is 'the parent sort's type_params_of_sort contains the head short name' (NOT is_type_param, which reads the current scope's own params and does NOT see the enclosing sort's members from an op scope; discovered by probe), with the INNER self-named registration (ns.W.P.P, like anthill.prelude.List.List) normalized before the parent lookup; validation/delta runs in resolve_rigid_projection (typing.rs) at the elimination sites where requires_chain is complete. (2) TERM FORM v1: Fn{RigidTypeProjection, named:[(member, Ref(M)), (sort, Ref(declSort)), (var, Ref(subject))]} -- the requires-APPLICATION slot is DEFERRED-EQUIVALENT (multi-candidate = loud ambiguity error, so (sort, var, member) determines the bound; attach the application when multi-bound lands). sort==var is the concrete-head discriminator. (3) SUBJECT IDENTITY = SubjectKey: the param's ALIAS-VAR id (sort P = ? opens an alias var; the param's two symbol registrations AND the requires-binding spelling all share it), Sym(symbol) for non-alias sorts; ZETA compares member + decl sort + subject structurally. (4) walk_type_deep is OPAQUE at the projection head: the WI-392/424 body-site rigidify walk otherwise resolves the var child Ref(P) -> a FRESH rigid var, erasing the subject identity the carrier-precise lookup keys on (probe-discovered). Increment B (call-site delta-on-instantiation) must thread substitution through the eliminator EXPLICITLY instead. (5) DELTA-THROUGH-THE-BOUND fires ONLY for a MANIFEST (Sym-keyed) binding: the stored requires application is AUTO-COMPLETED -- every declared param carries a binding, unwritten ones as var-keyed placeholder refs to the spec's own param (Key = Storage.Key) -- so a var-keyed binding (placeholder or carrier C = P) keeps the projection NEUTRAL; cross-param delta (requires Convert[A = P, B = Q]: P.B -> Q) is conservatively Neutral too (sound, recorded). (6) normalize_ground_leaf: provides/spec bindings store plain sort names as NULLARY Fn{S} (name_to_sort_term), which is NOT the Ref(S) type shape -- grounded results are normalized (MemStore.Key was 'expected String, got String' before). DEFERRED (increment B+): call-site delta-on-instantiation (P.Key in a callee signature grounding at a concrete call -- needs sort-param binding at apply, the WI-392/424 seeding world); cross-call rigid threading; the requires-application slot; structured manifest bindings (Key = List[Int]); bare-spec sugar OUTSIDE the sort via unique-carrier desugar (the loud T#K error stands in). Tests: wi428_rigid_projection_test (11).", at: "2026-06-10T21:36:17Z", workitem: "WI-428", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REVIEW ROUND (2026-06-10, /code-review high: 5 finder angles + probe verification). FIXED in increment A: (a) qualified CHILD refs were hijacked by the concrete-head classifier -- 'Outer.Inner' (nested alias sort) and relative 'Enum.Entity' under an import got 'has no member' instead of resolving; FIX: a non-param child of the head sort resolves via by_qualified_name child lookup BEFORE projection classification (tests nested_child_sort_qualified_ref_resolves / qualified_enum_entity_ref_preserved). (b) The self-named-level normalization could strip a sort sharing its NAMESPACE's last segment (namespace app.Config / sort Config); FIX: logical_sort_qn strips only when the outer name maps to a Sort-kind symbol; helper shared by head+member sides. (c) ZETA compared subjects by raw term identity while the eliminator used SubjectKey; two registrations of one param would spuriously mismatch; FIX: zeta subject comparison via subject_key_of_term/subject_keys_equal + the loader stores the LOGICAL registration as subject. (d) The placeholder discriminator treated ANY var-keyed binding as bound-open, so a user-written binding to an OPAQUE nominal (Key = Token, sort Token = ?) wrongly stayed neutral (false reject, probe-verified); FIX: placeholder iff binding key == the SPEC'S OWN member-param key (spec_member_param_key); sibling-param bindings (Key = K) stay neutral EXPLICITLY (cross-param delta = increment B; grounding to the sibling's bare ref mis-compares against rigidified signature forms -- probe p8). (e) cleanup: dead error arm removed, normalize_ground_leaf folded onto normalize_spec_binding_type, error strings built lazily, parent-kind gate keeps the type_params_of_sort scan off namespace-parented heads. REMAINING OPEN SCOPE (ticket stays OPEN; review-confirmed, all sound -- over-rejection or silent-skip-in-unreached-positions, no false accept): (1) CALL-SITE delta-on-instantiation -- the ticket's 'delta-on-binding = ordinary sigma walk' is NOT how increment A landed: walk_type_deep is OPAQUE at the head (needed to protect subject identity from the rigidify walk), so a concrete call (w: Wrapper[P=MemStore]) does NOT ground the callee's P.Key -- surfaces as a plain type mismatch, not a not-yet-supported diagnostic; increment B must thread the subst through resolve_rigid_projection explicitly AND give zeta a sigma-class footing (distinct instantiations' neutrals currently compare by subject key alone -- fine while neutrals cannot cross calls, unsound once they can). (2) A projection in a position the typer never eliminates (entity field, fact/rule type slot) loads UNVALIDATED -- silent for typos that previously warned; this is WI-429's hard-error scope (validate stored projections post-load). (3) Neutral can bind an unconstrained inference var at a call (let x = ...) and escape into let-types/Frame.type_args -- increment B boundary guard. (4) sibling deep-walkers (substitute_ref_syms / substitute_spec_via_subst / canonicalize_goal_value) descend the projection's slots -- exact-Symbol keying makes collision unlikely today; align when increment B touches walking. (5) resolve_sort_alias SHORT-NAME fallback can key a subject to the wrong sort's alias var when exact-symbol match misses (pre-existing machinery caveat, mitigated by canonical-registration storage). (6) perf: type_params_of_sort is a linear by_qualified_name scan -- memoize (synth_req_names_cache pattern) when it shows up; spec_binding_head_sym vs sort_ref_functor near-dup -- fold when touched. Tests: wi428_rigid_projection_test now 15.", at: "2026-06-10T22:01:39Z", workitem: "WI-428", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "SCOPE ADDITION from WI-428's review round (2026-06-10): WI-428's concrete-head classifier converts an unresolvable Sort.Member dotted TYPE name into a stored RigidTypeProjection term; positions the typer ELIMINATES (op signatures, call sites, let annotations) now get a LOUD factually-correct error -- but a typo in a position the typer never eliminates (entity FIELD types, fact/constraint/rule type slots) loads SILENTLY (previously at least an UnresolvedName warning + degenerate nominal). WI-429's hard-error must therefore cover BOTH the remaining warning+nominal fall-throughs (non-Sort-headed dotted names) AND a post-load validation sweep of STORED RigidTypeProjection terms in non-eliminated positions (or run formation validation eagerly at end-of-load, when requires/provides info is complete).", at: "2026-06-10T22:01:39Z", workitem: "WI-429", author: "user")
fact Tag(name: "typing", workitem: "WI-431")
fact Feedback(content: "RE-POINTED ONTO THE sec.5.4 MODEL (2026-06-11, user-decided; docs/design/path-dependent-types.md sec.5.4 + the 002 CpsMonad note). PROBE: 002's CpsMonad surface ALREADY LOADS (structured member sort F body-form + F[T = A] applications in op signatures parse, load, anthill-check clean) -- the application is an ordinary term whose functor is the RIGID PARAM SYMBOL (never a logic var; first-order/decidable; the ticket's 'no semantic support' is exactly right -- only instantiation semantics is missing). MODEL: (a) TWO RIGID HEADS algebra -- applications are INJECTIVE (decompose freely; what makes inference work: List[Int] pins F and A) dual to sec.5.3's NON-injective projections; beta F[T=A].T == A; eta C == Fam(C)[T = C.Elem]. (b) FILL-AS-REQUIREMENT-DISCHARGE (user-proposed): a projection/application over an abstract subject = fresh var + requirement (generalizing THIS ticket's recorded desugar get(target:T) -> T.V == get[Vi](target:T) -> Vi requires T[V=Vi]); CONCRETE fill = CHECK (SLD against provides facts; the fresh var binds; delta falls out -- dissolves WI-428 increment B's substitution-through-terms problem); ABSTRACT fill = ADD (forward to the caller's interface, the WI-415/418 dict discipline; type-level obligation = value-level dict, one mechanism two levels); residuals = sec.4's three levels. (c) LICENSING IMPLICIT (Option 1 decided; flatten was the tell -- explicit Applied-clauses cost a var+clause per nesting level): F[T=B] licensed by the bound introducing F; the loader MINTS the obligations; the Applied-clause form is the LOWERING reflection shows, never the surface; unlicensed application = loud error. SCOPE under the model (4 pieces): (1) structured-param member registration through the loader (F's T feeds the declared-interface lookups exactly like a requires-lent member -- unify with WI-428's type_params_of_sort path); (2) FILL-TIME CHECK/ADD-REQUIRE -- the one new typer mechanism, CO-DELIVERS WI-428's increment B (projection-fill and application-fill are the same step; use the WI-419/WI-428 canonical-application identity for which requirement covers); (3) injective decomposition for rigid-functor applications (may be free via the parameterized unify arm -- probe with bodies); (4) Miller-fragment guard for flexible heads in RULE BODIES only (signatures have rigid heads). Dependency WI-428 ADDED (builds on the delivered projection substrate; its increment B closes with this mechanism). The instance half (retroactive op-valued provision facts) is WI-431.", at: "2026-06-11T05:43:50Z", workitem: "WI-383", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT B RE-MODELED (2026-06-11, user-decided; design sec.5.4): call-site delta-on-instantiation will NOT be substitution-through-terms (the opacity problem stands) -- it is FILL-AS-REQUIREMENT-DISCHARGE, delivered WITH WI-383's mechanism (which now depends on this ticket): a projection over an abstract subject lowers to a fresh var + requirement; a concrete fill CHECKS it by SLD against provides facts (binding the var = delta), an abstract fill ADDS/forwards it through the WI-415/418 dict discipline. This also retires the recorded increment-B sub-items 'thread the subst through the eliminator' and 'zeta sigma-class footing' in favor of requirement identity (WI-419/sec.5.3 canonical application). Projection-fill, T.V-fill (WI-383), and HK application-fill (sec.5.4) are ONE mechanism.", at: "2026-06-11T05:43:50Z", workitem: "WI-428", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "EXTRACTABILITY CRITERION ADDED (2026-06-11, user; design path-dependent-types.md sec.5.3 'Extractability criterion'): no type is ever represented as an opaque value -- every type value's backing term must classify into exactly one STRUCTURAL TypeExtractor variant; TypeExtractor.Error is reserved for malformed USER input, never a system-minted shape. This is DECISION PRESSURE for this ticket: the nullary Fn{S} that name_to_sort_term stores for provides/requires binding values extracts as ERROR -- whatever the fact-side untyped-term reading decides, a binding value USED IN A TYPE POSITION must lower to the extractable type shape (Ref(S) / Fn{S, named}), not the opaque nullary functor. WI-428's normalize_ground_leaf is the criterion's LOCAL fix at one consumer (delta-grounding); this ticket's decision is the global one. ACCEPTANCE ADDITION: after the decision, extract() over every stored type-position value in the loaded stdlib+examples yields a non-Error variant.", at: "2026-06-11T05:49:28Z", workitem: "WI-391", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "ACCEPTANCE ADDITION (2026-06-11, user; design sec.5.3 'Extractability criterion'): every type form this ticket adds/normalizes must classify into a STRUCTURAL TypeExtractor variant -- never Error, never an opaque value carrier. Specifically: (a) the rigid-functor application F[T = A] currently classifies as Parameterized{base = <rigid param sym>} -- decide at implementation whether that reading or a DEDICATED variant is honest (the self-hosted typer must be able to distinguish an abstract-base application from a concrete one when casing over extract()), but it MUST classify; (b) the fresh vars + requirements the fill mechanism mints must keep type positions extractable (a minted obligation is a requirement, not a type; nothing requirement-shaped may be stored AS a type); (c) structured-param members registered by the loader must reflect like requires-lent members do.", at: "2026-06-11T05:49:29Z", workitem: "WI-383", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "ACCEPTANCE ADDITION (2026-06-11, user; design sec.5.3 'Extractability criterion'): the instance fact's TYPE-valued bindings (F = Option, ...) must lower to extractable type shapes (Ref / Fn{S, named}) BEFORE reaching any type position -- never the nullary-Fn opaque functor (the WI-391 divergence this ticket depends on) and never an opaque Value carrier; op-valued bindings are dictionary entries, not types, and must never be stored as types. extract() over every type the instance machinery mints yields a non-Error structural variant.", at: "2026-06-11T05:49:29Z", workitem: "WI-431", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED AS THE FORM (2026-06-11 bookkeeping, per the 2026-06-11 user re-model): the ticket's deliverable is increment A -- classifier (try_rigid_type_projection), delta-at-formation + delta-through-the-bound, SubjectKey zeta, TypeExtractor entity, 15 tests (9e32706 incl. review fixes; suite 1311 green). Increment B (call-site delta) is FILL-AS-REQUIREMENT-DISCHARGE and closes with WI-383 scope piece (2), which depends_on this ticket -- keeping this open would deadlock the sequence. Review-round leftover routing: (1) call-site delta -> WI-383 fill mechanism; (2) unvalidated projections in never-eliminated positions -> WI-429 (its hard-error scope); (3) neutral-escape-at-unconstrained-var boundary guard + (4) sibling deep-walker alignment -> WI-383 (recorded there as inherited items); (5) resolve_sort_alias short-name fallback + (6) type_params_of_sort linear-scan perf stay machinery caveats in this ticket's review feedback.", at: "2026-06-11T06:14:42Z", workitem: "WI-428", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INHERITED FROM WI-428 (2026-06-11 delivery handoff; full detail in WI-428's review-round feedback): the fill mechanism (scope piece 2) must also close WI-428's two open increment-B boundary items -- (a) BOUNDARY GUARD: a RigidTypeProjection neutral can bind an unconstrained inference var at a call (let x = ...) and escape into let-types/Frame.type_args; guard when fill lands. (b) WALKER ALIGNMENT: sibling deep-walkers (substitute_ref_syms / substitute_spec_via_subst / canonicalize_goal_value) descend the projection's slots (exact-Symbol keying makes collision unlikely today); align when fill touches walking. REMINDER: walk_type_deep is deliberately OPAQUE at the projection head (subject-identity protection) -- fill must NOT reintroduce substitution-through-terms; that is the point of the sec.5.4 re-model. Also deferred-from-WI-428 and absorbed by the requirement model: cross-call rigid threading (= abstract fill ADD/forward), the requires-application identity slot (= WI-419 canonical application), structured manifest bindings (Key = List[Int]) in the SLD check.", at: "2026-06-11T06:14:42Z", workitem: "WI-383", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-432",
  description: "anthill-todo CLI: fail LOUDLY on missing work item / mistargeted store (loud-error principle; probed 2026-06-11 during WI-428 delivery). (a) 'deliver WI-NNN' on an id absent from the store prints 'error: work item ... not found' but EXITS 0, so shell '&&' chains continue past a failed delivery -- ALL mutating subcommands must exit nonzero on their error path. (b) 'feedback WI-NNN' APPENDS the Feedback fact WITHOUT validating the work item exists (two facts landed in a store containing no WI-428) -- validate existence before append. (c) The -d footgun that surfaced both: rustland/anthill-todo/ is the CRATE directory and contains a STALE legacy workitems.anthill (last touched WI-237-era, May; crate tests build their own temp stores so it appears unreferenced), so '-d rustland' silently targets it and even parses Cargo.toml as a data file (warning-only). Mitigations: verify+delete or relocate the stale crate-local file; have every MUTATING command print which store file it is writing; consider refusing to operate when the resolved store dir lacks a parseable workitems.anthill.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "BOUND/MANIFEST HALF DELIVERED 2026-06-11 (307d60a + review fixes 84dcad6; suite 1320 green, 4 ignored anchors; user-scoped this run to the bound case, ticket STAYS OPEN for the existential half). IMPL: bare_provider_binding_precise (typing.rs, next to sort_provides_admissibly) -- a bare concrete carrier (entity -> parent-sort hop) conforms to a parameterized spec it provides iff EVERY expected binding checks against the provider fact's view value (short-name match, check_binding_by_variance, WI-428 normalize_spec_binding_type leaf fix); wired with || after sort_sym_compatible into BOTH (sort_ref, parameterized) arms (term dispatch + view-structural twin); runs on a PROBE subst committed only on success (the arm was substitution-pure pre-WI-402). The sec.5 worked forms now typecheck: '-> DataProvider[K=String] = s', entity-literal return, arg position, and the KVStore TWO-BACKEND factory (the if-join pushes the manifest spec as upper bound); wrong-binding / non-provider stay type mismatches; PARTIAL manifest still rejected by the WI-401 gate (now for the right reason). Tests wi402_manifest_provider_test (10, 1 ignored).", at: "2026-06-11T06:52:19Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REVIEW ROUND (2026-06-11, /code-review high: 7 finder angles). FIXED: probe-subst hygiene (failure-path pollution); structured-binding pass-raw; stale docs; to_owned. DEFERRED, all sound (conservative false-reject or latent), recorded here per no-spinoff: (1) STRUCTURED manifest bindings (K = List[T = Int64]) false-reject -- the NESTED plain-sort leaf rides the nullary-Fn shape type_head classifies Error; WI-391-gated (sec.5.3 extractability criterion names exactly this); #[ignore] anchor structured_provider_binding_accepted pins the target. (2) Provider PARAM-PASSTHROUGH bindings (List provides Stream[T = T]) stay conservative-reject for a BARE actual (nothing to check the passthrough against; the same-sort bare-vs-param unconstrained leniency is NOT extended cross-sort) -- revisit with the existential half if a driver appears. (3) FIRST-PROVIDER-WINS: two same-spec provides facts at different bindings -- only the first view is checked (provider_spec_view_bindings contract); interacts with WI-431's coherence rule (two same-(spec,carrier) instances = loud ambiguity), so multi-fact search deliberately not built. (4) TRANSITIVE provider chains (A provides M, M provides Spec[K=..]): bare<->bare is transitive (WI-407) but binding-precise is direct-fact-only -- tightening a bare annotation to its manifest form can stop compiling; binding COMPOSITION through the chain is genuinely new scope. (5) The (parameterized, sort_ref) MIRROR arms remain nominal-only (pre-existing): non-monotone triangle -- List[T=Int] vs bare Stream rejects in NESTED binding positions while bare List accepts and WI-385's arg fallback accepts at args; touching it is escape-model-sensitive (WI-401), needs its own decision. (6) DISPATCH REACH (latent, suite green): dispatch_values_match/entries_cover now match a concrete carrier against a provided-spec-VALUED requirement binding -- widens the WI-419 identity-hazard class; watch with WI-419. (7) check_override_refinement's effect covered-by (types_compatible over effect labels) now admits carrier-provides-spec effect pairs -- exotic, latent, row-subsumption path unaffected. (8) ALTITUDE (both reviewers): FOUR provider-admissibility paths now exist (bare<->bare sort_provides_admissibly transitive; FIX 2 parameterized cross-sort, raw leaf, no entity hop; this one, normalized leaf, entity hop; WI-385 arg fallback bare-only) -- end-state is ONE provider_admissible(carrier, spec-application) relation; fold when next touched (FIX 2's raw-leaf convention is the divergence to kill first). (9) PERF: provider_spec_view_bindings full-scan rides the failed-nominal path -- measured nearly cold (10 hits across the whole suite); memoize when it shows up. REMAINING WI-402 SCOPE: the UNBOUND existential half -- ensures Spec[C] surface (loader), interface-rooted existential C, branch-join against the spec bound for DIVERGENT-member joins, dict-OUT at eval (sec.5 worked example end-to-end); driver = anthill-todo pluggable backend, after WI-009.", at: "2026-06-11T06:52:43Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "PARKED 2026-06-11 (user-decided after explicit probe 'is WI-009 really needed?'): depends_on WI-009 added as a SCHEDULING device (WI-376 precedent), NOT a technical dependency -- nothing in the existential half consumes a WI-009 capability; it could be built against synthetic fixtures today. The edge encodes the recorded wait-for-a-real-driver principle: the dict-OUT flow (the one genuinely new mechanism, no existing counterpart to crib from) should be shaped against the first real consumer -- the anthill-todo pluggable backend (examples/github-todo/docs/pluggable-backend.md), which becomes the live code path only after WI-009's cutover. Loop: ticket now Claimed-but-BLOCKED, skipped until WI-009 delivers.", at: "2026-06-11T06:57:34Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-434",
  description: "anthill-todo: per-project VERSIONING + startup PRESCAN of the project's todo files (user request 2026-06-11; driver = the 9fa0da6 incident: a broken rules.anthill template copy persisted SILENTLY in every project scaffolded by an older 'anthill-todo init', breaking claim/next with no diagnostic). Two halves, one mechanism: (1) VERSION STAMPS -- 'anthill-todo init' stamps every scaffolded file (rules.anthill, domain.anthill, ...) AND the workitems data format with a version fact (e.g. fact TemplateInfo(file: \"rules\", version: N) / fact StoreFormat(version: N)); the binary embeds the current versions next to its include_str! templates. (2) PRESCAN at CLI startup, before any subcommand executes against the project: compare stamped versions vs the binary's; on mismatch warn LOUDLY (loud-error principle -- the motivating bug was a silent never-match) naming file, found/current versions, and the upgrade path; a missing stamp = pre-versioning project, warn once. (3) UPGRADE path: 'anthill-todo migrate' (or init --refresh) rewrites an outdated template ONLY if unmodified (hash against known historical template versions; locally-edited files are reported, never overwritten); data-format bumps get explicit migrators. RELATION: rides naturally AFTER WI-009 (prescan belongs in the anthill bundle, not new native run_* logic); not a cutover blocker. Project-side twin of WI-412 (embedded-stdlib drift) and sibling of WI-433 (the never-match the stale template carried).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "CUTOVER RECON + INCREMENT 1 (2026-06-11, resumed by user request). CATALOGUE GAP measured (bundle dispatch vs clap): bundle had 15 subcommands; missing = insert, tag, untag (whole WI-388 named-list layer) + 'list --tag' + 'add --tag' option; 'init' stays shim-side (pre-KB-load) per the ticket. INCREMENT 1 DELIVERED (this commit): bundle tag/untag -- WorkItemStore spec+impl gain tag_item (persist_through a 'fact Tag' term) / untag_item (find_tag_term -> find_fact -> retract -> flush) / has_tag (facts_of(kb(), Tag) scan; the synthetic entity-decl fact filters out via term_as_string none); main.anthill gains spec_tag_change (two positionals id+name), dispatch arms, cmd_tag/cmd_untag with BYTE-IDENTICAL native messages + validation order (non-empty name, lookup, already-tagged; untag checks only is-tagged). Verified: smoke end-to-end + 7 integration tests (cmd_tag_bundle_test.rs) incl CROSS-PATH interop both directions. FILE-PLACEMENT FINDING (parity-test relevant): bundle persist (Meta entries nil) writes NEW facts to facts.anthill while native appends to workitems.anthill -- pre-existing bundle convention (read_combined exists for it), both paths read all project .anthill files, interop verified; the WI-009 parity test must therefore assert STDOUT/exit parity, not file-placement parity (or a target-file Meta entry gets added later). PARITY NOTE: bundle name-empty check is eq(name,'') vs native name.trim().is_empty() -- whitespace-only tag name diverges (exotic). REMAINING INCREMENTS: (2) 'add --tag' (thread tags through do_add) + 'insert' (compose do_add + tag_item + the add-dependency replace path); (3) 'list --tag' (topo-ordered tagged view w/ blocked + '<- next' markers -- the largest read-only port, mirrors native run_list_tagged); (4) CUTOVER: default dispatch -> bundle (init + an explicit --legacy escape? decide), delete run_* + update_*_in_source from src/main.rs (~1200 LOC), thin shim; (5) parity test: golden stdout/exit comparison per subcommand (capture from native BEFORE deletion).", at: "2026-06-11T09:12:43Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "FILE-PLACEMENT FIXED (2026-06-11, user steer 'persist to workitems.anthill -- we have custom persistency, proposal 007'): the increment-1 finding is RESOLVED, not accepted -- new FileConvention::SingleFile(name) (file_store.rs, the 007 'pluggable file conventions' slot) and the bundle host now constructs IndexedFileStore with SingleFile('workitems.anthill'). The old Flat convention hardcoded facts.anthill while the host comment CLAIMED legacy-layout parity (comment/behavior divergence). Now bundle persist + native append target the SAME workitems.anthill; span-retract + replacement write land in one file in one flush (cmd_claim_test re-asserted on the status transition; cmd_tag_bundle_test asserts placement + facts.anthill absence). Older projects with a stray facts.anthill keep loading (BulkStore::pull is filename-blind). STILL OPEN in this layer: the persist builtin DISCARDS its Meta argument and hardcodes sort='Fact'/domain='anthill.todo' (builtins.rs persistence_persist) -- the 007 stage0 convention (file_path(fact, meta, conv), per-sort routing) is the eventual home; SingleFile is the legacy-layout realization, sufficient for the cutover.", at: "2026-06-11T09:39:05Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT 2 DELIVERED (2026-06-11): add --tag + insert in the bundle. do_add threads repeatable --tag (collect_all_args) through new apply_tags + tag_note (native-identical 'added: ID — desc [tags: a, b]'); cmd_insert/do_insert mirror run_insert: --before must exist ('error: --before target ... not found'), CYCLE GUARD first (dep == before OR transitive reach via reaches_dep/any_dep_reaches with a seen-list so a corrupt cyclic store can't hang; rejects BEFORE anything persists), then the native orphan-avoidance ordering (next_id -> rewrite before's depends_on via replace/with_deps -> commit new item -> tags) and the exact 'inserted: ID before B [tags...] (B now depends on ID)' message. spec_insert + spec_add tag-flag added to the OperationSpec catalogue. Tests: cmd_insert_bundle_test (5: tagged add, rewire, both cycle shapes, unknown before); workspace 50 binaries green. CATALOGUE REMAINING: 'list --tag' (topo-ordered view w/ blocked + '<- next' markers, mirrors run_list_tagged) -- increment 3; then the cutover + parity test.", at: "2026-06-11T10:19:04Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "INCREMENT 3 DELIVERED (2026-06-11): list --tag in the bundle — THE CATALOGUE IS NOW COMPLETE (every subcommand except shim-side init). items_with_tag (store) + topo_order_tagged (Kahn, smallest-id tie-break, reach through untagged intermediates via row_reaches over the Row map, cycle remainder appended in id order) + print_tagged_rows ((blocked: …), <- next, [missing] rows, char-based 100-char truncation). BYTE-FOR-BYTE parity with native asserted in cmd_list_tagged_bundle_test (4 tests incl. a direct bundle-vs-native diff over 4 variants). BONUS FIX: matches_filter was a partial eq_ignore_ascii_case emulation (capitalize-first; claimed to match 'OPEN' but could not) — now toLower-both-sides, fixing plain 'list --status OPEN' too. INTEROP FINDING (cutover-relevant): the NATIVE reader mis-parses BUNDLE-WRITTEN depends_on (TermPrinter cons form vs bracket list literal) — native list showed no blocked markers for bundle-written items and update_depends_in_source text surgery expects brackets (run_insert's own comment names 'a non-bracket depends_on' as a failure case). Bundle reads both forms fine. Disappears at cutover (native reader deleted); for the transition, parity fixtures must be NATIVE-written; consider list-literal sugar in TermPrinter for human-readable on-disk deps (cutover polish). REMAINING: (4) the CUTOVER (default dispatch -> bundle, init stays shim, delete run_*/update_*_in_source ~1200 LOC, thin main.rs); (5) golden parity test captured from native BEFORE deletion. Workspace 50 binaries green.", at: "2026-06-11T11:13:13Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "CUTOVER DELIVERED (2026-06-11, 820120e + review fixes; workspace 53 binaries green). Closing bar met: (1) default dispatch routes EVERY subcommand through the bundle (--anthill = accepted no-op); (2) src/main.rs 2501->~650 lines, thin shim only (bootstrap, embedded stdlib+bundle parse, project load + source-span seeding, store/cell minting, init + SKILL_MD statics, global-flag strip, entry dispatch) -- zero run_* business logic, zero update_*_in_source, clap dependency REMOVED; (3) golden-transcript parity test (28-command session, deterministic, run twice to verify) + 5 shim regression tests. FIVE DOCUMENTED divergences vs legacy (test header + here): show acceptance prints loader-canonical named form; next multi-claimable order unpinned (resolver order is run-to-run NONDETERMINISTIC -- HashMap iteration somewhere; sort-by-id in cmd_next would pin it, deferred); delete omits the file path; unknown-subcommand = one-line error + spec-driven --help; show/delete unknown-id now EXIT 1 (legacy exit-0-with-stderr retired -- scripts branching on $? see failures now, deliberate loud-error alignment). CUTOVER-SURFACED FIXES (each was a latent bundle bug): show gained Tags/Context/Acceptance/Feedback sections (NEW reflect builtins term_to_string + term_list_items, store ops tags_of/raw_term_of); next was BROKEN since WI-385 (widening walk_solutions LogicalStream->Stream killed the static rewrite; dynamic dispatch could not classify Value::Stream -- carrier_of now maps stream handles to LogicalStream) + WI-411 qualified-call workaround applied; TermPrinter now prints ground cons/nil spines AND parse-side ListLiteral as [..] literals (a bare nullary print reloads as a NAME REFERENCE unifying with neither nil() nor cons patterns -- persisted items were INVISIBLE to workflow rules; strict all-or-nothing shared spine walker, named arm requires exactly head+tail); add-dependency gained the legacy cycle guard the bundle lacked; matches_filter is now true eq_ignore_ascii_case; global-flag strip runs BEFORE init/skill interception (the documented '-d $PWD init' form previously exploded) + =-joined forms + loud dangling-flag/--stdlib-removed errors.", at: "2026-06-11T13:30:47Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REVIEW-ROUND DEFERRED ITEMS (2026-06-11, /code-review high, 7 finders; all sound -- recorded per no-spinoff where WI-009-scope, else filed): (a) reaches_dep cycle guard is store-lookup-per-node (full facts_of materialization per visit) + per-dep seen reset in first_cycle_dep -- the dep-map pattern (build_dep_map, used by list --tag) should subsume it; TWO transitive-reach walkers now exist (store-based reaches_dep, map-based row_reaches) -- consolidate when next touched (HOF-parameterized deps lookup is expressible since WI-275). (b) cmd_show does 3 full WorkItem-table scans (lookup + raw_term_of x2) + Tag + Feedback scans -- fetch the raw term ONCE; acceptable at WI-183's interpreted bar, fix on next touch. (c) unwrap_list_spine matches cons/nil by SHORT functor name -- a user sort with cons/nil constructors would print as a list literal and reload as prelude List (silent cross-sort corruption edge; no in-repo instance; a symbol-identity guard needs KB-side resolution the parse-side printer lacks -- revisit with the Ref/nullary-Fn ticket). (d) PRE-CUTOVER persisted files (cons + bare-nil text) still load as rule-invisible name refs -- ONLY /tmp probes exist today (real projects are native-written brackets), but WI-434's prescan/migrate is the home for a one-shot rewrite if any surface. (e) carrier-param dispatch fallback: a Value::Stream in a NON-receiver slot of a multi-C-param spec op could steal dispatch (narrow; the WI-424 provision gate limits it) -- covered by the filed runtime-carrier WI. (f) deleted host unit tests partially re-covered: the seen-guard no-hang (cyclic store) and Kahn cycle-remainder cases have NO bundle test -- add with (a)'s consolidation. (g) golden parity test = 35s (28 subprocess KB loads) -- load-bearing (pins persistence round-trip per command), keep; trim scenario rather than de-subprocess if it grows. (h) stdlib_embedded.rs is still the WI-412 hand-list -- the cutover makes the bundle the ONLY path, raising the next drift's blast radius (WI-412 priority bump). (i) on-disk churn: the replace path reprints items in FULL canonical form (context: none etc.) vs add's sparse form -- print=parse-fixpoint stability is WI-391/WI-408-adjacent.", at: "2026-06-11T13:31:34Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RE-PARKED 2026-06-11: WI-009 (the proxy edge) DELIVERED -- the real driver is the pluggable backend, now filed as WI-437 (depends WI-009); parking edge swapped WI-009 -> WI-437 so this stays Claimed-but-BLOCKED until the factory consumer exists.", at: "2026-06-11T13:32:02Z", workitem: "WI-402", author: "user")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "user 2026-06-11: Iterable.find MUST get the same -Modify[x] pred form — scope item (d) is not 'evaluate retrofitting' but a requirement; find's pred is '(x: Element) -> Bool @ -Modify[x]' alongside filter's. (map's transform remains 'evaluate'.)", at: "2026-06-11T15:04:26Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-439", author: "user", content: "Delivered b2e55df. Two gaps SURFACED by the tests, out of this WI's acceptance scope: (1) SYNTHESIS GAP — collect's Elem does not ground from a member result whose Element comes from a CONCRETE provision binding (BoxColl 'Element = Int64' fails 'expected a type for Elem, got unconstrained') while the GENERIC List provision (Element = T) grounds fine; suspect the WI-391 Ref-vs-nullary-Fn provides-lowering divergence — root-cause alongside WI-391; workaround in test = explicit collect[Elem, Eff] bindings. (2) PARSE GAP — qualified call with explicit type-arg brackets, e.g. FilteredStream.filter[S = Int64, Eff = {}](...), is a syntax error; only the unqualified-import form takes brackets; relates WI-311 (application/name grammar merge). Laziness not separately asserted — it is the delivered FilteredStream engine's property (WI-410/413 tests).", at: "2026-06-11T15:05:23Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-439", description: "Iterable.filter member (WI-424 pattern): derived combinator via iterator(c) — 'operation filter(c: C, pred: Function[Element, Bool, E]) -> Stream[Element, E] = FilteredStream.filter(iterator(c), pred)' (or the filtered(...) constructor directly; inner call MUST be qualified/foreign — the WI-411 short-name hazard, same as find/map). Engine = the delivered FilteredStream lazy carrier (WI-410/413). Same mechanism as WI-424 find/map: enclosing-sort param rigidification + carrier-param receiver + provision-written E threading. NOTE the current-pattern limitation to document in a comment: tying pred's row to the collection's access row E forces a PURE pred for List (E = {}); the decoupled arrow form is WI-441. ACCEPTANCE: filter on List evaluates (keep/drop/laziness), typechecks pure, wrong-element pred rejected; parity tests vs Stream-level filter; cargo-test green.", context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: [], generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-11T15:05:24Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-440", author: "user", content: "Delivered 293b0bd. DECISIONS: (1) row-openness — absence-only '@ -Modify[x]' = CLOSED row + lacks atom, per 045's co-finite rule ('{ ?, -e }' is 'anything but e'); explicit open base required ('@ {?, -Modify[x]}' or '@ {Eff, -Modify[x]}'); implicit fresh tail tried + REVERTED (unnameable var -> a HOF APPLYING the callback surfaces an undeclared ?rho it cannot declare — probe p2). GAPS SURFACED, for WI-441: (a) the arrow annotation's 'Eff' and the op's 'effects Eff' clause lower to DIFFERENT VarIds (boundary check: 'expected declared [?Eff], got undeclared ?Eff'), and (b) a row-valued instantiation of a declared effect var is not decomposed at the boundary ('expected [Beep], got merge[present(Beep), empty_row]') — so a HOF that APPLIES an open-row callback and declares 'effects Eff' is blocked; both are the WI-441 result-row threading work. v1 CONSERVATISMS (documented in fn docs): lambda args skipped (eta op-refs only); open/absent-bearing ACTUAL rows skipped; arity-mismatch alignment skipped (generic WI-385 check owns it). ALTITUDE note (review): binder-normalizing arrow rows at CONSTRUCTION (positional places in the type itself) would subsume the side-validator, the unify path's binder-BLINDNESS (pair_present_labels/label_violates_lacks still compare places structurally), and gap (a) — candidate direction when WI-441/342 touch this; the wi440 tests pin against vacuous-pass regressions meanwhile.", at: "2026-06-11T15:50:32Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-440", description: "-Modify[binder] CHECKING direction: discharge a lacks-constraint on a callback param at the call site — the slice WI-353 explicitly left out ('pairs with WI-341 for the find-style -Modify(a) CHECKING direction, the lacks-constraint path, separate from this propagation slice'). Given a param typed '(x: Element) -> Bool @ -Modify[x]', a call site passing pred must verify pred's Modify row contains NO Modify on the place(s) fed through x — pred's row from its declared/derived effects (WI-352 flow facts + WI-353 keep_modify classifier output), absence via the WI-328 lacks machinery, label identity via the WI-341 occurrence-aware denoted comparator (all three DELIVERED — this WI is the wiring). PROBE EVIDENCE 2026-06-11 (supersedes the WI-353-era 'Modify[a] fails to LOAD/UnresolvedName' finding): '(x: Int64) -> Bool @ -Modify[x]' LOADS CLEAN and the arrow's own binder x RESOLVES in the effect annotation (differential probe: a bogus place name gets only a WARNING and loads — so today a declared absence is VACUOUS, silently unenforced). SCOPE ALSO: (a) loud-error: unresolved place name in an absence/effect-row position must be an ERROR not a warning (vacuous-constraint footgun, probe p4); (b) DECIDE row-openness of a bare-absence annotation '@ -Modify[x]' — open row {-Modify[x] | rho} (intended reading: any effects EXCEPT modifying x) vs closed; document in 045/spec. ACCEPTANCE: a pred that writes through its argument is REJECTED against a -Modify[x] callback param; a pred with unrelated effects (e.g. reads a Cell) is ACCEPTED under the open-row reading; typo'd place in absence position errors loudly; cargo-test green. Interacts with WI-342 (Value-carried types) but comparator-level deps are delivered.", context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: ["WI-353"], generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-11T15:50:33Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "Delivered 3883e13 (v1). All three members converted: find/filter pred '(x: Element) -> Bool @ {E, -Modify[x]}', map's f '(x: Element) -> Dst @ {E, -Modify[x]}' (the 'evaluate' item resolved YES — worked for free). SCOPE OUTCOMES: (a) arrow~Function interop VERIFIED end-to-end — the arrow-typed callback forwards into the Function-typed Stream.find/mapped/filtered engines with zero engine changes (wi424/wi439 suites unchanged); (b) RESULT ROW: v1 keeps the row TIE ({E | -Modify[x]}; result rows unchanged Stream[.., E]) — acceptance item 'effectful-but-element-pure pred typechecks on List' is CONSCIOUSLY NOT met in v1 (E := {} closes the row; same pure-pred-on-List semantics as the old Function form, now with a LOUD row message — pinned by test). The decoupled independent pred row + merge(E, pred_row) result is the remaining half, blocked on the WI-440-recorded boundary gaps (arrow-Eff vs effects-clause VarId split; row-valued boundary instantiation not decomposed) — keep ticket open or re-file per user preference; (c) binder named 'x' (no receiver shadowing); -Modify[collection] (pred must not mutate the COLLECTION mid-iteration) NOT expressible yet — the receiver 'c' is an outer op param, referencing it from the callback's annotation is the WI-353-era outer-binder case, untested here. (d) find mandated + done.", at: "2026-06-11T16:00:13Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-441", description: "Iterable.filter arrow-typed pred with dependent absence: 'operation filter(c: C, pred: (x: Element) -> Bool @ -Modify[x]) -> Stream[Element, ?row]' — the user-proposed form (2026-06-11 design discussion). Two payoffs over the Function[Element, Bool, E] pattern: (1) MUTATION SAFETY — pred cannot modify the element under test (lazy FilteredStream re-walks; a mutating pred makes the filtered view inconsistent), enforced by the WI-440 checking direction; (2) ROW DECOUPLING — pred's effect row is its own (open row minus Modify[x]) instead of being TIED to the collection's access row E, which today forces a PURE pred on List (E = {}). SCOPE: (a) arrow-typed HOF param interop — probe p1 2026-06-11 shows '(x: Int64) -> Bool' param + f(5) application LOADS; verify typecheck+eval with a real lambda/Function value at the call site (arrow vs Function[A,B,E] structural-variance bridge, proposal 035 / WI-293 lineage; WI-275 HOF was Function-sort apply); (b) RESULT ROW — the produced lazy stream pays pred's effects on consumption, so the result row must be merge(E, pred_row); decide whether row-merge of two open tails is expressible (045 merge normal form) or v1 keeps pred_row tied to E with only the -Modify[x] absence added (still gains mutation safety, defers decoupling); (c) NAMING — avoid 'c' for the arrow binder (shadows the receiver 'c: C'; both -Modify[element] and -Modify[collection] are meaningful constraints — consider BOTH: pred must not mutate the element NOR the collection being iterated); (d) evaluate retrofitting find (and map's transform) with the same form. ACCEPTANCE: filter with an effectful-but-element-pure pred typechecks on List; a pred writing through x rejected; result row covers pred effects; cargo-test green.", context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: ["WI-439", "WI-440"], generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-11T16:00:14Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "user 2026-06-11 (post-v1 direction): in find, pred should NOT carry the iterable's E — pred gets its OWN row (EffPred), and the op's effect = MERGE of EffPred and E ('effects {E, EffPred}'). This activates the deferred decoupled half for the EAGER member: requires fixing the two boundary gaps (arrow-annotation row var vs effects-clause var must be ONE VarId; boundary declared-vs-incurred must decompose row values). Stream.find engine must decouple too (its single Eff currently ties pred row to stream row). Lazy map/filter stay tied for now (their decoupling needs merge-rows in result TYPE position — the two-open-tails row).", at: "2026-06-11T16:05:25Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "Decoupled rows DELIVERED f3894fb (the post-v1 user direction): Iterable.find[EffP] + Stream.find[Elem, Eff, EffP] — pred row EffP independent of the access row, op effect = merge {E, EffP} (op-level effects are an ATOM LIST, so the eager member needs no merge-row TYPE). PAYOFF VERIFIED: effectful-but-element-pure pred typechecks on List AND its effects thread to the caller's boundary (undeclared -> loud). THE THREE ENGINE FIXES (were the WI-440-recorded gaps): (1) rewrite_type_occ_deep — the rigidify/canon walk now penetrates Value::Node carriers (the 'Nodes carry Refs, not type-param vars' assumption was false for callback arrow row tails; this was the REAL root of the 'VarId split' — one var, un-rigidified on the Node side); (2) boundary declared-vs-incurred is row-aware: row-shaped incurred effects EXPLODE into present labels + tail vars (absences dropped), canon-walked through the op's rigidify subst stored on OpInfo; (3) rigid tail-to-tail ALIASING in unify/subtype both-open arms (forwarding sites pair a flexible callee row var with a rigidified outer tail; flexible now aliases the rigid via open(rigid) continuation instead of the failing symmetric fresh-tail step). KNOWN CONSERVATISM: lacks on the flexible side are NOT propagated onto a rigid continuation (enforced at the rigid's own instantiation site). REMAINING (lazy half): map/filter stay on the tied {E, -Modify[x]} form — decoupling them needs merge-rows in the result TYPE position (Stream[Element, merge(E, EffP)]), plus FilteredStream/MappedStream carrier row threading. Also fold_left/fold_right still Function-form.", at: "2026-06-11T16:25:59Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "user 2026-06-11 (third direction): map and filter callbacks also get their OWN operation-effects row (EffP), distinct from the Iterable E — the lazy half. Requires: multi-tail rows ({E, EffP} in the result TYPE position — decompose_effect_row's WI-339 F13 two-tail reject must become Vec<tails> with conservative unify arms), two-row MappedStream/FilteredStream carriers (source row ES + callback row EF, provides Stream[T, {ES, EF}], splitFirst effects {ES, EF}), and Iterable.map/filter[..., EffP] -> Stream[.., {E, EffP}].", at: "2026-06-11T16:56:31Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-441", author: "user", content: "Lazy half DELIVERED 271e80b: map/filter callbacks carry their OWN row end-to-end. Iterable.map[Dst, EffP]/filter[EffP] -> Stream[.., {E, EffP}]; two-row MappedStream/FilteredStream (ES + EF, provides Stream[T, {ES, EF}], splitFirst effects {ES, EF}); the callback's effects ride the produced stream, paid on CONSUMPTION (pinned: collect(filter(xs, noisy)) caller must declare Beep, undeclared is loud). ENGINE: multi-tail row UNIONS — decompose Vec<tails> (supersedes WI-339 F13), multi_tail_rows_compat (equal tail sets / bare-flexible wholesale absorb, occurs+lacks guarded), FULL row algorithm in both (effects_rows, effects_rows) unify arms (the WI-320 structural inner-unify was merge-ORDER-sensitive), row-shaped routing in all four dispatch fallbacks (?rho vs open(?rho)), build_canonical folds ALL row vars as opens, kb.row_tail_var_of resolves SORT-level row params' Ref(S.E) lowering to the alias var, provider-view canon vars instantiated through the actual instance's bindings in the cross-sort arm. CONSERVATISMS: multi-tail pairing only via set-equality or wholesale absorb (general two-tail-vs-two-tail pairing rejected — no principal unifier); entity-FIELD arrows carry the plain {EF} row (no field binder places; lacks enforced at the public signatures). REMAINING: fold_left/fold_right still Function-form (same decoupling applies if wanted); -Modify[collection] outer-binder still untested. WI-441 scope now FULLY delivered per the three user directions.", at: "2026-06-11T17:23:17Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-443", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (pending commit): identifier-receiver dot calls work — get_arg IS 'args.find(lambda b -> ...)' in main.anthill. THREE pieces: (1) LOADER reroute (load.rs try_identifier_dot_call, called from the generic apply arm of convert_expr's visit): a dotted functor whose HEAD segment is a local binding — let/lambda/match binder via local_names_stack, or an op param (resolve_in_scope -> SymbolKind::Param) — becomes the same Expr::DotApply the '?x.m(...)' form produces, with a synthesized var_ref receiver (kb term + leaf occurrence pushed before the arg Visits; no parse node exists for it); member resolved via new remap_name_str (remap_symbol factored to take &str). Locals checked FIRST -> binder shadows a same-named sort (pinned: param named Pair typed Box, Pair.grab() = grab(param)). (2) TYPER (typing.rs DotApply frame): args are NO LONGER pre-typed hintless at the frame — only the receiver is typed; the RAW arg occurrences ride the frame into the synthesized call where they type ONCE with the callee's param hints. This is what makes 'xs.find(lambda n -> n > 2)' work (hintless pre-typing mis-fired Ordered.gt coherence on the untyped lambda param); benefits the '?x.m(...)' form equally. (3) PERSISTENCE (kb.has_dot_applies flag, set at the loader's DotApply build, OR'd into the typer's simp_enabled gate): the typer's tree-reassembly previously ran ONLY when [simp] equations existed, so a NESTED dot call's rewrite never reached the stored body — eval crashed on raw DotApply ('unhandled Expr variant'). PRE-EXISTING gap (also hit '?x.m(...)' nested in any expr; wi279 was typecheck-only and never saw it). REMAINING (conservative, all LOUD): multi-segment tails ('p.x.m(...)') keep qualified flattening; dot calls carrying type-args keep flattening (dot_apply has no type-args channel); bare field access 'p.x' (no call parens) on an identifier receiver untouched (field_access path, not fn_term). TESTS: wi443_identifier_dot_call_test (5): eval parity dot==plain incl. lambda + none case; no-import literal receiver; let-bound receiver; shadowing pin; unknown-head stays loud. Full workspace 1663 passed / 0 failed; anthill-todo suite + golden parity green; CLI smoke (show/status) through the dot-form get_arg verified.", at: "2026-06-12T04:33:26Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-443", description: "Converter+loader: IDENTIFIER-receiver dot calls — route 'args.find(...)' to dot_apply when the identifier is a local binding (the deferred 'p.x' identifier case, convert.rs ~888). TODAY: dot syntax (WI-278) works for receivers the scope-blind converter can recognize as values — '?x' vars in rules, call-result chains ('iterator(xs).find(is_big)' loads clean, probed 2026-06-11), literals — dispatched via sort-guarded [simp] dot rules + the default method fallback on the receiver's least sort. But a BARE IDENTIFIER receiver (an op param or let-binding, e.g. 'args.find(lambda ...)' / 'xs.find(is_big)') is classified as a NAME by is_value_receiver (convert.rs ~892) and flattened to a qualified name — fails loudly as 'unknown functor xs.find', since at parse time 'args.find' and 'Stream.find' are indistinguishable. FIX DIRECTION: defer the name-vs-value classification to the loader/typer, which knows the scope — an identifier-rooted dot callee whose root identifier resolves to a local binding (op param / let / lambda binder) becomes Expr::DotApply (receiver preserved); one that resolves to a sort/namespace keeps qualified-name flattening; an identifier that resolves to NEITHER stays the loud unknown-functor error (no silent fallback). Watch the WI-411 short-name hazard in reverse: a param named like a sort in scope should prefer the local binding (shadowing, like every binder language) — pin with a test. ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA: anthill-todo main.anthill get_arg rewritten as 'args.find(lambda b -> ...)' (currently find(args, ...), rewritten under this session's find-adoption) and the anthill-todo suite + golden parity stay green; a wi424-suite test where 'xs.find(is_big)' on a List[Int64] param typechecks + EVALS equal to find(xs, is_big); existing qualified-name call sites (Stream.find / Cell.set / Map[K=...].empty) unaffected across the full workspace suite.", context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: [], generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T04:33:27Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-445", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-408", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-12 (cb82116 + review-fix commit, pushed; suite full-workspace green). THREE LEGS. (1) TYPER (op bodies): validate_arg_against_param -> tri-state ArgValidation (Ok / WrapSome{declared} / Fail); check_apply_iter (ARGS — previously strict) + check_constructor_iter (fields) record WrapSome during the WI-385 validation and rebuild the apply/constructor via wrap_some_children + synthesize_some_wrap — a synthesized NAMED some(value: child) Constructor occurrence (canonical shape), stamped with the resolved declared Option type; the rebuild runs BEFORE any annotation write (classification / resolved_type_args land on the fresh node — reassemble starts empty cells). Tree reassembly in ALL Build arms is now UNCONDITIONAL (reassemble's ChildCursor ptr-eq short-circuit keeps the no-rewrite case allocation-free); simp_enabled gates only rule FIRING — required so a typer-inserted rewrite reaches the stored body via set_op_body_node in KBs with no [simp] rules (in real stdlib loads simp was always on, so no practical perf change). (2) LOADER (term world): wrap_bare_option_value in convert_term_with_expected's entity-arg loops wraps a bare value in an Option-typed field via build_some — on-disk FACTS and rule-body entity ATOMS, so bare rule patterns (depends_on: cons(...)) auto-wrap and keep matching wrapped facts; a Var binds the WHOLE Option (never wrapped); some/none heads skipped. Validation order: types_compatible FIRST, then Option-peel — so Option[T] into Option[Option[T]] takes exactly ONE outer wrap, and a doubly-bare value under nested Option is rejected loudly (no guessed double-wrap). (3) CANON + MIGRATION: canonical in-KB some form = NAMED some(value: v) (build_some + value->term reflection); source-written positional some(v) is CANONICALIZED at load (term-world unification does not bridge positional<->named — a positional wrap never matched the CLI-persisted named facts); an explicit some(payload) threads the PEELED element hint into its payload (without this a persisted depends_on: some([...]) literal lost the List hint and never desugared — surfaced as 'pattern match failed on Term(ListLiteral)' in cmd_tag_test). anthill-todo: normalize_deps reflect-launder REMOVED (acceptance); description readers (print_description_w / row_of_w) peel some/none; workflow rules bind description: some(?desc) (absent-description facts still match via the loader's fresh-var stuffing); unused as_term/term_as_entity imports dropped. Fact ROUND-TRIP now writes explicit some(value: ...)/none (acceptance; verified live — WI-445's own fact + probe project); legacy bare data keeps loading via the wrap, so workitems.anthill migrates INCREMENTALLY per touched fact (no bulk rewrite — avoids the WI-436 TermPrinter round-trip bug class on 3400 lines). Spec: kernel-language.md gained a some-coercion paragraph after the Option sort (sec 4.2 area). TESTS: wi408_some_coercion_test (5: field+arg eval coercion proving runtime some-shape, Option[T=Term] bare string, nested-Option rejection + single-wrap acceptance, fact-wrap + explicit/bare rule-pattern alignment + none preservation); wi385 test comments de-interim'd; cmd_add/tag/update assert the explicit persisted format; golden parity green. BOUNDARIES (recorded, not blocking): (a) coercion gated on GROUND declared+actual (same gate as WI-385 validation) — a still-polymorphic Option slot stays unwrapped; (b) RETURN-position coercion not in scope ('field or arg') — op declared -> Option[T] with bare-T body still mismatches; (c) general entity positional<->named canonicalization NOT done (only some) — hand-written positional patterns vs named persisted facts (ToolPasses(\"x\") vs ToolPasses(tool: ...)) remain un-unifiable in term world, a PRE-EXISTING silent-mismatch class worth its own ticket if it bites; (d) op-body match PATTERNS in Option slots are not coerced (patterns aren't typed) — a bare sub-pattern there needs explicit some(...); (e) eval value world records the supplied constructor-arg shape, hence the named wrapper prints some(value: ...) on persist. FILED: WI-445 — pre-existing typer gap found by probe (named constructor sub-patterns don't bind: 'case Box(v: some(x))' UnresolvedName while positional binds; plus TermId-keyed span side-table misattributes diagnostics to another file's span).", at: "2026-06-12T10:41:52Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-408", description: some(value: "Typer/eval: some-coercion INSERTION pass — when a value of type T flows into an Option[T] slot (field or arg), INSERT some(...) so the value is properly Option-typed (sound; lets normalize_deps drop its reflect-launder). Classify-during-typing + rewrite-pass (à la WI-231 req_insertion) for op-body constructors; loader path for on-disk facts (asserted before the typing pass); migrate the on-disk fact format to explicit some(...)/none() (user decision 2026-06-06). REPLACES WI-385's bare-T-vs-Option[T] FIELD lenient-accept INTERIM. The first concrete slice of the deferred implicit-conversion / 'into' framework (general framework still deferred). Acceptance: cargo-test green; normalize_deps launder removed; anthill-todo fact round-trip uses some()/none()."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-385"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T10:41:54Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-425", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-12 (aaa718f + review commit; full workspace 53 binaries green twice). The four view fns (occ_head/occ_pos_child/occ_named_child/occ_named_keys, term_view.rs) now read a DotApply occurrence byte-identically to the loader's dot_apply(receiver, name, args: List[ApplyArg]) term: head always arity-3 named (was 2+named / pos-flattened), keys in the BUILDER slice order [receiver, name, args] (the term is NOT name-sorted; discrim descends in named_keys order so matching stored order = lockstep), call args folded into a per-call-synthesized List[ApplyArg] child mirroring mk_apply_arg+build_list (none()/some(value: Ref(k)) wrapping, Fn-nil spine). Subsumed items done: (a) type_head explicit dot_apply->Error arm (bare DotApply can no longer classify Parameterized{base: phantom dot_apply sort}; sort_functor_of_view now None); (b) missing field keys PANIC (dot_apply_key) instead of silently desyncing named_keys from named_arity. Tests wi425_dotapply_view_isomorphism_test (3): head/keys/deep-equality both directions; term-indexed fact matched by occurrence query + negative control + match_view direction; goal var INSIDE the synthesized args spine binds through VarPath extraction. VERIFIED during review: declared entity field orders (dot_apply/cons/some/ApplyArg) all match the hardcoded view orders, so sort_named_canonical-canonicalized carriers stay in lockstep. KEY TRAP documented in-code: build_occurrence_cons_list must NOT be reused here — it builds Ref-nil (bare-pattern convention) while the term twin builds nullary Fn{nil}; reusing it re-opens the divergence (Ref/nullary-Fn identification = WI-436). STILL LATENT (pre-existing, ticket-documented, not in scope): try_occurrence_to_term/occurrence_to_term has no DotApply arm (lowers to Bottom); per-call symbol resolution rides the file's P3-deferral precedent (fold into the future TypeSyms consolidation). Generic [simp] engine unaffected (returns None for non-Apply/Constructor redexes before match_view).", at: "2026-06-12T11:26:43Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-425", description: some(value: "Make Expr::DotApply's structural view ISOMORPHIC to its dot_apply term twin (kb/term_view.rs occ_head / occ_pos_child / occ_named_child / occ_named_keys). WI-397 made DotApply structural (was Opaque-by-omission) so a fact embedding a DotApply (a compound-projection receiver `s.cell`) indexes in the discrim tree. But the structural view is NOT isomorphic to the dot_apply TERM the loader emits: load.rs (LoadBuildFrame::DotApply ~5483) ALWAYS builds `dot_apply(receiver, name, args: List[ApplyArg])` — arity-3, with `args = nil` even for a field access `r.name` — whereas occ_head maps a FIELD-form DotApply to arity-2 `{name, receiver}` (no args) and a METHOD form rides its call args as positional/named children instead of the `args` List. So a DotApply OCCURRENCE and its dot_apply TERM twin produce DIFFERENT discrim keys (Functor dot_apply -> Arity 2-vs-3 -> different NamedKeys), violating node-carrier-mirrors-term-structure. LATENT today: nothing matches a DotApply occurrence against a dot_apply term in the discrim tree — the typer dot engine uses a dedicated hand-matcher (try_fire_dot_rule, typing.rs ~1823, NOT the generic view); op-bodies are not discrim-indexed as facts; try_occurrence_to_term has no DotApply arm, so an occurrence never co-lowers to the arity-3 twin in the same tree. WI-397 is self-consistent (its projection receiver is an OCCURRENCE indexed by occ_head, never matched against a TERM). But the divergence is a soundness landmine the moment any consumer crosses the two carriers (discrim-query-is-the-unifier: a missed cross-carrier match is a WRONG answer, not just a perf loss). FIX: make occ_head/occ_pos_child/occ_named_child/occ_named_keys mirror the dot_apply term EXACTLY — head `dot_apply`, named children `{receiver, name, args}` where `args` is the List[ApplyArg] synthesized from the Expr's pos_args+named_args (each wrapped as an ApplyArg with optional name, matching the loader's mk_apply_arg encoding) — so a DotApply occurrence reads byte-identically to its hash-consed dot_apply term via TermView. RELATED latent items from the WI-397 /code-review, SUBSUMED by this fix: (a) type_head now classifies a bare DotApply Node as Parameterized{base: dot_apply} (the named_arity>0 fallthrough in type_head, typing.rs) — harmless today (the projection eliminator reads the receiver via extract_sort_ref_sym, which returns None for a DotApply, then the explicit DotApply branch), but sort_functor_of_view(DotApply) returns Some(dot_apply), so a future consumer calling extract_type/sort_functor_of_view on a DotApply receiver would treat `dot_apply` as a real sort; (b) occ_head reports named_arity = 2 + named_args.len() unconditionally while occ_named_keys only emits `name`/`receiver` keys guarded by lookup_symbol — an invariant worth asserting (sound today: name/receiver are interned at prelude load before any DotApply fact insert). ACCEPTANCE: a DotApply occurrence and the dot_apply term built for the same `r.name(args)` produce identical TermView head/keys/children + identical discrim keys; a regression test indexes one carrier and queries with the other and matches; full anthill-core green. Rust-only (kb/term_view.rs). Surfaced by the WI-397 /code-review (high effort)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T11:26:44Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-427", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-12 (1e5a6a2 + doc-fix commit; full workspace 53 binaries green). MECHANISM: tiny — the expected->argument half rides the EXISTING per-arg visit-hint channel (WI-275 hof_arg_hint) + the EXISTING expected consumption in check_apply_iter (WI-270 expected-seeding, which since WI-379 runs AFTER arg unification and fills only STILL-FREE params). New nested_call_arg_hint (typing.rs ~1999): an argument that is itself Expr::Apply gets the declared param type as its Visit expected IFF the type pins by EQUALITY = resolved_type_is_ground (no logic var, no sort-param ref, non-Term carriers excluded — so projection params k: s.cell.T auto-skip) AND no TypeExtractor.TypeVar form anywhere (new type_term_mentions_type_var walk; an op's own [X] in a param type is out of scope for a different call and a subtype wildcard — never push it). SOUNDNESS: inside the arg's own check the hint fills only still-free params and a contradicting hint binds nothing (boolean discarded), so a wrong hint cannot mask the normal arg-vs-param diagnostic, and no metavar is solved through <: (the WI-379 variance sidestep, expansion-during-unification.md). SCOPE FOLD-IN: the CONSTRUCTOR-FIELD twin proved real by probe (hold(poly()) failed X-unconstrained identically) — same gate via kb.entity_field_types in the Constructor visit arm; field types mentioning the sort's own params (cell: P) are non-ground -> no hint. Anchors un-ignored + new bidirectional_flow_constructor_field_pins: all 3 green (conforms; wrong-value rejected as String/Int64 not X-unconstrained; ctor field pins). /code-review (high): zero correctness findings (3 finder angles + verify all []); applied stale-doc fix. DELIBERATELY NOT TAKEN from review: folding the TypeVar test into resolved_type_is_ground (would silently change the WI-385 validation gate's other callers — separate decision); Apply/Ctor hint-block dedup (asymmetric: hof only on Apply); visit-time lookup_operation_info_full now also fires for has_call_arg (was hof-only) — one extra uncached OperationInfo lookup per call-bearing Apply, suite runtime unchanged (~106s), fold into any future op-info cache. REMAINING GAPS (by design): hint only for Expr::Apply args (DotApply/HoApply/Instantiation args un-hinted — extend if a real case shows); partially-ground param types (List[T = X]) take no hint (equality-pinning rule); let/return positions already had expected via WI-270.", at: "2026-06-12T13:26:47Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-427", description: some(value: "Typer: BIDIRECTIONAL expected->argument inference -- push the declared PARAMETER TYPE into an argument as a top-down checking hint, so a polymorphic argument whose type parameter is determined ONLY by the param type (a return-only type param) is pinned by the call context. Today Apply args are synthesized in ISOLATION (push_visit_no_hint), then unified against params -- so poly[X]() -> Wrapper[P=Inner[T=X]] passed to check(s: Wrapper[P=Inner[T=String]]) fails with 'X unconstrained' instead of inferring X=String from the param type. This is the expected->arg HALF of bidirectional inference; WI-379 delivered the arg->expected half (args-before-expected). SOUNDNESS: push the hint only where the param type pins by EQUALITY (a concrete/structured param type) -- NOT where it would force solving a metavariable through a <: subtype constraint (the hard case WI-379's args-first order deliberately sidesteps; variance note in expansion-during-unification.md). Acceptance: the bidirectional-flow checklist example (path-dependent-types.md). Depends WI-379. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-379"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T13:26:47Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-429", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-12 (0174f5d + review commit; full workspace 53 binaries green twice). TWO LAYERS as the WI-428-feedback scope demanded. (1) remap_name's NotFound arm: new load-BLOCKING LoadError::UnresolvedTypeName for a dotted Capitalized-MEMBER name in type position — gated by a new Loader.in_type_position flag set by a type_expr_to_child wrapper (the WI-440 in_effect_absence pattern), so every type slot that flows through the TypeChild lowering (op sigs, fields, aliases, requires/provides, bindings) is covered; lowercase-member dotted names (value places, Modify[result.a]) keep the advisory path. Verified the severity split is REAL: is_load_blocking gates the warning-vs-error filter in anthill-cli run/main + anthill-todo main (the ticket's 'anthill check shows only a warning' probe), while load_all itself fails on any error — the CLI flows are where the nominal silently rode. (2) End-of-load formation sweep validate_rigid_projection_formations (typing.rs): the loader records every formed RigidTypeProjection + source span on kb.rigid_projection_formations (both make sites in try_rigid_type_projection); the sweep drains+dedups (hash-consed TermId) and re-runs the eliminator's own resolve_rigid_projection once requires/provides are complete (after resolve_instantiations, before type_check_sorts) — a malformed projection in a NEVER-ELIMINATED position (entity field, fact/rule type slot) now fails the load: typo'd member (MemStore.Kye) and bare-spec subject (Storage.Key, 'conflate distinct carriers') both rejected in field position; valid manifest (MemStore.Key->String) and rigid-param (P.Key under requires Storage[C=P]) field projections load CLEAN. SURFACED + FIXED in the process: field_is_recursive resolved every Simple field type through the ERROR-PUSHING remap_name — a duplicate resolution that pushed a spurious advisory UnresolvedName for ANY projection-typed field (P.Key/MemStore.Key failed even the load_all flow pre-WI-429!); now a side-effect-free resolve_in_scope probe (+ preserved by_qualified_name fallback for fully-qualified self-references, review fix). Sweep of stdlib/examples/todo .anthill files = the corpus-wide green suite (nothing rode the nominal path, as the ticket expected). Tests: wi429_unresolved_type_name_test (6). Diagnostic text improvement when projecting off ops etc. remains naturally tied to future classifier growth. NOTE: sweep errors render via TypeError::Other->LoadError::TypeMismatch as 'type mismatch in <Sort>.<Member>: expected a well-formed type projection, got <reason>' — blocking, span-bearing.", at: "2026-06-12T13:56:08Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-429", description: some(value: "Loader FIX (against delivered WI-376 classifier): an unresolvable Capitalized dotted name in TYPE position must be a LOUD load error, not a warning + degenerate nominal sort. try_expr_carried_projection (load.rs ~6108) gates on a VALUE head; a type-receiver head (MemStore.Key / Storage.Key / P.Key) falls through to remap_name, which emits only an 'unresolved name' WARNING and mints an opaque nominal sort literally named 'Storage.Key'. PROBED 2026-06-10 (/tmp/tm-probe, anthill check): FALSE REJECT -- probeConcrete(k: MemStore.Key) -> String fails 'expected String, got MemStore.Key' though MemStore provides Storage[Key = String] (semantically it IS String); FALSE ACCEPT -- probeBareSpec(s: Storage, k: Storage.Key) -> Storage.Key = k TYPECHECKS, both positions conflated to one meaningless global nominal (Scala-2 T#K carrier-conflation arriving by accident; two Storage params in one signature would wrongly share it). Violates loud-error-over-silent-skip in BOTH directions. FIX: in type position, a multi-segment name that classifies as neither a projection (value head; type head once WI-428 lands) nor a resolvable qualified sort ref is a HARD error naming the supported spellings (s.Key value path; P.Key after WI-428). Independent of WI-428 -- deliverable first; the diagnostic text just improves when WI-428 lands. Sweep existing stdlib/examples/todo .anthill files for any spelling that silently rode the nominal path (none expected; the form was unwritable)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T13:56:08Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-374", author: "user", content: "PROBE ROUND 2026-06-12 (claimed, stopped for a design decision - no impl code written). Probes vs current main: (P1) FOREIGN op twoLists(a: List, b: List) called with List[Int64]+List[String] = ACCEPTED (the canonical false-tie sets subst.contradiction but nothing on the call path checks it; threading is first-binding-wins). (P1b) MEMBER append(intList, strList) = ALSO ACCEPTED (the sec.3-blessed tie is not enforced as a rejection either). (P2) bare producer return (-> Stream) consumed via Stream.count = REJECTED 'Elem unconstrained' - CORRECT per the type-not-provenance boundary (erasure is real; expansion supplies variables, never values); stays an error under any WI-374 variant, possibly with a better message. (P3) bare let-annotation 'let s : Stream = List.iterator(cons(1,nil))' ERASES the inferred Stream[T=Int64,E={}] so downstream count(s) is rejected 'Elem unconstrained' - the crisp 'keeps an unannotated reference usable' convenience case expansion should fix. Load-bearing acceptance items ALREADY HOLD on main: wi368 collect_iterator_list_is_pure + collect_iterator_threads_element_int are active and green (WI-380 explicit forms). ARCHITECTURE FINDING: the ticket's literal mechanism (context-blind fresh expansion at the unify boundary) CONFLICTS with delivered member parametricity - the canonical-var channel (unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref binding loader-cached Sort.T vars + PER-CALL local Substitutions in check_apply_iter/check_constructor_iter + WI-424 same-sort rigid seeding) IS the type-parameter-scoping.md sec.3-bullet-1 within-own-definition tie: cons cross-field ties, append element threading, wi357/wi375 all ride it; expanding every bare ref fresh severs it. The unify boundary cannot see member-vs-foreign; that context exists at LOAD (signature normalization, design doc sec.7 Layer 1) or at the SITE (annotation). DESIGN AMBIGUITY needing the user: sec.3 bullet 1 blesses the within-own-definition tie ('its constructors and own operations') while bullet 2's example f(a: List, b: List) declares two bare refs independent WITHOUT qualifying member-vs-foreign - append(xs: List, ys: List) sits exactly on that line (and today its tie is unenforced anyway, P1b). VARIANTS POSED: (A) site-scoped expansion - bare/partial let-annotations expand per occurrence at visit_type (fixes P3), foreign bare refs in op signatures normalize at load to per-occurrence vars (generalizes the canonical trick from per-(sort,param) to per-occurrence; per-call local substs supply freshness; member self-refs keep the canonical tie); (B) literal unify-boundary expansion + rewrite all member signatures to explicit/projection forms (big cascade across stdlib+wi357/wi375 fixtures, contradicts sec.3 bullet 1); (C) descope WI-374 to the P3 annotation-expansion convenience only, record foreign-signature hygiene as deferred feedback.", at: "2026-06-12T16:24:20Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-374", author: "user", content: "SESSION 2 (2026-06-12, after the design dialogue): user resolved the placement question -- 'context is used to unroll definitions' = export the declaration context into the term BEFORE the unify boundary (loader knows a signature's enclosing sort; the typing site knows an annotation's scope); unify_types stays a pure context-free term relation. Q2 decided: member tie ENFORCED. DELIVERED (commits d758df2 + 0a0a1ca, suite green 53/53 binaries, pushed): (1) LET-ANNOTATION REWRITE (user-confirmed P3 fix) -- unroll_annotation_with_inferred in LetAfterValue: bare/partial parametric annotation keeps the value's inferred params (bare Stream -> Stream[T=Int64,E={}]; partial keeps written T, takes E; alias shape resolves first per WI-381; written bindings stay authoritative; written-wildcard ? takes the inferred value); (2) MEMBER-TIE ENFORCEMENT -- check_apply_iter consults Substitution.contradiction_details (NEW: first conflict recorded PER VAR) after WI-385 arg validation, before expected-seeding; gated to callee parent being a SORT (kind_of) + sort_canonical_param_vids (immediate params only); conflicts vs the WI-424 seeded body rigid EXEMPT (sibling call at different instance keeps acceptance -- enforcing the rigid tie = separate open decision); each pair re-tested through unify_types so refinement (bare-vs-param, wildcards, row carriers/orders) is not a violation; append(intList,strList) now rejects, foreign twoLists stays independent; (3) MATCH-COVERAGE FIX -- scrutinee ctor set + exhaustiveness read base sort via sort_functor_of_view (parameterized scrutinees were SILENTLY SKIPPED, pre-existing; the annotation rewrite would have widened it) -- this un-hid the DANGLING-CASE grammar hazard, filed WI-446, 3 live .anthill sites fixed (store status_short/find_term_by_id, main collect_feedback_set: trailing case after a nested match attaches INNER); (4) docs: type-parameter-scoping.md sec.3 member/foreign split = declaration context + sec.4 delivered increments; tests wi374_expansion_test (13, 1 ignored anchor wildcard_annotation_keeps_inferred -- pre-existing types_compatible gap: a written ? binding slot reads as incompatible head, rejects before the merge; un-ignore when fixed). REVIEW ROUND (/code-review high, 7 angles): 4 confirmed regressions in d758df2 all fixed in 0a0a1ca (raw-TermId over-reporting, namespace-as-parent false member ties, first-detail masking, exhaustiveness skip extension). REMAINING WI-374 SCOPE (ticket stays Claimed): (a) FOREIGN bare refs in op signatures still share the foreign sort's canonical vars internally (benign: gated out of enforcement, nothing outside the sort can name Sort.T) -- normalize to per-occurrence vars at signature processing per the decided model; (b) then the PLAN stdlib revert to bare forms + projections; (c) the written-? conformance anchor.", at: "2026-06-12T17:26:55Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-374", author: "user", content: "HASH CORRECTION: the review-round commit is 506b1aa (not 0a0a1ca as the previous entry says).", at: "2026-06-12T17:27:09Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-374", author: "user", content: "SESSION 2 CONTINUED (2026-06-12, commits 408f319 + ec5dc27, suite 53/53 green, pushed): FOREIGN SIGNATURE EXPANSION DELIVERED -- expand_foreign_sort_application in check_apply_iter expands a FOREIGN bare/partial parametric sort application in callee PARAM positions to per-call fresh-var applications (per-occurrence freshness; foreign canonical vars no longer touched, sec.3 bullet 2 made real); member self-refs keep the canonical tie. Declared params come from the WI-424 sort_param_pairs_cache (no per-call symbol/fact scans); alias shapes via shared sort_application_parts (WI-381 in ONE place; bare-alias-of-bare-sort now reports the underlying base). INFERENCE/CHECKING SPLIT (review-confirmed necessity): expansion feeds ONLY the unify loops -- WI-385 validation AND WI-398 projection elimination read the params AS WRITTEN (written_params), because an expanded partial application's unbound fresh var is non-ground and the groundness gate silently skips mismatches (wi275 Function[Int64,Int64]-vs-String->Bool caught this). RETURN deliberately NOT expanded: zero benefit (bare<->param width rules accepted the same programs) + two regressions (un-grounds downstream arg validation; dangling vars in annotated-let merges) -- documented in-code. CONSTRUCTOR member-tie enforcement added (shared enforce_member_tie): cons(head: 1, tail: strList) and pair2(1, 'x') now reject (were silently accepted with first-binding-wins); runs after field validation, before the expected-seed; no rigid exemption needed (a rigid reaches the ctor subst only through a real field arg = genuine violation). Tests: wi374_expansion_test 17 active+1 anchor. REMAINING/DEFERRED (recorded, non-blocking): (a) NESTED positions are not expanded (a bare ref inside a written binding, Pair[B = List]) -- deep expansion has no driver yet; (b) Node-carried param types skip expansion (span plumbing; canonical channel still serves them); (c) written-? conformance anchor (types_compatible rejects a written ? binding slot); (d) per-call non-parametric params still pay one resolve_alias_shape fact scan (SortAlias-only index, ~100 facts -- cheap; memoize if it shows); (e) ctor gate reuses OperationTypeParams error context for entities (cosmetic). NEXT DECISION FOR USER: the ticket's reframed convenience scope is now implemented end-to-end -- remaining question is whether WI-374 DELIVERS here and the stdlib revert to bare forms + projections (the recorded PLAN, worded 'after WI-376 + WI-374 land') proceeds as its own step, or the revert is in-scope before delivery.", at: "2026-06-12T18:57:44Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-374", author: "user", content: "REVIEW ROUND 3 (2026-06-12, commit b5bec2d, suite 53/53 green, pushed): audited the two FIX commits (506b1aa, ec5dc27) that earlier rounds had not re-reviewed. One CONFIRMED bug (probe: order-dependent acceptance) + two adjacent gaps, all fixed: (1) first-conflict-PER-VAR recording masked a later genuine violation on the SAME var when the first conflict was benign-unifiable -- mkA's WI-384 arity-keeping 'B = ?_' wildcard pair recorded first, the real Int64-vs-String B conflict was never recorded; contradiction_details now records EVERY distinct conflict per var (dedup by structural_eq on attempted; growth bounded, contradicted substs discarded promptly on all consumer paths); regression test member_tie_wildcard_first_still_rejected pins BOTH argument orders. (2) enforce_member_tie's scratch re-unify now walks each recorded pair through the LIVE subst first (a pair carrying a var the call later pinned would spuriously re-unify); diagnostic renders walked forms. (3) the annotation-merge wildcard arm restricted to ANONYMOUS wildcards ('?'/'?_') so a written named-var tie (Pair[A = ?t, B = ?t]) is never independently overwritten -- latent today (the arm is dead for named vars behind the written-? conformance gap), fixed while cheap. Round-3 reviewer also verified clean: resolver-side detail growth (substs discarded on contradiction), parameterized binding-key symbol convention (all producers intern the SHORT name), sort_application_parts' parametric-shortcut soundness (a parametric sort is never an alias; effect params ARE in the WI-424 pairs), match-path consistency, and the three .anthill arm reorders. ALL WI-374 code is now review-covered: d758df2 (round 1), 408f319 (round 2), 506b1aa+ec5dc27 (round 3), b5bec2d (round-3 fixes validated by suite + the order-independence regression test).", at: "2026-06-12T19:35:15Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-447", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-374", description: some(value: "Typer: implement EXPANSION DURING UNIFICATION at every sort application (kernel-language.md section 8.1 'Expansion during unification', added 2026-06-03). A parametric sort referenced as a type with unbound parameters must unify as that sort applied to a FRESH VARIABLE per unbound parameter -- type parameters AND effect-row parameters (effects E; proposal 045 section 2) alike -- so the parameters participate even when no binding is written. TODAY this is only HALF-implemented: unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref (typing.rs:7965) binds a sort's loader-cached canonical param Vars from a PARAMETERIZED side against a bare sort_ref, propagating the parameterized side's bindings into the sort's return-type/effect positions. But a BARE-vs-BARE application (both sides sort_ref(S)) does NOT expand -- so when iterator(l: List) -> Stream returns a BARE Stream (list.anthill:67) and collect's param s: Stream is also bare, the call collect(iterator(xs)) unifies sort_ref vs sort_ref, binds NOTHING, and the Stream's element T and effect-row E never thread (the WI-368 leak: undeclared effect ?_). FIX (kb/typing.rs unify_types / the sort_ref arms): expand a bare sort_ref to its full fresh-var-parameterized form at the unification boundary so every sort application threads its parameters, including the effect row. The expanded effect-row fresh var must then CLOSE to the closed empty row {} against a pure declared context (row unification at the effect check -- WI-307 territory). SUBSUMES the special-cases it generalizes: WI-357 (carrier element threading) and WI-365 (effect grounding) both special-case what this general rule does uniformly. NOTE the surface gap: writing Stream[E = {}] in .anthill is ungrammatical (the SortBinding value slot is _type = simple/parameterized/variable/tuple/arrow; the {} effect-row literal is not in it -- the library/002:132 gap); the typer expansion + row-close is the route that needs NO new source syntax (the empty row IS representable internally: make_effect_expression_empty_row, mod.rs:3090; effects_rows Type node, term_view.rs). ACCEPTANCE: a bare-vs-bare sort application expands its params (incl. the effect-row) during unification; length(collect(List.iterator(xs))) typechecks pure (no undeclared ?_); an abstract-carrier walk (operation walk(c: C) effects E where C provides Iterable = collect(iterator(c))) stays effect-polymorphic; wi357/wi362/wi365 + full anthill-core green. BLOCKS WI-368, and is the principled generalization of WI-357/365. RELATED WI-307 (045 row-unification -- the row-close half). Rust-only (typer; scaland has no typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-376", "WI-429"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-12T20:19:44Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-437", description: some(value: "anthill-todo: PLUGGABLE BACKEND -- per-project work-item data source selection (examples/github-todo/docs/pluggable-backend.md; the multi-developer driver: git conflicts in workitems.anthill). Project config selects one of: local (files, today's IndexedFileStore via the WI-009 SingleFile convention), github (work items are GitHub issues), api (future standardized remote). Natural shape = the path-dependent-types design sec.5 factory: openStore(cfg) -> C ensures Store[C, ...] returning local/github/api behind one store interface -- THE first real consumer of WI-402's existential half (ensures Spec[C] + dict-out), which is parked on this ticket for exactly that reason. Builds on the delivered WI-009 cutover (backend selection lives in the bundle's store layer; WorkItemStore spec already separates spec from FileBasedWorkitemStore impl). NOTE from the 2026-06-11 WI-200 analysis: multi-instance Modify state (WI-200) is NOT needed for the CLI path -- one backend instance per invocation, distinct backend SORTS occupy distinct slots, and the bundle state rides Cell (per-allocation arena identity); WI-200 becomes relevant only for the api/server direction (many stores in one process)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-009", "WI-402"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-402", author: "user", content: "UNPARKED 2026-06-13 (user-decided): the parking edge is INVERTED -- WI-402 no longer depends_on the backend driver; instead WI-437 (pluggable backend) now depends_on WI-402, the natural technical direction (the consumer waits for the existential half it uses). Supersedes the PARKED/RE-PARKED notes above: WI-402 is no longer Claimed-but-BLOCKED. The existential half (ensures Spec[C] surface, interface-rooted existential C, dict-OUT at eval) is now the unblocked resume target and will be built against synthetic fixtures per the PARKED note's own observation that nothing in it consumes a WI-009/WI-437 capability.", at: "2026-06-13T03:29:22Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-402", author: "user", content: "SEQUENCED AFTER WI-383 2026-06-13 (user-decided): added depends_on WI-383. Rationale: WI-383's fill-as-requirement-discharge is the requires-side PRIMAL; the ensures/dict-OUT existential half here is its DUAL ('symmetric in concept, new implementation' per design). WI-402's MANIFEST existential (KVStore[C,K=String,V=Bytes]) rides the delivered WI-376/400 path and needs nothing from WI-383, but the FULLY-ABSTRACT-member existential (ensures Spec[C], members abstract) projects an abstract member off the existential carrier = exactly WI-383's projection-fill. Build the primal first. WI-402 stays Claimed (bound half delivered), now Claimed-but-blocked behind WI-383.", at: "2026-06-13T03:55:11Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "IMPL SCOPING 2026-06-13 (probe-grounded; CLAIMED). Overturned initial guesses — the gap is NOT manifest-alias/member-registration: probes show a top-level manifest alias 'sort MyInt = Int64' already does NOT deref as a return type ('expected MyInt, got Int64') — pre-existing NOMINAL-alias behavior, orthogonal to this ticket; and 'sort V=?' nested members ARE already registered as enclosing-sort type-params (load.rs:875-876). FOUNDATIONAL GAP (confirmed, blocks the fill desugar): op-type-params resolve in TYPE position (type_expr_to_value) but NOT in TERM/CLAUSE position (convert_term/remap_name). Tell (probe E): 'getV[T](target:T) -> T.V requires Resource[C=T]' — the return T.V resolves T correctly (error names 'getV.T'), but the SAME T in the requires clause is 'unresolved name T in scope <ns>'. Root: remap_name->resolve_in_scope and resolve_in_scope EXCLUDES type-params from non-enclosing parent lookups (intern.rs:355; test resolve_excludes_type_params). So the WI-383 fill desugar (get[Vi](target:T)->Vi requires T[V=Vi]) can't even form — the requires-clause carrier ref T doesn't bind. LAYERED PLAN: (L0, prereq) make op-type-params resolvable in requires/ensures clause spec-application arg positions (the type-level bindings inside a goal atom) — delicate (requires/ensures are load-bearing stdlib-wide; verify no regression). (L1) explicit-requires T.V: once T binds in the clause, RigidTypeProjection formation (resolve_rigid_projection, typing.rs:10245; spec_mentions_key + type_params_of_sort filter) should find the bound + concrete-fill CHECK grounds V against the provides fact (probe E target: getV(counterState):Int64 via 'provides Resource[C=CounterState,V=Int64]'). (L2) IMPLICIT licensing (§5.4 decided): loader MINTS the requires obligation for T.V / F[T=A] from the bound introducing T/F (or structured param) — no explicit clause. (L3) Modify ground-valued provider-fact bind: 'fact ModifyRuntime[T=R,V=...]' consulted at non-self-receiver get(target:T) (bind_spec_params_from_carrier extension). (L4) injective F[T=A] decomposition (likely free via parameterized-unify arm) + Miller guard for flexible rule-body heads. Probes saved in /tmp/p{A..E}.anthill conceptually; rebuild from this note. Tree green, WI-383 Claimed; resume at L0.", at: "2026-06-13T04:03:24Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "L0 ROOT-CAUSE CORRECTION (same session): define() DOES add an op-type-param to op_scope.locals (intern.rs define()), and resolve_in_scope checks .locals FIRST (intern.rs:339) — so IF an op-level requires clause were resolved in op_scope, T would resolve via locals before the parent type-param exclusion (355) ever applies. The exclusion is therefore NOT the root. The real gap: op-level requires/ensures clauses are resolved OUTSIDE op_scope (probe E warning says namespace scope 'e', not 'getV'), where T is not a local and the climb is then blocked. So L0 = trace WHICH pass/scope resolves op-level requires/ensures clause terms (likely a scan/pass-2 resolution at the enclosing namespace, or convert running with a non-op current_scope) and make it op-scope-aware so a clause's spec-application carrier ref binds the op-type-param. Sort-level requires (requires Eq[T]) works because it resolves in the SORT scope where T is local — contrast confirms the op-level path is the outlier. Tree green; resume L0 from here.", at: "2026-06-13T04:05:39Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-448", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "L0 DIAGNOSIS CORRECTED 2026-06-13 (supersedes the two prior L0 notes): the 'op-type-params unresolvable in requires clauses' claim was a PROBE ARTIFACT — my probe had a comment line before the op, which is a SEPARATE parse bug (filed as the new WI-448, parse/grammar; a comment before an operation mis-scopes its requires/ensures clause names to the namespace). In CLEAN code op-type-params resolve FINE in requires clauses. THE REAL GAP (confirmed) is in the TYPER, and it is WI-383's OWN fill-mechanism scope (not a separate ticket): resolve_rigid_projection (typing.rs:10288) licenses an op-type-param projection T.V by calling requires_chain(decl_sort), which reads SortRequiresInfo facts only. An OPERATION's 'requires Resource[C=T]' is stored on OperationInfo.requires (a different store), so for an op-type-param subject the chain is EMPTY and the op-level bound is never consulted -> 'no requires bound on getV.T mentioning T declares V'. FIX (WI-383 piece 2, fill mechanism): when the projection subject is an OP type-param, consult the enclosing operation's OperationInfo.requires for a bound whose spec mentions the subject (carrier) and declares the member; then the existing concrete-fill CHECK grounds the member against the carrier's provides fact (probe target: getV[T](target:T) -> T.V requires Resource[C=T], called getV(counterState) where CounterState provides Resource[C=CounterState,V=Int64], grounds T.V to Int64). RESUME HERE: typer formation, op-requires consultation for op-type-param subjects. WI-448 retired+refiled-as-parser-bug; WI-383 unblocked + Claimed.", at: "2026-06-13T04:27:45Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "FORMATION HALF DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 95c2cdc; suite green 443+, ticket STAYS OPEN). The op-type-param projection T.V now FORMS as a rigid neutral, licensed by the operation's OWN requires clause. IMPL: (1) classifier try_rigid_type_projection (load.rs ~6543) accepts an OPERATION parent for a type-param head (was Sort-only), so decl_sort = the operation; (2) resolve_rigid_projection (typing.rs ~10315) reads OperationInfo.requires via new op_requires_entries when decl_sort is an Operation, instead of the empty sort-level requires_chain. Multi-goal requires clauses (lowered to conjunction(...)) are flattened (push_op_requires_clause) per /code-review. Tests: wi383_op_type_param_projection_test (forms / undeclared-member-loud / multi-goal pass). /code-review (xhigh, 2 finder agents + sweep): FIXED conjunction-silent-drop; DOCUMENTED transitivity limitation (op path reads DIRECT requires only, not transitive closure -- conservative/sound over-reject, deferred, no driver). REMAINING (ticket open): (L-next) CALL-TIME CONCRETE-FILL GROUNDING -- getV(c) where c provides the spec must ground T.V to the carrier's bound member (today the neutral survives the call ungrounded -> 'got T.V'; anchor test op_type_param_projection_grounds_at_concrete_call is #[ignore]'d). This is the deferred fill-discharge step: the deep walk keeps the projection subject OPAQUE (subject-identity protection), so grounding needs a deliberate fill at the call site (discharge the requirement against the carrier's provides fact, read the member binding), NOT a passive sigma-walk. Then (L+1) IMPLICIT licensing (loader mints the requires, no explicit clause) and (L+2) the Modify ground-valued provider-fact bind.", at: "2026-06-13T04:52:34Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "CALL-TIME GROUNDING DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit fecb933; suite 447 green; ticket STAYS OPEN). The op-type-param projection T.V now GROUNDS at a concrete call -- getV(c) where c provides the licensing spec grounds T.V to the carrier's bound member (Int64); a wrong-typed body is rejected. MECHANISM: walk_type_deep's RigidProjection opacity is now CONDITIONAL (ground_rigid_projection_if_concrete) -- ground when the subject resolves to a CONCRETE sort, stay opaque while abstract (var/rigid-var/enclosing-sort-param = the abstract-fill forward case). This was the user's call ('change the opacity'): sound vs WI-400 because reading a member off an ALREADY-concrete subject binds no vars (non-injectivity P.K!=Q.K untouched; wi428 distinct tests green). BRIDGE: op-type-params have no SortAlias->var link, so the subject Ref lands on an unbound sibling var; the helper matches the subject BY NAME to the op's OperationInfo.type_params var (the one arg-inference binds). /code-review (xhigh) caught TWO soundness holes in the first cut (project_type_member first-match): Q2 provides-order dependence + Q3 unlicensed-carrier grounding. FIXED: grounding is now LICENSING-SPEC-PRECISE -- read member ONLY through a spec that an op requires-clause licenses (declares member + mentions subject) AND that the carrier provides (provider_spec_view_bindings), else stay opaque. Adversarial re-verify: both holes CLOSED, ambiguity safe (formation rejects >1 candidate), no new issue. Tests: grounds_at_concrete_call, grounding_rejects_wrong_type, grounds_via_licensing_spec_not_provides_order (Q2), unlicensed_carrier_does_not_ground (Q3). NOTE: same-base double-provision (provides Spec[V=A] AND Spec[V=B]) order-dependence is PRE-EXISTING in provider_spec_view_bindings (shared w/ WI-415..423 dispatch; WI-402 review feedback + WI-431 coherence already track it) -- not introduced here. REMAINING (ticket open): (L+1) IMPLICIT licensing -- loader MINTS the requires obligation for T.V (no explicit requires clause; the user-written surface per sec.5.4); (L+2) Modify ground-valued provider-fact bind (fact ModifyRuntime[T=R,V=...]); plus HK application F[T=A] injective decomposition + Miller guard (pieces 3/4). FORMS+GROUNDS via EXPLICIT requires bound is now end-to-end.", at: "2026-06-13T05:36:49Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "IMPLICIT LICENSING (self-carrier, structured member) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 23fda34; suite 451 green; ticket STAYS OPEN). The user can now write 'getV[T](target: T) -> T.V' with NO explicit requires; T.V is SELF-LICENSED and grounds at a concrete call to the carrier's OWN declared 'sort V' member (the resource-declares-its-value-type tie). IMPL: (1) formation (resolve_rigid_projection [] arm) -- an OP type-param projection whose op has no requires bound MENTIONING the subject forms as the rigid Neutral instead of erroring (a bound that mentions the subject but lacks the member stays a loud typo; sort-type-param projections unaffected); (2) grounding (ground_rigid_projection_if_concrete) -- when no licensing spec yields the member AND no requires mentions the subject, read the carrier's declared 'sort <member>' via an EXACT-symbol SortAlias lookup (sort_alias_target_exact) + Sort-kind gate, grounding only a GROUND target (type_value_is_ground). /code-review (2 finders) caught a soundness bug in the first cut: resolve_sort_alias's short-name FALLBACK leaked an UNRELATED sort's same-named member when the carrier's child sharing the name was an entity/op/body-sort. FIXED (exact-only lookup + Sort gate + ground-check); also closed the minor 'sort V = W' sibling-param over-ground. Adversarial re-verify: bug CLOSED, no new issue. Tests: self_carrier_grounds_via_declared_member, _rejects_wrong_type, _abstract_member_does_not_ground, _name_collision_does_not_ground. REMAINING (ticket open): (L+2) Modify ground-valued PROVIDER-FACT bind -- 'fact ModifyRuntime[T=R, V=...]' as the carrier's V source (the OTHER discharge the ticket lists; Cell uses it), the bind_spec_params_from_carrier extension; plus HK application F[T=A] injective decomposition + Miller guard (pieces 3/4). Self-carrier via STRUCTURED sort member now end-to-end (forms + grounds, sound).", at: "2026-06-13T06:11:24Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "B (MODIFY PROVIDER-FACT BIND) INVESTIGATED + ANCHORED 2026-06-13 (commit pending; NO functional change shipped — the fix regressed WI-424/441, deferred to a focused late-pass). FINDINGS: (1) the Modify get is a SPEC op ModifyRuntime.get(target: T) -> V where T is ModifyRuntime's OWN carrier type-param (a sort-type-param, not op-type-param). receiver_carrier=NotApplicable (target typed by the carrier param, not the spec sort), so the WI-424 carrier_param_receiver path (typing.rs:3769) handles it. (2) GOOD: the op-type-param + external-spec path ALREADY grounds via a STANDALONE fact (provider_spec_view_bindings reads it, WI-407), and Cell's REF-shape 'fact ModifyRuntime[T=Cell, V=V]' already ties a TYPED Cell's V (WI-424). (3) RESIDUAL GAP = the GROUND-valued provider-fact bind ('fact Box[T=IntCell, V=Int64]', the entity-resource case): bind_spec_params_from_carrier_param (typing.rs:7938) ground arm never fires for a value-param because typaram_ref_short_name returns Some for ANY leaf ref incl. Ref(Int64), so a ground concrete-sort binding takes the REF arm (recv_bindings miss -> None) instead of the ground arm. ROOT CAUSE PINNED. (4) A fix (ground-verbatim in the ref arm's or_else, excluding the carrier param via provides_spec_base_sym to avoid the 'expected BoxColl, got BoxColl' carrier double-bind) makes ModifyRuntime sound (case L: Box.rd(c) ties V=Int64, String read rejected). BUT doing it EARLY (before arg unification) disrupts WI-424/441 Iterable threading: binding BoxColl's 'Element = Int64' (a GROUND element, structurally identical to V) early -> 'EffP unconstrained' on find/foldLeft. (5) CLEAN FIX = a LATE pass: bind still-free ground value-params from the provider fact AFTER per-call threading (so Iterable's Element, threaded via iterator, is already bound -> guard skips it; ModifyRuntime's V, never threaded, is still free -> bound). Needs a new late hook (after the arg loops, recompute resolved_ret) + full WI-424/441 regression. Anchors: provider_fact_ground_value_ties_spec_op + _rejects_wrong_type (#[ignore]'d). DELIVERED so far this ticket: op-type-param projection forms+grounds (explicit requires + self-carrier structured sort member). REMAINING: this B late-pass; HK application F[T=A] + Miller guard (pieces 3/4).", at: "2026-06-13T07:11:56Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "OPACITY CLEANUP + B DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commits 00ea1c1 + 3a75272; suite 1710 green / 0 failed / 11 ignored; ticket STAYS OPEN for HK pieces 3/4). Drove the brainstorm docs/brainstorms/opaqie-in-deep-walk.md (the 'why is opaque left in walk_type_deep' question). RESOLUTION = the user-picked 'split walk from ground': the opacity was a SYMPTOM of fusing delta-reduction (call-time concrete-fill of an op-type-param RigidProjection) INTO the sigma-walk, so every walk (rigidify/effects/canonicalize) implicitly grounded and had to special-case the projection's identity slot. (1) OPACITY CLEANUP (00ea1c1, behavior-preserving): walk_type_deep / walk_type_deep_value are now PURE sigma -- a neutral head (RigidProjection OR ExprCarried) is an inert leaf (its subject/receiver is an identity slot expr_carried_zeta compares structurally; the WI-392/424 rigidify pass must not rewrite it). New resolve_type_deep_value (the ground=true sibling, via a threaded  flag through walk_type_deep_g/walk_type_deep_value_g/rewrite_type_occ_deep) does sigma + the call-time concrete-fill, wired at the 3 resolved_ret resolve points in check_apply_iter. Grounding fires at the SAME points/times/inputs as before (the walk only ever ground a concrete-subject op-type-param projection, which only arises there) -> behavior-preserving, 1708 green. /code-review (2 finders) adjudicated the one flagged asymmetry (effects walk stays pure sigma): CORRECT -- effect-position projections are ExprCarried eliminated upstream, and an op-type-param RigidProjection delta-grounds VALUE members only (Sort-gated; effects aren't type args, WI-301) -> documented, no code change. (2) B MODIFY PROVIDER-FACT GROUND BIND (3a75272): new LATE pass bind_ground_value_params_from_provider in check_apply_iter, AFTER the arg loops + BEFORE expected-seeding. Binds a STILL-FREE spec value-param to its GROUND provider-fact value (fact Box[T=IntCell,V=Int64] => Box.V:=Int64). ROOT CAUSE was bind_spec_params_from_carrier_param's ground arm never firing for a leaf sort ref (typaram_ref_short_name(Int64)=Some -> ref path -> misses the bare carrier's empty type-args). The STILL-FREE gate is the discriminator: a param an argument pinned (Iterable Element via the predicate; the carrier param via the receiver arg) is bound by now -> skipped (so NO WI-424/441 regression, which the EARLY bind caused via 'EffP unconstrained'); only a never-threaded return-only V is free -> bound. Runs before expected-seeding so the resource's V wins over the caller's -> String claim (closes the value-untied soundness hole: readStr(c)-> String now REJECTED). carrier_param_info hoisted/captured once and reused. Value normalize_ground_leaf'd (Fn{S}->Ref(S), WI-428). Both anchors un-ignored (provider_fact_ground_value_ties_spec_op / _rejects_wrong_type) + green. Two adversarial /code-review finders found NO soundness holes / NO regression (verified isEmpty/size free-Element bind is harmless + consistent with the WI-325 dispatch ground-provider check; same-base double-provision order-dependence is PRE-EXISTING WI-402/431, not introduced). REMAINING (ticket open): HK application F[T=A] injective decomposition (maybe free via the parameterized-unify arm -- probe with 002 CpsMonad bodies) + Miller-fragment guard for flexible heads in RULE BODIES only (pieces 3/4). Op-type-param projection (forms+grounds via explicit-requires, self-carrier structured member, AND now entity-resource provider-fact) is end-to-end.", at: "2026-06-13T08:12:22Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "CpsMonad PROBE DONE 2026-06-13 (commit ae70968; 7 regression tests; suite green). Pieces 3/4 outcome: PIECE 3 (injective decomposition of rigid-functor applications F[T=A]) is ALREADY FREE -- no source change. F[T=A] is the term backing Fn{F, named:[(T,A)]}, so the existing parameterized unify arm decomposes it structurally (functor-equality + per-binding unify). PROVEN SOUND by probe + locked in tests (anthill-core/tests/include/wi383_hk_application_test.rs): structured-param + full CpsMonad operation surface LOAD; decomposition ACCEPTS a correct application (reFmap pass-through), REJECTS a wrong binding (wrongFmap: F[T=B] vs F[T=A]) AND a wrong functor (confused: F vs G); nested F[T=F[T=A]] decomposes. PIECE 1 (structured-param member registration) confirmed DONE (loads). PIECE 4 (Miller guard): the monad-law rule bodies incl. the flexible head ?f(?x) LOAD clean; resolve_ho_apply/lower_ho_apply in resolve.rs already lower ?f(?x) at SLD time, so a strict Miller-fragment guard is a RESOLVER refinement (exercised only once concrete monad values flow through the rules) -- NOT a typer/WI-383 concern, and downstream of instances anyway. PIECE 2 (fill-as-requirement-discharge): the mechanism is already delivered for the PROJECTION case (T.V forms+grounds); the HK CONCRETE FILL (F := Option) is the same check/add step but needs INSTANCE FACTS to be exercised -- gated on WI-431 (referencing the abstract F concretely from outside, e.g. Box.F[T=Int64], does not resolve, as expected; concrete fill arrives via 'fact CpsMonad[F=Option, pure=optionPure, ...]'). DIAGNOSTIC FOLLOW-UP (noted, not fixed -- broader than HK): a same-functor distinct-rigid-binding clash prints 'expected F[T = ?_], got F[T = ?_]' (both rigids show ?_) because type-param alias vars from 'sort A = ?' are anonymous; the rigidify pass inherits the anonymous name. Distinct FUNCTORS print clearly (F vs G). A fix = name the 'sort X = ?' alias var after X (loader change; may touch tests asserting ?_). DISPOSITION (for user): WI-383's TYPER-LEVEL HK scope (pieces 1+3) is DELIVERED; the remaining HK usability (piece 2 concrete fill + piece 4 Miller-at-resolution) is genuinely gated on WI-431 instance facts. Options: (a) keep WI-383 open + add depends_on WI-431 for the HK-usability tail; (b) consider the typer mechanism complete and track HK usability solely under WI-431. The op-type-param projection + Modify provider-fact tie + HK application decomposition are all end-to-end at the typer level.", at: "2026-06-13T08:32:12Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "DISPOSITION DECIDED 2026-06-13 (user): WI-383 TYPER-LEVEL SCOPE COMPLETE -- op-type-param projection T.V (forms + grounds via explicit-requires, self-carrier structured member, and entity-resource provider-fact bind), the Modify value-type tie, and HK rigid-functor application decomposition are all end-to-end at the typer level. Added depends_on WI-431: the remaining HK USABILITY tail (piece 2 concrete fill F:=Option, and piece 4 Miller-fragment guard exercised at SLD resolution) is gated on instance facts (WI-431), which itself deps WI-391. WI-383 stays Claimed/open behind WI-431; paused here at a clean checkpoint. Deliverables this arc: opacity cleanup (walk/ground split, commit 00ea1c1), Modify provider-fact ground bind (3a75272), HK decomposition probe + 7 regression tests (ae70968).", at: "2026-06-13T08:35:42Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "user", content: "DIAGNOSTIC FIX DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit bdeca79; suite 1717 green) -- the noted rigid-display follow-up, now closed. rigidify_op_type_params names each skolemized type-param after its PARAMETER short name (was inheriting the alias var's anonymous name from 'sort A = ?'), so a binding clash reads 'expected F[T = ?A], got F[T = ?B]' instead of two identical 'F[T = ?_]'. Purely cosmetic: a rigid's identity is its fresh VarId (unification compares VarIds; SubjectKey keys on v.raw()), and the sole name-keyed var lookup (Expr::Var binder resolution, typing.rs ~2766) is gated on Var::Global, never Rigid -- no logic reads a rigid's name. Verified: full suite green, no test asserts on the old '?_' rigid display (the wi374 '?_' is a user-written wildcard, not a rigid). wi383_hk_application wrongFmap test strengthened to assert the ?A/?B distinctness.", at: "2026-06-13T08:54:26Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-430", description: some(value: "Typer FIX (against delivered WI-400; promoted from its deferred list per user 2026-06-10): carrier-precise requires matching for ExprCarried neutrals. abstract_member_declared_by_requires consults the declaring sort's WHOLE requires chain rather than only the bound whose carrier is the SPECIFIC param -- a sort with several params each carrying its own requires over-accepts a member projection off the wrong param (runtime-sound today: the mistyped signature is uncallable; but an over-acceptance, and with multiple same-spec bounds the neutral's identity is ambiguous). FIX DIRECTION: thread the param->bound mapping (WHICH requires entry binds THIS param as carrier) into neutral formation -- the ExprCarried-side counterpart of WI-428's carried canonical bound application. Natural end-state = the sec.5.3 convergence: an ExprCarried neutral whose receiver's type is carried by an instance var NORMALIZES to the var-keyed RigidTypeProjection, which is carrier-precise by construction (var-keying reproduces the delivered WI-400 verdicts: fields typed by the same P instance share the member; two State-typed params open fresh P instances so s.provider.K != t.provider.K; the genuinely expression-keyed remainder is the sec.5 erased plain field, whose type carries no instance var). Related: WI-419 (the dict-side twin of the same-spec-multi-bound ambiguity)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-428"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-13T09:27:53Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-430", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 4090495; suite 1406 green / 0 failed / 3 ignored). Carrier-precise ExprCarried neutral formation: project_type_member's abstract-receiver branch now threads the RECEIVER'S carrier SubjectKey (the field-type's alias var-id, from resolve_field_type) and gates each requires entry on spec_mentions_key, so only a bound WHOSE CARRIER IS the receiver param lends the member. MECHANISM: the carrier P of 'requires DataProvider[P]' auto-completes (WI-359 loader normalization) to a NAMED binding value carrying P's var-id, which spec_mentions_key reads (a positional carrier never survives); the receiver's var-id equals the binding's via sym_subject_key alias resolution (probe-confirmed Var(877)==Var(877)). DEDUP (/code-review altitude finding): extracted the carrier-precise candidate predicate into ONE shared helper requires_entry_lends_member, used by BOTH this gate AND resolve_rigid_projection's WI-428 rigid-projection candidate filter (one source of truth for which bound's carrier is this subject); ground_rigid_projection_if_concrete deliberately keeps its SEPARATE component calls (it needs the mentions-subject outcome alone to drive the self-carrier fallback). REVIEW (max-effort, 4 finders + verify): NO correctness/soundness regression. Two imprecisions noted, both INERT and INHERITED verbatim from the WI-428 rigid path: (a) spec_mentions_key matches the carrier in ANY top-level binding value, not strictly the spec's carrier SLOT (a param mentioned as a non-carrier binding e.g. Bar[C=Q, Extra=P] still licenses off P) -- sound because the ExprCarried neutral NEVER delta-grounds or absorbs demand (stays distinct from the genuine member, rejected downstream when a concrete value flows); exact carrier-slot precision is the sec.5.3 normalization end-state, shared with WI-419/WI-428. (b) the bool gate does NOT reject multi-candidate (unlike resolve_rigid_projection's loud ambiguity) -- sound because the neutral's identity is receiver-expr+member, never a bound-selected grounding. Tests: wi430_carrier_precise_projection_test (4: wrong-param rejected, right-param accepted, mirror rejected, genuinely-missing-member still loud; red-green confirmed -- negatives FAIL pre-fix).", at: "2026-06-13T09:28:37Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-449", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-391", description: some(value: "Decide the interpretation of 'fact Spec[...]' vs 'provides Spec[...]' (re-filed; was a local WI-389 that collided with the remote's WI-389/HandlerAction on sync). The two emit DIFFERENT SortProvidesInfo specs for CONCRETE ground bindings: 'fact Stream[T=Int]' lowers T to Ref(Int) via parse convert_type_value, but 'provides Stream[T=Int]' lowers T to name_to_sort_term(Int) (a nullary Fn) via sort_inst_to_value (empirically TermId 2583 vs 12; WI-366 B1 probe). WI-366 B1 already fixed the LOSS half (a written effect-row {} no longer dropped on the fact head); THIS is the distinct NON-LOSS half. OPEN DESIGN QUESTION FIRST (user) -- do NOT presuppose byte-identity is the goal; the difference MAY be correct: step 0 is to DECIDE how to interpret a fact relative to a provides. WHY IT MAY BE LEGITIMATE (user): on the FACT (term) path we do NOT KNOW that 'Int' is a TYPE -- convert_type_value lowers the binding as an OPAQUE NAME (Ref), since a 'fact Spec[T=Int]'s bracket bindings are logical terms with no type-checking context; the PROVIDES (type-aware) path knows it's a type, so lowers it as a sort/type term (name_to_sort_term -> nullary Fn). So the Ref-vs-Fn divergence reflects a type-KNOWLEDGE asymmetry. DECIDE: do a fact's bracket bindings carry type info (-> unify the two paths, route fact-head emission through sort_inst_to_value, byte-identical SortProvidesInfo) OR are they deliberately untyped logical terms (-> the difference is CORRECT; document the intended semantics of each and close)? Acceptance is CONDITIONAL on that decision, not 'make byte-identical' unconditionally. Interacts with kernel-language.md sec.1418 (fact->SortProvidesInfo convention) and the wi210/wi357 dispatch canaries (which already rely on Ref=wildcard vs Fn=concrete -- evidence the difference may be intentional). Relates: WI-366 B1 (predecessor), WI-387 (aligned the type-PARAM half T=T -> Ref on both)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-13T10:56:05Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-391", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commits 0bc440f + review cleanup 4bb93a2; suite 466 wi_tests green). DECISION (user 'normalize early'): the fact-vs-provides binding-shape divergence is an IMPLEMENTATION ARTIFACT, not a semantics -- dispatch is KIND-aware (dispatch_values_match -> is_sort_param_symbol reads the symbol's kind: Ref(Int)=concrete, Ref(T)=wildcard, tolerating BOTH shapes), and the kernel treats fact/provides as duals. FIX (normalize early at the PRODUCER): new sort_binding_to_value lowers a concrete bare-sort binding VALUE to the canonical Ref(S) -- the one extractable bare-sort shape (type_head: a nullary Fn{S} is malformed -> TypeExtractor::Error), byte-identical to the fact path's parse Ref. The spec-IDENTITY slot (bare 'provides Spec') keeps the Fn{Spec} functor unwrap_spec_view needs; only the binding-VALUE position normalizes. Subsumes WI-387 (aligned only the T=T param half). PAYOFF: the 4 late normalize_ground_leaf consumer-patches are now DEAD BY CONSTRUCTION (no producer emits a nullary-Fn binding value) -- probe-proven (0 actual transforms across the whole suite incl. stdlib + SortAlias targets), RETIRED + function removed. normalize_spec_binding_type KEPT (live structured-binding gate at resolve_rigid_projection + bare_provider_binding_precise). /code-review (max effort, 3 finders): NO correctness bug, NO consumer breakage -- both finders independently confirmed every binding reader is shape-agnostic for concrete sorts (sort_sym_of_term/is_type_param_value/values_structurally_equal treat Ref==Fn; specificity scoring routes both through the same arm); fixed 2 stale doc refs. Tests: wi391_binding_extractability_test (fixture: concrete binding extracts SortRef + fact/provides BYTE-IDENTICAL; stdlib-wide sweep: every binding non-Error). DEFERRED -> WI-449 (filed, typing tag, deps WI-391, user-decided): FACT-path positional/nested parameterized binding canonicalization -- (1) fact Effect[T = Modify[?]] -> positional Fn{Modify, pos:[?]} still Error (sweep bounds+tolerates structurally); (2) convert_instantiation_term FLATTENS nested Inner[Int64] -> Ref(Inner) lossily (pre-existing, diverges from provides). WI-391 unified the BARE-SORT half; WI-449 = the parameterized half.", at: "2026-06-13T10:56:07Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-449", description: some(value: "Loader+parse: canonicalize POSITIONAL/nested parameterized binding values on the FACT path so every stored type-position value extracts non-Error (completes the WI-391 §5.3 extractability acceptance; removes the WI-391 sweep carve-out). Two gaps the WI-391 stdlib sweep bounded+deferred: (1) 'fact Effect[T = Modify[?]]' lowers the binding value Modify[?] to a POSITIONAL Fn{Modify, pos:[?]} (parse convert_type_value / fact head), which type_head classifies as TypeExtractor::Error (only Fn{base, named} is Parameterized; a positional-only Fn is malformed) -- map positional->named at the producer, as the provides path's sort_inst_to_value already does. (2) convert_instantiation_term (parse/convert.rs ~1552) FLATTENS a nested positional parameterized binding Inner[Int64] -> Ref(Inner), DROPPING the type args (intentional 'preserve compatibility' but lossy, and diverges from the provides path which preserves them) -- so fact vs provides parameterized bindings are NOT byte-identical (WI-391 unified only the bare-sort case). DECIDE: canonicalize at load (re-lower fact binding values like sort_inst_to_value) vs defer-to-load (carry the TypeExpr like WI-366 effect rows). ENTANGLED with effect-kind registration (the Effect[T = Kind[?]] facts; WI-301: effects aren't type args) -- verify effect dispatch unaffected. Acceptance: the WI-391 sweep's positional-parameterized carve-out removed, every stdlib SortProvidesInfo/SortRequiresInfo binding non-Error. Relates WI-402 structured-binding #[ignore] anchor (structured_provider_binding_accepted), WI-391 (the bare-sort half)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-391"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-13T11:46:42Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 1 (RULE 1 — FACT-SIDE COVERAGE) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit c1c90c6; suite 1413 green + 3 new wi431 tests; ticket STAYS OPEN for the runtime/coherence pieces). PROBE FIRST: the §5.4 instance fact 'fact CpsMonad[F = Option, pure = optionPure, flatMap = optionFlatMap]' ALREADY LOADS as a provision (maybe_emit_fact_provides_info derives carrier = Option from the F binding; the op-valued bindings pure/flatMap are PRESERVED in the SortProvidesInfo SortView) — the ONLY blocker was the coverage check check_provider_operations (UnbackedProviderOperation: 'Option provides CpsMonad but backs no operation pure'), which consulted only carrier-own / spec-default / builtin backing, never the fact's op bindings. FIX: check_provider_operations now also treats a spec op BOUND in the instance fact (to an Operation symbol) as backed — coverage moves to the fact. New helpers op_bound_in_instance_fact (reads the provision's SortView bindings via unwrap_spec_view, short-name match via short_name_of) + binding_value_is_operation (reuses provides_spec_base_sym + kind_of==Operation — the SAME op-discriminator sort_view_substitution uses; review cleanup). A type-valued binding (F = Option, a Sort) is never mistaken for op-coverage (symbol kind discriminates); a type-only provision (provides Stream[T=X]) has no op binding so behaviour is unchanged (1413 green proves no stdlib regression). An op neither bound nor defaulted stays a LOUD UnbackedProviderOperation. Tests wi431_instance_fact_coverage_test (3): op-binding-covers (accept), missing-op-binding-is-loud (reject + the bound pure NOT reported), spec-default-op-needs-no-binding. /code-review (high, 3 finders + verify): NO correctness bug (short-name ambiguity REFUTED — bindings are per-provision spec_view-scoped); both cleanups applied. REMAINING (ticket open, all §5.4): (A) RUNTIME DICT-BUILDER = the meat — eval dispatch must read the fact's op bindings to resolve pure/flatMap on an Option (build_concrete_dispatch_dict / build_dep_projection Strategy 3 / emit_tree_as_projection build the dict from the impl sort + sub-requires today, NOT from fact op-bindings; calling pure(opt) currently fails to RESOLVE — sound but unusable). (B) OP-BINDING SIGNATURE VALIDATION — the bound op's type is not checked against the spec op's expected type with F:=carrier substituted (latent: nothing dispatches these yet, no unsoundness today; pairs with A). (C) COHERENCE (rule 2) — two instance facts for the same (spec, carrier) = loud ambiguity at the use site (WI-419 canonical-application identity). (D) WITNESS-SORT (rule 3) — verify/test that 'sort OptionMonad provides CpsMonad[F=Option]' indexes by sort_ref not carrier (invisible to Option receivers). (E) CARRIER-DERIVATION robustness — maybe_emit_fact_provides_info (load.rs ~8019) derives carrier from named_terms.first(); canonical arg-sorting protects the Capital-type-param case (probed: op-bindings written first STILL derive Option), but a spec whose carrier param sorts AFTER an op name would pick the op -> fact_value_to_sort_sym None -> SILENT early-return (pre-existing, violates loud-error; derive from the spec's carrier param + make a failed derivation loud when the carrier/coherence increment is built). Next session = the eval half (A).", at: "2026-06-13T12:12:42Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 2 (EVAL DISPATCH — the runtime dict-builder half) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 661ea7f; suite 1414 green + 1 new eval test + 1 ignored coherence anchor; ticket STAYS OPEN). PROBE: a spec-op call on a concrete instance-fact carrier — combine(tag,tag) where Tag provides Combiner via 'fact Combiner[T=Tag, combine=tagCombine]' — TYPECHECKS (first-order spec: typer binds T:=Tag from the arg, no concrete-fill) but died Err(UnknownOperation{combine}) at eval. ROOT: value-directed dispatch resolve_spec_op_target_by_value (eval.rs ~479) bottoms out at sort_ops_lookup(carrier, op), which for a RETROACTIVE instance returns the INHERITED BODY-LESS SPEC OP itself (== target, no real impl), so step-3b's 'if impl_target != target' skipped it. FIX (eval.rs): filter out that body-less spec-op placeholder (.filter(op != spec_op)) then .or_else(instance_fact_op_binding(carrier, spec, op)) — the new pub(crate) typer helper reads the op-valued binding off the SortProvidesInfo SortView via provider_spec_view_bindings. A carrier that OWNS a real override still wins (filter keeps it). The op-binding lookup is now ONE shared accessor instance_fact_op_in_bindings used by BOTH the loader coverage check (increment 1) AND this eval dispatch (binding_value_is_operation folded in; addresses the increment-1 review's altitude note). Test instance_fact_op_dispatches_at_eval: combine(tag(1),tag(2)) -> tagCombine -> 99 end-to-end (carrier MUST be a SORT — a bare namespace-level entity has no constructor_parent_sort, so carrier_of returns None and value-directed dispatch never classifies it; real carriers Option/List are sorts). /code-review (high, 2 finders + verify): refactor confirmed behavior-preserving (find_map continues past a same-short-name non-op binding, == old 'any'); ONE real finding = the KNOWN coherence gap (rule 2): two instance facts for the same (spec,carrier) -> provider_spec_view_bindings picks the FIRST silently (pre-existing first-provider-wins contract shared w/ WI-402/415..423, NOT introduced here; before this increment NOTHING dispatched so it was vacuously 'loud'). Added #[ignore]'d anchor duplicate_instance_facts_are_a_loud_ambiguity pinning the rule-2 target. SCOPE THIS INCREMENT = the VALUE-DIRECTED path (spec-op call on a concrete instance-fact carrier). REMAINING (ticket open): (A2) the DICT-THREADED path dispatch_via_sort_ops_table — generic 'requires Spec[F]' bodies whose call-site dict is built via build_dep_projection Strategy 3 (SLD against SortProvidesInfo) then threaded; same sort_ops_lookup-miss needs the same fallback there, gated on Strategy 3 actually finding the instance fact; (B) op-binding SIGNATURE validation; (C) COHERENCE rule 2 (un-ignore the anchor; loud at LOAD, keyed on WI-419 canonical application — crude '>1 fact' over-rejects, do it right); (D) WITNESS-SORT rule 3; (E) carrier-derivation robustness (load.rs ~8019). The HK concrete-fill F:=Option (CpsMonad direct call 'expected Option got F[T=?_]') is the TYPER half = WI-383 piece 2, still gated/coupled. Increments 1+2 = instance-fact ops now LOAD (coverage) and DISPATCH (value-directed eval) end-to-end for a first-order spec.", at: "2026-06-13T12:44:26Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 3 (RULE 2 — COHERENCE) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 9ae04e3; suite 1420 green incl. 5 new coherence tests; ticket STAYS CLAIMED). Two DISTINCT instance facts for the same (spec, carrier) each supply a different dictionary; increment 2's value-directed dispatch silently picked the FIRST (provider_spec_view_bindings first-provider-wins). FIX: check_provider_operations (typing.rs) now groups op-binding provisions by (spec, carrier) and rejects a group with >1 DISTINCT canonical application via new load-blocking LoadError::AmbiguousInstanceFact (load.rs: variant + Display + format_with_source + is_load_blocking). Identity = full canonical application (WI-419/§5.4), realized FREE by hash-consing: identical facts share one spec_view (idempotent, collapsed by per-group !views.contains dedup); only genuinely-differing facts collide. Restricted to op-binding provisions via new provision_binds_any_op — a type-only provision (provides Stream[T=X], fact ModifyRuntime[T=Cell,V=V]) supplies no dict and never participates, so NO existing provides/type-only fact over-rejected (full suite proves it). Op-discriminator factored into ONE shared binding_op_symbol helper now used by coverage(rule1)+dispatch(inc2)+coherence(rule2) (closes inc1 review altitude note). SYMBOL IDENTITY compared RAW (no canonical_sort_sym): coherence is PROVIDER-to-PROVIDER (both resolve to canonical symbols + hash-cons same spec_view) UNLIKE caller-to-provider dispatch which must canonicalize; canonicalizing only the key would FALSE-flag identical facts. SCOPE: design says 'ambiguity at the use site' but this realizes it at LOAD (global coherence) — coincides in the current model (no selection mechanism = two distinct dicts for one (spec,carrier) can never be disambiguated, so they error the moment both load); use-site/scoped reporting is the deferred refinement. Un-ignored anchor duplicate_instance_facts_are_a_loud_ambiguity; added idempotent (same+different field order), distinct-carrier, cross-namespace (distinct=>ambiguous, identical=>idempotent) tests. /code-review high (7 finder angles): 2 correctness claims (raw-symbol grouping miss; field-order false-ambiguity) both EMPIRICALLY REFUTED by the cross-namespace + different-order tests; cleanup findings (O(n2) grouping, error-path .to_string) intentional/negligible. REMAINING (ticket open): (A2) dict-threaded dispatch (dispatch_via_sort_ops_table, generic requires Spec[F] bodies, same sort_ops_lookup-miss fallback gated on Strategy 3 finding the fact); (B) op-binding SIGNATURE validation; (D) WITNESS-SORT rule 3; (E) carrier-derivation robustness (load.rs ~8019 silent early-return). HK concrete-fill F:=Option = WI-383 typer half.", at: "2026-06-13T13:16:30Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 4 (A2 — DICT-THREADED DISPATCH) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 811cd11; suite 1423 green incl. 3 new dispatch tests; ticket STAYS CLAIMED). A generic body requires Spec[T] calling a spec op on abstract T routes through the requirement-dict path (apply_within + threaded dispatching dict), not value-directed. PROBE/TRACE confirmed: Strategy 3 (build_dep_projection SLD vs SortProvidesInfo) DOES build the dict with functor=carrier for an instance fact, but dispatch_via_sort_ops_table (eval.rs ~448) read only sort_ops_lookup(carrier,op) -> body-less spec-op placeholder, unwrap_or(fn_sym) -> handed back the placeholder = THE MISS. FIX (mirrors increment 2's value-directed fallback): filter the placeholder (op != fn_sym), else instance_fact_op_binding(carrier, spec, op) with spec via lookup_spec_op_dispatch(fn_sym); genuine spec rewrite-rule/builtin default still rides fn_sym fall-through, real carrier override still wins. KEY INSIGHT (why first-order didn't expose it): for combine(x:T,y:T) value-directed dispatch reads the carrier from a T-typed ARG and rescues the same miss, masking it. The strict acceptance test uses zero()->T (carrier ONLY in result, no arg) so value-directed cannot reclassify and the threaded dict is the ONLY route: dies UnknownOperation without the fix. This is ALSO the prerequisite for the HK case (CpsMonad.pure, WI-383 — ops carry the carrier only in the result). TESTS: instance_fact_op_dispatches_via_threaded_dict (strict, nullary zero); instance_fact_op_dispatches_when_spec_has_requires (spec ITSELF requires another spec — regression guard: instance-fact-derived dict is an arity-0 LEAF so expand_dispatching_dict arity check stays 0==0, no spurious EvalError::Internal); instance_fact_eq_powers_list_member (REALISTIC: Color gets Eq via fact Eq[T=Color,eq=colorEq], List.member finds it). /code-review high (7 angles): 2 correctness claims (placeholder-filter behavior change; expand_dispatching_dict arity mismatch for spec-with-requires) BOTH empirically REFUTED (latter by the new spec-has-requires test). Altitude: the filter+fallback shape now duplicated across value-directed + dict-threaded paths — left for WI-383 (3rd path makes a shared resolve_carrier_op helper unambiguous). HOT PATH (stdlib member/Eq, WI-415/418) all green. REMAINING (ticket open): (B) op-binding SIGNATURE validation; (D) WITNESS-SORT rule 3; (E) carrier-derivation robustness. HK concrete-fill F:=Option = WI-383 typer half (this A2 fallback is its eval-side prerequisite).", at: "2026-06-13T17:23:17Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 5 (B — OP-BINDING SIGNATURE VALIDATION) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit 580282c; suite 1428 green incl. 5 new sig tests; ticket STAYS CLAIMED). Increments 2/4 made instance-fact dispatch LIVE, so a mis-bound op (fact Combiner[T=Tag, combine=unrelatedOp]) silently dispatched to a wrongly-typed impl — active soundness gap. FIX: new load-blocking pass check_instance_fact_op_signatures (typing.rs) + LoadError::IncompatibleInstanceBinding (load.rs: variant+Display+format_with_source+is_load_blocking). For each op binding, with σ (spec type param -> provision binding) applied to the spec op's types: same param ARITY; each PARAM type contravariant-compatible (σ(spec) <: bound, bound accepts spec arg); RETURN covariant-compatible (bound <: σ(spec)); via types_compatible. GROUND-GATED (substitute_impl_params_alloc + contains_type_param): only when σ-substituted spec type AND bound type both ground — so HK bindings whose param stays parametric (CpsMonad.pure: F[T=A], σ leaves Option[T=A] with op's own A) FAIL OPEN, deferred to WI-383; arity always checked. LOAD-BEARING SUBTLETY (debugged via trace): σ MUST key on the RESOLVED spec-param symbol (Combiner.T, what spec op Ref(T) references), NOT the raw binding-key copy (resolved in the fact's scope) — else substitute_impl_params_alloc's Symbol-equality match silently no-ops, spec type stays parametric, ALL checks fall open (observed: param/return skipped until fixed). New helper type_param_sym_of_binding returns the resolved sym; is_type_param_binding delegates to it. NOTE: check_override_refinement keys σ on the raw key too but its effect check is fail-open by design (under-checks, never misfires) — left as-is (WI-347 scope; avoid new false-positives on parametric providers). DEDICATED pass (not folded into check_override_refinement) — carrier-own path untouched (zero regression), instance facts have no stdlib presence so it can be strict (suite proves no false-reject). TESTS: well-typed loads clean; wrong arity / wrong param type / wrong return type each loud 'signature-incompatible'; well-formed HK CpsMonad binding fails open. /code-review high (7 angles): NO correctness findings survived (variance dirs confirmed; ground gate sound; refactor behavior-preserving; spec-symbol-copy hazard mitigated by global by_qualified_name interning + SortInfo-per-sort). Applied 1 cleanup (hoist per-provision carrier_qn/spec_qn); left σ-snapshot dup + O(P*B*opinfo) lookup as-is (match check_override_refinement precedent; consolidate later w/ the increment-4 resolve_carrier_op note). REMAINING (ticket open): (D) WITNESS-SORT rule 3; (E) carrier-derivation robustness. HK signature validation rides WI-383.", at: "2026-06-13T17:48:11Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "INCREMENT 6 (E — CARRIER-DERIVATION ROBUSTNESS) DELIVERED 2026-06-13 (commit b82eba2; suite 1431 green incl. 3 new (E) tests; ticket STAYS CLAIMED). maybe_emit_fact_provides_info (load.rs ~8100) derived the namespace-level carrier from named_terms.first(), which is NOT reliably the carrier: named args canonicalize by SYMBOL INDEX (declaration order) and a POSITIONAL carrier is translated+APPENDED after the named bindings, so `fact Combiner[Tag, combine = tagCombine]` put `combine` first -> fact_value_to_sort_sym returns an op Ref's symbol UNCHECKED -> provision filed under the operation tagCombine, not Tag -> value-directed dispatch on a Tag value looked up SortProvidesInfo(Tag, Combiner), missed, died UnknownOperation. FIX: carrier = the non-op (type) binding of LOWEST symbol index (= first-declared carrier/Self param) via `.filter(binding_op_symbol.is_none()).min_by_key(s.index())`, positional fallback for non-parametric (WI-407). Robust to written order, positional carriers, AND a higher-kinded carrier (CpsMonad's F) that type_params_of_sort OMITS — it returns the `= ?` params (A,B) only, so an earlier spec_params[0]-by-name attempt mis-picked A and broke the CpsMonad coverage tests; min-by-index over non-op bindings is the correct selector. LOUD: a parametric instance fact (binds >=1 op, spec_params non-empty) whose carrier can't be derived now pushes load-blocking LoadError::UnresolvableInstanceCarrier instead of the silent early-return.\n\nLATENT COHERENCE BUG exposed + fixed: assemble_sort_view_value builds the spec view via kb.alloc, which hash-conses Term::Fn named_args AS-GIVEN (the make_* builders sort, alloc does NOT) -> two field-order-different facts formed DISTINCT spec views. The pre-(E) carrier mis-derivation had HIDDEN this (the two field-order facts landed in DIFFERENT (spec,carrier) groups), so identical_instance_facts_different_field_order_are_idempotent passed for the WRONG reason; correcting the carrier put both under (Combiner,Tag) and surfaced a false AmbiguousInstanceFact. FIX at the shared producer: named.sort_by_key(s.index()) -> order-insensitive spec view for fact + provides (WI-449 byte-identity preserved). binding_op_symbol made pub(crate) (the one shared op-discriminator, reused by the carrier filter).\n\n/code-review high (4 finder angles: line-by-line, removed-behavior, cross-file, cleanup/altitude): NO confirmed correctness bug — stdlib has ZERO op-binding facts so the carrier change cannot regress existing provisions (finder B verified all namespace facts: Eq/Lattice/Modifiable/Effect/ModifyRuntime/VectorSpace/BulkStore/QueryableStore — none bind ops); sorting is read by name/iteration not position; the loud error is correctly scoped. Applied 1 refinement (gate the loud error on a parametric spec so a contrived non-parametric op-fact never reports the nonsensical 'the carrier' param; dropped the unwrap_or_else fallback). Altitude notes left out-of-scope/intentional: canonicalize-in-kb.alloc (too broad — would touch every Term::Fn; the make_* builders already sort, assemble was the one gap); a missing carrier-param KB helper; binds_any_op vs provision_binds_any_op (different representations — raw named_terms vs spec_view).\n\nTESTS: instance_fact_carrier_param_after_op_resolves_and_dispatches (positional carrier + named op; value-directed dispatch misses before the fix, returns 99 after); instance_fact_unresolvable_carrier_is_loud (op-bearing fact, carrier T unbound -> loud); type_only_fact_unbound_carrier_stays_lenient (bare parametric fact, no op binding -> no error).\n\nREMAINING (ticket open): (D) WITNESS-SORT rule 3 — verify/test that `sort OptionMonad provides CpsMonad[F=Option]` indexes the provision by sort_ref (OptionMonad), NOT the carrier (Option), so its ops are invisible to Option-valued receivers (provides path, not the fact path). HK concrete-fill F:=Option (CpsMonad direct call) = the WI-383 typer half. After (D), WI-431's own scope is complete.", at: "2026-06-13T18:38:20Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-450", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-431", author: "claude", content: "(D) WITNESS-SORT (rule 3) — RESOLVED 2026-06-13 (w/ user) by investigation + decision, NOT code. Probed the §5.4 rule-3 caveat. FINDING: a witness sort (`sort TagCombiner provides Combiner[T=Tag]` + member `combine`) is invisible to VALUE-DIRECTED dispatch (`combine(tag,tag)` -> UnknownOperation: provision filed under sort_ref=TagCombiner; value-directed keys on sort_ref==receiver-sort, load_provides_clause sets sort_ref=enclosing sort), BUT IS REACHABLE and dispatches via the REQUIRES-dict path (a `Box requires Combiner[T]` consumer -> Ok(99); the requires SLD matches the spec APPLICATION, not sort_ref) — confirmed sound (TagCombiner genuinely is-a Combiner[Tag]). So rule 3's flat \"NOT supported / invisible\" is TOO STRONG.\n\nDECISION (w/ user): the \"carrier\" — privileging ONE spec type-param as the dispatch key — is an ARTIFACT of value-directed dispatch's value->its-sort->lookup-by-sort_ref mechanism, NOT a principle. The requires path is ALREADY param-agnostic (unifies the whole spec application). The fix = make value-directed dispatch UNIFY THE SPEC APPLICATION against provisions (reusing the bindings the typer already computes — T:=Tag from args, increment 2 — instead of collapsing to carrier_sym + sort_ref match), dropping the carrier privilege; witnesses then resolve identically to facts. Dispatch-model change with hot-path risk (eq/List.member/Iterable.find+map, WI-415/418/424), so scoped as its OWN ticket WI-450 (depends WI-431) rather than forced into (D). Design §5.4 rule 3 REWORDED to the decided direction (param-agnostic, carrier-is-artifact). NO pinning tests written — the current value-directed-invisible behavior is TRANSITIONAL (WI-450 reverses it; pinning it would just be deleted). Out-of-scope of WI-450 (genuinely different shapes): self-receiver specs (Stream.splitFirst(s:Stream), no param pinned by an arg, WI-357); result-determined params (pure(a:A)->F[T=A], F only in the result, from expected type, WI-383 HK fill).\n\nWI-431 OWN SCOPE COMPLETE: increments 1 (rule-1 coverage) + 2 (value-directed eval dispatch) + 3 (rule-2 coherence) + 4/A2 (dict-threaded dispatch) + 5/B (op-binding signature validation) + 6/E (carrier-derivation robustness) all DELIVERED; (D) resolved-via-WI-450. The HK concrete-fill F:=Option (CpsMonad direct call) is the WI-383 typer half, not WI-431's. Delivering. Unblocks WI-383 tail + WI-402.", at: "2026-06-13T19:52:09Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-431", description: some(value: "Loader+typer+eval: INSTANCE FACTS -- retroactive typeclass instances as OP-VALUED provision facts (design path-dependent-types.md sec.5.4, decided 2026-06-11 w/ user; the instance half of the HK/CpsMonad model). REQUIREMENT: adding a typeclass to a carrier must NOT modify the carrier's code. SUBSTRATE (exists): provisions are facts assertable anywhere (stdlib fact Eq[T = Type] / fact Lattice[T = Type]; third-party fact Iterable[MyVec[T], T] per WI-424); carrier DERIVED from the binding value (WI-387/WI-407, load-order-independent). NEW PRIMITIVE: op-valued bindings in the provision fact ARE the requirement dictionary -- fact CpsMonad[F = Option, pure = optionPure, flatMap = optionFlatMap]; the dict builder (build_concrete_dispatch_dict / entries_cover / req_insertion) reads entries from the fact's bindings instead of (only) the carrier sort's own ops; surface already sketched by stdlib's Monoid example comment (requires Monoid[T = Int64, combine = add]). RULES: (1) COVERAGE moves to the FACT -- every spec op bound in the fact or defaulted on the spec, checked LOUDLY at the fact declaration (replaces the carrier-side 'provides ... but backs no operation' coupling for retroactive instances; derived ops like flatten stay spec defaults); (2) COHERENCE is loud -- two loaded instance facts covering the same (spec, carrier) = ambiguity error at the use site, keyed on the full canonical application (the WI-419 / sec.5.3 identity rule); scoped/named instance selection deferred; (3) the WITNESS-SORT spelling is NOT a provision -- 'sort OptionMonad provides CpsMonad[F = Option] + ops' indexes by the DECLARING sort (sort_ref) while dispatch looks up by the receiver's CARRIER, so the witness's ops are invisible to Option-valued receivers (probe-class caveat recorded in sec.5.4); a witness sort is at most a place for the implementation ops. DEPENDS WI-391: the fact-vs-provides binding-lowering decision (Ref-vs-nullary-Fn divergence -- the same shape WI-428's normalize_ground_leaf papered over on the provides side) determines how instance-fact bindings (both type- and op-valued) lower. Related: WI-383 (the HK mechanism this completes), WI-419 (covering identity)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-391"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-13T19:52:10Z"))
