fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "claude", content: "HK CONCRETE FILL (piece 2) RE-DESIGNED + DECOMPOSED 2026-06-13 (user-steered; WI-431 now delivered unblocks it). PROBE-GROUNDED GAP: the structured carrier 'sort F {...}' loads as a RIGID nominal sort with NO backing var (type_params_of_sort OMITS it; unlike 'sort T = ?' it has no SortAlias->Var::Global), so 'F[T=A] =?= Option[T=X]' can't bind F -- BOTH 'flatMap(o:Option,k)' (arg-carrier, 'got F[T=?_]') and 'unit(42):Option' (result-carrier, 'got F[T=Int64]') fail; generic ('requires CpsMonad[F]') + first-order already work. DECISION (user): mark the carrier a NON-RIGID TYPE VARIABLE -- spellings 'sort X = ?' / 'sort ?X' / 'sort [X]' are SYNONYMS, structured = a marked var with a member body ('sort [F] { sort [T] }'), enclosing list 'sort CpsMonad[F[T]]' after the name (op-style). Desugars to 'CpsMonad.F -> ?F' (SortAlias->Var::Global) so the fill rides ORDINARY unification + the implicit-requires CHECK; marker distinguishes a param-variable from a concrete nested sort; rigid at def-site, filled at use-site. Captured in path-dependent-types.md §5.4 'The carrier is a non-rigid type variable' (commit d9bbcaf). A/B ARE PER-OPERATION params ('unit[A]', 'flatMap[A,B]'), NOT CpsMonad sort params (only F parameterizes the monad) -- the current fixtures wrongly declare 'sort A = ?'. DECOMPOSED into the typing sequence: WI-451 (grammar/parse binders) -> WI-452 (loader: marked param -> backing-var alias) -> WI-453 (typer+eval fill); WI-383 now depends_on WI-453. WI-383 CLOSING SCOPE (after WI-453): MIGRATION sweep -- mark F (?F/[F]) and move A/B to op type-params in the §5.4 / wi383_hk / WI-431 fixtures + any stdlib-shaped spec, then end-to-end verification.", at: "2026-06-13T22:36:50Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-451", description: some(value: "Grammar+parse: NON-RIGID type-variable BINDERS for sort params (design path-dependent-types.md §5.4 'The carrier is a non-rigid type variable'). Accept three SYNONYMOUS spellings for a type-param variable -- 'sort X = ?' (existing), 'sort ?X' (the ?x logical-var marker prefix), 'sort [X]' (bracket binder, operation-style) -- PLUS the operation-style ENCLOSING LIST after the sort name: 'sort CpsMonad[F[T]]' (mirrors 'operation name[...]', grammar operation_type_param_list). The HIGHER-KINDED 'F[T]' (a param whose binder carries a bracketed member) is the one new param shape; simple params reuse the flat op-param shape. tree-sitter grammar.js corpus + parse/convert.rs IR. All spellings parse to the SAME IR as 'sort X = ?' for the no-member case; the marked structured form carries its member sub-decls. The marker DISTINGUISHES a param-variable from a concrete nested sort -- unmarked 'sort F {...}' parses UNCHANGED (still a concrete structured sort). Rust-only (grammar+parse)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-13T23:43:16Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-454", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-452", description: some(value: "Loader: a MARKED structured sort param registers a NON-RIGID BACKING VAR (design path-dependent-types.md §5.4). 'sort ?F' / 'sort [F]' (or '[F[T]]' in the enclosing list) registers the qualified 'CpsMonad.F' as a SortAlias -> Var::Global with its member sub-decls hung off it -- 'CpsMonad.F maps to ?F', EXACTLY as 'sort T = ?' registers 'CpsMonad.T' (so type_params_of_sort / sort_type_params_as_pairs now INCLUDE F with a backing var; today they OMIT the structured param -- the recorded gap). UNMARKED 'sort F {...}' stays a CONCRETE nested sort (NOT a param) -- the marked/unmarked split is load-bearing (distinguish param-variable from concrete nested sort). Def-site treatment: F skolemizes like other sort params so the spec's own bodies + coverage + the WI-270/WI-392 unconstrained-type-param check stay green and the wi383_hk decomposition stays RIGID. Acceptance: marked CpsMonad.F resolves to a Var via sort_type_params_as_pairs; unmarked concrete nested sort unchanged; suite green. Rust-only (load.rs)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-451"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T04:34:50Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-453", author: "claude", content: "STEPS 1-2 (TYPER-SIDE FILL) DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commit 78932ea; suite 1442 green; ticket STAYS Claimed). User chose the REQUIREMENT-DISCHARGE way. PROBE FINDING (corrected a wrong premise): post-WI-452 the fill still failed because F[T=A]'s base is stored as the SYMBOL F (a Fn functor can't hold a var); the unify resolves F's backing var and binds it, but the return-WALK reads the symbol, so the binding was invisible. (NOTE: my initial claim that §5.4 forbids this via 'no substitution-through-terms' was WRONG and the user caught it — that caveat is about the §5.3 NON-INJECTIVE projection neutral, whose subject identity must not be rewritten; the §5.4 HK application is INJECTIVE and its table literally says 'F := List' — grounding the functor is the intended mechanism.) IMPLEMENTED: (1) unify_parameterized_view — when the two bases DIFFER, a type-param base resolves to its backing Var (new parameterized_base_term) so F[T=A] ≟ Option[T=X] binds F:=Option at a use-site / skolem-compares at def-site; gated to differing-base so same-functor unify skips the alias scan. (2) walk_type_deep_g (gated on , like the RigidProjection fill) — a parameterized type whose FUNCTOR is a carrier filled to a concrete sort grounds its base via new filled_carrier_sort + make_parameterized_type rebuild (F[T=A] ⟹ Option[T=A]). RESULT: the typer now ACCEPTS the fill for BOTH arg-carrier (flatMap(o:Option,k)) and result-carrier (unit(42):Option); wrong-type rejected (Option[Int64]≠Option[String]); def-site decomposition intact (wi383_hk + wi452 skolem green); full suite 1442 green, NO regression from the hot-path unify+walk changes. REMAINING (steps 4-5, UNIFIED via requirement-discharge): route the spec-op call through dispatch_spec_op_cached with the carrier read from F's fill (subst) — the SLD discharge against the WI-431 instance/provides facts IS the discharge: it (a) confirms  exists (NoCandidates ⟹ loud no-instance error, closing the silent-accept hole — currently unit(42):MyBox with no instance type-checks), and (b) yields the dispatch dict (unit↦optionUnit). arg-carrier may already value-direct at eval (WI-431 inc 2 — VERIFY); result-carrier (unit, carrier only in result) needs the typer-resolved dispatch. INTEGRATION POINT: the carrier detection near typing.rs ~4389 (receiver_carrier / the  var feeding dispatch_spec_op_cached ~4394) — extend to read the HK carrier from F's binding. /code-review (hot-path: unify+walk) runs at deliver.", at: "2026-06-14T06:04:58Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-453", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commits 78932ea steps1-2 + 778eb6a steps4-5 + 2fd3893 review-fixes; suite 1449 green). HK CONCRETE FILL end-to-end via REQUIREMENT-DISCHARGE: arg-carrier (flatMap(o:Option,k)) + result-carrier (unit(42):Option) typecheck AND eval to the instance impl (some(42)=>42, =>5); wrong-type rejected; no-instance LOUD; def-site decomposition intact (wi383_hk + wi452 skolem green). MECHANISM: (1) unify resolves a differing type-param base to its backing var (F[T=A] vs Option binds F:=Option, parameterized_base_term); (2) walk_type_deep_g (ground-gated) rebuilds the functor F[T=A]=>Option[T=A] when F filled (filled_carrier_sort); (3) the spec-op dispatch block computes the HK carrier from a filled STRUCTURED param (gated on a parameterized op sig), discharges the implicit Spec[F=C] against the WI-431 instance fact (no provision => loud, unless host-builtin), and PinNow/ConcreteApplyWithin to the bound impl with the impl effects surfaced. 7 tests. /code-review (2 finders, max): FIXED an EFFECT-SOUNDNESS HOLE (effectful impl bound to a pure spec op masked its effect -- now surfaced via dispatched_impl_effects, +regression test), requires-threading (ConcreteApplyWithin), escape hatch (spec_warrants_abstract_check), and a perf regression (gate the probe on a parameterized sig). DEFERRED FOLLOW-UPS (non-blocking, recorded): (a) PERF parameterized_base_term does 2x O(SortAlias) scans per DIFFERING-base parameterized unify (List vs Set mismatch probes) -- needs an O(1) is-type-param gate or cache; (b) LATENT multi-HK-param: hk_carrier find_map picks the FIRST filled structured param + make_parameterized_type reuses the carrier-param binding NAMES -- a >=2-HK-param spec (sort BiMonad[F[T],G[T]]) or a carrier whose param is not named T would mis-dispatch / drop the arg (no such spec in stdlib; should be loud-if->1); (c) CLEANUP: filled_carrier_sort vs the inline hk_carrier find_map are the same core (factor); the block scans provider facts twice (provider_spec_view_bindings then instance_fact_op_binding); (d) TEST gaps: spec-DEFAULT op on an HK spec, multi-HK-param. ALTITUDE NOTE: the HK dispatch is a path beside dispatch_spec_op_cached (which does not read instance-fact op-bindings, WI-431 inc 2); a full unify would teach that SLD to read them -- larger, deferred. UNBLOCKS WI-383 tail + WI-402.", at: "2026-06-14T06:41:10Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-453", description: some(value: "Typer+eval: HIGHER-KINDED CONCRETE FILL rides the backing var (design path-dependent-types.md §5.4 'Fill => check/add require'; realizes WI-383 piece 2, now UNBLOCKED by WI-431 instance facts). With the marked carrier F backed by a var (WI-452), an EXTERNAL spec-op call fills F by ORDINARY unification -- 'F[T=A] =?= Option[T=X]' => 'F:=Option' (the injective parameterized unify arm, piece 3 already free) -- for BOTH the ARG-carrier (probe: 'flatMap(o: Option[T=Int64], k)' today errors 'got F[T=?_]') AND the RESULT-carrier / expected (probe: 'unit(42) : Option[T=Int64]' today errors 'got F[T=Int64]', F only in the result). The implicit 'requires CpsMonad[F]' discharges by CHECK by SLD against the instance fact ('fact CpsMonad[F=Option,...]', WI-431); NO instance => LOUD error (no silent accept-then-runtime-fail). DISPATCH to the instance's bound impl: arg-carrier via value-directed (already works once F binds -- verify), result-carrier ('unit') via the typer's resolved binding (PinNow/rewrite). Def-site stays skolemized so the wi383_hk decomposition tests stay green. Acceptance: arg+result carrier typecheck AND eval to the instance impl; wrong/no-instance loud; full suite green incl. wi357/wi210/wi424. Rust-only (typing.rs check_apply_iter + eval dispatch)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-452"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T06:41:47Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-179", description: some(value: "Extract embedded stdlib + bundle plumbing into anthill-stl. Today rustland/anthill-cli/src/stdlib_embedded.rs and rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs are near-duplicates that have already drifted (cli copy had cli/spec, cli/parse, cli/help, prelude/console, prelude/field, realization/witness, realization/policy that the todo copy lacked — synced after the gap broke WI-009 phase 1c). The bundle-loading helper rustland/anthill-todo/src/anthill_bundle.rs::parse_embedded_bundle is byte-identical-shape to parse_embedded_stdlib. The run_anthill_bundle function in rustland/anthill-todo/src/main.rs duplicates rustland/anthill-cli/src/run.rs::run_inner substantially: parse stdlib + bundle, build KB, register builtins, register effect handlers, build args list, call main, clamp Int return. Required: extract into anthill-stl (already a workspace member that depends on anthill-core). New module anthill_stl::stdlib::{SOURCES, parse_embedded} as the canonical list; both binaries depend on anthill-stl and call it. New module anthill_stl::runner::{run_with_main(extra_files, stdlib, resolver, main_qname, args) -> Result<i32, BootstrapError>} that both anthill-cli's run command and anthill-todo's --anthill flag use. Remove the EXIT_COMPILE/EXIT_RUNTIME/EXIT_OUT_OF_RANGE constants from each binary; centralize in the runner. Acceptance: deletes rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs and ~70 lines of run_anthill_bundle in main.rs; cargo test green; both binaries still emit identical output for their canonical subcommands. Estimated 130 LOC removed once extraction lands. Not blocking WI-009 — phase 2+ subcommand implementations work fine on the current shape."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T07:03:05Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-455", description: some(value: "Typer/eval: route the OpRef / spec-op REDISPATCH through the run() trampoline so host call depth stays O(1). After the WI-179 iterative-eval transform the value-cascade is trampolined (StepOutcome::Deliver), but dispatch_call_with_requirements_inner's OpRef arm (eval.rs ~1042/1047) and the spec-op-by-value redispatch still tail-call dispatch_call_with_requirements NATIVELY (do NOT return to run() between hops), so a pathological eta-chain recurses on the host Rust stack and can overflow before step_cap ticks. Narrow edge (eta-chains are 1 hop), documented in-code. FIX: add StepOutcome::Dispatch{target,args,requirements,type_args} re-entered by run() (like Deliver) and have the redispatch RETURN it instead of native-tail-calling. Acceptance: cargo-test green; a synthetic deep eta-chain surfaces StepsExhausted (named) not a native overflow. Rust-only (eval)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-179", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (rebased onto origin/main faffbac). Extracted embedded-stdlib + bootstrap into anthill-stl (anthill::stdlib explicit ORDERED SOURCES + drift test + compile-time empty-guard; anthill::runner EXIT_*/register_runtime/build_args_value/exit_code_from_main); both binaries deduped, behaviour-preserving. SURFACED + FIXED a pre-existing eval bug: the dispatch value-cascade recursed NATIVELY so a deep FINITE non-tail computation overflowed the host stack (anthill-todo status). Fix = iterative trampoline (StepOutcome::Deliver; run() alternates step/deliver via pending; host depth O(1)). Guard unified on step_cap (design B; 7 eval finders converged): ticks per trampoline iteration so a no-reduction dispatch cascade is bounded; StepsExhausted names looping ops via a recent-dispatch ring (gated to capped runs); lib default step_cap None, CLIs opt into 100M backstop. Both code-reviews done (11 finders). Rebased repeatedly as origin advanced; eval.rs auto-merged vs origin WI-431 resolvers (NO new self.deliver sites); later rebases code-untouched. eval_tests 108/108 + github_todo 8/8 + drift green vs latest typer; full suite green at an earlier identical-code base. Perf no regression (release 0.90s vs 0.95s; 4.5s was debug). FOLLOW-UP filed WI-455: OpRef native-redispatch edge -> StepOutcome::Dispatch.", at: "2026-06-14T07:03:12Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-383", author: "claude", content: "MIGRATION SWEEP DELIVERED — WI-383 CLOSED 2026-06-14 (commit 1972b19; suite 1765 green). The §5.4 closing scope (after WI-453's HK concrete fill): every HK structured sort param written in the unmarked body form ('sort CpsMonad ... sort F ... sort T = ? ... end' + 'sort A/B/C = ?') migrated to the MARKED enclosing-list form 'sort CpsMonad[F[T]]' (WI-451/452), element types A/B/C moved to PER-OPERATION type params ('operation map[A, B](...)'). FILES: (1) wi383_hk_application_test.rs — all 7 fixtures to marked form; the F-vs-G wrong-functor reject uses the MULTI-carrier enclosing list 'Box[F[T], G[T]]' (verified: confused rejected 'expected F[T = ?A], got G[T = ?A]'); per-statement 'sort [F]'/'sort ?F' deferred to WI-454. (2) wi431_instance_fact_coverage_test.rs — the 4 CpsMonad specs to marked form (coverage/signature/eval/coherence tests all green). (3) docs: proposal 002 Functor/CpsMonad/CpsTryMonad + note, path-dependent-types.md §5.4 migration note + seam-map WI-383 row -> DELIVERED. STDLIB: no migration needed — Ring.T / VectorSpace.V,F / Modify.T / ModifyRuntime.T,V / Error.T are first-order type members (already var-backed via 'sort X = ?') or the genuine rigid Modify (concrete structured sort), NOT HK carriers applied as F[member=A]. VERIFICATION: 8 pre-edit CLI probes confirmed every migrated shape (surface-loads / accept / wrong-binding ?A-vs-?B / wrong-functor F-vs-G / nested / monad-laws / full-CpsMonad / CpsMonad+instance-fact); full suite 1765/0. /code-review (inline, max): no actionable findings (test-fixtures+docs only; assertions unchanged; decomposition rides the identical unify_parameterized arm). DEFERRED (NOT WI-383 scope): rule-body Miller-fragment guard = resolver/SLD refinement (flexible ?f(?x) heads load; fires once concrete monad values flow through law rules, downstream of instances); WI-454 = per-statement non-rigid binder sugar. WI-402 (translucent abstract returns) now UNBLOCKED.", at: "2026-06-14T07:25:06Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-383", description: some(value: "Typer: higher-kinded / structured sort parameters + sort-carried projection (X.L / T.V) -- the SOUND-tie destination surfaced by the Modify-model redesign (WI-379 follow-on). GAP (recon OQ-E, expansion-during-unification.md sec.3.6 + sec.4 case 3 / WI-376): the typer has NO semantic support for (a) a STRUCTURED/higher-kinded sort parameter -- a sort param that itself declares members, e.g. 'sort T' with a nested 'sort V = ?' (the BODY form; the alias spellings 'sort T = { sort V = ? }' and 'sort T = sort { sort V = ? }' do NOT parse -- verified tree-sitter; the body form DOES parse, including the projection in op sigs), nor (b) the sort-carried projection 'T.V' (= the X.L form) that reads such a member as a type. The doc's 'check_ho_apply_pattern' reference is a conflation -- only check_ho_apply_pattern_occ exists (rule-body ho_apply SLD fragment), unrelated to type-level HKT. MOTIVATING USE CASE (the immediate driver): the SOUND Modify value-type model. ModifyRuntime[T = resource, V = value] now carries the value type V as a SEPARATE param, but V is inferred per-call and UNTIED to the resource (free: filled from the value arg for set, from the expected return for get) -- so 'read() -> String = get(counterHoldingInt)' is wrongly accepted (a soundness hole). The principled fix records the tie ON THE RESOURCE: 'sort CounterState' declares 'sort V = Int' (body form), and 'get(target: T) -> T.V' projects it so get(counter()) : CounterState.V = Int and a String read is REJECTED. DESUGARING (type-parameter-scoping.md sec.1 / 042): T.V == an op type param + a requirement, get(target: T) -> T.V  ==  get[Vi](target: T) -> Vi requires T[V = Vi]; the requirement binds Vi from the resource's declared V member (or a 'fact ModifyRuntime[T=R, V=...]' provider fact -- the GROUND-valued provider-fact bind is itself a small bind_spec_params_from_carrier extension, the cheaper half). Cell already provides 'fact ModifyRuntime[T = Cell, V = V]' (V threads from Cell's own V param, the List-provides-Stream-style carrier bind) -- but the TYPER does not yet consult that at a non-self-receiver get(target:T) call (target is typed T, not ModifyRuntime, so receiver_carrier returns NotApplicable). SCOPE: (1) structured sort-param representation through parse(verified)->load->typer; (2) sort-carried projection T.V elimination at the unify boundary (the WI-376 case-3 half) + its requires plumbing; (3) ground-valued provider-fact binding (the small bind_spec_params_from_carrier extension) for entity resources; (4) ground/abstract split + decidable-pattern-fragment bound for an unbound higher-kinded head (loud error outside it). RELATES WI-376 (projection x.A/X.L; this is the sort-carried T.V half over structured params), expansion-during-unification.md sec.3.6/sec.4 case 3, OQ-E, type-parameter-scoping.md. Body-form syntax 'sort T ... end' with nested 'sort V = ?' is the ACCEPTED surface (user-confirmed). Until delivered, ModifyRuntime keeps V free (loose; m5 tests pass but the wrong-value-type read is not caught). Rust-only (typer). DESIGN-then-impl."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-376", "WI-429", "WI-428", "WI-431", "WI-453"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T07:25:08Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-448", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commit 2a944c6; suite 1768 green; corpus 153/153). ROOT CAUSE (parse/grammar, confirmed via tree-sitter parse-tree diff): two productions begin with the 'requires' token — requires_clause (the operation's trailing clause, op-scoped, takes a rule_body) and requires_declaration (a standalone sort/namespace declaration, enclosing-scoped, takes a _type). The GLR conflict [$.operation_declaration] explores both; their parse costs are otherwise EQUAL, so a comment node preceding the op tipped the tie toward the standalone requires_declaration, re-scoping the clause's names to the enclosing namespace (op-type-param T → 'unresolved name T in scope m', non-blocking so the file checked green = the silent mis-scope). PRECISE TRIGGER (probed): fires ONLY when (1) a comment (line OR block — both verified) immediately precedes the op, (2) the op ends in a 'requires' clause (NOT 'ensures' — it has no standalone form, no ambiguity), (3) no body (= …) follows (a body forces the op-clause parse). A blank line does NOT trigger (whitespace is not an attached node). FIX: prec.dynamic(1, …) on requires_clause biases the conflict deterministically toward the op-clause, matching the comment-free behavior. Only breaks ties between two VALID parses, so a genuine sort-level requires_declaration (placed before the ops, as ALL stdlib does — verified none sits after an op) is unaffected; full stdlib re-parse green. parser.c is regenerated from grammar.js by build.rs (untracked artifact; committing grammar.js suffices). REGRESSION TEST wi448_comment_before_op_requires_test (RED-GREEN verified: 2 tests fail on the reverted grammar, pass with the fix): comment+requires resolves op-type-param op-locally; commented==comment-free; sort-level-requires-before-ops still resolves (over-application guard). Was surfaced during WI-383 L0 probing (the explicit-bound 'requires Resource[C=T]' licensing surface). Scope was parse/grammar only, as filed.", at: "2026-06-14T07:41:24Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-448", description: some(value: "Parse/grammar BUG: a COMMENT line immediately preceding an operation declaration breaks scope of names in that operation's requires/ensures clause -- they resolve at the ENCLOSING NAMESPACE scope instead of the OP scope, so op-type-params (and other op-local names) silently become unresolved. MINIMAL REPRO: 'namespace m / sort Eq { sort T = ? } / -- doc / operation f[T](x: T) -> T requires Eq[T = T] end' emits 'unresolved name T in scope m' (namespace, not op 'f'); DELETE the '-- doc' line and it resolves cleanly. A blank line between the comment and the op does not help. The RETURN type is unaffected (only the trailing requires/ensures clause breaks), pointing at a comment-node attachment shift in the CST->IR conversion (tree-sitter-anthill grammar.js and/or parse/convert.rs) that mis-associates the trailing clause or mis-wires the op scope -- a cousin of WI-446's trailing-attachment quirk. SEVERITY: latent / silent -- it is a WARNING, file still checks green (violates loud-error-over-silent-skip: the clause binds to a namespace-scoped unresolved symbol rather than the op-type-param). Does NOT break the stdlib today (no stdlib op uses an op-level requires). Surfaced during WI-383 probing (the explicit-bound 'requires Resource[C=T]' licensing surface): a DOCUMENTED operation with a requires clause mis-resolves. SCOPE: parse/grammar only (NOT typing). Acceptance: cargo-test green + the repro resolves the op-type-param in the requires clause to the OP scope regardless of a preceding comment."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T07:41:25Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-174", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14. Reworked anthill-todo list ordering in the embedded bundle (anthill/main.anthill cmd_list_plain — the WI's native run_list ref was stale, ported at WI-009 cutover). Replaced the unblocks-count ready sort with: status grouping (Open/Claimed/Delivered/Verified/PreOpened/Rejected/Stale headers, lifecycle order via status_rank; grouping driven by statuses actually present so no row is dropped) over the kept ready/-- blocked -- split, each section ordered by chrono_topo (postorder DFS: walk rows by id, emit each row's in-section not-yet-emitted deps first so deps cluster immediately before their dependent). [unblocks N] kept display-only (not a sort key). Deleted ready_lt/merge_ready/sort_ready. Golden parity regenerated; full anthill-todo suite 66/0 green; eyeball acceptance confirmed (WI-280/WI-282 cluster before WI-278). /code-review (4 angles): dup-id collapse latent (add auto-assigns unique ids; the one historical WI-169 dup spans two statuses->two groups, both shown) + documented; Rejected/Stale rank gap fixed.", at: "2026-06-14T08:36:28Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-174", description: some(value: "Replace dependents-count ordering in 'anthill-todo list' with chronological+topological mixed ordering. Today run_list (anthill-todo/src/main.rs:522-616) splits items into ready/blocked, sorts ready by transitive dependents count (most-unblocking first), and sorts blocked by id. Behavior to deliver: walk filtered items in chronological order (by id, since WI-NNN is sequential); for each item X not yet emitted, recursively emit X's still-unemitted dependencies first (topological/postorder), then X. Result is one global sequence where (a) each item appears after all its dependencies, and (b) the top-level cursor advances through items in chronological order, so the earliest WI anchors a topologically-ordered cluster of its deps just before it. Concretely: replace the count_transitive-sorting block with a postorder DFS over a chronologically-sorted item list, marking emitted to avoid duplicates and to short-circuit shared deps. Keep the ready-vs-blocked split (and the blocked section labelling) only if it still adds value — preferred shape is one merged list with [blocked] tags inline. Open question to resolve in the WI: whether closed (Delivered/Verified) deps should be skipped from the emitted list (probably yes — they're satisfied and don't need re-display) or shown as anchors. Acceptance: cargo-test green; eyeball-check 'anthill-todo list' output on the current ~65 open items shows the earliest open item appearing near the top with its open deps clustered immediately before it."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T08:36:32Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-456", description: some(value: "add SortedSet sort to prelude (Persistent version),  which will backed by Ord defined by Element. Before - think, maybe local Eq should be derived from Ord?"), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-402", author: "user", content: "EXISTENTIAL HALF DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commits 8da3b11 + review-fixes 9aca3b0; suite 1777 green). The output dual of requires is now END-TO-END for the KVStore factory (wi402_existential_return_test.rs, 8 tests): load+admit, branch-join on the ensures bound, dotted dispatch at the caller, eval dict-out. APPROACH (option b, max-reuse): the loader detect_existential_carrier flags '-> C ensures Spec[C, …]' (C = undeclared Capitalized return name that is also the ensures carrier; a concrete-sort return + ensures is left alone) and REWRITES the return type to the ensures spec with the carrier dropped — BOUND ('ensures Spec[C, K=String]') yields the manifest Spec[K=String], reducing EXACTLY to the delivered bound half (branch-join takes the spec as upper bound, WI-401 sees all members bound); UNBOUND ('ensures Spec[C]') yields a bare Ref(Spec) (nullary Fn would mis-classify as TypeHead::Error — WI-391 leaf gotcha). The WI-401 abstracting_return_error gate skips ops the loader actually rewrote (kb.existential_return_ops marker) — NOT any op naming the return spec in an ensures. Caller + eval ride existing machinery: dotted dispatch on the bound spec; value-directed dispatch resolves on the concrete value's runtime sort (dict-out, zero new code). KEY FINDING: dict-out at eval needed NO change (WI-350 value-directed + WI-431 instance dispatch already key on runtime functor). /code-review (high, 3 finder angles + verify) caught 2 HIGH-severity bugs, both fixed+tested: (1) SOUNDNESS — the original ensures-aware gate skip (op_ensures_vouches_for) was too broad, admitting the bare real-sort sealing escape '-> DataProvider ensures DataProvider[K=String] = s'; re-scoped to the marker. (2) strip_spec_carrier dropped a named member binding whose VALUE names the carrier (V=C); now drops only the carrier slot (first positional).", at: "2026-06-14T09:05:23Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-402", author: "user", content: "DEFERRED (sound, no driver — recorded per no-spinoff): (1) NAMED-CARRIER NON-INJECTIVITY — the rewrite DROPS the carrier C rather than preserving it as a distinct nominal/skolem, so two existentials returning the same spec get the same type. Fine for the BOUND case (members concrete, interchangeable through the interface); for UNBOUND it means two results' abstract members are not kept distinct (matters only when mixing two distinct existentials' abstract members in one expression — the driver, the pluggable backend, uses a single result). Fuller fix = per-call skolem a la the WI-400 non-injective neutral. (2) CARRIER-VALUED MEMBER (ensures Spec[C, V=C]) — the strip now KEEPS V=C, but conformance does not unify the abstract carrier C with a provider's concrete member, so the op does not fully type-check (expected Spec[…, V=C], got Node); exotic, no driver. ORTHOGONAL / pre-existing (NOT WI-402): (3) dispatch surface is the DOTTED form (store.op() / Spec.op(store,…)); a direct op(store) to a body-less spec op does not resolve regardless of the existential (pre-existing spec-op-call limitation, fails for concrete receivers too). (4) An if-join bare return WITHOUT an ensures ('-> KVStore = if … then disk else mem') currently LOADS — the branch-join yields the bare spec = the return sort, so the WI-401 same-symbol check returns None; the DIRECT upcast ('-> KVStore = mem') is correctly rejected. This is a pre-existing WI-401 gap for join-typed bodies, NOT tightened here (WI-401 scope, cascade risk) — candidate for its own ticket. (5) CODEGEN divergence — the frozen bootstrap Rust codegen reads parse-IR op.return_type (the literal '-> C', undefined), while the rewritten return lives in OperationInfo; latent (no existential op is codegenned), WI-403/WI-002 territory (the KB-driven mapper consumes OperationInfo). UNBLOCKS WI-437 (pluggable backend, which depends_on WI-402).", at: "2026-06-14T09:05:44Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-402", description: some(value: "Typer: ADMIT an abstract return WITH an ensures manifest -- translucent returns, the requires/ensures OUTPUT dual (docs/design/path-dependent-types.md sec.5). ensures result.K = String (= ML with type t = string, a manifest type spec as a postcondition; sound because types are terms so an equation is a fact) makes result.K manifest at the caller -> it grounds, roots at nothing local -> no escape, result usable. Generalizes the strict no-sealing rule: an abstract return member is admitted exactly when an ensures (or a type-arg, for the simple case -> DataProvider[K=String]) roots it back at the interface; the ensures must be COMPLETE (cover every otherwise-local-rooted member; a partial ensures still escapes -> rejected, no-silent-drop applied to returns). requires evidences abstract INPUTS, ensures evidences abstract OUTPUTS -- both discharged STATICALLY at the call site (dictionary-passing / req_insertion / 011 per-call elaboration). DEFERRED: add when a real translucent-return need appears. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-401", "WI-383"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T09:05:45Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-457", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-445", description: some(value: "Typer: NAMED sub-patterns in constructor match patterns do not BIND — 'case Box(v: some(x)) -> x' fails with UnresolvedName(x) while the positional 'case Box(some(x))' binds fine. extend_env_from_pattern (typing.rs ~10270) reads only the constructor_pattern's positional 'args' list and zips fields.get(i) positionally; a NAMED sub-pattern lands elsewhere and is silently skipped, so its vars never reach the branch env (eval-side match_pattern handles named patterns, making this a typer-only gap). Found while writing wi408 tests (probe 2026-06-12, fails on pre-WI-408 main too). ALSO observed: the UnresolvedName diagnostic printed a SPAN FROM ANOTHER FILE (list.anthill 1945..1946 for a test-source x) — the span side-table keys on hash-consed TermId, so a shared subterm's span resolves to whichever file registered it first; consider span lookup via occurrence, not TermId."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T10:08:19Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-458", description: some(value: "Diagnostics: error SPAN side-table keys on hash-consed TermId, so a shared subterm's span resolves to whichever file registered it FIRST — an error about a term in file A can print a span pointing into file B (observed in WI-445: an UnresolvedName for a test-source 'x' printed list.anthill 1945..1946). Span lookup should key on the OCCURRENCE (per-use), not the hash-consed TermId. Surfaced while debugging WI-445; not blocking (the WI-445 fix removed that particular error)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-445", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (7c0f280, pushed; full anthill-core suite 1466 green + workspace 1782 green). ROOT CAUSE was NOT typer-only as the ticket guessed: the 'pattern_constructor' LOAD Visit handler (load.rs ~5305) read only the parse term's positional pos_args and IGNORED its named_args, so a named sub-pattern was dropped at load entirely — never reaching typer OR eval (eval did NOT handle them either). FIX preserves named sub-patterns through load as a new constructor_pattern.named: List[NamedPattern] field (NamedPattern(name,pattern) registered programmatically alongside MatchBranch/ApplyArg; reflect.anthill updated). Field->position is deliberately NOT resolved at load: the entity may be declared AFTER the op (verified — entity_field_names is None at the Visit handler then), so resolution is deferred to the typer (extend_env_from_pattern, by field name) and eval (match_constructor_pattern, field->entity_field_names declaration index into the scrutinee's declaration-ordered sub_values). Order-independent (a reordered Pair(b: y, a: x) binds correctly; a positionally-built value matches a named pattern). Threaded SYMMETRICALLY through the pattern occurrence<->term round-trip — term_to_param_occurrence (term->occ) populates Pattern::Constructor.named_args, pattern_to_term (occ->term) re-emits named; all existing Pattern::Constructor walkers (for_each_pattern_child, reassemble_pattern, De Bruijn open/close, flow_derive) already iterate named_args so they 'just work'; printer renders 'field: pat'. All-positional patterns keep byte-identical 2-field shape. /code-review (9 angles): shared single-source build_named_pattern_term so the load and pattern_to_term builders can't drift (round-trip safety). CAVEAT (verified pre-existing, NOT a regression): constructor_sub_values for a Value::Term scrutinee returns named_args in symbol/canonical order, not declaration order — both the named AND the long-standing positional path assume declaration order (honored by Value::Entity, the only realistic match scrutinee); a Value::Term scrutinee with reordered named fields would mis-bind either way. Not in scope. TESTS: wi445_named_subpattern_test (5: single-field both arms, multifield reordered, mixed pos+named over both constructions, entity-declared-after-op, positional/named arm coexistence). FILED WI-458 for the ticket's secondary span-side-table observation (TermId-keyed spans misattribute to another file).", at: "2026-06-14T10:10:18Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-447", author: "user", content: "BLOCKED — premise 'Mechanisms all delivered' is FALSE. Verified: bare-projection DECLARATIONS load (head/tail/splitFirst-decl/isEmpty, List.splitFirst body via B=List[T=xs.T]), but the consumer/recursive BODIES fail on 4 distinct typer gaps. (A) DOMINANT — projection-neutral identity through call-sites/recursion: a recursive consumer (collect/takeN/count/nth/foldLeft/foldRight) reads rest.T/rest.E off the recursion var (typed Stream[T=s.T,E=s.E] or List[T=xs.T] from splitFirst's explicit-param tail); the projection yields a neutral NOT identified with the enclosing s.T/s.E, so result/effect won't reconcile with the projection return. Isolated repro /tmp/probeD.anthill: recursive collectd(rest) -> 'expected List[T=xs.T], got List[T=xs.T]' (same print, distinct identity). (B) find's callback (x: s.T) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]} nests s.T in a denoted-bearing arrow = documented-unsupported WI-376 follow-on (wi376 projection_in_denoted_node_is_rejected). (C) iterator(l: List) -> Stream[T=l.T,E={}] = l: body l:List not admissible-as-Stream (bare element not pinned to l.T for provider-admissibility). (D) split's some((h,t)) vs (xs.T, List[T=xs.T]) -> (?_, List): tuple-LITERAL doesn't thread (Pair-CONSTRUCTOR pair(h,t) DOES). Note: B=s.Sort/xs.Sort is WRONG for recursion-fed tails (opaque neutral won't decompose); B=Stream[T=s.T,E=s.E] / List[T=xs.T] is the right shape but exposes gap A. STOPPED for user decision: build typer prereqs (esp. A, core unify/projection change w/ cascade risk) vs keep explicit [Elem,Eff] forms (work today) vs re-scope. Tree reverted to green; WI-447 left claimed.", at: "2026-06-14T10:35:58Z")
