fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-447", author: "user", content: "DECISION (user 2026-06-14): BUILD TYPER PREREQS. Filed WI-459 (Gap A — projection-neutral identity through recursion, DOMINANT), WI-460 (Gap B — projection in denoted-bearing arrow / find), WI-461 (Gap C — self-admissibility for '= l' identity body / iterator), WI-462 (Gap D — tuple-literal threading / split); WI-447 now depends on all 4 = BLOCKED. Do NOT resume WI-447 until they deliver. (Stays 'Claimed' only because the CLI has no un-claim verb — treat as Blocked; the sequence's <- next is WI-450, then the WI-459-462 prereq cluster.)", at: "2026-06-14T10:43:02Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-279", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commit 3f20427). INC1b (?x.field constructor-field access) — the final acceptance item — landed; INC1/INC2 already on main. Typer (build_type DotApply arm): a zero-arg ?x.field that matches no operation resolves member->field by SHORT name (use-site intern != declaring entity's field symbol), projects the field type via resolve_field_type (substitutes receiver type-args, same path pattern field types use), and synthesizes field_access(receiver, \"field\") = the reflect field-access desugaring; result type set directly + inferred_type stamped (no field-specific signature to re-type against); method fallback runs first so an op shadows a same-named field. Eval: new Value-level anthill.reflect.field_access builtin (runtime twin of the SLD BuiltinTag::FieldAccess) reads Value::Entity.named by short name. ALSO surfaced+fixed eval-runnability of the ?x value-receiver dot forms: a value-receiver ?x reaches eval as Expr::Var(Global) (the only op-body var not already Ref/VarRef), which eval's Var arm rejected outright — now Global resolves by name; DeBruijn (unopened param) + Rigid (skolem type-param) stay loud errors. So BOTH ?x.method and ?x.field are now runnable (prior INC1/INC2 tests only type-checked, never evaluated a ?x receiver). Tests: field type+eval (concrete + generic Option substitution), field no-match, e2e ?b.total(10)+?b.value method-and-field eval. Full anthill-core 1470/0 green. /code-review (2 finders): fixed Var::Rigid unsound-resolution (kept loud) + stamped synth inferred_type; effects=recv.effects confirmed correct (receiver sub-expr evaluated, effects propagate).", at: "2026-06-14T16:23:58Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-279", description: some(value: "Dot dispatch as a CLIENT of the type-directed [simp] engine (WI-283). See docs/design/simp-dot-finding.md. A dot rule is the same shape as a spec/sort equational rule — sort-scoped, requires-guarded (e.g. a custom Either.map: dot(?e,map,[?f])=either_map(?e,?f) :- requires Either; concrete RHS) — selected by min_sort(receiver) = widen the receiver to its least declared sort (= sort_head(TypeResult.ty); sort_functor_of extracts it; a compile-time typer notion, never a goal, never a runtime/callable typeof). Firing reuses the engine's tree-producing walk (DotApply -> Apply, rebuild ancestors, write the body back — type_check_node only types, so dot NEEDS the walk) and runs IN the typer (scope-correct min_sort). Beyond sort-specific rules there is an engine DEFAULT fallback (resolve name to an op on min_sort(receiver), or a field on a free-standing entity -> field_access) — engine logic, NOT a writable rule (functor dynamically resolved). Produced Apply rides normal type-param inference + req_insertion (043 6.6). Reverted predecessor (this session) ran a standalone PRE-typer pass with a reconstructed flat op-level env (build_op_env) — wrong: typer-independent, omits let/lambda/match scope. DEPENDS ON WI-283. Acceptance: ?x.method(args)/?x.field dispatch via receiver sort with no import; a sort-specific requires-guarded dot rule (Either-style) overrides the default; receivers referencing let/lambda/match-bound locals dispatch; clear no-match error at the dot span; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-283"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T16:24:04Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-450", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (commits 02bb7df + dc85e53). Param-agnostic value-directed dispatch for WITNESS SORTS: a 'sort TagCombiner provides Combiner[T=Tag]' with member impl op now dispatches a spec op like an instance fact, across generic requires-context, qualified direct value call, and dot-call forms. New witness_provision / witness_op_for_carrier (param-agnostic dual of the carrier-keyed provider_spec_view_bindings), shared by eval dispatch, the carrier classification (provision_binds_param_to_carrier fallback), and the typer dot-call (find_spec_op_for_provided_sort). Witness detection unified on provision_carrier_sort (spec's first/carrier type param) across dispatch+coherence (review fix). Coherence rule-2 extended: 2 witness sorts for one (spec,carrier) = loud AmbiguousWitness, gated to ops-bearing specs + NON-concrete providers + carrier!=provider (so existential/manifest backends MemStore/DiskStore and bare carrier-extraction provisions like KVStore/W449 are NOT over-rejected). Full workspace green; hot path (eq/List.member/Iterable/Stream) verified. SUB-PROBLEMS 1 (op-location) + 2 (coherence) done. FOLLOW-ON (filed separately): the UNqualified direct call 'combine(tag,tag)' is ambiguous when a witness member shares the spec op's short name (name-resolution, resolve_by_short_name returns None on 2 candidates) — qualified/generic/dot forms all dispatch, so it's an ergonomic gap not a dispatch gap.", at: "2026-06-14T16:47:00Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-450", description: some(value: "Typer/eval: make VALUE-DIRECTED dispatch resolve a spec op by UNIFYING THE SPEC APPLICATION against provisions (param-agnostic), exactly as the requires-dict path already does -- so a WITNESS SORT (`sort OptionMonad provides CpsMonad[F=Option]` + member impl ops, or first-order `sort TagCombiner provides Combiner[T=Tag]` + combine) resolves a spec op called directly on a carrier VALUE identically to a `fact CpsMonad[F=Option,...]`.\n\nDISCOVERY (WI-431 (D) probe, 2026-06-13, decided w/ user): the \"carrier\" -- privileging ONE spec type-param as the dispatch key -- is an ARTIFACT of value-directed dispatch's \"value -> its sort -> look up by sort_ref\" mechanism, NOT a principle. The `requires` path is ALREADY param-agnostic: it unifies the whole spec application (`Combiner[T=Tag]` / `Iterable[C=List, Element=Int]`) against provisions, no privileged param -- which is exactly why it finds a witness and value-directed does not. Value-directed ALREADY computes the structured bindings (the typer binds `T:=Tag` from the args, increment 2) but THROWS THEM AWAY, collapsing to (carrier_sym=Tag, match sort_ref).\n\nFIX: value-directed dispatch should KEEP the bindings and unify the spec application against provisions, dropping the sort_ref/carrier privilege. Witnesses then resolve with no \"which param is the carrier\" question. The two value-directed lookups that key on sort_ref==carrier_sym: find_spec_op_for_provided_sort (typing.rs ~2215), provider_spec_view_bindings (typing.rs ~8445).\n\nSUB-PROBLEMS: (1) OP-LOCATION -- a `fact` stores the op in the provision bindings (`combine=tagCombine`); a witness stores it as a MEMBER of the witness sort (`TagCombiner.combine`), with no op in the provision; so value-directed op-resolution (instance_fact_op_binding, which reads bindings only) must also resolve in the PROVIDER's scope (sort_ref) -- the requires path already does this. (2) COHERENCE -- two witnesses for one application are a live ambiguity; extend the rule-2 check (provision_binds_any_op gates it to op-binding facts today) to witness provisions.\n\nSTRATEGY: dispatch-side param-agnostic unification -- NOT a load-time desugar. (Desugar would have to PICK a carrier to index the provision under, re-introducing the very privilege the param-agnostic model removes.)\n\nOUT OF SCOPE (genuinely different shapes, NOT touched by the param-agnostic change): self-receiver specs (`Stream.splitFirst(s: Stream)` -- no type-param pinned by an arg; element comes from the provider fact = WI-357); result-determined params (`CpsMonad.pure(a: A) -> F[T=A]` -- `F` appears only in the result, so the args cannot pin it; it comes from the expected type = WI-383 HK fill).\n\nHOT PATH (eq / List.member / Iterable.find+map -- WI-415/418/424) plus Stream (self-receiver) and Iterable (carrier = enclosing sort, a normal provider) MUST stay green -- heavy regression testing, not just the new witness tests. SUPERSEDES design path-dependent-types.md sec.5.4 rule 3 (reworded to the decided direction). Reuses WI-431's provision/coherence machinery (depends WI-431). Est. ~2-4 reviewable commits."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-431"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T16:47:02Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-463", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-459", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (dd00198). Root cause was NOT a too-strict zeta check but a NEUTRAL RECEIVER LEAK: at call-site elimination a projection off a callee formal that stayed Neutral (arg type didn't bind the member, e.g. sfd(xs) with bare xs:List) kept the CALLEE's receiver symbol (sfd.xs.T) when it leaked into the caller — so rest:List[T=sfd.xs.T] then failed the non-decomposing zeta vs the declared collectd.xs.T (same print, distinct symbol). FIX: re-key a surviving neutral's receiver formal->arg (param_to_arg_sym) SURGICALLY in rewrite_term_projections' Neutral branch (new arg_syms param threaded through eliminate_type_projections; call-sites pass Some, body-sites None). Grounded delta-reduction (recursive collectd(rest)) is untouched (precedes the re-key) — a blanket substitute_ref_syms_value would corrupt it (self-recursion: callee formal == enclosing param). EFFECT DUAL (count s.E): the pre-existing blanket effect re-key at 4187 had the SAME over-application bug (s.E->rest.E 'undeclared effect'); gated it to skip projection-bearing effects, keeping only ground Modify[c] re-key. /code-review (3 finders + sweep): no soundness bug; fixed a vacuous negative test (was rejected by cons.type_args clash, not the return gate). FOLLOW-ONS (NOT needed for WI-447 — stdlib threads only single-Ref receivers s/xs/rest): (1) compound-receiver a.b.T neutral is NOT re-keyed (Node arm; loud sound over-reject, documented at eliminate_type_projections Node arm); (2) deferred-receiver case (non-value-ref arg) keeps callee-keyed neutral; (3) PRE-EXISTING sibling: dispatched_impl_effects (~8916) still blanket-substitutes without the projection guard.", at: "2026-06-14T19:46:30Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-459", description: some(value: "Typer: projection neutrals must compare by DEFINITIONAL (delta) EQUALITY, not syntactic identity -- a recursive/consuming body's projected member off a LOCAL whose type BINDS that member must delta-reduce to the bound value, rather than survive as a fresh neutral that then fails an identity check. MINIMAL REPRO (/tmp/probeD): operation sfd(xs: List) -> Option[Pair[A=xs.T, B=List[T=xs.T]]] = match xs case nil->none case cons(h,t)->some(pair(h,t)); operation collectd(xs: List) -> List[T=xs.T] = match sfd(xs) case none->nil case some(pair(h,rest))->cons(head:h, tail:collectd(rest)) -> 'match.rule: expected List[T=xs.T], got List[T=xs.T]' (SAME print, but rest.T and xs.T are DISTINCT neutrals). collectd(rest) is List[rest.T]; rest:List[T=xs.T] so rest.T is DEFINITIONALLY EQUAL to xs.T (delta: project T off rest's type binding) but NOT syntactically identical. DIAGNOSIS -- it is a MISSING REDUCTION, not a too-strict check: expr_carried_zeta (typing.rs ~11459) compares two ExprCarried by same-member AND receiver structural_eq -- correct BY DESIGN (non-decomposing; ExprCarried is non-injective per WI-400, must NOT infer rest=xs from rest.T=xs.T) and is only the FALLBACK for genuinely-rigid neutrals (abstract receiver, no type to reduce against). The delta-reduction lives at the ELIMINATION site (project_type_member via check_apply_iter), which has the typing ENV to look up rest's type; unify_types/the zeta arm has only kb+subst, NOT the env, so delta cannot simply move there. BUG: at the recursive call rest's type IS known (List[T=xs.T]) yet the return projection leaks to zeta as rest.T instead of delta-reducing to the canonical xs.T. Same on the EFFECT dual (count: 'undeclared effect: s.E', body's s.E = rest.E). DISTINCT from WI-413 (delivered; that was the UNBOUND ??_ close-didn't-run case) -- here the neutral is BOUND but UN-REDUCED. FIX DIRECTION: make the projection delta-reduce at the recursive/consuming call (receiver type known -> rest.T reduces to canonical xs.T) so it never reaches the zeta arm; KEEP expr_carried_zeta non-decomposing (WI-400 soundness). DECIDE (scope): the deferred-receiver case -- receiver type fixed only AFTER the projection forms (rest a fresh var bound later) -- eager elimination cannot catch and needs delta-aware comparison OR a DELAYED projection that re-reduces when the receiver binds; handle now or record as a follow-on. DOMINANT WI-447 blocker (collect/takeN/count/nth/foldLeft/foldRight). TEST: probeD typechecks; full stdlib + wi357/365/368/376/396/398/424 green; WI-400 negatives (neutral vs concrete, two distinct rigid neutrals) stay rejected."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T19:46:36Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-293", description: some(value: "Typer: consume declared variance facts (Covariant/Contravariant) in types_compatible / parameterized_compatible / join_types, instead of hardcoded uniform covariance. PROBLEM: variance is declared AS FACTS (proposal 035; stdlib/anthill/reflect/typing.anthill:117-151 — entity Covariant(sort: Symbol, param: Symbol) / Contravariant(sort, param), with no-fact=invariant / both=bivariant, plus indirection rules effective_covariant / effective_contravariant and a check_variance(?S,?P,?V1,?V2) resolver rule), but NOTHING consumes them: grep finds zero Rust readers of check_variance/Covariant/effective_*, and no stdlib rule queries check_variance either — the facts/rules are inert. Instead the typer hardcodes variance: parameterized_compatible (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs) checks every binding value covariantly via types_compatible(actual_val, expected_val) REGARDLESS of declared variance, so a contravariant or invariant parameter is checked covariantly (potential unsoundness — e.g. a function-typed or mutable-cell parameter); arrow_compatible separately hardcodes structural arrow variance (contravariant param, covariant result/effects). TASK: wire effective_covariant/effective_contravariant (or check_variance) into types_compatible/parameterized_compatible so per-parameter variance is honored: invariant default => exact/equal binding value; covariant => actual_val <: expected_val (current behavior); contravariant => expected_val <: actual_val (flipped); bivariant => either. Then extend WI-287's join_types to recurse into bindings using the same variance, so a covariant T gives join(Option[T=Cat], Option[T=Dog]) = Option[T=Animal] instead of the current conservative clash (today join_types can't form parameterized lubs — it only does sort_ref widening — so WI-287 deliberately left the synthesized result a sound common supertype, not the strict lub; this WI is what would make it a real lub for parameterized sorts). SCOPE: distinct from WI-184 (the variance INFERENCE algorithm, Open) — this CONSUMES hand-declared facts and can land before inference exists; it is the prerequisite that makes WI-184's output meaningful. OPTIONAL (proposal 035 line 178): fold the hardcoded arrow_compatible into Function[A,B] with covariant(Function,B)/contravariant(Function,A) facts for uniformity. TESTS: contravariant param rejected where covariant-checking would wrongly accept; invariant param requires exact binding; covariant join Option[Cat]/Option[Dog] => Option[Animal]; bivariant accepts either. Note: scaland has no typer (see WI-287), so rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T17:01:25Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-464", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-382", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION (concrete join/meet pulled out to WI-464): the variance-aware join_types PARAMETERIZED-LUB + meet_types is now its OWN near-term WI (WI-464), depends ONLY on WI-293 (delivered) — NOT on this item or WI-010. Rationale: the typer is term-backed Rust (join_types/declared_variance/parameterized_compatible_view all in kb/typing.rs), and the WI-293 subtyping half proved you build the order-relation ops directly in Rust without the per-sort registered-algorithm substrate. The earlier 'deferred from WI-293, lands here' framing over-coupled: it turned a CONCEPTUAL kinship (variance/join/meet = the order relation, sibling of unification) into an IMPLEMENTATION dependency, via the false 'meet does not exist => need the framework' leap (meet_types is just join_types's dual over the same lattice). WI-382 REMAINS the eventual generalization HOME: when this framework lands, join_types/meet_types (built in WI-464) fold into registered per-sort ordering ops — a future refactor target, not a blocker for the LUB.", at: "2026-06-14T17:01:48Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-405", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-311", author: "user", content: "SUBSTANTIALLY DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (closed). The FUNCTIONAL half landed on main: parameterized_type + instantiation_term are merged into one 'application' rule (grammar.js:1184, tagged WI-311), base is the dotted $.name (Eq[T=Int64] / a.b.Stack[T=Int64] / Modify[c] / Vector[Int64,3] all parse), old node names gone, 'npx tree-sitter generate' is conflict-free. The name/field_access overlap for 'a.b' is absorbed by the CONVERTER, not eliminated at the CFG: explicit WI-311 classification (convert.rs:392 + receiver-walk ~885-910) splits a sort/namespace name (qualified-name flattening) from a value receiver (field projection). SMOKE-TEST (2026-06-14, main): the cited breakages are STALE — p.x(?x) parses as fn_term(name: field_access(p,x), ?x); g(a.b) as fn_term(g, field_access(a,b)); Color.red as field_access(Color,red) then classified — all ZERO ERROR nodes, full suite green (Color.red-style access is pervasive in stdlib, so the path is exercised). REMAINING (descoped): only the pure CFG-cleanliness goal — restrict field_access to non-name receivers (?x.y, foo().y) and route a.b through 'name' everywhere so the loader classifies. The WI itself states this is 'NOT new capability — the loader already classifies'; cost is restructuring the precedence-delicate field_access/fn_term/_atom_term + converter rewrite + corpus rebaseline for ZERO capability gain, and CLAUDE.md's representation note has since walked back the 'types are terms at CFG level' motivation. Converter-classifies is an acceptable terminal state. Closing.", at: "2026-06-14T19:49:55Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-311", description: some(value: "commonTypeExpr grammar unification (STEP 1 toward FULL type/term conversion). FULL-CONVERSION GOAL: the grammar should NOT distinguish type-vs-term — merge the dual type/term productions into shared rules so 'types are terms' holds at the CFG level, and the LOADER classifies (sort_ref vs denoted/value vs application) via SymbolKind. This WI is the first, validated step: the application merge (parameterized_type == instantiation_term -> one 'application' rule) plus the dotted-path/field_access unification. VALIDATED (measured 2026-05-26, prototype reverted, baseline green): the application name MUST be the identifier-only dotted path $.name, NOT field_access — field_access's _atom_term receiver CASCADES type/term conflicts ([_atom_term,application] -> [_atom_term,_type] -> [_atom_term,_effect_type] -> ...). With $.name it generates CLEAN and Eq[T=Int] / a.b.Stack[T=Int] / Modify[c] / Vector[Int,3] all parse. REMAINING WORK: the contained name-vs-field_access overlap (a.b matches both) breaks p.x(?x) and g(a.b). Fix per 'do not distinguish in grammar, distinguish in loader': make a.b ONE path node everywhere — route fn_term names, bare references, and ident-chain projections through the dotted path — and RESTRICT field_access to non-name receivers (?x.y, foo().y); the loader classifies projection-vs-qualified-vs-application. SCOPE: grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js: application rule, fn_term/_atom_term/field_access restructure; full conversion later also merges tuple_type==tuple_literal) + converter (anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs) + corpus rebaseline (~27 trees, mostly node renames) + cargo green. PAYOFF: grammar cleanliness ('types are terms' at CFG level), NOT new capability — the loader already classifies. PREREQ/RELATED: builds on committed _common_type_expr = _type | literals + TypeExpr::Denoted (commit fcb75e6, branch wi302-denoted-value-in-type; WI-302 denoted value-in-type)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T19:49:59Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-332", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (already landed; verified + closed). The fix is on main (commit c9fc97f, 'WI-332: arrow_function_compatible compares effects via row subtyping'): arrow_function_compatible (typing.rs:14682-14702) now invokes subtype_effect_rows on the Function[E] effects field via canonical_effects_row, consistent with arrow_compatible — so the arrow-shorthand and Function[A,B,E]-alias spellings of the same denotational type now agree on subtyping. Missing E is polymorphic (accept any), symmetric with missing A; explicit E={} stays closed-empty and rejects effectful actuals (WI-335 shares the subst across param/result/effects). The stale docstring was updated. ACCEPTANCE EXCEEDED: the WI asked for one test (arrow(_,_,{Reads}) NOT <: Function[...,E={}]); main has FOUR WI-332 tests (named subtype_arrow_with_effect_not_le_function_no_effect = the exact acceptance case; + subtype_arrow_pure_le_function_with_effects covariant-subset; + subtype_arrow_with_effect_le_function_no_E_binding_polymorphic missing-E; + the Function-vs-arrow reverse direction), all part of a 16-test subtype_arrow block. VERIFIED GREEN 2026-06-14: cargo-test parse_tests -- subtype_arrow = 16 passed / 0 failed. Only the literal acceptance test NAME differs from the WI text (subtype_arrow_function_path_effects_consistent); the substance is covered and exceeded. Closing.", at: "2026-06-14T20:02:14Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-332", description: some(value: "Code-review WI-326 F3: arrow_function_compatible discards effects while arrow_compatible (post-WI-326) checks them via row subtyping. PROBLEM: types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{ReadIO}), parameterized Function[A=Int,B=Int]) routes to arrow_function_compatible (typing.rs ~5664) which destructures (Some((a_param, a_result, _)), Some((b_param, b_result, _))) — discards effects via _, returns true. The semantically-identical types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{ReadIO}), arrow(Int,Int,{})) goes through arrow_compatible and is correctly rejected by subtype_effect_rows. Same denotational type written in two syntaxes (typer's arrow shorthand vs stdlib Function[A,B,E] alias) gives opposite subtype answers. Doc comment at ~5668-5671 ('Effects are not compared here, also as in arrow_compatible') is now stale. SCOPE: extend arrow_function_compatible to invoke subtype_effect_rows on the effects field of the Function[E] parameterized side (extract via arrow_parts which returns the flattened Vec — use effects_rows_to_flat_list canonicalization or reconstruct an effects_rows term first); update the docstring. Confirm both directions (arrow vs Function[E], Function[E] vs arrow) get consistent treatment. ACCEPTANCE: new test 'subtype_arrow_function_path_effects_consistent' demonstrates arrow(int,int,{Reads}) NOT <: Function[A=Int,B=Int,E=List[]] (was true pre-fix; should be false). Full cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-326"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T20:02:18Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-333", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (done-but-not-closed sweep; spot-verified GREEN). Fix on main (commit 7db5351, 'WI-333: (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm uses row subtyping'): the (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm of types_compatible (typing.rs ~14238) dispatches to subtype_effect_rows (directional row subtyping) instead of conservative structural recursion; WI-335 later threaded the shared subst. 5 WI-333 tests in typing_test.rs (subtype_function_E_fewer_effects_le_more = acceptance substance Function[E={A}]<:Function[E={A,B}] + negative; _disjoint_effects_incompatible; _open_le_closed; _open_le_closed_extras_reject; _closed_le_open). Sibling WIs WI-334/WI-335 already Delivered. VERIFIED 2026-06-14: parse_tests -- subtype_function_E = 5 passed / 0 failed. Tracking-only close.", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:25Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-333", description: some(value: "Code-review WI-326 F5: parameterized_compatible bypasses row subtyping for the Function[E] denotation. PROBLEM: types_compatible(Function[E={Reads}], Function[E={Reads, Writes}]) recurses via parameterized_compatible on each binding, hitting types_compatible(effects_rows({Reads}), effects_rows({Reads, Writes})). The (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm at typing.rs ~5633 does conservative recursive structural compatibility on effects_expr only — explicit doc-comment notes 'distinct logical-var positions inside differently-allocated EffectExpression terms compare incompatible. Sound (no false positives).' But arrow(Int,Int,{Reads}) <: arrow(Int,Int,{Reads,Writes}) is now correctly accepted via subtype_effect_rows post-WI-326. Same denotational type written as Function[E] gives a different answer than the arrow form. SCOPE: dispatch the (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm in types_compatible to subtype_effect_rows instead of recursive structural equality. Need a local Substitution (matches arrow_compatible's pattern); the result is the directional row sub. This makes Function[E={Reads}] <: Function[E={Reads, Writes}] hold consistently with the arrow form. ACCEPTANCE: new test 'subtype_function_E_binding_uses_row_sub' covers Function[E={A}] <: Function[E={A, B}] and the negative case. Full cargo-test green. Closely related to WI-326 F3 (WI-332) but distinct: F3 is the arrow-vs-Function alias path, F5 is the Function-vs-Function path."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-326"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:29Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-342", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (done-but-not-closed sweep; spot-verified GREEN). The entity-representation migration (typer onto TermView; carrier-agnostic denoted->Value::Node) landed across ~30 commits (0b29019->8085b74): P1/P2 substrate+producer, P3 unify_types over TermView (b3a4d9e), P4 structural+types_compatible lockstep (990bce8..0f31beb), loader flip + consumer migration (E1/E2/E3 41e7c4d/90479cd, T8 ee0b5db..8085b74). make_denoted retirement spun to WI-366. Code: term_view.rs:327, node_occurrence.rs (NodeKind::Type), typing.rs carrier-agnostic unify_types/types_compatible. Tests: wi342_e2_modify_c_loads_value_carried, wi342_tyslot_lambda_carries_modify_effect, wi342_value_carried_modify_c_arrow_reads_through_termview, value_value_parameterized_denoted_unify, node_named_tuple_reads_fields_through_termview. Residual deferrals spun to WI-348/353/440. depends_on []; acceptance (cargo-test) met. VERIFIED 2026-06-14: parse_tests -- wi342 = 3 passed / 0 failed. Tracking-only close.", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:33Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-342", description: some(value: "Entity-representation migration / §8 core (path A) — make denoted carry a NodeOccurrence and route the typer's type-unification onto TermView. Spec: docs/design/entity-representation-term-or-value.md. Carrier rule: a denoted carries a NodeOccurrence (non-hash-consable) so any entity transitively containing a denoted must be a Value, recursively (Type AND EffectExpression). Representation (decided): a Value-carried type is Value::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence{kind: NodeKind::Type(TypeNode)}>) — NodeKind::Type added as a sibling kind mirroring the WI-318 Pattern precedent; TypeNode is a new enum mirroring the Type sort (sort_ref/parameterized/arrow/denoted/effects_rows/named_tuple/type_var/nothing), holding TermId for ground subtrees and Box<TypeNode>/Rc<NodeOccurrence> only on the denoted-poisoned spine. PHASES (each independently green): P1 substrate-only add (NodeKind::Type + TypeNode + the 4 mandatory walkers drain/for_each/reassemble/debruijn-open+close + as_type + new_type + occ_* view arms in term_view.rs; populated-but-not-consumed; zero behavior change; LOW risk). P2 first producer behind a NEW builder make_denoted_occ + upward Value-carriage propagation, route ONE loader site, dual-path (make_denoted/Ref consumers untouched; MEDIUM). P3 route unify_types onto TermView validated against P2 — re-express structural reads via head/pos_arg/named_arg, switch var-bind to bind_value+as_bind_value, KEEP variance/row arms as type-specific relations; 17 callers keep passing TermId via TermIdView (HIGHEST risk). P4 widen loader sites + migrate Ref-denoted consumers (extract_effect_resource_sym/region.rs/unwrap_denoted_value) + retire make_denoted. Chicken-and-egg broken by additive-substrate-first then dual-path then narrow-vertical then widen. Two unifications stay DISTINCT relations (resolver match_view exact vs typer subtype) sharing only the TermView+Substitution substrate. Open: equality/caching for Value-carried types (TermId== fast paths lose O(1)); propagation-lift location (builders vs normalizer); TypeNode arm granularity; alpha-equivalence home (unblocked by P3). Subsumes WI-341 step 2."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:37Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-366", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (done-but-not-closed sweep; spot-verified GREEN). Dep WI-390 is Delivered (b474ef7/b183018) so not blocked. B1 (written effect-row {} rides the term path byte-identical to provides) — dbc8a7e, 4 tests in wi366_value_in_type_facts_test.rs. B2a (OperationInfo.requires/ensures -> Vec<Value>) — f7b439b, op_info.rs:65,69. B2b (RequiresEntry.spec->Value) superseded by WI-390 (Term world made lossless for denoted); *_rides_as_term tests pin a faithful hash-consed Term with the denoted value preserved. ACCEPTANCE CAVEAT: original said 'make_denoted deleted / #[cfg(test)]-only'; it was deleted (fa5d885) then WI-390 deliberately re-introduced a faithful form (mod.rs:3423) — the dependency overrode that sub-clause BY DESIGN, not a regression. Test module wired (wi_tests.rs:184). VERIFIED 2026-06-14: wi_tests -- wi366 = 14 passed / 0 failed. Tracking-only close.", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:41Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-366", description: some(value: "WI-342 follow-up: fully retire make_denoted — migrate the ground-FACT value-in-type positions to value facts (gated on effect-expressions-as-types). After WI-342 T8 (commit 'WI-342 T8 wrap-up'), make_denoted is OFF the typer (T1-T7) and OFF every live value-in-type PRODUCTION path: entity fields (S4c), the Entity/EntityInfo schema facts (T8 'A'), op signatures (WI-348), and call type-args (T8 'C+B') all mint a Value::Node denoted via make_denoted_occ; a full-workspace probe confirms the loader no longer reaches make_denoted for any corpus input. make_denoted SURVIVES only as the GROUND (hash-consed) lowering in type_expr_to_term for the parameterized ground-FACT positions: SortAlias (sort-def 'sort T = ...'), SortView ('requires' / fact 'provides', via sort_inst_to_term + build_instantiation_term's Denoted placeholder at load.rs ~1085). (The redundant let k_type_name term slot was already dropped in T8 cleanup B.) These cannot carry a Value::Node until effect-expressions-as-types lets those fact slots THEMSELVES become value facts (a Modify[c] / value-in-type binding inside a SortView/SortAlias must ride as Value::Node, which a hash-consed TermId fact cannot hold). WORK: (1) make SortAlias / SortView / provides value facts — mirror the WI-348 OperationInfo + WI-342 EntityInfo/Entity value-fact split (build a Value head when any binding is Node, assert_fact_value, migrate consumers carrier-agnostically via rule_head_value/TermView); (2) THEN type_expr_to_term collapses to type_expr_to_value(ty).as_term().expect(ground) and make_denoted DELETES; rework the #[cfg(test)] cross-carrier fixtures (region.rs modify_label, mod.rs wi342 test, typing.rs cross-carrier tests) — keep a #[cfg(test)]-gated ground-denoted builder or raw alloc since the loader then emits only Node. CAUTION: the panicking as_term wrapper for type_expr_to_term was TRIED in T8 and REVERTED — /code-review empirically caught it regressing parseable programs that previously loaded as a ground denoted ('sort T = Vector[Int,3]', 'requires Vector[Int,3]'). So step (1) MUST precede the wrapper. Gated on effect-expressions-as-types (proposals 045/046 effect rows ride on the type representation; relates to WI-341 dependent arrows). Acceptance: ToolPasses(cargo-test); make_denoted deleted (or #[cfg(test)]-only); a SortAlias/SortView/provides value-in-type binding rides as Value::Node."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-390"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T20:11:45Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-373", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-14 (done-but-not-closed sweep; spot-verified GREEN). Phase C value rule heads (carrier-agnostic rule HEAD) delivered across 4 commits: 1969ff1 (slice 1 storage), 9b3a8e3 (gap 2 discrim keying), 6004d07 (closure re-add), 0d3bcda (gap 3 nested binding-extraction). Code present in tree: mod.rs:809,2162,2225 (assert_rule_*_nodes head: impl Into<Value>, var-collect/De-Bruijn-close), discrim.rs:595,987, persist_subst.rs:30,123,420 (VarPath nested descent), resolve.rs:5120 (arity>0 panic-guard removed). 6 acceptance tests exist+match: value_rule_head_node_stored_and_read_back, value_head_debruijn_var_in_occurrence_indexes_like_term, value_rule_head_with_var_asserts_closes_and_indexes, value_rule_head_with_var_resolves_and_binds_nested, + regressions nested_var_binds_to_fact_subterm, nested_var_goal_binds_against_ground_fact. Residual gap-1 carved to WI-378. VERIFIED 2026-06-14: anthill-core --lib -- value_rule_head = 3 passed / 0 failed. Tracking-only close.", at: "2026-06-14T20:12:25Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-373", description: some(value: "WI-348 Phase C: value rule heads — make a rule HEAD carrier-agnostic (carry Value::Node), not just facts. Today RuleEntry.head is already a Value (Phase B) but the rule-assertion entries (assert_rule_nodes / assert_rule_debruijn_with_nodes / _in_frame / finalize_rule_debruijn_nodes) take head: TermId and wrap Value::Term; assert_fact_value already proves carrier-agnostic head storage+indexing (incref_value_ground, TermView::head functor, skip-dedup-for-Node, insert_pattern via Value). SLICE 1 (assertion/storage/closure): head param -> impl Into<Value> (+ impl From<TermId> for Value so TermId callers are unchanged); carrier-agnostic var-collect (collect_vars_rec | collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered), DeBruijn-close (term_to_debruijn | node_to_debruijn), converge assert_rule_nodes storage/indexing with assert_fact_value; behaviour-identical for term heads; driving test = assert Value::Node-headed rule, read via rule_head_value, find via query_view. SLICE 2 (resolver): with_fresh_vars opening a value head = De-Bruijn-over-occurrence (the documented Phase C gap, mod.rs ~2358); + rule_head term-only readers migrate reactively. NO consumer yet (forward-correct substrate, like the rest of WI-348). sort stays TermId (nominal bucket key, by_sort/by_domain/fact_dedup; hash-cons-appropriate per the representation note; even assert_fact_value keeps sort: TermId). Follows WI-348 (delivered) + WI-372."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T20:12:29Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-405", author: "user", content: "UN-CLAIMED back to Open 2026-06-14 (was Claimed but NOT STARTED — confirmed by sweep): both facets still latent on main, only tracking-only commits, no WI-405-tagged code/tests. Matches the prior 'un-claiming' note. Off the critical path but real.", at: "2026-06-14T20:45:04Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-302", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (ce21e7a). Scope = the VALUE-IN-TYPE representation per the scope-correction. The SINGLE-segment case (Modify[c], scope-aware value->denoted via SymbolKind) was already complete from prior sessions (WI-313/342/348/361/366/390/424). This session closed the COMPOUND value field-path case (Modify[result.a] / Modify[c.contents], proposal 027.1 'per projection'), which previously emitted a stray 'unresolved name' warning + loaded a bogus sort_ref (remap_name joined the segments). FIX: new loader try_denoted_value_path builds the DotApply field-access chain wrapped in make_denoted_occ (compound peer of single-segment denoted, lowercase-last twin of ExprCarried). Made the new DotApply-carrying denoted a FIRST-CLASS shape across the 4 paths that handled only the Ref carrier: rewrite_ref_expr (call-site effect re-key d->c, recurse the DotApply spine), unify_denoted_view (structural equality of non-Ref value occurrences), denoted_value_display (render c.contents not ?), occurrence_to_term (WI-390 lossless lowering to the dot_apply term twin, byte-identical to LoadBuildFrame::DotApply = WI-425 isomorphism, verified by a round-trip test). Cleanup: extracted symbol_is_value_place (the value-vs-sort discriminator was copied 3x). 3 /code-review passes (initial + downstream + focused term-lowering verifier): the downstream pass found the re-key/unify/display gaps (fixed), the sweep found the occurrence_to_term term-lowering gap (fixed+verified), the focused verifier CONFIRMED the encoding byte-identical with no bug. 5 new tests; full workspace 1798 green. FOLLOW-ON (the ticket's explicit deferral): denoted->CONCRETE-TYPE REDUCTION ('the actual reduction', typer elaboration) is NOT done -- a denoted value indexes the type opaquely; reducing c.contents to its concrete type is the dependent-typing follow-on. Also deferred: args-bearing (method-call) denoted values (only arg-less field access minted); WI-404 (denoted self-conformance in subtype) is a separate Open ticket.", at: "2026-06-14T21:20:06Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-302", description: some(value: "Computed type arguments: allow an expression (operation / method call) as a type-binding value, e.g. `Function[A = param_type, B = result_type(br), E = result_effects(br)]` and `List[T = TypingEnv.apply_subst(env3, elem_type)]`. PROBLEM: sort_binding's value slot is `_type` (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:1001) = {simple_type, parameterized_type, variable_term, tuple_type, arrow_type}; a function/method call (fn_term / field_access call) is not a `_type`, so `[T = f(x)]` is ungrammatical. The reference typing spec docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill NEEDS this to express type construction from computed components (a Function type whose B / E are computed from sub-results) in its reference-algorithm part. These parse errors are masked because parse() swallows tree-sitter ERROR / MISSING nodes (see WI-303). CONSEQUENCE: the test typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads (rustland/anthill-core/tests/include/typing_test.rs) is GREEN only because the errors are swallowed; making it honest is part of WI-303. TASK: decide and implement how computed expressions may appear in type-argument position — likely widen the sort_binding value slot (and convert_instantiation_term's named branch + convert_type_value, which today only preserves parametric type shapes) to accept a term expression, with the typer evaluating / normalizing it to a Type; define the interaction with the existing _type forms. ACCEPTANCE: `List[T = f(x)]` and `Function[B = g(y)]` parse; typing_pass_spec.anthill parses with 0 errors; cargo-test green. SCOPE: grammar + converter are shared; typer is Rust-only (scaland has no typer). RELATED: WI-301 (effect-set type args) — both widen what may appear as a type argument; coordinate the grammar change."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T21:20:12Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-302", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION to the prior delivery note's FOLLOW-ON line: 'denoted->concrete-type REDUCTION (dependent typing)' was IMPRECISE — that label was pulled from the EARLIER (superseded) option-B feedback about COMPUTED CALLS and wrongly re-attached here. Accurate picture: value-in-type denoted is value-DEPENDENT typing (proposal 011 / 027.1) — the value INDEXES the type opaquely BY DESIGN (Modify[c] = 'modifies resource c'; Vector[Int,3]); there is NO reduce-to-concrete-type step, the opacity IS the end state. PATH-DEPENDENT typing (s.T, UPPERCASE member -> ExprCarried/RigidProjection, delta-reduction) is the ORTHOGONAL, ALREADY-IMPLEMENTED type-MEMBER projection (WI-376/400/428/430); the two split on the LAST SEGMENT's casing (uppercase=type projection, lowercase=value-index denoted) at load.rs ~6574. 'denoted->concrete reduction' (evaluate a redex to a type) actually belongs to the COMPUTED-CALL case (List[T=f(x)]), which the scope-correction explicitly carved OUT of WI-302 (separate; grammar reverted). ACCURATE DEFERRED LIST: (1) DEFINITE/verified — CALLS in a type-arg slot don't parse (Modify[f(x)], c.foo(x), List[T=f(x)]): _common_type_expr admits names/projections/literals/rows, not calls (reduce-tier, deferred); my loader only builds arg-less field-access chains. (2) LIKELY/not-probed — value-ALIASING equality of denoted indices: unify_denoted_view compares value paths STRUCTURALLY, so let y=c; Modify[y.contents] would not equal Modify[c.contents]; the projection side already canonicalizes let-aliases (WI-400 inc C), the denoted side doesn't. (3) LIKELY/not-probed — full per-projection effect DISCHARGE (027.1 Modify[result.a] escape/partial-coverage): the re-key d->c + declaration-matching were verified this session; the complete flow/escape inference was not. SEPARATE TICKET (not WI-302's own deferral): WI-404 = denoted self-conformance in the SUBTYPE check (types_compatible) — the subtype peer of this session's unify fix. What WAS fully verified: load -> re-key -> unify -> display -> lossless term-twin lowering for the structural case.", at: "2026-06-14T21:31:17Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-465", description: some(value: "Grammar+typer: ADMIT TERM/CALL forms in a TYPE-ARGUMENT slot -- computed type args (List[T = f(x)], Function[B = result_type(br)]) and CALL-VALUED value-in-type indices (Modify[f(x)], Modify[c.foo(x)]). GAP: _common_type_expr (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js ~147) admits _type | int/float/string/bool literal | effect_row but NOT _expr/fn_term/a call, so a call where a type-arg value is expected is ungrammatical (parse rejects it). Grammar comment: 'Calls (Modify[f(x)]) are reduce-tier and deferred until the typer has a reduction hook.' This is the WI-302 deferred item #1 (calls in a type-arg slot don't parse) and the dual of WI-301 (effect-set-in-type-arg, REJECTED -- rows parse now). WHY HARD (validated by WI-311): admitting a call/field_access form as the type-arg-slot/application base CASCADES type/term grammar conflicts -- WI-311 measured 'field_access's _atom_term receiver CASCADES type/term conflicts ([_atom_term,application]->[_atom_term,_type]->[_atom_term,_effect_type]->...)'. WI-311 therefore did STEP 1 only (parameterized_type+instantiation_term -> one 'application' rule, dotted $.name base) and DEFERRED the rest. This ticket IS that deferred 'FULL type/term conversion' -- the part that admits a term/call where a type is expected, LOADER classifying (sort_ref vs denoted vs application vs computed-redex). DESIGN DECISION REQUIRED FIRST (do not just implement): this REVERSES the project's current 'loader-classifies, no CFG-level types-are-terms' stance. WI-311 was closed partly because 'CLAUDE.md's representation note walked back the types-are-terms-at-CFG-level motivation', and WI-302 (value-in-type denoted) + WI-311 (application merge) both doubled down on loader-classification of forms that ALREADY parse. Admitting calls needs EITHER (i) the full type/term CFG unification (route every term/call through shared rules, loader classifies -- the conflict-cascading path WI-311 validated; contradicts the walked-back motivation = a real direction change), OR (ii) a NARROWER targeted widening of just the type-arg-value slot to accept a call/expr if it can be done conflict-free. Pick one. NO ACTIVE DRIVER today: the original computed-call driver (typing_pass_spec Function[B=result_type(br)] / List[T=...apply_subst...]) was SIDESTEPPED by WI-308 (rewrite to explicit Type constructors), and WI-301 was rejected -- so this is a future/speculative capability; file-and-park until a real consumer needs it. REPRESENTATION: a CALL-VALUED index rides as Type.denoted(value: <call-occurrence>) (WI-302's denoted carrying a redex, not a field-path); a COMPUTED-TYPE arg (List[T=f(x)] where f(x) evaluates to a Type) additionally needs the typer ELABORATION hook = denoted->concrete-Type REDUCTION (evaluate the redex to a type) -- the genuine 'reduction' deferral, distinct from value-in-type which indexes opaquely and never reduces. SCOPE: grammar (grammar.js type-arg-value slot / application base + precedence; corpus rebaseline) + converter (parse/convert.rs) + loader classification (load.rs type_expr_to_child) + optionally the typer reduction hook for computed-type args. BUILDS ON WI-311 (application merge, delivered). RELATED: WI-302 (denoted, delivered), WI-303 (parse-error substrate), WI-301 (effect-set-in-type-arg, rejected). ACCEPTANCE: record a design decision FIRST (CFG-unification vs targeted widening); then Modify[f(x)] / List[T=f(x)] parse (0 errors) and load (call-valued -> denoted redex; computed-type -> reduced or denoted), full suite green."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-311"]), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-466", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-405", description: some(value: "Typer GAP: the subtype relation (types_compatible) applies its helpers NON-UNIFORMLY across dispatch arms, causing latent FALSE-REJECTS. Surfaced by the WI-381 and WI-384 /code-reviews; both latent today (suite green) but real. FACET A (provider-admissibility, WI-384 deferred): sort_provides_admissibly (WI-344) is confined to the (sort_ref,sort_ref) bare<->bare arm of types_compatible_term_dispatch (anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs ~9602); the (parameterized,sort_ref)/(sort_ref,parameterized) arms do sort_sym_compatible (nominal base) ONLY. So a value whose type is a PARTIAL parameterized form (e.g. a constructor result S[T=?_] after WI-384, or any S[bindings]) compared against a BARE provider spec Spec (where 'S provides Spec') loses provider admissibility -> false-reject. Not triggered: the only stdlib provider (List) is single-param so never produces a partial ?_; reproduces with a multi-param S[A,B] + fact Spec[carrier=S] + a constructor binding only A, returned where bare Spec is expected. FACET B (alias-resolution, WI-381 deferred): WI-381 wired resolve_alias_shape into the (sort_ref,parameterized)/(parameterized,sort_ref) arms (both carriers) but NOT the (sort_ref,sort_ref) arm; so two aliases of the same shape (sort IntList = List[T=Int]; sort IntList2 = List[T=Int]) compared bare<->bare do a nominal NAME compare only -> IntList does not conform to IntList2 (false-reject). ROOT CAUSE: relation helpers (alias-shape resolution, provider admissibility) are applied per-arm, not uniformly. FIX DIRECTION (pick one): (i) normalize/resolve at a SINGLE point before dispatch -- the WI-381 altitude option, but no single walk point covers types_compatible's TERM path (it does not walk at entry) and the blast radius is broad; or (ii) thread the helpers through the remaining arms ((sort_ref,sort_ref) alias resolution; provider admissibility in the parameterized<->sort_ref arms). ACCEPTANCE: a partial parameterized result conforms to a bare provider spec it provides; an alias conforms to a same-shape alias; regression tests for both facets; full anthill-core green. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-14T23:51:33Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-454", description: some(value: "Grammar+parse SUGAR (deferred from WI-451): the PER-STATEMENT non-rigid type-variable binder synonyms 'sort ?X' (prefix, the ?x logical-var marker) and 'sort [X]' (standalone bracket binder), as synonyms of 'sort X = ?' / the enclosing-list param (design path-dependent-types.md §5.4 'The carrier is a non-rigid type variable'; all desugar to the same SortAlias->Var backing var + is_type_param marker). Includes the structured forms 'sort ?F { sort ?T }' / 'sort [F] { sort [T] }'. NEEDS new grammar productions: bare 'sort ?X' fits neither abstract_sort ('sort X = type') nor sort_with_body (requires a body); standalone 'sort [X]' is the binder-as-name case. WI-451 delivered the canonical ENCLOSING-LIST form 'sort CpsMonad[F[T], A, B]' (sufficient for the migration + WI-452/453); these synonyms are pure surface ergonomics, NOT on the critical path. Rust-only (grammar.js + parse/convert.rs); reuses the WI-451 is_type_param marker + desugar. Acceptance: cargo-test (parse-IR equivalence to the enclosing-list form)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-451"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T00:58:44Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-066", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-15. Int64.div/mod/rem/divExact + Field.div/recip declare 'effects Error[DivisionByZero]'; effects.anthill adds the DivisionByZero payload sort (nullary, alongside MatchFailed); DivisionByZero added to IMPLICIT_PRELUDE_EFFECTS (parallel to MatchFailed) so external callers need no explicit import. Typer threads it via check_operation_bodies (no typer code change); runtime UNCHANGED (bespoke EvalError::DivisionByZero, mirroring MatchFailed). Extended beyond the literal list for consistency: divExact (a div alias) + Field.recip (the partial 1/a primitive). TESTS: 3 eval fixtures updated + new wi066_division_effect_test (undeclared int-div use = load error 'undeclared effect: Error[DivisionByZero]'; declared use loads via implicit prelude; mod carries it). Full anthill-core suite GREEN (1485/0/3). /code-review (3 finder agents): cross-file sweep clean (no .anthill op body does int-div outside rules; no Field instance exists); FIXED finding-2 (DivisionByZero->IMPLICIT_PRELUDE_EFFECTS). Findings deferred to follow-ups: F1 type-vs-runtime catchability (div returns bespoke EvalError, not routed via raise_error -> a handler can't catch it; consistent with MatchFailed precedent) + F5 (nullary payload loses op name) -> filed as the catchability bridge WI; F3 (Field.div effect vs a future Float-as-Field carrier wanting pure div) -> noted. REFINEMENT PATH: proposal 048 (conditional/guarded effects) makes div's effect '{ Error[DivisionByZero] :- eq(b,0) }', discharged when neq(b,0) is proven (WI-067); WI-066's unconditional effect is the degenerate :- true case.", at: "2026-06-15T06:00:44Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-066", description: some(value: "Encode partiality of integer division as Error-effect. Currently Int.div and Field.div errors on divide-by-zero only at runtime (EvalError::DivisionByZero). Add Error[DivisionByZero] to signatures: Int.div, Int.mod, Int.rem, Field.div all grow effects Error[DivisionByZero]. Add sort DivisionByZero payload alongside MatchFailed in effects.anthill. Float.div stays pure (IEEE 0.0/0.0=NaN, 1.0/0.0=Inf are defined values, not errors). Downstream: callers using / on Ints must declare Error[DivisionByZero] in their effect rows OR handle it. Typer may need to thread this; existing tests might need updates."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-065"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T06:00:48Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-467", description: some(value: "Runtime catchability for bespoke Error-effect failures: route Error.MatchFailed and Error.DivisionByZero through the Error handler (interp.raise_error -> Raised) so an installed Error[...] handler actually catches them. TODAY both are bespoke EvalError variants (EvalError::MatchFailed / EvalError::DivisionByZero, constructed directly in eval.rs / eval/builtins.rs), NOT routed through raise_error, so the declared 'effects Error[MatchFailed]' / 'effects Error[DivisionByZero]' (WI-066) is type-level only -- a handler is never consulted. The bridge already exists and is used by the store-I/O builtins (eval/builtins.rs raise_error at persist/retract/flush/retrieve -> HandlerAction::Throw -> EvalError::Raised). From the WI-066 /code-review (Finding 1 + Finding 5). SCOPE: (a) the div builtins (int_div/int_mod/int_rem, eval/builtins.rs) already take &mut Interpreter -> call interp.raise_error(<DivisionByZero payload>) instead of returning EvalError::DivisionByZero; (b) give the DivisionByZero sort an 'op: String' field (parity with EvalError::DivisionByZero { op }) so the payload carries which op failed; (c) match-failure similarly; (d) update m3_int_division_by_zero (expects EvalError::DivisionByZero) to expect the routed/Raised form, or assert handler-catch. Note runtime behavior change: an unhandled div-by-zero becomes Raised(payload) not DivisionByZero. RELATES: proposal 047 (effect handlers), proposal 048 open-question E (static guard discharge must agree with the dynamic handler)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-066"]), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-467", name: "effects")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "user", content: "DESIGN HOME: proposal 048 (conditional/guarded effects, docs/proposals/048-conditional-effects.md). WI-067 IS the discharge mechanism that 048 specifies: div's effect becomes '{ Error[DivisionByZero] :- eq(b,0) }' (048 Phase 3, refining WI-066's unconditional effect), and WI-067 DROPS the guarded element at a call site by REFUTING the guard (proving neq(b,0)) from: abstract interp (literal divisor), context propagation (enclosing if neq(b,0) / match arm), KB resolution, or a proof declaration (018 discharge taxonomy). The discharged contribution is a CONCRETE row, so row unification is unchanged. Framed as SLD refutation over the effect-row-as-Horn-theory (aligns with WI-010/382 resolver-as-typechecker). NOT a precondition/obligation (pure-effects; discharge is an optional optimization). Build order per 048: grammar (':- guard' on effect-row elements) -> WI-067 discharge (literal + flow-fact first) -> migrate Int64.div/mod/rem + Field.div. depends_on remains; see 048 open questions A-E.", at: "2026-06-15T06:00:57Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-468", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-457", description: some(value: "Typer/WI-401 escape-gate gap: an ABSTRACTING (sealing) return via an IF/MATCH-JOIN body slips abstracting_return_error. Today '-> KVStore = if persistent then diskStore else memStore' (bare-spec return, NO ensures) LOADS: the branch-join (compute_branch_join_type) widens the divergent concrete providers up to the bare spec, so body_ty = the declared return sort and the gate's same_symbol(body_sort, ret_sort) returns None (no error). The DIRECT upcast '-> KVStore = memStore' is correctly rejected (body_sort=MemStore != KVStore). So an abstract member (KVStore.K) can ESCAPE via a join-typed body without an 'ensures' vouching for it, bypassing WI-401's escape-free guarantee for the strict base model. Runtime-sound (the value is a real backend) but over-accepting — the type discipline's escape model is bypassed for join bodies. SURFACED during WI-402 (the existential half); deliberately NOT tightened there (WI-401 scope + cascade risk into delivered functionality). FIX SKETCH: when the body type is a JOIN that widened divergent concrete providers up to the bare/partial spec, treat it like the direct upcast in abstracting_return_error — flag unless ensures vouches (kb.existential_return_ops marker). Must NOT reject a legitimate same-sort join or a fully-manifest-spec join. Verify wi402_existential_return_test + wi401_escape_free_return_test + branch-join tests stay green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T06:26:12Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-469", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-460", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED: eliminate_node_projections recursively rewrites a projection nested in a denoted-bearing Value::Node carrier (arrow/parameterized/effect-row) -- Node twin of rewrite_term_projections, mirrors rewrite_type_occ_deep; Ground children via rewrite_term_projections, Node children recurse (may collapse Node->Term via value_to_type_child); Denoted leaves preserved; NamedTuple-with-projection + malformed ExprCarried member bail loudly (no silent leak). wi376 negative test projection_in_denoted_node_is_rejected REPLACED by projection_in_denoted_arrow_threads (+wrong-element reject) + projection_in_denoted_parameterized_no_longer_bails + projection_in_denoted_arrow_evals (typecheck+eval). /code-review (3 finder agents): (1) effect-row/WI-441 lacks rebuild SOUND (binder alignment is symbol-driven, span/owner never compared); (2) silent-passthrough nit in ExprCarried else HARDENED to loud error; (3) callback-PARAM/RESULT validation gap = PRE-EXISTING WI-385 limitation (validate_arg_against_param skips Value::Node denoted-arrow params), reproduces for non-projection denoted arrows too, filed as WI-469. Return/threading direction (the ticket scope) IS soundly validated. ORTHOGONAL: Modify[c] denoted effect-ROW equality fails across a call even with NO projection (pre-existing, WI-459-class) -- why projection_in_denoted_parameterized_no_longer_bails asserts only no-bail+no-leak.", at: "2026-06-15T07:05:54Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-460", description: some(value: "Typer: admit an expression-carried projection (s.T) NESTED in a denoted-bearing ARROW type -- the documented WI-376 'Node-carrier rewrite' follow-on (wi376 projection_in_denoted_node_is_rejected). REPRO: operation find[EffP](s: Stream, pred: (x: s.T) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]}) -> Option[s.T] effects {s.E, EffP} -> 'find.pred/return: a type projection nested in a denoted-bearing type (a written effect row / value-in-type) is not yet supported'. The arrow carries a denoted row (the -Modify[x] binder), so s.T inside it is rejected AT FORMATION rather than eliminated. FIX DIRECTION: eliminate the ExprCarried projection INSIDE the Value::Node arrow carrier (rewrite it against the receiver's synthesized type, as the non-denoted projection path already does) instead of bailing. BLOCKS WI-447 find. TEST: Stream.find in bare projection form typechecks+evals; the wi376 negative test still rejects a genuine value-in-type (e.g. E={Modify[c]}) projection, or is updated to the supported subset."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T07:06:19Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-461", description: some(value: "Typer: a bare-receiver IDENTITY body returning the receiver as a PROVIDED sort must thread the projection through provider-admissibility. REPRO: operation iterator(l: List) -> Stream[T=l.T, E={}] = l -> 'iterator.return: expected Stream[E={empty_row}, T=l.T], got List'. The body l:List (bare) is admissible-as-Stream via 'List provides Stream[T,{}]', but the bare param's element is NOT pinned to l.T for the admissibility unify, so List's provided Stream[T=?] won't match the declared Stream[T=l.T]. The original explicit iterator[Elem](l: List[Elem]) -> Stream[Elem,{}] worked (Elem pinned). FIX DIRECTION: in provider-admissibility unify, treat the bare self-receiver's element as its projection l.T (the WI-374 member tie) so List[T=l.T] provides Stream[T=l.T,{}]. BLOCKS WI-447 iterator. TEST: bare iterator typechecks+evals; wi368 (collect(iterator(xs)) pure + element threaded) green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T08:07:11Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-461", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED a38faae (amended). /code-review (3 agents): 2 correctness/soundness agents found NOTHING (byte-identity of refined l.T verified, additive subst handling clean, walk-pv resolution sound). Test agent: strengthened eval to pin order (123 not just len 3), negatives now assert the .return mismatch specifically, ADDED multi-param carrier tests (Box2[A,B] provides Spec2[X,Y]: idok loads, idswap REJECTED) — empirically confirms the multi-binding loop + member-rename (carrier A/B vs spec X/Y) is correct AND sound. DEFERRED (out of WI-461's narrow identity-body scope, NOT blocking): (1) ALTITUDE — refine_self_receiver_body_type is a return-site special case; the general member-tie (a bare carrier-param value  has type List[P=l.P] wherever USED) would also cover let-bound/nested-arg/if-join receivers. The stdlib iterator is a DIRECT identity body so the narrow fix suffices for WI-447; generalize if a later site re-hits 'expected Stream[T=l.T], got List'. (2) let-alias identity  would build y.T vs declared l.T — needs WI-400 let-alias canonicalization threaded into this check; untested, not needed by stdlib.", at: "2026-06-15T08:17:28Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-470", author: "user", content: "Empirical O(1)-equality usage map (the 'derived index where it pays' detail). LOAD-BEARING & NOMINAL -> keep hash-consed, OUT OF SCOPE (not arrow/row structure): by_sort/by_domain rule indexes (kb/mod.rs:251-253), fact_dedup HashMap<(term,sort,domain),RuleId> (kb/mod.rs:270, WI-233). OPTIMIZATION -> structural compare or Rc::ptr_eq recovers: unify_types + unify_effect_rows fast-path 'if x==y return true' (typing.rs:11937, 13971), bind_term consistency (subst.rs:100), query_cache (resolve.rs:353), within-row atoms.dedup() (mod.rs:3386), rigid-projection diag dedup (typing.rs:6954). ALREADY NOT TermId-keyed: discrim tree (structural DiscrimKey), answer dedup (GoalKey/StructToken structural fingerprint, WI-348 - the proven precedent for dropping TermId keys once goals are Node-carried). Conclusion: the load-bearing equality uses key on FACTS + NOMINAL SORTS (which stay hash-consed); arrows/effect-rows appear only in the recoverable unify fast-path, so migrating them to occurrences leaves the load-bearing uses intact.", at: "2026-06-15T08:10:56Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-470", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION to the prior usage-map note's 'facts + nominal sorts out of scope': facts CAN carry arbitrary expressions incl. arrow/effect-row types (and a parameterized sort key Fn{S,bindings} can embed them too), so they are NOT categorically separable from the structure this WI moves. The reason it is still safe is different: the O(1) fact mechanism is already best-effort + carrier-tolerant. fact_dedup (kb/mod.rs:786-805) is inserted ONLY for a Term-carrier head -- 'a value Node head has no TermId key, a dedup-miss not unsoundness' (WI-348 Phase B). Resolution-time fact MATCHING is the discrim tree (structural DiscrimKey via TermView, carrier-agnostic), NOT an O(1) TermId lookup. by_sort/by_domain are coarse buckets keyed by sort/domain TermId, populated carrier-agnostically via TermView. So a fact/sort embedding an occurrence-backed arrow/row would Node-degrade its assert-time dedup (soundly -- the existing WI-348 path) and still resolve via discrim: no correctness loss, at most a lost assert-time dedup optimization on those facts. Also: the nominal-sort index key is the sort IDENTITY TERM (Ref(sym) / parameterized Fn), NOT a SortInfo predicate -- SortInfo (reflect.anthill:464) is the reflective description, and it already mixes Term (definition, effects) and NodeOccurrence (requires/ensures) carriers.", at: "2026-06-15T08:21:13Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-470", author: "user", content: "CANDIDATE IMPL MECHANISM (design discussion): give NodeOccurrence a lazy per-node term cache -- Cell<Option<TermId>> memoizing the node's INTRINSIC structural term form (vars as Var leaves, sigma-independent), materialized on demand via the existing occurrence_term path through the hash-consing TermStore. Because alloc dedups, two structurally-identical occurrences materialize to the SAME TermId -> recovers hash-cons identity on demand for the few TermId-demand consumers (fact_dedup, by_sort keys embedding function types, the unify identity fast-path). It CLOSES the current Node-head fact-dedup-miss: assert_fact_value (mod.rs:1273-1286) skips fact_dedup for Node/Entity heads, so two structurally-identical Node-headed ground facts both insert today; the cache gives the head a TermId to key on. Constraints: (1) cache the sigma-INDEPENDENT intrinsic form only -- resolution-time answer dedup keeps using goal_fingerprint THROUGH sigma, never this cache; (2) invalidate on STRUCTURAL mutation only -- occurrences are Rc-shared and simp_rewrite is tree-producing, so effectively compute-once, and non-structural type annotations do NOT invalidate; (3) the cached TermId holds a TermStore refcount -> release on node drop / cache clear; (4) it re-introduces the materialization WI-348 deliberately avoided, so use it ONLY on genuine TermId-demand paths and keep goal_fingerprint where a hashable key suffices. This is the occurrence-primary + TermId-on-demand bridge that makes the migration non-invasive.", at: "2026-06-15T08:37:57Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-462", description: some(value: "Typer: TUPLE-LITERAL element threading parity with the Pair-CONSTRUCTOR (bidirectional expected->component push). REPRO: operation split(xs: List) -> Option[(xs.T, List[T=xs.T])] = match xs case nil->none case cons(h,t)->some((h,t)) -> 'match.rule: expected Option[(_1: xs.T, _2: List[T=xs.T])], got Option[(_1: ?_, _2: List)]'. The Pair-CONSTRUCTOR pair(h,t) vs Pair[A=xs.T,B=List[T=xs.T]] THREADS (verified probe B1); the positional TUPLE literal (h,t) vs (xs.T, List[T=xs.T]) does NOT (head h stays ?_, tail t stays bare List). DIAGNOSIS: the WI-427 bidirectional expected->argument push reaches named constructor args but not positional tuple-literal components. FIX DIRECTION: push expected tuple component types into the tuple-literal elements (h<-xs.T; t:List expands to List[T=xs.T]). BLOCKS WI-447 split. TEST: bare split typechecks; tuple-component threading test."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T11:15:36Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-472", description: some(value: "Wire the WI-471 NodeOccurrence term cache into fact_dedup so Node/Entity-headed ground facts are de-duplicated (close the Node-head fact-dedup-miss). Today assert_fact_value (kb/mod.rs:1273-1286) stores a Node/Entity head directly and SKIPS fact_dedup ('a dedup-miss, not unsound'), so two structurally-identical Node-headed ground facts both insert. Use occ.cached_term(kb) (WI-471) as the dedup key for a Value::Node head; for a Value::Entity head materialize the whole head via value_to_term (or stash the key TermId in RuleEntry at assert). Extend retract (kb/mod.rs:1398-1408) to remove these Node/Entity-head fact_dedup entries, mirroring the existing Term-head removal (rid-guarded). RECLAMATION of the cache's owned +1: v1 = pin-for-lifetime (retract removes the entry but leaves the cached term alive; freed wholesale at KB teardown; bounded, benign, sharing-safe). Optional upgrade (split into its own ticket if the pin ever matters): a process-wide deferred-release queue keyed by (KbId, TermId) -- Drop enqueues at last-Rc-drop (sharing handled automatically, no unique-ownership gating; node stays KB-decoupled via Copy tags), KB force-drains at op boundaries (terms.release), KnowledgeBase::Drop purges its own orphan KbId entries. NOTE: any owned +1 breaks the WI-246 invariant that body occurrences hold no term-store refcount -- update the retract comment (kb/mod.rs:1417-1418). VERIFY: whether fact HEAD occurrences are ever Rc-shared (decides if reclamation gating is needed -- the deferred queue handles it regardless); Entity-head dedup-key storage. TEST: two structurally-identical Node-headed ground facts dedup to one RuleEntry; assert/retract/re-assert behaves; existing Term-head dedup + value_fact_dedup_keeps_distinct_node_answers stay green."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-471"]), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-471", author: "user", content: "Field-shape decision (increment 1 puts the KbId tag in NOW): term_cache is Cell<Option<(KbId, TermId)>> from the start, so WI-472's deferred-release queue can land without re-touching the ~7 construction sites. Requires KnowledgeBase to carry a unique id (KbId newtype, assigned at new() from a process-wide AtomicU64 counter so distinct KBs never collide), stamped by cached_term at materialize time. Increment 1 POPULATES (KbId, TermId) on demand but wires NO drain/release (dormant, pin-for-lifetime); the drain + KnowledgeBase::Drop orphan-purge are WI-472. cached_term is a free fn taking &Rc<NodeOccurrence> (mirrors occurrence_to_term) since it needs the Rc for the recursive materialize; callers clone the occ Rc out of the kb first to avoid the &mut kb / &occ borrow clash.", at: "2026-06-15T10:21:38Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-472", author: "user", content: "Carry-forward from WI-471's /code-review (3 finder angles): (1) DRAIN MUST RELEASE PER-CELL, not per-unique-TermId. Two distinct occurrences with identical structure each take their OWN +1 on the same hash-consed TermId (alloc increments on the existing-term hit), so the term's refcount = number of populated cells. The deferred-release queue must release once per cached CELL entry (matching the per-cell +1) -- NOT once per unique TermId -- else it under-releases (leak) or, combined with any stray caller release, over-releases (free/dangle). (2) cached_term returns a BORROWED TermId (the cache owns the pinned +1); demand sites here (fact_dedup key) must use it WITHOUT releasing -- consistent with the existing non-owning bind_term model. (3) cached_term ALREADY guards the read by KbId (returns the memoized id only when id == kb.id, else re-materializes against the current store), so the queue's per-KB drain can trust the KbId stamp. (4) REUSE opportunity (separate perf, not required for WI-472): the existing occurrence_to_term caller at kb/mod.rs:2603 (rule-body Value::Node binding normalization) re-walks each binding spine per firing and could call cached_term to memoize (same-KB, safe).", at: "2026-06-15T10:43:36Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-471", description: some(value: "Lazy per-node term cache on NodeOccurrence: an optional on-demand TermId memoizing the node's INTRINSIC structural term form (vars as Var leaves, sigma-independent), materialized via the existing occurrence_term path through the hash-consing TermStore and cached (field term_cache: Cell<Option<TermId>>), cleared on structural mutation. Because alloc dedups, two structurally-identical occurrences materialize to the SAME TermId, recovering hash-cons identity on demand for the TermId-demand consumers (fact_dedup, by_sort keys that embed function types, the unify identity fast-path) WITHOUT making occurrences term-backed. Standalone value: closes the Node-head fact-dedup-miss -- assert_fact_value (kb/mod.rs:1273-1286) skips fact_dedup for Node/Entity heads, so two structurally-identical Node-headed ground facts both insert today; an on-demand TermId gives fact_dedup a key. Constraints: (1) cache the sigma-INDEPENDENT intrinsic form ONLY -- resolution-time answer dedup keeps using goal_fingerprint through sigma, never this cache; (2) invalidate on STRUCTURAL mutation only (occurrences are Rc-shared and simp_rewrite is tree-producing, so effectively compute-once; type annotations do not invalidate); (3) the cached TermId holds a TermStore refcount, released on node drop / cache clear; (4) materialization re-grows the TermStore (what WI-348 avoided), so use the TermId only on genuine TermId-demand paths and keep goal_fingerprint where a hashable key suffices. Enables WI-470 (occurrence-primary Type/EffectExpression) non-invasively: the occurrence->TermId-on-demand bridge keeping the TermId-demand consumers working."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T10:46:26Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-473", description: some(value: "Deferred-release queue: reclaim WI-471's pinned cache terms when their NodeOccurrence drops, instead of pin-for-lifetime. WI-471's term_cache owns a +1 it never releases (Drop cannot reach the store), so cached terms live until KB teardown -- a bounded but real leak under retract/re-assert churn or heavy transient-type inference. Mechanism (KB-DECOUPLED, no node->KB reference): NodeOccurrence::Drop, if term_cache is Some((KbId, TermId)), pushes that Copy pair into a process-wide thread_local release queue (Drop stays store-free); the KB force-drains its OWN KbId entries at safe op boundaries (top of assert/retract/query), calling terms.release once PER CELL (matching the per-cell +1; NOT per-unique-TermId -- see WI-472 note 1); KnowledgeBase::Drop purges its own orphan KbId entries (no release -- its store is dying). Drop fires only at last-Rc-drop, so sharing is handled automatically (no unique-ownership gating needed). Reconciles the WI-246 invariant exception WI-471 introduced (a cached occurrence now owns a term-store refcount). OPTIONAL, NOT a gate: WI-470 and WI-472 work with pin-for-lifetime and do NOT depend on this; it only trims the leak once they populate the cache in production. Depends only on WI-471; buildable + testable against WI-471's mechanism alone (cache occurrences, drop them, drain, assert refcounts released and the term freed)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-471"]), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-472", author: "user", content: "The deferred-release-queue 'optional upgrade' described above is now EXTRACTED as its own ticket (the just-filed deferred-release queue WI). WI-472 v1 stays pin-for-lifetime (retract removes the fact_dedup entry but does not release the cached +1); adopt the queue ticket later only if the pin's leak matters. Neither ticket gates the other.", at: "2026-06-15T10:56:07Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-470", author: "user", content: "REFRESH (WI-471 delivered, df792a6): the 'CANDIDATE IMPL MECHANISM' note above is now BUILT as WI-471 (lazy per-NodeOccurrence term cache) -- the Node->TermId-on-demand bridge this migration rides for its 'derived index where dedup/equality pays'. As-built refinements vs that note: the cache read is KbId-GUARDED (returns the memoized id only for the stamping KB, else re-materializes against the current store), the returned TermId is BORROWED (the cache owns the pinned +1; callers must not release it), and reclamation is PER-CELL. That note's constraint 'release on node drop' is SUPERSEDED -- Drop cannot reach the TermStore, so WI-471 is pin-for-lifetime (freed wholesale at KB teardown); optional reclamation is the deferred-release queue WI-473 (sibling, depends only on WI-471; NOT a gate on this migration). Net for WI-470: depends on delivered WI-471; call cached_term wherever a node-carried type needs a TermId (the 'TermId-keyed row indices' holdout); pin-for-lifetime by default, WI-473 to trim the leak if churn warrants.", at: "2026-06-15T10:57:48Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-462", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED (merge 83cdc18 + review-cleanup follow-on). The positional tuple (h,t) lowers to Constructor{TupleLiteral} (NOT Expr::TupleLit) -- fix threads expected components in check_tuple_literal_constructor (unify+walk via thread_expected_tuple_field) + pushes the ctor's expected into a tuple-literal field value (tuple_field_expected_from_ctor); parity with pair(h,t). /code-review (3 agents): 2 correctness/soundness clean (no-op for concrete-matching components, unify-failure ignored so concrete mismatch still REJECTS, scratch/local substs no leak, parity with pair accept-set). Cleanup applied: removed dead Expr::TupleLit arm from is_tuple_lit (surface tuples are all Constructor{TupleLiteral}; the Expr::TupleLit build frame discards expected); added named-tuple threading test. DEFERRED/NON-BLOCKING: (1) ALTITUDE -- root cause is that an unbound flexible Var::Global is NOT a wildcard in types_compatible (only TypeExtractor.TypeVar is); a general fix (treat flexible unbound vars as wildcards) would subsume tuples + arrows + all containers and delete the per-shape plumbing, BUT it's a soundness-sensitive change to a SUBTYPE check (bind-vs-accept, flexible-vs-rigid skolem distinction) = cascade risk, NOT for the loop to guess. Record as intended convergence so per-literal threading (tuple, future records/variants) doesn't accrete. (2) DIRECT-return tuple (non-Option) is semantically impossible for a total list fn (nil has no head) -- the some-wrapped form is THE form and works; the direct tuple BODY path does thread (verified mkpair).", at: "2026-06-15T11:27:40Z")
