fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-476", author: "user", content: "DIAGNOSIS (claude 2026-06-15, probed; tree reverted to green, no code committed). resolve_by_short_name has exactly TWO callers: remap_name_str (load.rs ~4623, reached via remap_symbol = the MAIN op-call functor path) and the free resolve_name_in_kb_opt (~4118, query/term building). The ~182 fallback reliance points (full anthill-core suite, instrumented) split into: (1) KERNEL/REFLECT VOCAB -- synthetic desugaring targets the loader generates for every match/if/let/lambda (anthill.reflect.Expr.{match_expr,if_expr,let_expr,lambda_expr,ho_apply,dot_apply,constructor,var_ref,*_lit}) + Pattern.{constructor_pattern,var_pattern,wildcard} + reflect {kind,not,as_term,field_access,occurrence_owner/span/term,sub_occurrences} + KB.{kb,fields,rules} + SourceSpan.source_span; FIX = global-import these (like cons/nil/some/none at load.rs ~2060). (2) GENUINE MISSING IMPORTS: stdlib (Stream laws use Pair.{fst,snd} but import only {pair}; cli/parse uses Stream.{head,tail}; Bool.and; Ordered.min; Lattice.lub; Float.{e,exp}; Eq/Function/IndexedSeq/Iterable as type refs; realization Filesystem.{exists,status}) + ~40 test fixtures. CORE BUG (the heart of 'fix scope chain'): NAMESPACE-level op-body scopes do NOT chain to the namespace scope where sibling defs live. REPRO: namespace test.wi385.ok { operation f(x:Int64)=x; operation use_f()=f(42) } -- 'f' falls to the fallback. Proven via BFS over all ancestor scopes: use_f op-body scope=107, f def_scope=388, def_reachable=FALSE. SORT members DO chain (Stream.splitFirst from within Stream resolves via scope, never hits fallback) -- so the bug is specific to NAMESPACE op scoping (a scan-vs-load scope-identity mismatch: op_scope@load != scan's op_term that got the enclosing->namespace parent). NOTE: length(xs) etc. never hit the fallback because call sites IMPORT List.{length} -- the idiom is already 'import the ops you call'; the fallback only masks omissions. CAUTION: wi443.{noimport,shadow,letrecv} fixtures may test the fallback/remap_name_str behavior directly -- removing it likely needs those reworked. PLAN: (i) fix namespace op-scope chaining (core) + global-import kernel vocab; (ii) flip fallback to loud, enumerate residual missing imports; (iii) add them (stdlib+tests); (iv) delete resolve_by_short_name; verify full suite. SUBSTANTIAL core-loader change -- focused session.", at: "2026-06-15T13:36:43Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-476", author: "user", content: "FOLLOW-UP / FRESH-SESSION START HERE (diagnosis above is complete; resuming in a new session). FIRST ACTION = pin the namespace op-scope divergence: instrument load_operation (load.rs ~8666-8678) to print functor.raw() + op_scope.raw(), and scan_operation_params (~654-669) to print op_sym + op_term.raw() + enclosing_scope.raw(), and load_namespace (~7492 name_to_sort_term) vs scan Item::Namespace (~985-1023 ensure_intermediate_namespaces) namespace term raws. Find where scan's op_term (which received the enclosing->namespace parent) diverges from load's op_scope (make_name_term_from_sym(functor)) for a NAMESPACE-level op (repro: namespace test.wi385.ok { f(x)=x; use_f()=f(42) } -> f hits the fallback; def_reachable=false). SORT members already chain (compare a sort op to see what's consistent there). Likely fix: make load+scan agree on the namespace/op scope term (reuse the scanned term, or make name_to_sort_term/make_name_term_from_sym consistent for nested-namespace names). THEN: (i) global-import the kernel/reflect desugaring vocab at load.rs ~2060 (match_expr/if_expr/let_expr/lambda_expr/ho_apply/dot_apply/constructor/var_ref/*_lit, Pattern.{constructor_pattern,var_pattern,wildcard}, reflect {kind,not,as_term,field_access,occurrence_*,sub_occurrences}, KB.{kb,fields,rules}, SourceSpan.source_span); (ii) flip resolve_by_short_name to a loud error, run full suite, enumerate residual missing imports; (iii) add them in stdlib (Stream<-Pair.{fst,snd}; cli/parse<-Stream.{head,tail}; Bool.and; Float.{e,exp}; Ordered.min; Lattice.lub; Eq/Function/IndexedSeq/Iterable) + the ~40 test fixtures the loud pass names; (iv) delete resolve_by_short_name + its 2 call sites' fallback branches; rework wi443.{noimport,shadow,letrecv} (they test the fallback); full workspace suite green. Re-probe method (if needed): eprintln in resolve_by_short_name's caller fallback branches, run with --nocapture, grep. Full map: memory wi476-scope-chain-root-fix.", at: "2026-06-15T13:48:15Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-476", description: some(value: "Name-resolution ROOT FIX (model decision, user 2026-06-15): make scope-chain resolution COMPLETE and REMOVE the global resolve_by_short_name fallback (load.rs ~4140 -- the documented '// TODO: fix scope chain' / 'short-name fallback masks missing imports' hack; it scans ALL by_qualified_name ignoring imports/scope). MODEL: an unqualified name resolves within its LOCAL ENVIRONMENT (resolve_in_scope, which already takes scope_raw); a spec-operation's unqualified short name denotes the SPEC OP (reached via import / requires / enclosing scope) and dispatches to the impl; an implementation -- fact field value OR witness member -- is NEVER an unqualified-namespace candidate (reached only by dispatch or qualification). A name not resolvable in scope must be a LOUD UnresolvedName, not silently rescued by a global scan that then trips over names the caller never imported. This DISSOLVES the WI-463 witness collision at the ROOT: the collision exists only on the global-fallback path; the WI-450 combineBox already resolves 'combine' cleanly via its 'requires Combiner[T]' scope (witness member not in scope). resolve_in_scope must comprehensively cover: (1) enclosing-sort members, (2) same-namespace sibling top-level defs, (3) imported names, (4) requires-brought spec ops. BLAST RADIUS (probed: instrument resolve_by_short_name to log non-builtin successes over full anthill-core suite = ~149 distinct reliance points): (A) enclosing-sort/same-namespace self-refs -- single-letter op/param/field names a/b/c/f/h/p, plus combine/zeroLike/pick/produce/render -- should resolve via lexical scope; (B) anthill.reflect.Expr.* / Pattern.* / KB.* + as_term/SourceSpan (~40 pts); (C) prelude spec/sort/op names: Stream, Iterable, Eq, Function, Pair.fst/snd/pair, Stream.head/tail, Bool.and, Ordered.min, Lattice.lub, Float.e/exp; (D) realization Filesystem.exists/status. SUGGESTED DECOMPOSITION: (i) extend resolve_in_scope to cover the 4 cases; (ii) flip the fallback to a LOUD error to surface genuine missing-import gaps; (iii) add imports/qualification where stdlib/tests truly omit them; (iv) delete resolve_by_short_name. CASCADE: core resolver used everywhere -- verify full workspace suite green. ACCEPTANCE: resolve_by_short_name deleted; full workspace suite green; the WI-463 unqualified witness call resolves to the spec op via proper scope. SUBSTANTIAL multi-area change -- fresh focused session (likely decomposed into the 4 steps above)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-06-15T15:33:12Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-477", description: some(value: "Remove/replace Value::as_term -- the silent Value->TermId downgrade that erases information. as_term() returns None for any non-Term carrier (Node/Tuple/Entity), so callers that read it as content treat None as 'nothing' and drop it -- the binding-erasure class fixed in bind_spec_params_from_carrier (WI-470, d42682c). ~80 non-test call sites: resolve.rs ~42 (the term-based resolver), mod.rs ~18, typing.rs ~13, load.rs ~6, builtins.rs ~1. Triage each into three buckets: (1) FAST-PATH branch where None is genuinely handled -> direct `if let Value::Term(t)` pattern match (already the dominant legit style -- 112 Value::Term( matches in typing.rs alone); (2) CONTENT read -> carrier-agnostic extract_type/TermView, never downgrade; (3) genuine TermId DEMAND (the term-based resolver) -> cached_term(kb) to materialize on demand (the WI-471 bridge), or a LOUD accessor that errors instead of returning None. Migration tactic: make as_term loud (or delete it) and let the compiler/suite flush out every site at once, then triage. This is the WI-470 thesis fully realized: occurrences primary, hash-consing a derived index recovered on demand -- no silent Value->TermId leak. The WI-470 commits (ec8c619 arrow flip, d42682c bind_spec carrier-agnostic read) are the first concrete instances. Deserves its own /code-review pass."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-471"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T14:40:49Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-463", description: some(value: "Name-resolution: an UNqualified spec-op call resolves to the SPEC op even when a WITNESS member shares its short name. WI-450 made witness dispatch work for generic-requires, QUALIFIED direct ('Combiner.combine(tag,tag)'), and dot-call forms; the UNqualified direct form 'combine(tag,tag)' stays broken because resolve_by_short_name (load.rs ~4118) returns None on 2+ non-builtin candidates — the witness member 'TagCombiner.combine' and the spec op 'Combiner.combine' both match short 'combine', so the call is silently left unresolved (kind=None) and dies UnknownOperation at eval. A fact-based instance has no collision (impl is a distinct name like tagCombine), so facts work unqualified; witnesses (member impl shares the spec op name, by the provider-coverage model) do not. REPRO: the WI-450 fixture with 'combine(tag(n:1),tag(n:2))' instead of 'Combiner.combine(...)'. FIX DIRECTION (decide): (a) prefer the SPEC op (lookup_spec_op_dispatch is Some) among same-short-name candidates — but risks masking genuine ambiguities + shifts stdlib resolution (splitFirst etc. have many spec/impl collisions, heavy regression); OR (b) exclude a witness's member IMPL ops from the unqualified namespace scope (reachable only via dispatch or qualified TagCombiner.combine) — cleaner Scala/Haskell-like semantics (instance methods are not top-level names), localizes to the witness case. This is the ergonomic completion of WI-450's 'identical to a fact' goal for the unqualified value-directed form. Delicate name-resolution / core-model change — verify the full stdlib (many spec-op/impl short-name collisions) stays green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-450", "WI-476"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T16:04:51Z"))
