fact WorkItem(id: "WI-464", description: some(value: "Typer: variance-aware parameterized join/meet in join_types (+ add meet_types). Build the real parameterized LUB so join(Option[T=Cat], Option[T=Dog]) = Option[T=Animal] instead of today's conservative common supertype. join_types (kb/typing.rs:14539) today only ever RETURNS one input or widens the nominal side up the sort lattice -- it never CONSTRUCTS a parameterized type. Extend it: when both inputs are Fn{S, bindings} with the same base sort S, recurse per-binding consulting the delivered declared_variance(S, param) (kb/typing.rs:14225): covariant => join_types(av, bv); invariant => require av == bv (else fall back to the conservative supertype); contravariant => meet_types(av, bv); bivariant => either. Add meet_types -- the lattice DUAL of join_types (greatest lower bound DOWN the sort lattice), a self-contained Rust fn. This is pure term-backed Rust typer work, the SAME idiom + file as the WI-293 subtyping half (parameterized_compatible_view + declared_variance, both kb/typing.rs) already delivered. SCOPE/SEQUENCING: depends ONLY on WI-293 (delivered). It does NOT need WI-010 (declarative anthill-rules unification) or WI-382 (per-sort registered-algorithm framework): the typer is term-backed Rust today, and the WI-293 subtyping half proved you build these directly in Rust without that substrate. WI-382 is the EVENTUAL generalization home (variance/join/meet as the order relation, sibling of unification) -- a future refactor target where join_types/meet_types fold into registered per-sort ordering ops, NOT a blocker. The earlier WI-382 dependency was a conflation of conceptual kinship with implementation dependency (the 'meet does not exist yet => need the framework' leap is false: meet_types is just join_types's dual over the same lattice). TESTS: covariant join Option[Cat]/Option[Dog] => Option[Animal]; invariant param join requires equal binding (else conservative supertype); contravariant param join uses meet; meet_types GLB basics. Note: scaland has no typer (WI-287), so rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-293"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T16:30:59Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-466", description: some(value: "Typer GAP (WI-405 follow-up, same root cause): the (parameterized, sort_ref) arm of types_compatible calls sort_sym_compatible with SWAPPED args -- (expected_spec, actual_base) instead of (actual, expected) as the working (sort_ref, parameterized) sibling arm does (actual-side gets extract_sort_ref_sym(expected), parameterized_base_sym(actual), then sort_sym_compatible(kb, e, ab)). WI-405 FACET A added a CORRECTLY-directed sort_provides_admissibly(kb, ab, e) right beside this swapped nominal call, exposing the inconsistency. TWO latent defects: (1) FALSE-REJECT -- a parameterized actual whose base REFINES / is-entity-of a bare expected does not conform. Verified probe: sort Base; sort Refined { requires Base; sort T=?; entity makeRefined(x:T) }; operation f(p: Refined[T=Int64]) -> Base = p  => 'type mismatch in f.return: expected Base, got Refined[T = Int64]'. (2) FALSE-ACCEPT (soundness) -- the reverse direction: a Base[..] would wrongly conform to an expected spec that refines Base. FIX: in BOTH types_compatible_term_dispatch and its carrier peer types_compatible_view_structural, change the (parameterized, sort_ref) nominal check to sort_sym_compatible(kb, ab, e) / (ab, ev) (actual-base, expected) -- matching the sibling arm and the FACET A provider call. SOUNDNESS-affecting semantic change (removes a false accept) -> own focused change + a both-directions regression test + full-suite verify; NOT folded silently into WI-405. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T16:48:15Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-480", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-468", description: some(value: "Typer/WI-401 escape-gate gap (sibling of WI-457): a LET-binding ANNOTATION launders a provider upcast past the escape gate. 'operation f(m: MemStore) -> KVStore = let s: KVStore = m  ;  s' LOADS today (verified: errs=[]) -- the let annotation widens s to the bare spec KVStore, so the returned tail leaf 's' has type KVStore == ret_sort and abstracting_return_error's same_symbol short-circuit returns None; the abstract member (KVStore.K/.V) escapes with no 'ensures'. INDEPENDENT of joins: it leaks with a direct provider value (no if/match) -- so it is NOT the WI-457 join-body vector (WI-457 walks if/match/let-BODY tail leaves; this is the let-VALUE laundering). The 'let s: KVStore = if p then diskStore else memStore ; s' join-via-let-value form leaks the same way. FIX DIRECTION: at the escape gate, see through a let-bound variable returned in tail position to the binding's VALUE (dataflow: a tail var resolves to its let value's leaves), OR treat an annotated let whose annotation upcasts a concrete provider to a bare/partial spec as itself an abstracting position. Must NOT reject a let-bound value NOT in return position, nor an ensures-vouched / manifest one. Verify wi401/wi402/wi457 stay green. Rust-only (typer). SURFACED by the WI-457 /code-review (deferred at delivery)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T17:11:34Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-469", description: some(value: "Typer/WI-385 GAP (pre-existing, surfaced by WI-460): a callback ARGUMENT is NOT validated against a DENOTED-BEARING arrow PARAM type. validate_arg_against_param bails to Ok for any Value::Node declared param (resolved_type_is_ground returns false for non-Term), so a callback whose PARAM or RESULT element type is WRONG is silently accepted when the param is a denoted arrow (e.g. (x: T) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]}). REPRO (loads clean, should reject): operation find2[EffP](s: Stream, pred: (x: s.T) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]}) -> Option[T=s.T] effects {s.E, EffP}; operation badcb(x: String) -> Bool = true; operation use_bad(es: Stream[T=Int64,E={}]) -> Option[T=Int64] = find2[EffP={}](es, badcb). Also reproduces for a NON-projection denoted arrow (pred: (x: Int64) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]} + badcb (x: String)->Bool), so the gap is PRE-EXISTING (WI-441/WI-387 denoted callbacks), independent of WI-460 -- WI-460 just brings projection-bearing arrows into the same unchecked path. Implicit-EffP calls are accidentally caught (the failed arrow unify leaves EffP unconstrained -> WI-392 check fires); EXPLICIT [EffP=...] bypasses that, exposing the hole. FIX DIRECTION: in the WI-385 validator, when the declared param is a denoted-bearing Node arrow with concrete param/result, validate the callback arg's arrow structure cross-carrier (arrow_compatible_view) rather than skipping on non-ground; distinguish polymorphic-non-ground from denoted-but-concrete. CASCADE: touches delivered callback validation (Iterable.find/filter/map, wi441) -- needs care."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T17:41:06Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-474", description: some(value: "Typer (WI-447 bare-form prereq, Gap E): a Stream spec op DISPATCHED directly on a non-Stream provider (e.g. List) must thread the element through the s.T PROJECTION in the abstract op's return. With splitFirst(s: Stream) -> Option[Pair[A = s.T, B = Stream[T = s.T, E = s.E]]] called as Stream.splitFirst(xs) on xs: List[Int64], the s.T projection (Stream.T off the receiver) must eliminate to the carrier's element (Int64) via the 'List provides Stream[T, {}]' binding; today it leaves ?_ ('type mismatch in match.rule: expected Int64, got ?_'). The DIRECT List.splitFirst call already threads (xs.T eliminates fine) -- only the dispatched CROSS-SORT path fails. This is the projection-form analogue of WI-357 (which bound the abstract op's explicit [Elem] param from the carrier) and the consumption dual of WI-461 (which threaded the projection on the PRODUCTION side iterator(l)=l). Repro: wi357 dispatched_stream_splitfirst_threads_element_type / dispatched_stream_head_threads_element_type with the bare s.T form. ACCEPTANCE: wi357 green with the bare s.T projection form (cargo-test)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-461"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T19:20:47Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-481", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-475", description: some(value: "Typer (WI-447 bare-form prereq, Gap F): an 'effects s.E' PROJECTION must eliminate to a Node-carried effect ROW (e.g. {Modify[p]}) instead of erroring 'expected a well-formed type projection, got type projection resolved to a non-term carrier, which is not yet supported'. When a pure consumer observes a written-effectful stream (Stream[E = {Modify[p]}]), the bare-form 'isEmpty(s: Stream) -> Bool effects s.E' must eliminate s.E to {Modify[p]} so the undeclared-effect check fires and the pure context is REJECTED naming Modify. Today s.E -> a Modify-bearing Node row trips the non-term-carrier guard. This is the WI-460-DEFERRED gap #2 ('Modify[c] denoted effect-row equality fails across a call EVEN WITH NO PROJECTION', WI-459-class) surfaced as a WI-447 blocker; expect the harder of the two (effect-row equality/elimination over Modify-bearing rows, cascade-sensitive). Repro: wi375 effectful_written_stream_rejected_in_pure_context with the bare s.E form. ACCEPTANCE: wi375 green with the bare s.E projection form (cargo-test)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-460"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T19:35:57Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-201", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-447", author: "user", content: "RE-ATTEMPTED THE REVERT 2026-06-15 (all deps WI-459/460/461/462/474/475 delivered). Stdlib loads in bare form, BUT the full suite surfaces TWO further typer gaps (5 failures: wi357 dispatched_stream_splitfirst/head; eval wi362_collect / wi362_take_n / wi064 combinators). Tree reverted to green; WI-447 stays Claimed/blocked. The gaps both root in the cross-sort EFFECT projection `s.E`:\n\nGAP H (root, soundness-sensitive): an `effects s.E` projection on a CONCRETE List receiver errors 'type anthill.prelude.List has no member E' — collect/takeN/foldLeft/foldRight/find all return `List[T = s.T] effects s.E`, and when consumed on a List (admissible-as-Stream) the s.E projection is NOT resolved through `List provides Stream[T, {}]` to `{}`. This is WI-376's DELIBERATE exclusion: 'EFFECT members EXCLUDED (WI-396): l.E stays loud, never {} via Stream provides — skip an EffectsRows-headed binding.' So the bare consumption forms collide head-on with a delivered, on-purpose design choice motivated by WI-396 effect-row soundness. WI-447's own plan ('threading WRITTEN via s.E') presumes cross-sort `s.E` works; it was excluded.\n\nGAP G (dispatch; likely the same root cascading): a DISPATCHED `Stream.splitFirst(xs)`/`head(xs)` on xs:List[Int64] whose abstract signature carries an `effects s.E` clause leaves the s.T ELEMENT projection at `?_` ('expected Int64, got ?_'), so wi357 dispatched_* fail. BISECTION on a minimal wi474-style Strm/Lst fixture (+ `import anthill.prelude.EffectsRuntime` so E resolves cleanly): the `effects E = ?` MEMBER alone PASSES; provides `E = {}` PASSES; `E = s.E` nested in the Pair B PASSES; ONLY the op-level `effects s.E` CLAUSE flips it to FAIL. So the s.E effect-projection on the dispatched op preempts/cascades into the element-projection elimination. WI-474 declared cross-sort s.T 'satisfied by WI-461' but its regression fixture (wi474_dispatched_projection_test) has NO effect dimension — no `effects E=?` member, no `effects s.E` clause — so this interaction was never exercised; the stdlib-based wi357 dispatched tests passed only because the stdlib was still EXPLICIT.\n\nDECISION NEEDED (core-model / cascade into delivered WI-376/WI-396 — stop-and-ask, not loop-guessable): lifting WI-376's cross-sort effect-member exclusion is the natural prereq, but it reopens the WI-396 effect-row soundness reasoning. Options: (a) file a prereq to make cross-sort `s.E` eliminate to the written provision effect (lift the WI-376 exclusion soundly; fixes Gap H and likely Gap G); (b) re-scope WI-447 to bare-the-ELEMENT-only and keep the effect dimension EXPLICIT ([Eff] param or written row, no `s.E` projection); (c) other. The bare element forms (splitFirst/nth/split/iterator `s.T`/`xs.T`) work; the EFFECT dimension is the sole blocker.", at: "2026-06-15T20:13:06Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-282", author: "user", content: "Delivered + rebased onto origin/main (e359feb; code 6ee9ee2). dispatch_rule_body_dots sweep in type_check_sorts_typed rewrites every rule-body Expr::DotApply to its method-Apply / reflect field_access form before SLD, over ALL rules (sort-scoped + free), via the rule's De Bruijn var types (new TypingEnv.debruijn_types + Var::DeBruijn typer arm). Reuses type_check_node per DotApply subtree (handles predicate-functor goals, which whole-goal typing cannot). Reflect Expr.dot_apply-as-data left untouched (receiver_sort None). Verified: no resolver panic (instrumented — Value::Node field_access goal never reaches the term-only as_term narrow); dispatched forms do not yet EVALUATE at SLD (field_access/method-op goals match-nothing/residualize) — NOT a regression (undispatched dot_apply did not either), evaluation tracked by the resolve.rs WI-246-follow-up TODO (migrate term-only builtins to TermView). 7 wi282 tests + full anthill-core suite green post-rebase (1562/0/3). /code-review (9 finder angles) ran; severe finding (resolver panic) empirically refuted.", at: "2026-06-15T22:04:41Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-282", description: some(value: "Rule-body dot dispatch. Dot/[simp] rewriting must fire on Expr::DotApply in RULE bodies, not just operation bodies (simp_rewrite::run walks only kb.op_bodies_iter). The webots computational style (?pose_prev.position.x + ?vx*?tc) lives in rule bodies; the governing principle is dot must mean the same in ALL expression positions. Needs the engine/typer to rewrite rule-body DotApply with typeof for rule variables (the typer types rule bodies via check_rule_typing, currently term-form with no DotApply arm). NOTE: occ_head now exposes DotApply structurally, so an undispatched rule-body DotApply flows into SLD as a structural dot_apply goal — benign today (no dot_apply facts -> matches nothing) but a wrong-answer risk once used. Ties to WI-246 (rule-body occurrences). Acceptance: a rule body with ?x.method(args) / ?x.field dispatches before SLD; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-279"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-15T22:04:43Z"))
