fact WorkItem(id: "WI-484", description: some(value: "Typer (WI-447 bare-form prereq, Gap G+H ROOT): lift WI-376's cross-sort EFFECT-member projection exclusion for WRITTEN GROUND rows. project_via_provided_spec (typing.rs ~11587) unconditionally SKIPS an EffectsRows-headed provides binding ('an EFFECT-row member E is NEVER projected via provides', WI-396) — so the bare-form stdlib's `effects s.E` errors on a concrete List (`List provides Stream[T, {}]`): consumption ops collect/takeN/foldLeft/foldRight/find return `List[T = s.T] effects s.E` and fail 'List has no member E' (eval wi362/wi064), AND a dispatched op carrying `effects s.E` leaves its s.T ELEMENT at ?_ (wi357 dispatched_stream_splitfirst/head — Gap G is Gap H cascading, confirmed: one fix clears both). FIX: project an effect member when the provision's binding is GROUND (reuse the existing resolved_type_is_ground gate already used for element members) — reading back a WRITTEN, ground row (`l.E = {}`) is sound and is NOT the 'silent pure default' WI-396 actually guarded against (reconstructing {} for an UNWRITTEN effect); a non-ground / unwritten effect binding still skips → loud missing-member. SOUNDNESS VALIDATED (spike): wi396 effect_projection_wrong_effect_is_rejected + the written-row siblings + wi375 stay GREEN — the groundness gate distinguishes written-{} from invented-{}. POLICY CHANGE (the sole test this fix flips on the explicit stdlib): wi376 effect_projection_missing_member_is_loud asserts `l.E` on a List is ALWAYS loud; it must become 'l.E projects to the WRITTEN {} (a pure caller conforms), loud retained ONLY for a carrier that wrote NO effect provision / a non-ground row' — add a positive (written-{} projects) + a preserved negative (a sort with no Stream provision → l.E loud). SPIKE RESULT: with this fix + the bare stdlib, anthill-core 5 failures→2, the remaining 2 being this policy-test update AND the SEPARATE wi443 find-dot-call gap (its own prereq, not effect-related). DELIVERED INDEPENDENTLY on the EXPLICIT stdlib (the wi376 inline test exercises the fix; the bare-form stdlib revert is WI-447). ACCEPTANCE: wi376/wi396/wi375 effect-soundness green with the updated policy test; full workspace green; cargo-test."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-474", "WI-475"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T05:08:24Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-485", description: some(value: "Typer (WI-447 bare-form prereq, Gap I): a `find` DOT-CALL on a List does not thread the callback's `s.T` ELEMENT when stream.anthill find is in BARE form. With `find[EffP](s: Stream, pred: (x: s.T) -> Bool @ {EffP, -Modify[x]}) -> Option[s.T] effects {s.E, EffP}`, a call `xs.find(is_big)` (xs: List[Int64], is_big(n: Int64)->Bool) leaves the callback param at the neutral `s.T`, so the concrete callback clashes — 'type mismatch in gt.b: expected s.T, got Int64' (is_big's body retyped against the un-grounded expected param). PRE-EXISTING bare-form gap, INDEPENDENT of effects: reproduces with the Gap-G+H effect-projection fix REVERTED (and that fix actually REDUCES the wi443 failure count 3→1, so it is orthogonal, not causal). Repro: wi443 identifier_dot_call_evals_like_plain_find / _needs_no_import / _let_bound_receiver fail once stream.anthill find is bare. The `s.T` sits inside a DENOTED arrow (the `-Modify[x]` lacks binder), so this is WI-460-adjacent (projection in a denoted-bearing arrow) but on the DOT-CALL DISPATCH + named-callback path: the receiver's element must ground the callback param projection before the callback arg is checked. Likely the dot-call dispatches to the bare Stream.find (s.T) rather than/alongside Iterable.find (named Element), and the element does not thread into the denoted-arrow callback param. FIX DIRECTION: thread the dispatched/dot-call receiver's element type into the callback param's `s.T` projection (eliminate it against the receiver) before validating the callback arg; OR resolve the find dispatch to the element-threading form. CASCADE: touches dot-call dispatch + denoted-arrow callback validation (WI-460/WI-469 area). BLOCKS WI-447. ACCEPTANCE: wi443 green with the bare Stream.find form; cargo-test."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-460", "WI-469"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T05:28:01Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-447", description: some(value: "Stdlib: revert to the SHORT bare typing forms -- the recorded WI-374 PLAN, now its own ticket. Revert the WI-380 explicit [Elem, Eff] operation-type-parameter signatures (stream.anthill splitFirst/head/tail/takeN/collect/foldLeft/foldRight/find/isEmpty/count; list.anthill iterator/splitFirst/nth/split) BACK to short bare member forms: bare self-sort params (s: Stream -- the sec.3-bullet-1 canonical tie, now ENFORCED per WI-374) with the threading WRITTEN via WI-376 projections (-> List[T = s.T] effects s.E; s.Sort for whole-sort returns) and WI-375 written effect rows where the producer must state E (iterator -> Stream[T = l.T, E = {}]). Bare RETURNS stay forbidden by the type-not-provenance boundary (sec.5: a bare return is ERASED; expansion supplies variables, never values) -- every return writes its relationship via projection, written row, or stays explicit. Mechanisms all delivered: WI-376/396-401 projections, WI-374 site-scoped expansion + enforced member tie + foreign per-occurrence vars, WI-375 rows, WI-424 same-sort rigid seeding for member bodies. ACCEPTANCE: reverted stdlib loads; full workspace suite green; wi368 (length(collect(List.iterator(xs))) pure + element threaded) stays green; an abstract-carrier walk (operation walk(c: C) effects E where C provides Iterable = collect(iterator(c))) stays effect-polymorphic; wi357/wi375/wi424 green. WATCH: effect-rows-on-cross-sort-carriers sensitivity (typing-build-loop.md gotchas) -- verify wi357 + wi210; consumer-side bare params rely on the canonical channel, so the WI-374 enforcement semantics (refinement re-unify, rigid exemption) are load-bearing here."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-374", "WI-459", "WI-460", "WI-461", "WI-462", "WI-474", "WI-475", "WI-484", "WI-485"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T05:34:12Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-482", author: "user", content: "Delivered: dispatched rule-body field_access EVALUATES at SLD. builtin_field_access TermView-migrated (Value::Node goal resolves, panic narrow dropped); project_field shared core; reduce_dot_value reduces a dot OPERAND in eq/cmp/arith (chains inside-out); builtin_arith now normalize_value's operands; field_access accepts a String field name (eval-twin form). carrier_term dedup; try_bind_result/bind_or_succeed removed. Tests use GROUND queries asserting the computed value. The literal eq-binds-unbound-?v half is carved out (eq is a test not unify + caller-var delay residualizes) → filed as the eq test->unify WI below. Code committed; rebased onto origin (8457d64).", at: "2026-06-16T06:38:19Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-482", description: some(value: "Evaluate dispatched rule-body dots at SLD: migrate the term-only reflect builtins (field_access + qualified_name/short_name/lookup_symbol/resolve_sort_inst_param) to TermView so a Value::Node goal resolves. WI-282 dispatches a rule-body ?x.field to field_access(receiver, field) BEFORE SLD, but the resolver does not EVALUATE it: a rule-body goal enters the goal stream as Value::Node (resolve.rs:1264); execute_builtin gates these 5 builtins behind as_term(goal) (resolve.rs:1576) which panic!s on a Value::Node goal, so a Node field_access goal is never classified/executed there — it falls through to ordinary goal resolution and matches-nothing/residualizes. Empirically (verified during WI-282): rule r(?p,?v) :- holds(field: ?p), eq(?v, ?p.x) resolves with ?v UNBOUND instead of the field value. This is the standing resolve.rs TODO(WI-246 follow-up): migrate these to TermView and drop this narrow — now load-bearing for WI-282 and the webots computational rule-body style (?pose_prev.position.x + ?vx*?tc). NOTE: arithmetic builtins (Add/Mul) already take the Value goal directly (no as_term), so ?vx*?tc likely already evaluates; field_access is the gap. Acceptance: rule r(?p,?v) :- holds(field: ?p), eq(?v, ?p.x) resolves with ?v bound to the field value; a Value::Node field_access goal evaluates (no panic, binds result); strengthen the WI-282 resolution tests (wi282_rule_body_dot_test.rs) from no-panic to correct-binding; cargo-test green. SCOPE: resolver (resolve.rs execute_builtin + builtin_field_access etc.), Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-282"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T06:38:22Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-201", author: "user", content: "DESIGN DECISION (user-confirmed 2026-06-16): desugar CARRIER-DIRECT (Reading A), NOT the ticket's 'rides RigidTypeProjection P.Member' prose. Empirically verified: Reading B (s: ?P.Member projection) is BROKEN at every call site for WorkItemStore.State — State IS WorkItemStore's sole param/carrier, so an arg typed ?P.State can't infer ?P (non-injective: 'expected a type for P, got unconstrained'). Reading A (s: ?P + synthesized 'requires Spec[Member=?P]', no projection) loads clean, infers ?P at concrete calls, and matches the acceptance's literal 'WorkItemStore.State == ?S requires WorkItemStore[?S]'. wi428/wi383 RigidTypeProjection handles NON-carrier associated members (Storage.Key/Resource.V off a separate carrier C); WorkItemStore.State is the degenerate carrier-IS-member case.", at: "2026-06-16T07:12:51Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-201", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (all 5 acceptance scenarios + review hardening), commit on main. Impl = loader-side carrier-direct desugar (anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs): BareSpecSugar accumulator armed only during op-signature conversion; try_rigid_type_projection bare-spec arm mints fresh op type-param ?P (kb.fresh_var, no symbol registration — extract_type_params reads vid.name()), deduped per (spec,member)/op, drained into OperationInfo.type_params + a 'Spec[Member=?P]' requires clause rebuilt from each entry. FIRES ONLY for a SPEC (Sort with no constructors, via sort_has_constructors) — a parameterized DATA sort (Option/List/enum) keeps the loud conflation error (code-review fix). Carrier-in-scope NARROWING via order-independent pre-scan of the enclosing sort's provides/fact bindings (scan_sort_carrier_bindings + current_sort_carrier_bindings): inside an impl binding Store[State=WIS], Store.State==WIS (named+positional forms); narrows ONLY to a CONCRETE, UNAMBIGUOUS carrier — a logic-var or conflicting binding falls back to the fresh existential (code-review fixes). Tests: wi201_bare_spec_member_sugar_test.rs (13). wi428 bare_spec_subject_rejected repointed to an entity-field position (op-sig case is now the sugar). Task (d) 'rewrite ONE stdlib spec': NO clean production candidate (Eq/Ordered use in-scope carrier T; the bundle Main sort's SORT-LEVEL shared 'requires WorkItemStore[State]' is cleaner than per-op sugar) — sugar is forward-looking, demonstrated in the fixture not forced as a regression. Sugar typechecks IDENTICALLY to the explicit form including pre-existing op-requires limits (orthogonal WI-383-era, not WI-201 regressions). Full workspace green.", at: "2026-06-16T07:13:11Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-201", description: some(value: "Abstract type members in spec sorts — bare-spec `Spec.AssociatedType` sugar (e.g. `WorkItemStore.State`). RE-POINTED 2026-06-15 onto the delivered RigidTypeProjection machinery: the path-dependent projection cluster — WI-376/WI-400 (value receiver `s.State`), WI-428 (type-receiver `P.Key` / RigidTypeProjection), WI-429 (loud unresolved-type-name), WI-430 (carrier-precise requires) — already ships the two SOUND receiver forms: a value (`s.State`) and a `requires`-bounded type parameter (`P.State`), per wi428/wi430 tests. This ticket is now SUGAR-ONLY: the one remaining surface form is the BARE spec-sort reference with NO carrier in scope — `operation cmd_add(a: AddArgs, s: WorkItemStore.State) -> Int effects ...` desugaring to the explicit `s: ?S requires WorkItemStore[?S]` (which typechecks today). What makes it sound — and distinguishes it from the carrier-CONFLATION reading WI-428/429 deliberately turned into a loud error — is SINGLE-BINDING-PER-DECLARATION scoping: every occurrence of `Spec.Member` within ONE declaration binds to the SAME fresh existential carrier `?P`; distinct declarations mint distinct `?P` (NOT the global Scala-2 `T#K` nominal). MECHANISM (all prerequisites exist): at classification, a bare `Spec.CarrierMember` in a signature type position lowers to a fresh type-param `?P` + a synthesized `requires Spec[?P]` clause (fill-as-requirement-discharge, WI-383), deduped across the declaration, then rides the existing RigidTypeProjection `P.Member` path. HOOK SITE: anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs ~11708 — the `ProjResult::Neutral` arm for a bare spec-sort subject currently emits the 'would conflate distinct carriers' error (reproduced 2026-06-15: `operation use_sugar(s: Store.State) -> Int` is rejected there); bare-spec desugaring replaces that arm with the fresh-carrier mint, keeping the loud error only for the genuinely-unsynthesizable cases. DISAMBIGUATION (both deferred in WI-428, in scope here): inside an impl sort that already binds State via `fact WorkItemStore[WIS]`, `WorkItemStore.State` resolves to the bound WIS (the unique-carrier-in-scope desugar); free-standing call sites resolve via caller-supplied arg types (existing spec-op dispatch). Work: (a) loader/typer classification of bare `Spec.Member` in signature type positions; (b) fresh-`?P` + synthesized-`requires` elaboration with per-declaration dedup; (c) tests — `WorkItemStore.State` typechecks identically to `?S requires WorkItemStore[?S]`; two refs in one signature share `?S`; two signatures get distinct `?S`; the carrier-in-scope impl case narrows to the bound type; ambiguous / zero-binding stays loud; (d) rewrite ONE stdlib spec (Eq / Ordered / WorkItemStore) to use the sugar. Out of scope: full VALUE-level path-dependent types (already delivered via `s.State`). Driver: proposal 036 — bundle commands drop the requires-clause noise and read like ordinary code."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-428", "WI-429", "WI-430"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T07:13:13Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-487", description: some(value: "Link op-body param variable references to the param's Symbol at load (fix op-body var <-> OperationInfo param symbol mismatch). ROOT CAUSE (diagnosed in WI-483): an op body's ?b reference to a param is a Term::Var in the parse IR; the op-body converter (load.rs visit_load) has no Term::Var arm, so ?b falls to generic convert_term which MINTS A FRESH logical var re-interning 'b' to a NEW Symbol, distinct from the param's OperationInfo Symbol (scanned SymbolKind::Param, load.rs:762). Empirically: OperationInfo param 'b'=Symbol(1485); op_body_node ?b=Expr::Var(Global) named Symbol(1572) — both 'b', different. Interpreter bridges by NAME (eval::find_local, eval.rs:1620). load_var_ref (Ident path -> remap -> param symbol) is NOT hit for ?b (a Var); build_expr_leaf/check_bare_ref preserve symbols but aren't reached. FIX: op-body variable conversion should resolve a ?b whose name matches an op param (resolve_in_scope -> SymbolKind::Param) to the param Symbol, so body var and OperationInfo share one Symbol; then find_local/WI-483 fold bind by symbol. BLAST RADIUS: op-body var identity touches typer env, eval find_local, discrim — test carefully; only param-named free vars resolve (not let/lambda/match-bound). BLOCKS WI-483. Acceptance: op_body_node param var Symbol == OperationInfo.params[i].0; full suite green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T08:05:31Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-480", description: some(value: "Typer/WI-401 escape-gate gap (sibling of WI-468): a DESTRUCTURING-pattern let annotation launders a provider upcast. Confirmed false-accepts today: tuple 'let (s,_): (KVStore,Bool) = (m,true) ; s', constructor 'let boxed(s): Box = boxed(m) ; s', and OPAQUE-value 'let (s,_) = mkpair(m) ; s' all LOAD clean (verified via CLI; the direct Pattern::Var case correctly errors post-WI-468). ROOT CAUSE: branch_leaf_abstracting_return_error's let_bound_var_name returns None for any non-Pattern::Var binder, so destructured names are NOT tracked in LeafScope; the returned component var falls back to its laundered annotation-component type and slips same_symbol. FIX DIRECTIONS: (a) pattern-directed value-component projection -- extend the LeafScope tracking so a Pattern::Tuple/Constructor binder maps each destructured name to the corresponding LITERAL value-component node (tuple element / constructor field, recursively for nested patterns); the see-through then reaches the concrete provider. (b) the OPAQUE-value case (value is a call returning the tuple/entity, no literal element node to project) CANNOT be seen through structurally -- it needs the ticket-WI-468 alternative 'annotation-as-abstracting position' approach: treat a RETURN-position destructured var whose annotation-component upcasts a concrete provider to a bare/partial spec as itself an abstracting position. Must NOT reject a destructured value NOT in return position, nor same-sort/manifest/ensures cases. Verify wi401/wi402/wi457/wi468 stay green. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-468"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T08:51:48Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-488", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-483", author: "user", content: "DECISION (user, 2026-06-16): implement the OCCURRENCE-NATIVE BY-SYMBOL FOLD (the WI-487-enabled path), NOT the interpreter bridge. A dispatched rule-body op-call peek(?b) reduces by inlining the op body occurrence with call args substituted into param-Symbol vars, then the existing WI-482 reductions (field_access/arith/eq) collapse it. NON-FOLDABLE gate (match/if/let/recursion): if the call is GROUND and its requires slots are RESOLVED -> LOUD error; if a requires slot is ABSTRACT (=> not ground) -> LEAVE un-reduced (residualize, status quo). Interpreter bridge for arbitrary bodies = deferred follow-up.", at: "2026-06-16T08:31:23Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-483", description: some(value: "Decide + implement method-op dispatch as a rule-body goal (?b.peek() -> peek(?b)). WI-282 dispatches a rule-body method call to an operation Apply, but the SLD resolver only matches goals against rule/fact HEADS via the discrimination tree — an operation lives in kb.op_bodies, not as a rule/fact head — so a method-op goal in a rule body matches NOTHING (silent fail). REPRO (verified WI-282): rule peeks(?b, ?v) :- holder(b: ?b), eq(?v, ?b.peek()) dispatches ?b.peek() -> peek(?b) but ?v does not bind to peek's result. DECISION NEEDED (stop-and-ask, not loop-guessable): whether a method/operation CALL in a rule body should EVALUATE (resolver reduces operation goals via the interpreter / eq-simp rewriting, like op bodies) OR whether 'a method call in a logical rule body' is not a meaningful goal and rule-body dot dispatch should be scoped to field-access + arithmetic only (keep method-call dots an op-body-only feature). Ties to the broader 'evaluate computational rule bodies' question (webots style). Relates to WI-482 (field_access-on-Node-goal piece). Acceptance: TBD per the decision; cargo-test green. SCOPE: resolver / eval, Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-282", "WI-487"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T09:14:08Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-404", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-481", description: some(value: "Typer: a value-in-type (denoted) Modify-bearing effect row fails effect-row EQUALITY across a call -- a correctly-DECLARED 'effects {Modify[p]}' is rejected as UNDECLARED when an op incurs Modify[p]. Repro (PRE-EXISTING, reproduces with the EXPLICIT [Elem,Eff] form too, so NOT a projection issue): given 'operation eff_stream(p: Producer) -> Strm[T = Int64, E = {Modify[p]}]' and a Strm op that incurs its observation row (bare 'effects s.E' OR explicit 'effects Eff'), the consumer 'operation okeff(p: Producer) -> Bool effects {Modify[p]} = obsEmpty(eff_stream(p))' errors 'type mismatch in okeff.effects: expected declared: [Modify[T = p]], got undeclared effect: Modify[T = p]' -- the declared and incurred Modify[T=p] (a denoted/value-in-type effect, Modify parameterized by the VALUE p) are structurally identical yet the undeclared-effect check (check_operation_bodies effect comparison / effects_subset over the incurred vs declared rows) treats them as distinct. This is the WI-460-feedback 'ORTHOGONAL: Modify[c] denoted effect-ROW equality fails across a call EVEN WITH NO PROJECTION (WI-459-class)' note + the WI-475-referenced 'gap #2', now reproduced as its own ticket. The pure-context REJECTION (declared []) and pure-stream ACCEPT (E={}) work (WI-475); only the DECLARED-Modify acceptance direction fails. Root: denoted (value-in-type) effect equality -- Modify[p] vs Modify[p] -- must compare the embedded value p by identity/sort-unifier (cf. WI-382 'denoted equality = the embedded value sort's unifier'); the effect-subset check likely compares the Modify rows by a path that drops/mismatches the value-in-type argument. Cascade-sensitive (effect-row equality over Modify-bearing rows). ACCEPTANCE: okeff-style declared-Modify acceptance loads clean while a WRONG/absent declaration still rejects; wi375/wi441/wi440/effects suites stay green (cargo-test). Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T09:25:26Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-310", description: some(value: "Add an 'unclaim' command to the anthill-todo CLI. Today there is no way to release a claimed work item back to Open: the command set is init/add/status/list/next/show/claim/deliver/verify/feedback/delete/update/add-dependency/remove-dependency/graph/skill — 'update' explicitly PRESERVES status, and there is no unclaim/release/reopen. Releasing a claim currently requires hand-editing workitems.anthill (status: Claimed(agent,since) -> status: Open), which is error-prone. Add 'anthill-todo unclaim WI-NNN' that transitions a Claimed item back to Open (clearing agent/since). Consider: only valid from Claimed (error otherwise); honor --agent for symmetry/auditing; possibly a paired status-transition audit. ACCEPTANCE: 'anthill-todo unclaim WI-NNN' on a Claimed item sets it to Open; on a non-Claimed item it errors clearly; help lists it. SCOPE: anthill-todo CLI crate."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T09:34:21Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-411", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-394", author: "user", content: "RESCOPED 2026-06-16 (analysis, user-confirmed): the ticket's 'REMOVE walk_type/walk_type_deep' premise is STALE. Architecture evolved the opposite way — the carrier-agnostic stack (walk_view/walk_term_to_resolved/walk_type_value) is built ON TOP of walk_type (walk_term_to_resolved calls walk_type then surfaces a Value::Node binding via resolve_as_value, typing.rs:12750). walk_type STAYS PERMANENTLY: it is the shallow term-world primitive AND the effect-row algebra (multi_tail_rows_compat/unify_effect_rows/subtype_effect_rows, 7 sites) genuinely needs its TermId output for row-var SET/IDENTITY comparison (Vec<TermId> dedup by raw(), a_walked==b_walked WI-334 shared-tail guard) — those are structural-neutral comparisons NOT exposed to the gap. REAL SCOPE = close the live WI-393 Node-binding soundness gap at the 5 DIRECT leaf-resolve callers that bypass carrier-aware surfacing (a var bound to a Value::Node written-effect-row/denoted is misread as unbound/unfilled): 4624 (HK-carrier dispatch probe), 13184 (filled_carrier_sort), 13303 (ground_rigid_projection_if_concrete) = ~mechanical swap to walk_term_to_resolved+view extract_sort_ref_sym; 4532 (op type-arg write-back, needs set_resolved_type_args carrier widened TermId->Value) and 15437 (check_param_bindings_against_provider 'pvr!=pv did-it-resolve-more' idiom -> route through resolve_type_deep_value, line 1036). After 4532+15437, walk_type_deep's external surface is dead and it collapses into walk_type_deep_g/resolve_type_deep_value. ACCEPTANCE: the 5 sites consult a non-Term binding; walk_type retained; full anthill-core green.", at: "2026-06-16T09:45:21Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-404", author: "user", content: "Delivered in b55f85e (merged 8475023). Two-halves resolution: (1) COMPARES — the denoted-binding subtype comparison was ALREADY correct at HEAD (cumulative value-in-type denoted work, decisively WI-481 re-keying denoted param refs into the synthesized call-return type, plus the (denoted,denoted) subtype arm from WI-342). Verified across all vehicles the ticket names (literal/value-place/alias/member-op) + soundness controls (N=3 vs N=4 and value-place N=c vs N=d both correctly REJECTED — the accept+reject pairs prove the body type carries the concrete denoted, not a wildcard). (2) RENDERS — found the residual 'renders as N = ?' half: denoted_value_display dropped a LITERAL denoted (Expr::Const) to '?', so a mismatch error read 'expected N = ?, got N = ?'. Fixed with a literal_display helper (Expr::Const arm; reuses public write_anthill_string for strings). 6 regression tests; full workspace 1927 green; /code-review run.", at: "2026-06-16T09:58:16Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-404", description: some(value: "Typer BUG: a DENOTED / value-in-type parameter binding does not round-trip through the SUBTYPE check, so a denoted-bearing parameterized type fails to conform to ITSELF. A binding like N = 3 in Vec3[T = Int, N = 3] (a value-in-type / denoted parameter, WI-366/WI-390 representation) renders/compares as N = ? inside parameterized_compatible_view (and check_binding_by_variance) in types_compatible -- so returning a Vec3[T=Int, N=3] value where Vec3[T=Int, N=3] is declared is SPURIOUSLY REJECTED (a type is not compatible with itself). REPRO: no alias needed -- reproduces with a plain value-in-type parameterized sort compared against itself via return-conformance. SURFACED 2026-06-06 by the WI-381 /code-review finder agents (a transient probe), confirmed independent of WI-381 (alias resolution): the denoted binding is dropped to a wildcard one level below alias resolution. IMPACT: (a) false-reject of valid code carrying a value-in-type parameter; (b) LATENT SOUNDNESS smell -- if both sides collapse the denoted binding to ? (an inference wildcard), a real mismatch (N=3 vs N=4) could be masked rather than rejected; needs checking which way it fails. CODE: parameterized_compatible_view / check_binding_by_variance (anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs); the Value::Node / denoted carrier (TypeExtractor::Denoted). RELATES to the WI-381 view-path follow-on (the denoted-bearing-alias test vehicle is blocked by THIS bug). ACCEPTANCE: a denoted-bearing parameterized type conforms to itself (and a differing denoted binding N=3 vs N=4 is correctly rejected); regression test; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T09:58:17Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-394", description: some(value: "Typer/carrier: REMOVE the term-only walk (walk_type / walk_type_deep, TermId->TermId) in favor of the carrier-agnostic walk_view (&impl TermView -> Value); fix in place only if removal is not yet possible. ROOT ISSUE: a TermId return cannot carry a Value::Node binding, so walk_type silently keeps the var when a var resolves to a non-Term carrier (a WRITTEN effect row {Modify[p]} / a denoted value). Surfaced in WI-393: check_unconstrained_type_params used walk_type_deep and read a Node-bound effect param as still-a-Var -> false 'Eff unconstrained' (latent SOUNDNESS gap); patched per-consumer there by switching to walk_view. walk_view already surfaces Node bindings (walk_term_to_resolved consults resolve_as_value), and WI-390 value_to_term gives a faithful Node->Term lowering, so full removal is likely feasible. TASK: audit every walk_type/walk_type_deep caller, migrate each to walk_view/walk_value_to_resolved; retire the TermId->TermId walkers; a caller that genuinely needs a TermId and cannot migrate must at least consult resolve_as_value for a non-Term binding. Aligns with the no-Value->TermId boundary + denoted-in-Term (WI-390)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T10:02:52Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-309", author: "user", content: "Subsumed by WI-087 (operation attributes/metadata). All three work items delivered there: (1) loader consumes op.meta into the OperationInfo fact (kb/load.rs ~9119-9172, lowers meta_block -> meta(key: value, ...)); (2) OperationInfo gained a meta: Term field (reflect.anthill:474); (3) regression tests in tests/include/wi087_operation_meta_test.rs (4 tests green). Proposal-046 [feeds: ...] on body-less operations now surfaces via OperationInfo.meta for free.", at: "2026-06-16T10:44:17Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-309", description: some(value: "Load and surface operation-declaration metadata. Operation declarations already accept a [key: value] meta_block in the grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:319, operation_declaration) AND it is parsed into the IR (Operation.meta: Option<MetaBlock>, parse/ir.rs:336). But the loader (kb/load.rs) NEVER reads op.meta — operation metadata is silently dropped at load — and OperationInfo (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:424) has no field to expose it (only name/params/return_type/effects/requires/ensures). Work: (1) loader consumes op.meta and stores it in the KB op record; (2) OperationInfo gains a meta field (or per-key surfacing) so operation metadata is queryable from reflection and the typer; (3) regression test: an operation declared with [key: value] has that metadata loaded and retrievable via OperationInfo. Motivation: proposal 046 (effect_derive / region tracking) needs [feeds: ...] metadata on operations to carry the feed-relationship for abstract/foreign higher-order operations that have no anthill body; more generally, ANY operation-level metadata (trust, source, project-defined keys) is currently parsed and thrown away. Prerequisite for 046's feeds annotation."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T10:44:20Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-444", name: "typing")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-442", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-411", author: "user", content: "Delivered in f053c53 (merged d715450). Root: an unqualified self-named spec-op call inside a provider's OWN impl (splitFirst(src) in MappedStream.splitFirst) was bound at LOAD by the scope chain to the enclosing member, shadowing the spec op Stream.splitFirst — so the typer saw a direct concrete call and never dispatched (eval hit 'case mapped' on a List cons -> MatchFailed). Design (user-steered, grounded in Scala/Rust/Haskell method-resolution research): the callee comes from the receiver's STATIC type, resolved in the typer — the dot form src.splitFirst already does this via find_spec_op_for_provided_sort; this brings the function-call form into line. Fix (typer, tree-producing): in the Apply build frame, when the functor is the enclosing sort's own provision of a spec op AND the receiver's static type is NOT the enclosing carrier, synthesize the spec-op Apply and re-Visit (like the dot form / fire_simp) so the STORED occurrence carries the spec-op functor; the existing dispatch then PinNows a concrete receiver (FilteredStream self-recursion stays static, preserving WI-424/WI-413) and value-directs an abstract Stream receiver. Combinators de-qualified (Stream.splitFirst(src) -> splitFirst(src)) = the acceptance. Regression wi411_unqualified_spec_op_dispatch_test (eval; typecheck alone missed it); wi064/wi413/wi439 now exercise the unqualified form. Full workspace 1938 green; /code-review (no correctness bugs / no over-fire / genuine guard) + 3 fixes applied.", at: "2026-06-16T11:34:16Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-411", description: some(value: "Typer: an UNQUALIFIED self-named spec-op call on an ABSTRACT receiver inside a provider's own impl statically self-dispatches to that impl instead of staying abstract (runtime value-dispatched). Surfaced building WI-064's lazy map carrier: MappedStream.splitFirst's body calls splitFirst(src) where src is the abstract source Stream; unqualified, it self-dispatched to MappedStream.splitFirst (so a List source's cons hit MappedStream's 'case mapped' -> MatchFailed; in general unbounded self-recursion). Worked around in combinators.anthill with the QUALIFIED Stream.splitFirst(src). Typecheck-only verification (the original fragment) did not catch it — only eval did. The typer should detect the abstract receiver and NOT bind the call to the enclosing sort's same-short-name impl. Acceptance: an unqualified nested abstract spec-op call in a carrier value-dispatches on the receiver's runtime carrier; the Stream. qualifier in combinators.anthill MappedStream.splitFirst can be dropped."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T11:34:17Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-280", description: some(value: "Bare-identifier value-receiver dot dispatch (p.x / l.method() on a param/local). A receiver that is a bare identifier resolving to a VALUE (op param, let/lambda/match local) must route to dot_apply, not flatten to a qualified name. Today the converter's is_value_receiver (convert.rs) treats an identifier-rooted receiver as a NAME (the WI-278(b)-deferred 'identifier case'), so p.x flattens to a bogus qualified symbol 'p.x' and l.length() to 'l.length' (no DotApply, no dispatch, no error). The value-vs-name decision is scope-dependent, so it must be a load-time, scope-aware re-route (identifier resolves to a local value -> dot_apply(local, member, args); resolves to a sort/namespace -> keep qualified-name flattening). Engine already dispatches once it is a DotApply. Acceptance: p.x field access and l.method() method dispatch work in op bodies; Foo.bar / Map[K=..].empty() still flatten; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-279"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T11:33:11Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-442", description: some(value: "Typer: NAMED-BINDER multi-param arrow types in higher-order argument positions. A declared callback type '(acc: Acc, x: Elem) -> Acc @ {EffP}' loads where written, but every call site fails LOUDLY with 'EffP unconstrained': operation_as_function_value (typing.rs ~1848) builds a multi-param op's eta arrow with the WI-355 positional _1/_2 named-tuple param, which never unifies with the named binder fields (acc, x) of the expected arrow, so the best-effort arrow unify binds nothing and the callback's row var stays unbound. PROBED (foldLeft modernization session, 2026-06-11): single-param arrows bind EffP fine (bare {EffP} row, no absence needed); two-param NAMED binders fail at external call sites; two-param UNNAMED '(Acc, Elem)' fails even on the stdlib body's recursive self-call. WORKAROUND IN PLACE: Stream.foldLeft/foldRight + Iterable.foldLeft/foldRight use the WI-355 positional-tuple arrow '((Acc, Elem)) -> Acc @ {EffP}' applied 'f((init, h))' (documented in stream.anthill). FIX DIRECTION: unify arrow param tuples positionally when one side carries the canonical _1.._n positional convention (or mint the eta arrow's field names from the expected arrow's binders). This also unlocks binder NAMES on multi-param arrows for dependent absences (-Modify[x]) and unlocks the row-gated Modify-bearing fold callback (see wi424 pinning test iterable_fold_mutating_callback_not_lacks_rejected_but_row_gated). ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA: Stream.foldLeft/foldRight and Iterable.foldLeft/foldRight rewritten to the two-param arrow form '(acc: Acc, x: Elem) -> Acc @ {EffP}' / '(x: Elem, acc: Acc) -> ...', bodies apply 'f(init, h)' directly; wi064 + wi424 fold suites (incl. the effectful decoupled-row pair) pass with NO explicit [EffP = ...] at any call site."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T12:10:30Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-262", description: some(value: "Type-level dot-access (field projection in type positions). Today dot-access is term-position-only: kernel-language.md §6.7 desugars 'term.field' to field_access(term, field) with two runtime modes (entity field, sort component). In type position — inside effects rows, requires/ensures type slots, parameterized-type bindings — dotted names are treated purely as qualified-name lookups (load.rs::remap_name joins segments and calls resolve_in_scope on the joined string). Consequence: 'effects Modify[result.a]', 'effects Modify[c.field]', 'effects Modify[s.backend]' all fail unless the symbol 'result.a' / 'c.field' / 's.backend' is pre-registered. WI-261 / proposal 041 shipped a narrow workaround for the named-tuple-return case: scan_operation_params pre-registers 'result.<field>' as a synthetic Param symbol per tuple field, so qualified-name lookup finds it. This does not generalize to parameters of entity / tuple type, where users will increasingly want to project ('Modify[c.backend]' for a Cell-typed param holding a backend, etc.). The infrastructure for type-level structure is already there: anthill.prelude.Type has arrow(param:, result:, effects:), named_tuple has fields by name, sorts have member operations and sub-sorts — reflection can answer 'what's the field f of type T?' for the cases that matter. What's missing is the language-side disambiguation rule and the typer's projection arm. Proposed direction: in type position, a dotted Name whose first segment resolves to a value-like name in the current scope (Param, the reserved 'result', a let-binding in scope, or any non-Sort/Namespace symbol) is parsed/resolved as projection over that value's type. The second-and-later segments are field names looked up structurally on the type. First-segment resolution to a Sort or Namespace continues to mean qualified-name (existing behavior). Open design: (1) parse-time vs load-time disambiguation — parse-time needs to distinguish but the parser may not have scope info; load-time keeps the parse uniform but means the resolver does both attempts. Probably load-time, mirroring how remap_name currently has a fallback path. (2) Multi-level projection 'result.a.b' — recursive field-access through the structure. (3) Interaction with type-parameter substitution (named-tuple field types may contain type vars that need to instantiate). (4) Whether positional tuple projection like 'result._1' should also work (probably yes, since named-tuple desugars positional to _1/_2/...). Drivers: WI-261 (proposal 041 — narrow workaround in place), proposal 027.1 (Modify[result.X] / Modify[result] for allocator-shaped ops), and any future feature that wants per-component effect attribution. Out of scope: pure-term-level field access (already works via §6.7). Acceptance: 'effects Modify[c.field]' typechecks for params c of entity / tuple type; 'effects Modify[result.a]' continues to work and uses the new projection path instead of the synthetic-symbol workaround; the workaround in scan_operation_params can be removed; cargo test green; existing stdlib parses unchanged."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T12:36:47Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-489", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-444", description: some(value: "Typer+eval: carrier override of a DEFAULTED spec op — the carrier's own member must win over the spec's default body at the spec call site (typeclass default-method semantics: defaults fill gaps, they do not shadow). TODAY a spec op WITH a default body (the WI-362/424 members: Stream.takeN/collect/find/foldLeft/foldRight/isEmpty/count, Iterable.find/map/filter/isEmpty/size/folds) cannot be overridden by a carrier: lookup_spec_op_dispatch (typing.rs ~5209) gates on operation_has_no_body, so the WI-210 rewrite-to-impl never fires; at eval, step 3 (cached_operation_body, eval.rs ~1004) finds the SPEC's own body and runs it — the step-3b receiver-sort dispatch (WI-350) is body-less-only and never consulted. PROBED 2026-06-11 (wi424 pinning test iterable_size_carrier_override_currently_shadowed): 'sort Counted provides Iterable' + its own 'size' returning a stored count 99 — the Iterable-imported size(counted([1,2,3], 99)) returns 3 (the derived walk); the override is SILENTLY ignored (silent-wrong-answer class, worse than loud). Motivating case: a counted/keyed carrier with O(1) size (cf. Map.size) under the new Iterable.size default. FIX DIRECTION: (typer) extend the WI-210/218 PinNow classification beyond operation_has_no_body — when the receiver's carrier classifies Concrete and the carrier sort declares a member backing the spec op, rewrite to the carrier op even though the spec op has a default body; (eval) for un-rewritten abstract calls, prefer resolve_spec_op_target_by_value's carrier impl over the spec's own default body when the receiver's runtime sort defines the member. ACCEPTANCE: the pinning test flips to 99 (update it to assert the override); a counted-carrier O(1) size override typechecks + EVALS through the Iterable-imported call site; all existing WI-362/424 defaulted-member tests stay green (defaults still fire for carriers WITHOUT an override, e.g. BoxColl)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T13:01:36Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-490", description: some(value: "anthill-cpp-gen REGRESSION: field-access codegen broken on main — expr_body_b_test::field_access_emits_dot_syntax and field_access_in_expression_position FAIL (still failing after the WI-262 type-level-projection merge). A field access '(p).x' in an operation body reaches the C++ emitter as an unresolved method call: emit produces 'cannot lower expression body — unresolved method call \".x\" reached cpp-gen — the [simp] dot rules should have rewritten it' and 'return {};' instead of 'return p.x;'. Both tests fail on a clean tree (verified by stashing unrelated WI-444 work), so PRE-EXISTING, not from WI-444 (spec-op dispatch, anthill-core only). Most plausibly the WI-280 'bare-identifier value-receiver field access' merge (ee14ac9): WI-280 re-routes a NAME-rooted 'p.x' to a zero-arg DotApply when p names a local value, but the test's parenthesized '(p).x' receiver is NOT a bare identifier, so it keeps the field_access path — and the field-access [simp] dot-rule lowering cpp-gen depends on no longer fires for it (possibly tied to the WI-443 kb.has_dot_applies simp-enable gate: a body with no DotApply and no [simp] equations skips the tree-reassembly, leaving raw field_access). FIX DIRECTION: ensure a field_access expression (incl. parenthesized/expression-position receivers) is lowered for cpp-gen regardless of the DotApply/simp-enable gate — either always run the field-access dot rewrite, or have cpp-gen lower a raw field_access('object', Ident(field)) to 'object.field' directly. ACCEPTANCE: both anthill-cpp-gen expr_body_b_test cases pass; full workspace cargo-test green; anthill-core unaffected. (Originally filed as WI-489 but that id collided with a WI-262 follow-up on origin/main and was re-filed here.)"), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T13:29:51Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-490", author: "user", content: "Root cause was NOT the WI-280 re-route per se (both '(p).x' AND bare 'p.x' re-route to a zero-arg DotApply now — the memory's 'bare stays field_access' hypothesis was wrong). The real gap: the typer's field resolution (DotApply field-fallback at typing.rs ~3565, and resolve_field_type at ~11565) only walked constructors_of_sort(rs), which is EMPTY for a free-standing entity (a top-level 'entity Pose(x,y)' is its own constructor with no parent sort), so the field never resolved and a raw DotApply survived to cpp-gen. Fix: new KB helper field_constructors_of_sort = constructors_of_sort + self when entity_field_types(self).is_some() (additive — never fires for multi-variant sorts since entity_field_types is keyed by the entity functor, not the parent sort symbol), wired into both typer sites. Typer now rewrites DotApply -> field_access(p, Const(String(\"x\"))) typed at the field's type (load error gone too). cpp-gen field_name_from_node also accepts the Const(String) form (the canonical post-typer field-name encoding that eval reflect_field_access reads as Value::Str). Full workspace green (56 binaries, 0 failures); /code-review xhigh: no findings. NOT committed (repo policy: commit only when asked).", at: "2026-06-16T13:30:09Z")
