fact WorkItem(id: "WI-278", description: some(value: "Method-call (dot) syntax — first client of the [simp] rewriting engine (WI-277; docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md section 6; docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md section 7.1). Give Anthill ?xs.map(?f).filter(?p) via [simp] dispatch rules fired by the engine. Deliverables: (a) Expr::DotApply node (node_occurrence.rs, sibling to Apply) wired into drain_expr_children and for_each_child, plus the reflect dot_apply entity. (b) Converter: emit dot_apply for value-receiver dot forms (both ?x.field and ?x.method(args)), fixing the dropped receiver in collect_field_access_segments (convert.rs:342, which has no variable branch); keep sort and namespace flattening for Foo.bar; add the dot_apply functor case to materialize_from_handle (node_occurrence.rs, called at load.rs:5450). (c) find_operation_on_sort(sort,name) KB query: tier-1 in-body ops with no import (compose operations_of_sort at op_requirements.rs:177 over SortInfo.operations, and find_operation_in_scope at load.rs:2814); tier-2 import-scoped extension ops (new, no first-param index exists). (d) Prelude default_dot and dot_field rules ([simp], guard-exclusive, field-first on collision); dot_field reaches the existing field_access builtin (resolve.rs:1975). (e) Engine-evaluated type-level guards (is_entity and has_field from entity_fields; find_operation_on_sort), reading typeof from the typer TypeResult, not from classification. Acceptance: cargo-test green; xs.map(f).filter(p) chains; p.x field access via the unified path; no-import method resolution; clear no-match error at the source span; byte-identical Foo.bar and ?x.field-as-field. Depends on WI-277. Ref: docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md section 7.1; docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md section 6."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-277", "WI-279", "WI-280", "WI-281", "WI-282", "WI-275"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T15:21:46Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-488", description: some(value: "Typer escape gate (producer-side, sibling of WI-480/WI-401): gate ABSTRACTING TUPLE/ENTITY-COMPONENT returns at the PRODUCER. Today a tuple/entity return whose COMPONENT is a bare-spec provider upcast is NOT flagged: 'operation mkBare(m: MemStore) -> (KVStore, Bool) = (m, true)' LOADS clean (verified via WI-480 probes), because abstracting_return_error's sort_functor_of_view returns None for a tuple/named_tuple carrier, so it never inspects components. Consequence (decided consistent in WI-480, user 2026-06-16): the bare interface-propagation consumer 'let (s,_) = mkBare(m) ; s' is correctly NOT flagged because the producer exposes the bare component through its own signature -- but the producer SHOULD be the one flagged (the §5 avoidance problem applies to each abstracting tuple/entity component, exactly like a bare top-level return). FIX DIRECTION: lift abstracting_return_error (and the WI-457/468/480 leaf walk's whole-value gate) to recurse into a tuple/named_tuple return type's components and an entity return's fields, re-applying the SAME bare-vs-manifest-vs-ensures test per component. Must NOT reject a manifest component, an input-rooted component, or an ensures-vouched one. Verify wi401/wi402/wi457/wi468/wi480 stay green. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-480"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T15:57:33Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-488", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED. Root: abstracting_return_error keyed on sort_functor_of_view (None for a tuple/named_tuple carrier) so a tuple return whose COMPONENT abstracts a concrete provider to a bare spec (mkBare(m:MemStore)->(KVStore,Bool)=(m,true)) was never inspected. Fix: recurse abstracting_return_error into tuple components, aligned BY NAME with the WI-442 positional _1.._n fallback (align_named_tuple_fields) -- NOT a positional zip (which mispairs a reordered named tuple and misses the escape; /code-review caught this; regression test added). Per-component reuse of the unchanged gate honors must-not-reject (same_symbol spares input-rooted/equal; unbound check spares manifest). SCOPE FINDING: the parameterized-ENTITY case (-> Box[T=KVStore] from Box[T=MemStore]) is NOT a gap -- nominal type-args are INVARIANT so it is rejected even earlier as a type MISMATCH, never reaching the gate (only tuple components are covariant). The same-sort binding-value recursion explored for it was dropped as dead (user-decided). WI-480 reconciliation: mkBare was in WI-480's shared PRELUDE and is now correctly flagged; removed it, reworked opaque_bare_interface_propagation_not_flagged to an input-rooted (unflagged) producer, added wi488 producer test file (7 cases). Full workspace green 56 binaries. Merged origin/main (WI-278 dot-chain) -- code auto-merged clean, only tracker conflict (took theirs + re-applied claim/deliver via CLI).", at: "2026-06-16T15:57:49Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-489", description: some(value: "Validate field existence in type-position field projections (WI-262 follow-up). The value-in-type projection path (try_denoted_value_path / the denoted place) interns field names raw and defers resolution to the elimination/eval site, so a projection onto a NON-EXISTENT field of a CONCRETE-typed head — e.g. Modify[result.nonexistent] for a named-tuple return (a:.., b:..), or Modify[c.bogus] for an entity/tuple param c — is silently accepted at load instead of erroring. The HEAD is already validated (an unresolved head is a loud unresolved-name error); only the field/tail is unchecked. Pinned by wi262_type_level_projection_test::bogus_field_projection_is_not_yet_rejected (currently asserts the silent-accept). Scope: when the projection head's type is statically known (param/result/local of entity or named-tuple type), validate each tail segment names a real field of the running type and emit a loud load error at the projection span otherwise; flip that test to assert the rejection. Must NOT regress the legitimately-deferred abstract projections (s.T / s.E off an abstract spec receiver, WI-376/WI-475) where the field/member is only known once the carrier is concrete. Honors the repo 'prefer a loud error over a silent skip' principle."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T16:19:56Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-489", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-16 (b890b99). Load-time field-existence validation for value-in-type field projections (try_denoted_value_path). New Loader.signature_place_types map (param syms + result -> declared type Value) populated in load_operation BEFORE the effects clause converts (return+params come first), save/restored per op; consulted by new validate_denoted_field_path which walks each tail segment via field_step_in_value over extract_type: NamedTuple (by-name, then positional _n) / SortRef|Parameterized (field_constructors_of_sort + entity_field_types) => Found(next type, multi-level walk) | NoField (loud, load-blocking LoadError::InvalidFieldProjection at the projection span) | Defer (abstract type-param / spec|builtin with no fields / arrow / effect-row / neutral -> the legitimately-deferred s.T/s.E case, WI-376/475, must not regress). Multi-variant sorts collect from ALL ctors + structural_eq, Defer on divergence (mirrors eliminator resolve_field_type, removes HashMap-order nondeterminism). New span-bearing variant wired into both render methods + is_load_blocking. /code-review (xhigh) caught the multi-variant nondeterminism (fixed pre-commit); no other findings. Tests: wi262 flipped bogus_field_projection_is_rejected + added bogus_entity_param / bogus_deep / abstract_head_defers (12 total). Full workspace green (56 binaries).", at: "2026-06-16T16:19:56Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-494", description: some(value: "anthill-todo help does not show preopen and promote commands"), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-494", name: "bug")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-492", description: some(value: "Transitive spec provision: if a carrier `provides Stream` and `Stream provides Iterable`, the carrier should provide Iterable automatically (element/effect bindings composed) — instead of every Stream-providing carrier re-declaring `provides Iterable` + a boilerplate identity `iterator`. CONTEXT (WI-278): provision is currently NON-transitive, so List, MappedStream, FilteredStream each hand-write `provides Iterable[…]` + `operation iterator(x) = x` even though Stream already provides Iterable (stream.anthill:107). Cost is O(carriers x specs): every future lazy combinator (ZippedStream, TakeWhileStream, ConcatStream, …) must remember the same two lines or silently fail to dispatch .map/.filter through Iterable at a downstream call site (surfaced in WI-278 as UnknownOperation{iterator} on a mapped value). Fix: engine-side transitive provider derivation in the value-directed dispatch gate (provision_binds_param_to_carrier / carrier_param_receiver_for_values in typing.rs) AND/OR the load-time SortProvidesInfo closure, composing the intermediate spec's bindings. Then delete the 3 `provides Iterable` clauses + 3 identity iterators from the stdlib. Acceptance: removing provides-Iterable+iterator from MappedStream/FilteredStream still lets xs.map(f).filter(p) evaluate; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T16:12:44Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-495", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-491", description: some(value: "Covariant / projection return types: allow an operation's return to be a projection of a parameter's own type — e.g. `operation iterator(m: MappedStream) -> m.Sort = m` — instead of forcing explicit type-param threading. CONTEXT (WI-278): the lazy Stream carriers must provide Iterable, so each needs `iterator` returning the receiver AS a Stream. The natural identity body `= m` could not be written concisely: (a) a bare `-> Stream` return is REJECTED by the escape-free-return / avoidance check (WI-401) because the abstract members T,E are left unbound and would escape; (b) so it had to be written verbosely as `operation iterator[Elem, EffS, EffP](m: MappedStream[T = Elem, ES = EffS, EF = EffP]) -> Stream[T = Elem, E = {EffS, EffP}] = m` (mirroring FilteredStream.splitFirst), re-declaring every carrier type param just to thread it through the return. The DESIRED form is a COVARIANT return rooted at the receiver: `-> m.Sort` (the receiver's own type/sort projection), input-rooted by construction (passes the avoidance check), meaning 'returns a value of the receiver's type', admissible wherever that type's provided spec (here Stream) is expected. Sibling of receiver-type projections (WI-376 x.A / X.L; WI-430 carrier-precise) but projecting the WHOLE type (`m.Sort` / Self). Acceptance: the two combinators' iterator ops (combinators.anthill) rewrite to `-> m.Sort = m` and still type-check + the xs.map(f).filter(p) chain still evaluates; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T16:49:55Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-491", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-16 (370a719). Covariant return rooted at the receiver (-> m.Sort = m). check_operation_bodies eliminates a TOP-LEVEL expression-carried projection return type (extract_type==ExprCarried) against the op's own param types (eliminate_type_projections over a param_map) into 'effective_return' BEFORE the conformance + WI-401 escape checks (also used as the body top-down hint). m.Sort grounds to the receiver's whole type (project_type_member member=='Sort'), so identity body '= m' conforms and the avoidance gate sees the input-rooted concrete type (same sort as body -> admitted). PURELY ADDITIVE: only a GROUNDING top-level projection return changes (previously failed conformance); an abstract/neutral return (-> p.K = m, WI-400) eliminates to the ORIGINAL term (arg_syms=None Neutral branch) = byte-identical; a NESTED projection (Stream[T=l.T], List.iterator) is not top-level ExprCarried -> untouched; BODYLESS projection-return ops (wi376/wi381 peek/echo) are skipped by check_operation_bodies. SCOPE NOTE: WI-492 (transitive provision, parallel session) had already DELETED the lazy carriers' explicit iterator ops this ticket originally targeted, so the literal acceptance (rewrite combinators.anthill iterators) was moot; per user decision (AskUserQuestion: 'Implement + test fixture') the capability is proven by a dedicated wi491_covariant_return_test.rs (4 tests: covariant identity yields receiver type + admissible where provided spec expected [eval]; MappedStream headline -> m.Sort=m type-checks [load-clean]; bare -> Stream still rejected [no escape hole]). /code-review (xhigh) clean — verified bodyless-skip + abstract-neutral byte-identity. Full workspace green 56 binaries.", at: "2026-06-16T16:49:56Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-173", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-173", description: some(value: "Surface pretty-printing for type expressions in `persistence/print.rs`. Today TermPrinter falls through to the generic `name(arg: val, ...)` Fn form for type terms — `arrow(param: …, result: …, effects: cons(...))` instead of `(A) -> B @ {E1, E2}`. Round-trip from KB → text → parse is therefore lossy/ugly for any operation signature, fact field referencing a type, or codegen output. Add per-shape handlers in `write_term`: (1) `arrow(param, result, effects)` → `(<param>) -> <result>` plus `@ <e>` for single effect or `@ {<e1>, <e2>, …}` for set; emit nothing when effects is `nil`. (2) `named_tuple(fields: List[TypeField])` → `(<f1>, <f2>, …)` where TypeField positional `_N` names print as bare types and named fields print as `n: T`. Arrow case detects when `param` is already a named_tuple and uses its parenthesised form directly to avoid double-wrap. (3) `sort_ref(name: Ref(S))` → bare `S`. (4) `parameterized(base, bindings: List[TypeBinding])` → `<base>[<k1> = <v1>, <k2> = <v2>]`. (5) `TypeBinding(name: Ref(K), type: T)` → `K = T`. Recursion goes through `write_term` so each handler's children re-enter and pick up the same surface form. Shared helper `walk_cons_list(tid) -> Vec<TermId>` for the list traversals. Tests in `persistence_test.rs` round-trip the canonical cases plus the multi-effect set (mirroring `load_arrow_type_with_effect_set_preserves_list` already in parse_test.rs). Driver: `(A) -> B @ {Modifies[host], Reads[host]}` should print as itself, not as the cons-list functor blob. Out of scope: `arrow_effect`-positional-form (used only by `build_instantiation_term` for sort instantiation contexts), tuple_type (no Fn shape used for it today)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T18:54:30Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-173", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-16 (137ceb8). Surface pretty-printing for TYPE terms in TermPrinter::write_term. write_term delegates a distinct TypeExtractor.* functor to a new type-context printer write_type_term: arrow -> (A)->B with @E (single)/@{E1,E2}(set)/nothing(pure); named_tuple -> (a:T,...) [positional _N field -> bare type]; sort_ref -> bare S (already); parameterized IN TYPE CONTEXT -> S[k=v]; plus Denoted/ExprCarried/RigidTypeProjection/TypeVar/Nothing. Arrow named_tuple param uses its own parens (no double-wrap). Effect row walked from EffectsRows(effects_expr: merge/present/absent/open/empty_row) tree. Type functors matched on QUALIFIED name via new TermSource::qualified_name (default=short name, KnowledgeBase overrides) so a user sort sharing short name Arrow/merge is never misread + non-KB ParsedFile keeps generic form. STALENESS/SCOPE (WI-361, user-decided 'type-aware printer' via AskUserQuestion): the ticket predates WI-361 which retired the deep parameterized(base,bindings)/sort_ref/TypeBinding WRAPPERS, so a parameterized type is now Fn{S,named} = structurally identical to a data term S(k:v). A STANDALONE bare parameterized type via generic write_term stays data-form (cannot disambiguate without type context); inside an arrow/tuple the S[k=v] form IS recovered. Items 4(parameterized standalone)/5(TypeBinding) of the ticket are moot as written. Tests: wi173_type_print_test (8 incl loaded callback signature via lookup_operation_info); updated parse_test load_arrow_type_with_effect_set_canonical_row printer-regression guard from the old Arrow(param:...,effects:EffectsRows(...)) blob to the surface (A)->B @ {Modifies[host],Reads[host]} form. /code-review clean. Full workspace green 56 binaries (no codegen/golden-parity cascade).", at: "2026-06-16T18:54:31Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-495", description: some(value: "Typer half of transitive spec provision (WI-492 follow-up). WI-492 made the EVAL-side dispatch transitive (carrier_param_receiver_for_values → transitive_carrier_for_param in typing.rs), letting the lazy MappedStream/FilteredStream carriers drop their explicit `provides Iterable` + identity `iterator` (their static type is always Stream, so the typer never classifies them). A CONCRETE carrier like List has static type List, so the TYPER's carrier_param_receiver (typing.rs, direct-only) DOES classify it and must compose Element/E from List's provision of Stream — the transitive-binding composition not yet built. Removing List's explicit `provides Iterable[C=List[T], Element=T, E={}]` + `iterator` currently regresses every Iterable.find/map/size/isEmpty/foldLeft on a List to 'undeclared effect: ?_' (the WI-424 effect-row grounding breaks). Fix: make carrier_param_receiver walk transitively like transitive_carrier_for_param AND compose the intermediate spec's element/effect bindings (Iterable.Element ← Stream.T ← List.T; Iterable.E ← Stream.E ← {}) so the grounded row threads. Then delete List's explicit provides Iterable + iterator (see list.anthill comment). Acceptance: remove List's explicit Iterable clause; Iterable ops on a List still type-check pure (no ?_ leak); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T17:30:54Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-496", name: "typing")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-289", author: "user", content: "Already IMPLEMENTED concurrently on main in commit a26ee99 (2026-05-24): flipped TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS=true, added arrow_function_compatible (higher-order Function[A,B] call typing) + free-op sweep in type_check_sorts_typed, and fixed the eval/parse/time_now/wi182/wi205 fixtures. Verified on current main (post-rebase): full workspace green (56 binaries, 0 fail); negative check confirms a namespace-level op with a return mismatch is now caught ('type mismatch in free_bad.return: expected Int64, got Bool') — not a no-op. Only remaining work was stale doc comments (the const + sweep said 'OFF'/'gated OFF' though delivered) — fixed. Delivering as substantially-done.", at: "2026-06-16T17:47:32Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-289", description: some(value: "Enable + fix type-checking of namespace-level (free) operations. Operations declared directly in a namespace (not inside a sort) — e.g. the anthill.cli.parse / anthill.cli.help CLI parser, and the eval-test m2/m5 fixtures — are NOT type-checked or simp-rewritten today: the typer's op-body driver (typing::type_check_sorts_typed) reaches operations only via each sort's reflect SortInfo, and namespaces produce no SortInfo. Pre-existing latent gap (independent of WI-283): such op bodies load with NO type validation. WI-283 added a gated sweep (const TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS in typing.rs, currently false) that type-checks + fires [simp] in EVERY op body incl. free ones. Flipping it to true surfaced ~25 eval-fixture failures from constructs eval supports but the typer (only ever run on sort ops) does not: (1) higher-order calls of Function[A,B]-typed values, e.g. f(f(x)) with f: Function[Int,Int] -> 'expected known operation or arrow-typed variable, got unknown functor' (typer must treat application of a Function-sorted value as a higher-order call / extract its arrow type, matching eval); (2) effect-declaration checks — free ops using eprintln/println/modify don't declare the effects (e.g. 'undeclared effect ConsoleError') — fix the fixtures; (3) some name resolution ('expected resolved name, got unresolved') in free-op bodies. Fix the typer for these, fix fixtures where a declaration is genuinely missing, then flip TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS=true. Acceptance: TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS=true; free-op bodies (cli/parse, cli/help, eval m2/m5 fixtures) type-check correctly; [simp] fires in free-op bodies; full cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-283"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T17:47:35Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-493", author: "user", content: "INVESTIGATION (claude, not delivered — reverted to green, stop-and-ask). The ticket's premise of a SINGLE 'lambda-effect bind site' is inaccurate. Empirically (removed the WI-278 mid-walk unwrap arm in decompose_effect_row, ran wi278/wi492): the wrapped tail is 'open[tail = {empty_row}]' i.e. a row-tail var bound to a WRAPPED effects_rows(empty_row) instead of bare empty_row. ROOT: effect-row TYPE-ARGS (Stream[E = {...}]) are uniformly stored WRAPPED as effects_rows(...) by convention, and they get bound onto row-tail vars across MULTIPLE independent paths, NOT one: (1) unify_parameterized_with_sort_ref (WI-375 arm, binds the whole effects_rows term/Node onto the spec alias var); (2) carrier_param_receiver_for_values / WI-393 grounding (binds the ground provider row 'concrete' onto the op's Eff param); (3) the provider-admissibility/subtype path (each combinator's source-effect param binds to the PREVIOUS combinator's whole provided E row → the wrap NESTS: filter's ES ← map's {ES,EF}). I fixed (1)+(2) with a new effects_rows_inner_term unwrap helper; the error just moved deeper (nested open[tail={merge[...]}]) because (3) still wraps. So removing the tolerance requires canonicalizing effect-row type-arg bindings to BARE at EVERY var-binding site (unify + subtype + provider admissibility) — a representation-level change with cascade risk into delivered effect WIs (wi357/375/424/441/492). The WI-278 decompose-site unwrap is actually the single CHOKE POINT where all row tails are walked, so it is arguably the correct place. Needs a human design decision (see options in the stop-and-ask).", at: "2026-06-16T19:12:08Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-493", description: some(value: "Canonicalize effect-row shape at the BINDING site, not at decompose. CONTEXT (WI-278): a row's tail can be bound to either a BARE EffectExpression (from a `provides Iterable[E = {}]` fact) or a WRAPPED `effects_rows(empty_row)` (from lambda-effect inference), so a `{E, EffP}` merge mixes both shapes. WI-278 patched the CONSUMER (decompose_effect_row in typing.rs now unwraps a wrapped tail mid-walk) — a 'make it parse' tolerance rather than 'make it well-formed'. The inverse fn effects_rows_to_flat_list already tolerates the same split, and the unify/subtype multi-tail arms special-case it; each new row consumer is a fresh place the mismatch can silently mis-decompose. Deeper fix: route the lambda-effect-inferred tail through the existing canonicalization (build_canonical_effects_rows / make_effects_rows_* / make_row_shaped ~typing.rs:9962) so every binding site emits ONE canonical shape; then delete the consumer tolerance arms. Acceptance: make the lambda-effect bind site emit the same shape as the provides-fact path; remove the WI-278 mid-walk unwrap arm in decompose_effect_row and confirm xs.map(f).filter(p) still type-checks + evaluates; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T19:33:30Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-493", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-16 (3ebebbc) — CONSOLIDATE option (user AskUserQuestion decision; the ticket's single-bind-site premise was inaccurate, see prior investigation feedback). Extracted ONE shared helper effects_rows_inner<V: TermView>(kb,&v)->Option<Value> (Some(inner) iff the value is the EffectsRows wrapper, matched by QUALIFIED symbol) and routed all four open-coded unwrap sites through it: decompose_effect_row top-level + WI-278 mid-walk arm, row_inner_value (the multi-tail arm), and effects_rows_to_flat_list. BEHAVIOR-PRESERVING: each site does the same unwrap; decompose's malformed-wrapper hard-rejects survive via fall-through (top-level -> bare/tail fallbacks -> empty; mid-walk -> the  unknown-functor ); effects_rows_to_flat_list's unreachable malformed case now flows to list_to_vec instead of a debug_assert (make_effects_rows_* always sets the child, so unreachable). The WI-278 tolerance STAYS (kept, not removed) — now single-sourced so a new row consumer can't drift. /code-review (xhigh) caught + fixed a doc-comment misattribution (the new helper was inserted between decompose's doc and its fn, orphaning decompose's doc); no correctness bugs. Tests: wi493_effect_row_tolerance_test (map.filter chain type-checks + evaluates = the bare+wrapped mixed row); wi278/wi492 broader regression. Full workspace green 56 binaries. NOT done (deliberate, user-decided): the full producer-side canonicalization (bind effect-row type-args bare everywhere + delete the tolerance) — a representation-level change with cascade risk into wi357/375/424/441/492; left as the decompose choke point.", at: "2026-06-16T19:33:30Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-291", description: some(value: "Grammar cleanup: remove the now-redundant 'export' statement + 'export' visibility prefix\n\nFollow-up to the Model C visibility migration (visible-by-default; 'internal' is the only hide gate). After that lands, the standalone 'export' statement (grammar.js:139) and the 'export' choice in the visibility prefix (grammar.js:720) are no-ops kept only for back-compat. This WI removes them:\n- tree-sitter grammar: drop 'export' statement rule + 'export' from visibility choice; regenerate parser.\n- scaland + rustland parsers/IR: drop Export from Visibility enum and the export-list fields on Namespace/SortWithBody.\n- Verify stdlib (already export-statement-free post Model C cleanup) and all tests still pass on both impls.\nLow priority / mechanical; do only once Model C is stable."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T19:50:27Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-291", author: "user", content: "Delivered (uncommitted). Removed export everywhere: tree-sitter grammar (export_clause rule + 'export' from visibility choice + 3 content lists; regenerated parser, 157/157 grammar tests), rustland (Visibility::Export, Namespace/SortWithBody.exports fields, convert.rs handling, codegen arm), scaland (Visibility.Export, exports fields, exportClause, body parser 3-tuple->2-tuple), kernel-language.md canonical spec + forward-mapping docs. Swept 394 standalone 'export X' statement lines across 114 .anthill/.rs/.scala test-fixture+snippet files (stdlib was already export-free). rustland 1987/0 green; /code-review clean.\n\nKEY FINDING: 'export' was NOT a pure no-op as proposal 044 assumed. Two test breakages exposed it: (1) prove_hint_test relied on 'export bound_d, target' to disambiguate a GREEDY rule_block parse — the brace-less form 'rule <entry>* end' (grammar.js rule_block) greedily swallows a following 'proof ... end', treating the proof's 'end' as the block terminator; the leading export statement incidentally steered GLR toward the single rule_declaration parse. Fixed the test to use a braced 'rule { ... }' block (unambiguous). This is a PRE-EXISTING latent grammar fragility, reproduces on clean main with the export line removed. (2) typing_pass_spec.anthill (docs/, not in sweep ROOTS) still had export statements -> removed.\n\nscaland: 6 PRE-EXISTING ParserIntegrationTest failures (AmbiguousSymbol(not,[anthill.reflect.not, anthill.reflect.not])) — confirmed identical on clean main, the known 'missing is_new gate on scaland variant-exposure parent link' parity gap, NOT introduced here. Not committed yet.", at: "2026-06-16T19:50:48Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-496", description: some(value: "Transitive dispatch of body-less spec ops + unify provision-transitivity. CONTEXT (WI-495): List keeps a redundant identity 'operation iterator(l: List) -> Stream = l' ONLY because the typer's body-less spec-op DISPATCH is direct-only: explicit 'iterator(xs)' on a concrete List (Iterable.iterator is body-less) needs a direct impl, and dispatch_spec_op_cached / the carrier-keyed provider_spec_view_bindings probe (typing.rs ~4867) match impls via DIRECT provider facts, not transitively. Make that dispatch transitive (reuse transitive_carrier_for_param: List provides Stream provides Iterable -> Stream.iterator) so 'iterator(xs)' resolves to Stream.iterator and List drops its iterator op (completes WI-495). ALTITUDE: provision-transitivity now lives in FOUR independent per-consumer walks — find_spec_op_for_provided_sort BFS, transitive_provision_view, transitive_carrier_for_param, sort_provides_reach. Evaluate ONE load-time transitive closure of SortProvidesInfo facts (synthesize 'C provides Spec2' with composed type-param AND op bindings) so every consumer (incl. body-less dispatch and WI-363 coverage) sees direct facts. compose_provision_views substitutes only BARE type-param refs today (compound kept verbatim -> loud ?_; deep substitution = WI-380 follow-up). Acceptance: List drops 'operation iterator'; 'iterator(xs)' on a List type-checks + evaluates; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T21:12:59Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-497", description: some(value: "Tree-sitter grammar: remove the unused brace-less `<entries> end` forms of rule_block and operation_block to kill the GLR ambiguity that lets a block greedily swallow a following declaration.\n\nROOT CAUSE (found in WI-291; see memory project_rule_block_greedy_parse): grammar.js `rule_block = 'rule' choice('{' rule_entry* '}', rule_entry* 'end')` and `operation_block` mirrors it. The brace-less `rule_entry* 'end'` alternative is GLR-ambiguous with a single `rule_declaration` (identical inner shape, both start with 'rule') — that's the DECLARED conflict [$.rule_declaration, $.rule_entry] (and [$.operation_declaration, $.operation_entry]) in the conflicts array. Because rule heads are SOFT-KEYWORD identifiers, a brace-less block consumes following 'rule'/'proof'/etc. keywords as bare-name entry heads and runs to the FIRST 'end' — so `rule X: ... \\n proof X ... end` parses as ONE rule_block whose terminator is the PROOF's 'end', SILENTLY dropping the proof (0 ERROR nodes). In WI-291 a leading 'export' statement had been incidentally steering GLR away from this; removing export exposed it (prove_hint_test, worked around with a braced block).\n\nKEY FACTS: (1) the brace-less form is used by ZERO real .anthill files (all rule/operation blocks use braces); (2) scaland (fastparse) has ONLY the braced form (\"{\" ~/ ruleEntry.rep ~ \"}\", \"{\" ~/ operationEntry.rep ~ \"}\") — so the brace-less form is a tree-sitter-ONLY divergence and removing it ALIGNS the two grammars.\n\nAPPROACH VALIDATED via throwaway prototype (reverted, not committed): removed both brace-less alternatives + deleted both conflicts -> npx tree-sitter generate exit 0 (conflicts genuinely no longer needed); the ORIGINAL brace-less prove_hint snippet (two 'rule X:' + standalone [hint] + two 'proof ... end') then parses as 2 rule_declaration + 2 proof_declaration + 0 rule_block + 0 ERROR. ONLY fallout: ONE corpus test 'Operation body in block' uses the brace-less operation form and fails -> update it to braced (or remove).\n\nFIX: (1) grammar.js: drop `seq(repeat($.rule_entry),'end')` from rule_block and `seq(repeat($.operation_entry),'end')` from operation_block (keep braced '{ }'); (2) delete conflicts [$.rule_declaration,$.rule_entry] and [$.operation_declaration,$.operation_entry]; regenerate; (3) fix the 'Operation body in block' corpus test; confirm 157-ish/all corpus green; (4) OPTIONAL cleanup: revert prove_hint_test.rs to the natural brace-less rule form (now parses correctly — two single rule_declarations no longer merge); (5) kernel-language.md: if it documents a brace-less rule/operation block, switch to braces-only for blocks (single decls stay 'rule X: ...'); (6) scaland: no change (already braced-only). Full rustland cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T21:13:39Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-497", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17 (uncommitted at write time). grammar.js: rule_block and operation_block now braced-{ }-only — dropped both brace-less 'rule_entry* end' / 'operation_entry* end' alternatives; deleted the two GLR conflicts [rule_declaration,rule_entry] and [operation_declaration,operation_entry] (tree-sitter generate exit 0 → genuinely dead). Kept [rule_entry] (still applies to braced blocks). Corpus 'Operation body in block' + rust parse_operation_body_in_block updated to braced form (expected trees byte-identical → converter unchanged). prove_hint_test reverted from the WI-291 braced-block workaround to the natural two-separate-'rule X:' form — now parses as 2 rule_declarations, passes under z3 (direct proof the greedy-merge is gone). Corpus 157/157, parse_tests 419/0, full rustland suite green. Generated src/parser.c is gitignored; build.rs regenerates from grammar.js on stale/missing, so only grammar.js committed. kernel-language.md already braces-only (no change). scaland already braced-only (no change) → this aligns the two grammars. /code-review xhigh: no bugs. Memory project_rule_block_greedy_parse updated FIXED.", at: "2026-06-16T21:13:41Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-323", description: some(value: "typing.rs pattern-fragment walkers (occurrence_contains_functor ~7043 and check_ho_apply_pattern_occ ~7038) walk Expr children only via for_each_child — a ho_apply smuggled inside a Pattern's type_ann Expr child evades the WI-246 hereditary-Harrop pattern-fragment check (rules 1/2/3/3b). PROBLEM: WI-319 lifted Lambda.param / LambdaWithin.param / Let.pattern / MatchBranch.pattern to Pattern-kind Rc<NodeOccurrence>. WI-298 extended six listed walkers (occurrence_has_unbound_var, collect_occurrence_global_vars, collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered, try_occurrence_to_term, collect_occurrence_type_constraints, collect_unbound_vars_node) with Pattern descent. These TWO parallel walkers in typing.rs were NOT on the WI-298 list and still early-return on Pattern-kind occurrences via `let Some(expr) = occ.as_expr() else { return }` (check_ho_apply_pattern_occ:7046) / `if let Some(expr) = o.as_expr()` (occurrence_contains_functor:7046). FAILURE: a rule body atom like Let { pattern: Pattern::Var { type_ann: Some(<expr containing ho_apply>) }, ... } bypasses check_ho_apply_pattern_occ — its rules-1/3/3b violation is silently missed; occurrence_contains_functor likewise misses a target functor nested in a Pattern.type_ann (used by the head-position check_pattern_fragment for the rules-1/3b body-vs-head co-occurrence test). LATENT today because Pattern.Var.type_ann is always None at load_pattern_var (load.rs:4963); live the moment proposal-035 binder annotations / reflection-synthesized patterns populate the slot. SCOPE: add Pattern arm to both walkers descending via for_each_pattern_child (mirror of resolve.rs collect_unbound_vars_node and node_occurrence.rs collect_occurrence_global_vars after WI-298). Code-review finding on WI-298 PR (98a9ea5). ACCEPTANCE: a rule body Let with Pattern.Var.type_ann containing ho_apply triggers the rule-fragment violation; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T21:23:12Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-446", description: some(value: "Grammar/parser: DANGLING-CASE attachment hazard -- a trailing 'case' arm written after a NESTED match attaches to the INNER match, silently removing the arm the author wrote for the OUTER one (match term_field(..) / case some(st) -> match ... case none -> '' / case none -> '' : the last arm lands on the inner match; the outer loses its none arm entirely). Discovered 2026-06-12 when WI-374's exhaustiveness coverage (sort_functor_of_view at the match scrutinee, replacing the bare-ref-only read that SKIPPED parameterized scrutinees) un-hid three live instances: anthill-todo store.anthill status_short + find_term_by_id and main.anthill collect_feedback_set -- all fixed by reordering the leaf arm before the nested-match arm (commit note in each). Parenthesized inner matches (lambda bodies) are delimited and safe. CANDIDATE FIXES: (a) tree-sitter grammar: make case attachment indentation-aware (external scanner / indent tokens) so a shallower case closes the inner match; (b) loader lint: reject or warn on a case whose indentation is shallower than its match's previous arm (cheap, catches the hazard without grammar surgery); (c) at minimum a corpus test pinning today's attachment so a future grammar change is deliberate. Repro anchor: the reordered sites in store.anthill carry a NOTE comment; wi374_expansion_test::annotated_let_match_exhaustiveness_kept exercises the coverage that detects the symptom."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T22:15:08Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-446", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17 (uncommitted at write time). Implemented candidates (b) loud detection + (c) corpus pin; rejected (a) indentation-aware grammar as overkill. (b) convert.rs check_dangling_case: hard parse error when a match branch's leading-whitespace indentation is a PROPER PREFIX of the match's first branch (visually shallower => written for an enclosing match but stolen by this nested one). Compared by whitespace-prefix not byte column (tree-sitter column is a byte offset; a tab is 1 byte and would falsely read as shallower than space-indented siblings) — tab/space-mix safe + conservative on incomparable indentation. Single-line nested matches carry no indentation signal => skipped (there the parse matches the visual reading). (c) corpus test 'Dangling case attaches to inner match' pins today's grammar attachment (outer keeps 1 branch; trailing case lands on inner's 2). FOUND+FIXED two REAL latent hazards the guard exposed in docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill: 'match ar' silently stole 8 outer arms (if_expr..TupleLiteral); 'match operation_body' stole the 'case _' fallback — both fixed by let-binding the nested match (trailing ref terminates its branch list), order+semantics preserved. 5 new parse tests (rejected/let-bound-ok/single-line-ok/mixed-indent-ok + spec parses), corpus 158/158, full rustland suite green x2, codebase scan 0/111 flagged. /code-review xhigh caught the byte-column tab false-positive (fixed). scaland: no change (already braced-only; the converter guard is rust-only).", at: "2026-06-16T22:15:11Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-426", description: some(value: "Loader/typer: named-argument OPERATION calls fail name resolution ('expected resolved name, got unresolved'). Any body call passing args by name -- pair(y = 1, x = \"a\") -- fails for BOTH non-projection and projection ops (constructor named args work; operation-call named args do not). The named-arg label is not resolved against the callee's params in convert/typing, so the arg is dropped/unbound. Surfaced by WI-398 review: the cross-param projection receiver-passed-by-name path is blocked by this (e.g. check(k = ..., s = w) reports 's.name unresolved'). Pre-existing, orthogonal to projection. Probe: a no-projection op two(a,b) called two(b=b, a=a) reproduces it."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-16T22:18:46Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-299", description: some(value: "Centralize Rust-side entity-term construction so named args are always canonicalized to declared field order. PROBLEM: the discrim matcher matches named args POSITIONALLY (discrim.rs:573 descends NamedKey(query_keys[i]) against the tree's i-th pattern key), and the loader canonicalizes loaded patterns/facts to declared field order via entity_field_names (load.rs:3112). But Rust-side term builders sort named args by Symbol::index() (interning order) — build_list (mod.rs:2187/2202), make_sort_ref, and others at mod.rs:2248/2261/2282/2317. index-order only COINCIDENTALLY equals declared-order (verified for source_span/cons during WI-297: works today, but reversing the order makes the structured pattern silently match 0 solutions). A future change to interning order (e.g. a new stdlib entity interning a shared field name earlier) would silently break matching of any Rust-built >=2-named-arg entity term against a loaded pattern, with no error. SCOPE: add a single canonicalizing constructor (e.g. KB::make_entity_term(functor, pos, named) that calls the existing pub(crate) KB::sort_named_canonical added in WI-297) and route the existing s.index()-sorting builders through it; remove the ad-hoc s.index() sorts. Rust-only. Loaded terms need no change (loader already canonicalizes). PRECONDITION CONTEXT: WI-297 added KB::sort_named_canonical (generic over value type) and already fixed its own two builders (make_source_span_term, build_occurrence_cons_list); this generalizes that fix to the pre-existing builders."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-297"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T01:18:56Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-212", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17 (234aabc). RE-SCOPED: the original symptom — AmbiguousSymbol(T/A/B) leaking prelude type-parameters — was ALREADY resolved by the parser resync (a81a8c9); the addTypeParam marker (Loader.scala scanItemsPass1 AbstractSort arm) keeps per-sort T/A/B from leaking between sibling sorts. Verified: no AmbiguousSymbol(T/A/B) remains. The same 6 stdlib-full-load tests still failed, but for an ADJACENT root cause: AmbiguousSymbol(not, [anthill.reflect.not, anthill.reflect.not]) — the SAME qualified name as two DISTINCT symbols. 'not' is registered first as a builtin (Prelude.registerStandardBuiltins, into the prelude anthill.reflect scope) and then ALSO declared 'operation not(...)' in reflect.anthill; scaland scans a re-opened namespace into a FRESH scope (does not reuse the prelude scope as rustland does), so the operation-scan's plain define minted a second anthill.reflect.not in a different scope, and a bare rule-body use (:- not(...) in typing.anthill) collected both via resolveInScope -> ambiguous. FIX: new defineOperationOnce helper routes both operation-scan arms (OperationItem + OperationBlockItem) to skip the define when the qualified name is already registered — mirrors rustland's is_new reuse gate (load.rs:1110, entity arm). One anthill.reflect.not survives; bare 'not' resolves to it via the global reflect-namespace parent. scaland sbt test 158/158 (was 152/158); /code-review (low) clean; rustland untouched. The DEEPER divergence (scaland re-creates the namespace symbol per file instead of reusing the prelude's, unlike rustland's namespace is_new gate at load.rs:1071) is left as-is — benign for resolution (qualified refs use byQualifiedName, bare refs reach the single builtin via the global parent) and aligning it has blast-radius into per-file namespace scoping; a candidate future cleanup, not needed here.", at: "2026-06-17T04:23:25Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-212", description: some(value: "scaland stdlib full-load regression — AmbiguousSymbol on prelude type parameters. Loading the full embedded stdlib (51 files, post-WI-153) in a single scaland KB pass fails with AmbiguousSymbol(T, …) repeated for the prelude sorts Numeric, Lattice, Modifiable, Option, Eq, BoundedLattice, List, Field, Effect, Stream, Ordered, plus AmbiguousSymbol(A) / AmbiguousSymbol(B) for Function and Pair. The unqualified type-parameter names appear to leak from per-sort scope into ambient namespace scope, so when many sorts that share the canonical T/A/B parameter names load together the resolver sees them as competing candidates. Single-file parse + load tests pass; failure is specific to the full-stdlib pass. Failing tests: ParserIntegrationTest \"WI-153: stdlib float.anthill parses + loads (depends on algebra)\", \"WI-153: stdlib geometry.anthill loads end-to-end (depends on algebra + Float)\", \"WI-153: stdlib witness.anthill loads end-to-end with full sort/entity counts\", \"WI-153: EmbeddedStdlib loads as a single KB load pass\", \"WI-155: ProofRecord fact with witness + state_hash round-trips through parser + loader\", \"WI-155: SmtDischarge witness with SmtVerdict round-trips\". Rustland does not exhibit this; check how rustland scopes type-parameter Symbols inside scan_definitions and mirror in scaland. Acceptance: sbt test green; full stdlib KB load reports no AmbiguousSymbol on prelude type parameters."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-153", "WI-155"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T04:23:28Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-433", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED via direction (b) DESUGAR (user-chosen). Loader desugars positional ctor args -> named (declaration order, filling fields NOT given by name) in convert_term_with_expected (fact heads + rule heads + rule-body entity atoms route through convert_term) and convert_query_term (CLI query path). Over-arity = loud LoadError; anthill.reflect.* Expr meta-ctors (ho_apply/match_expr/...) + is_reflect_form_functor excluded. Match patterns do NOT share the gap (eval match_constructor_pattern maps positional sub-patterns to leading field indices). Tests: wi433_positional_ctor_desugar_test (6) + github_todo wi433_claimable_with_verified_deps. Full workspace green; /code-review xhigh. Two sibling gaps on non-loader paths filed as follow-ups: load-order forward-ref (loader scan-pass) + runtime-built positional ctors not canonicalized (eval/persist).", at: "2026-06-17T04:52:33Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-433", description: some(value: "Loader/typer: positional constructor pattern vs NAMED-field sort is a SILENT NEVER-MATCH -- make it loud or make it work (loud-error principle; bug class found+fixed 2026-06-11, 9fa0da6). 'WorkItem(id: ?dep, status: Verified(?))' loaded clean against 'entity Verified(at: String)' but the positional sub-pattern never unifies with named-field facts, so all_deps_verified silently rejected EVERY dependent item (claim/next broken for any non-empty depends_on; found driving heimdall WI-005; existing github_todo tests missed it because the claimable fixture has empty deps). No layer flags it: the loader accepts the pattern, the typer does not validate rule-body constructor patterns against the sort's declared fields, and SLD/discrim unification just fails. TWO FIX DIRECTIONS (pick one): (a) LOUD -- at load/scan, a constructor pattern with positional args whose sort declares named fields is a hard error naming the declared fields (minimal, conservative); (b) DESUGAR -- positional args map to declaration-order named args when arity == field count (the sugar the kernel spec already uses for spec applications: 'positional application is sugar for names'), making Verified(?) just work; arity mismatch stays a loud error either way. Same check should cover match-expression patterns if they share the gap (probe). ACCEPTANCE: the exact 9fa0da6 pre-fix pattern either fails the load loudly or matches; add a github-todo test where a claimable item HAS verified deps (the coverage hole that hid this)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T04:52:34Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-498", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17 (uncommitted at write time). Routed the 3 persistence entity-term builders in persistence/term_ser.rs through kb.make_entity_term (the WI-299 canonicalizing funnel) instead of ad-hoc sort_by_key(sym.index())+alloc(Term::Fn): (1) load_entry entity deserialize, (2) array_to_list_term cons cells, (3) build_constructor_term named-ctor/enum-variant arm. make_entity_term -> sort_named_canonical sorts to DECLARED field order when entity_field_names is registered, else falls back to index() (== old behavior), so it's a strict consistency improvement matching the loader (convert_term canonicalizes fact heads to declared order) and the discrim matcher (descends named keys positionally). SortView site (load.rs assemble_sort_view_value) LEFT AS-IS with a clarifying note: its index sort is deliberate (WI-449 byte-identity); its named keys are the viewed spec's TYPE-PARAM bindings (T/E), NOT declared SortView fields, so routing through the funnel would mis-canonicalize them against SortView's own field schema. Single-field shorthand + positional arms intentionally not routed (1 named arg is trivially canonical; positional has no named args). TEST: wi498_deserialized_entity_matches_source_loaded_form (toml_ser_test.rs) — top-level entities (Pre interns aafield first => lower index than zzfield; Rec declares zzfield first) so declared order [zzfield,aafield] REVERSES index order — same shape as the real WorkItem entity (id declared first, interned after description/status). Asserts the TOML-reloaded fact hash-cons-matches the source-loaded fact head; precondition asserts index!=declared so it can't pass vacuously. VERIFIED the test catches the bug: temporarily reverting site 1 to index-sort makes it FAIL. Full workspace green (56 binaries, 2022 tests, 0 fail) via scripts/test.sh; /code-review (parallel correctness + cleanup/altitude/conventions) clean, 0 findings. NOTE: an adjacent pre-existing gap (serialize skips none()-valued Option fields + deserialize doesn't fresh-var-fill absent fields, so absent-Option facts don't round-trip-match) is orthogonal to this ordering fix — not addressed here.", at: "2026-06-17T06:06:07Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-498", description: some(value: "Route the persistence/deserialization entity-term rebuilders through KB::make_entity_term so they canonicalize named args to DECLARED field order (the WI-299 funnel), not Symbol::index() interning order. PROBLEM (same hazard class as WI-299, found by its code-review, but in the persistence layer rather than the make_* term builders): three sites in persistence/term_ser.rs hand-build entity Term::Fn sorting named_args by sym.index() only — entity_to_term deserialize (term_ser.rs:307, arbitrary user-entity facts), list_to_term (term_ser.rs:415, cons cells), json_object_to_ctor_term (term_ser.rs:470, named-constructor / enum-variant terms). The loader canonicalizes source-loaded facts to declared field order via entity_field_names (load.rs), and the discrim matcher descends named keys POSITIONALLY, so a fact RELOADED from a persisted store (index-order) would silently fail to hash-cons / discrim-match the SAME fact loaded from .anthill source (declared-order) for any entity whose field interning order != declaration order. Coincidentally safe today (field interning usually happens in declared order), exactly the latent fragility WI-299 eliminated for the builders. SCOPE: these are &mut KnowledgeBase contexts already calling kb.alloc(Term::Fn), so replace each ad-hoc sort+alloc with kb.make_entity_term(functor, pos, named). SEPARATE/NUANCED (evaluate, do not blind-reroute): load.rs:7901 assemble_sort_view_value sorts SortView bindings by sym.index() DELIBERATELY for WI-449 spec byte-identity — its named args are TYPE-PARAM bindings (not declared SortView fields), single-field today; routing through sort_named_canonical would fall back to index() and be equivalent now, but the intent differs, so handle with care or leave with a clarifying note. ACCEPTANCE: term_ser deserialize round-trips an entity whose declared field order != interning order and the reloaded term hash-cons-matches the source-loaded form; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T06:06:08Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-303", description: some(value: "Fire parse errors early: surface tree-sitter ERROR / MISSING nodes from parse() instead of silently dropping them. PROBLEM: parse() (rustland/anthill-core/src/parse/mod.rs) never inspects tree.root_node().has_error(); it returns Ok with only the converter's own errors. tree-sitter recovers from malformed input by inserting ERROR / MISSING nodes and continuing, and the converter walks past anything it does not recognise — so a broken construct is silently dropped (an `Effect = {}` binding vanishes; the anthill-stl carrier host bindings were dropped; computed type args dropped). Violates CLAUDE.md 'avoid fallbacks, know about errors early'. PROTOTYPE (validated then reverted this session): a collect_syntax_errors(root, source) walk that prunes clean subtrees via has_error, reports is_error / is_missing once per error subtree (source-ordered), and has parse() return Err if any are found. BLAST RADIUS (measured with the prototype): zero behavioural regressions, but it surfaces ~37+ latent malformed TEST FIXTURES across at least 4 binaries (builtin/toml_ser 16, parse 12, wi 2, integration+cpp-gen 7) that only ever parsed via error recovery, in three mechanical classes: (1) brace-less namespace or bare sort missing `end` (toml_ser_test build_test_kb namespace; parse_test bare `sort ns.A`); (2) variable / abstract-sort inline description missing the grammar-required trailing `?` — `?x {< .. >}` must be `?x {< .. >}?` (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:778-786); (3) `?`-logic-vars in EXPRESSION positions — `let ?y = x` must be `let y = x`. PLUS a false-green canary: typing_test.rs typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads panics on parse errors and is green ONLY because they are swallowed; it must be made honest (depends on WI-302 plus the spec gaps). TASK: land collect_syntax_errors in parse(); fix all surfaced fixtures (mechanical, no logic change); make typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads honest; confirm full suite green. RELATED gaps that fire-error exposes: WI-301 (effect-set type args), WI-302 (computed type args), dotted-name instantiation functors (a reflect.anthill workaround was applied), and the carrier host-binding sugar (anthill-stl rewritten to the braced carrier-bindings form; anthill-cpp-gen/anthill/int.anthill was deliberately LEFT in the swallowed carrier-equals-string form because the braced form actually loads the carrier, which makes cpp-gen emit this provides block's artifact — a .rs path — as a C++ #include and breaks the header-compile tests; fix the cpp-gen carrier braced-form AND its bogus .rs artifact together). The carrier braced-form rewrite, list.anthill effect-set removal, reflect.anthill short-name fix, and the check_effects return type were landed separately this session as safe cleanups. ACCEPTANCE: parse() returns Err on a source containing an ERROR / MISSING node (e.g. a fact whose binding is `Effect = {}`); all in-tree .anthill files and test fixtures parse clean; typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads honest; cargo-test green. SCOPE: the parser is shared (Rust impl drives this); the fixture fixes are Rust-test-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T06:54:14Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-502", description: some(value: "Typed terms and rules — deep re-engineering of the Term/resolution representation so a term (and a rule's head/body) carries its type, enabling type-directed reasoning (esp. [simp] firing, proposal 043 §4) to READ the type rather than re-derive it. Motivation: WI-283 made [simp] firing type-directed but split it across two sites — the typer has typed occurrences (NodeOccurrence.inferred_type, WI-284) and fires requires-guarded rules via simp_fire_guard_holds (typing.rs); the resolver holds type-erased Terms and so skips them (equation_is_requires_guarded, resolve.rs). Converging the two (WI-292) needs the resolver to know each term's type. Re-deriving it structurally is REJECTED (a second notion of type that can drift from the typer); reusing NodeOccurrence is wrong (occurrence = source-code form, not the resolution carrier). So the type must live on the term/value carrier itself, populated ONCE at the typing boundary and carried through resolution without recomputation. Scope/design (TBD in this WI): where the type slot lives (Value at eval/value.rs is unboxed/zero-alloc — don't bloat scalars), how it is populated at the source->resolver boundary (incl. typing rule bodies / the simplify-prove entry, which are untyped today), and how it is preserved through De Bruijn opening + substitution (where inferred_type is currently dropped). Clients: WI-292 (resolver-side type-directed firing) and WI-283's typer firing become clients of one typed substrate. Acceptance: terms carry types accessible during resolution such that a requires-guarded [simp] rule can fire on the resolver/prove path by reading the carried type (no re-derivation); cargo-test green."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-292", description: some(value: "Resolver-side type-directed [simp] firing via a reflect min_sort builtin. Today the resolver (apply_eq_rules) holds type-erased terms with no min_sort, so it fires only type-independent identities and SKIPS requires-guarded rules (equation_is_requires_guarded, resolve.rs); the typer (simp_fire_guard_holds, typing.rs) does the type-directed firing on typed occurrences. To truly converge the two firing sites onto one engine (proposal 043 4.1/4.2 'one rewriter'), expose min_sort over typed occurrences to resolution: a reflect/expression-accepting builtin that, given a typed occurrence, yields its inferred sort head, so the resolver can evaluate the sort-level requires/satisfaction guard itself and fire requires-guarded rules where the carrier provides the spec (instead of skipping them). Needs: (a) resolution over typed occurrences (Value::Node carrying inferred_type), (b) min_sort wired as the expression-accepting builtin, (c) the implicit enclosing-sort requires materialized/checkable as a resolvable guard. Also fold in the matcher gap noted in WI-283 (positional rule LHS does not match a named-arg redex) if it blocks carrier-by-name firing. Acceptance: a requires-guarded [simp] rule fires correctly via the resolver/prove path where the carrier satisfies the spec; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-283", "WI-502"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-501", author: "user", content: "PREMISE CORRECTION + DELIVERED 2026-06-17. The filed premise (serializer DROPS none() fields -> backfill) was WRONG: a written none loads as Term::Ref(anthill.prelude.Option.none), term_to_value rendered it (and every nullary entity / enum variant Ref) to a bare SHORT-NAME string and stripped some(value:x)->x, while reload rebuilt strings as Const(String)/Fn — so a serialize->reload round-trip hash-cons-matched the source for almost NO field. User chose TYPE-DIRECTED DESERIALIZATION. FIX (both sides, term_ser.rs): SERIALIZE: term_to_value Ref(Option.none) -> JSON null so the entity-field loop DROPS it (absent encodes none); json_to_toml null -> LOUD Err (was silent null->empty-string, which corrupted none-inside-a-list via TOML). RELOAD: load_entry threads each field's DECLARED type (entity_field_types) into value_to_term_typed — Option[T=U]: null/absent -> none()=Ref(Option.none), present -> some(value: recurse U); List[T=U] -> build_cons_list of typed elems (canonical List.cons/nil, falls back to interned short names when prelude absent so schema-less loads don't panic like KB::build_list); entity/enum sort + string -> Ref(variant resolved <qualified-sort>.<name>); object {Variant:payload} -> typed ctor (recursing field types); nullary entities rebuilt as Ref (was Fn) to match loader. backfill_absent_fields: absent Option -> none(), absent required -> LOUD SerError::MissingField. option_none_ref/some_wrap build EXACT loader forms; type_head_and_inner extracts head sort + inner T. Old untyped fns replaced by _typed family; schema-less entities keep untyped path (ty=None) so prior behavior preserved. /code-review xhigh: acted on 3 in-scope findings (TOML null loud-error; reload null-in-non-Option loud-error; String-typed value no longer mis-resolved to a global entity Ref — declared type is authoritative). Residual NARROW gaps (nested-Option some(none()) collapse; serialize short-name dispatch asymmetry; foreign positional-payload never-match) filed as WI-503. TESTS (github_todo_test.rs): wi501_workitem_round_trips_through_store (full WorkItem some/none/nullary/empty-list hash-cons-matches source; VERIFIED fails if serialize none-drop reverted) + wi501_missing_required_field_errors_loudly. Full workspace green (56 binaries, 2024 tests). Rebased onto origin/main (WI-id collision: remote independently filed a different WI-502, so this residual ticket = WI-503).", at: "2026-06-17T07:37:10Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-501", description: some(value: "Persistence (term_ser): a serialize -> reload round-trip DROPS none()-valued Option fields, so the reloaded term has FEWER named args than the source-loaded form and silently fails to hash-cons / discrim-match it. Same hazard class as WI-498/WI-433 (silent never-match) but about field PRESENCE, not field ORDER. MECHANISM: the serialize side (term_to_value, persistence/term_ser.rs:601-604) emits a field only when its value != JSON null, i.e. it SKIPS none()-valued Option fields ('Skip none() values (Option absent)'). The deserialize side (load_entry, term_ser.rs ~290-313) builds named_args ONLY from the JSON keys PRESENT and then make_entity_term — it does NOT backfill the entity's declared-but-absent fields. By contrast the source loader's convert_term DOES expand partial named args (load.rs:5259-5279: fills missing declared fields, with fresh vars). So a source-loaded fact carries ALL declared fields (the persisted workitems.anthill writes 'context: none, generates: none, requires_capability: none' EXPLICITLY => 8 present args), but the same fact serialized->reloaded comes back with only the non-none fields (e.g. 5 args) => a structurally DIFFERENT Term::Fn => distinct TermId => never unifies with a pattern/fact loaded from source. Round-trip is also non-idempotent. PROVEN-ADJACENT: surfaced during WI-498 review; WI-498 fixed field-ORDER canonicalization, this is the orthogonal field-PRESENCE gap on the same boundary. DECISION NEEDED (pick one, loud-error principle in mind): (a) serialize emits none() explicitly (stop skipping null) so JSON carries every declared field — simplest, keeps the store self-describing, but bloats output with nones; (b) deserialize backfills absent DECLARED fields with none() (Option fields) at load_entry via entity_field_names, matching how source facts carry explicit none() and making round-trip idempotent + discrim-matchable — note the source loader fills missing with FRESH VARS which is wrong for a GROUND persisted fact, so don't blindly copy that; none() is the right ground fill for absent Option fields. Consider non-Option missing fields too (likely a loud error: a required field absent from the store is corruption, not a fresh var). ACCEPTANCE: an entity with a none()-valued Option field, serialized then reloaded, yields a term that hash-cons-matches the source-loaded form (and round-trip is idempotent); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T07:37:11Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-499", description: some(value: "Loader: positional-ctor desugar (WI-433) + partial-named-arg expansion are LOAD-ORDER-DEPENDENT — a forward-referenced entity silently skips both. ROOT CAUSE: the desugar (convert_term_with_expected ~load.rs) and the pre-existing partial-expansion (and the convert_query_term copy) gate on kb.entity_field_names(functor), but scan_definitions pass-1 registers only entity NAMES (add_exposed/define); the FIELD list is registered later in load_entity (register_entity_fields) during the source-order load pass. So a positional constructor whose entity is declared TEXTUALLY AFTER the referencing fact/rule (same namespace), or in a later-loaded file, sees entity_field_names=None at convert time -> the positional term stays positional and never unifies with the canonical named form (the exact WI-433 silent never-match, just reordered), AND the over-arity loud error is silently skipped. PROVEN via probe: rule r(?id):-WorkItem(id:?id,status:Verified(?)) + fact WorkItem(...Verified(at:...)) placed BEFORE sort Status{entity Verified(at:String)} resolves 0 (should be 1); reverse order -> 1. Common case (entities in a domain file loaded before rules/facts) works, which is why WI-433 tests pass. FIX: register entity field NAMES in scan_definitions pass-1 where entities are already iterated, so entity_field_names is available before ANY term conversion — makes BOTH the desugar and partial-expansion load-order-independent and lets the over-arity check fire loudly regardless of order (loud-error principle). Field TYPES can stay in load_entity. Watch scan idempotency (stdlib-bootstrapped + re-run). Spun out of WI-433 review. ACCEPTANCE: the forward-ref probe matches (or errors loudly on over-arity); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T07:55:45Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-500", description: some(value: "Eval/persistence: RUNTIME-built positional constructors are not canonicalized to named — the WI-433 never-match bug class on the non-loader path. WI-433 fixed only source-written terms (the loader). At runtime: finish_constructor (eval.rs) builds Value::Entity keeping a positional ctor (e.g. an op body evaluating Verified(\"2026-06-17\")) positional, and alloc_from_value (execute.rs, the Value->Term lowering used by the persist builtin) sorts named_args into field order but builds Term::Fn with pos_args VERBATIM (no positional->named desugar); assert_fact then stores+indexes that term positionally. So a runtime-built positional entity persisted and queried WITHIN THE SAME PROCESS never unifies with the canonical named pattern (e.g. all_deps_verified Verified(at:?)) — the heimdall WI-005 symptom on the runtime path. MITIGATED across a persist->reload cycle (printer emits positional source which the loader WI-433 desugar repairs) and by anthill-todo being per-process. NOTE: distinct from WI-498/WI-299 (those canonicalize NAMED-arg ORDER via make_entity_term; this is POSITIONAL->named desugar). match_constructor_pattern already handles positional sub-patterns at eval, so runtime PATTERN matching is fine — the gap is the persist/value->Term->discrim path. FIX: canonicalize positional->named (declaration order, fields-not-named) at the runtime constructor boundary (finish_constructor and/or alloc_from_value), reusing the loader rank-among-not-named rule (shared helper if practical). Spun out of WI-433 review. ACCEPTANCE: a runtime op-body Verified(\"x\") persisted then matched against Verified(at:?) in one process succeeds; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T08:34:33Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-110", author: "claude", content: "AUDIT COMPLETE — no test currently depends on tree-sitter permissive recovery; the root concern was already closed by WI-303 and the lone straggler (ho_bigint_induction_parses) is already fixed. METHODOLOGY + FINDINGS: (1) parse::parse (src/parse/mod.rs) is the SOLE tree-sitter entry point in anthill-core — grep-confirmed no other tree_sitter::Parser / Converter use in src or tests; the test common helpers (tests/common/mod.rs:95,98) and every per-test loader route through it, so there is NO bypass path. (2) It ALWAYS runs collect_syntax_errors, which descends the WHOLE CST (prunes clean subtrees via has_error(), reports each ERROR via is_error() and each MISSING via is_missing()) — NOT just top-level as the WI background described the OLD behavior. WI-303 (9d73fdc) made this change and swept every then-existing fixture. (3) PROBE-CONFIRMED the fix is robust for the exact WI-110 shape: feeding the old unparenthesised '-:' rule-body source (ERROR buried deep in the body) now returns Err('syntax error near ...'); '-:' inside a fn-term arg likewise Err. So any .is_ok()/.unwrap() parse test that PASSES is by construction free of embedded ERROR/MISSING nodes — a green suite IS the audit proof. (4) Full anthill-core suite green: 1706 passed, 0 failed, 3 ignored (wi237_diag dump by design; wi374 '?'-binding-slot feature gate; wi402 WI-391 lowering pending) — none are permissive-recovery false-greens. (5) WI-303's one #[ignore]d false-green, typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads, is now a LIVE genuinely-passing #[test] (WI-302/WI-306 landed; it parses clean). DELIVERABLE: added regression guard parse_fires_on_embedded_syntax_error (parse_test.rs) using the exact historical '-:'-in-rule-body shape, asserting parse() surfaces the DEEPLY-EMBEDDED ERROR — locks the contract so a future 'only check the root' regression can't silently reopen the gap. RESIDUAL (out of WI-110 scope): tree-sitter recovery that emits NO error node (a silent alternative parse) is undetectable by collect_syntax_errors — a semantic concern, distinct from this ticket's ERROR-node recovery (the ho_bigint case was an ERROR-node case, probe-confirmed).", at: "2026-06-17T09:54:48Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-110", description: some(value: "Audit anthill-core tests that may rely on tree-sitter's permissive error recovery. Background: ho_bigint_induction_parses (typing_test.rs) used a malformed source — '-:' inside a fn-term arg with no grammar rule for that position — and was passing only because tree-sitter embedded the ERROR node inside an fn_term and the Rust parse::parse only flags top-level ERROR nodes. WI-C1's '-:' rule-conclusion clause exposed the bug by promoting the ERROR to top-level. Sweep: grep for tests that call parse::parse with .is_ok() asserts but never check the resulting tree for embedded ERROR nodes; tighten parse::parse to surface embedded errors OR fix test sources to use grammar-supported shapes. Acceptance: identify and either fix or document each test that depends on permissive recovery."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T09:54:55Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-300", description: some(value: "Requirement goals in rule bodies (conditional-rule requirements). Today a realization requirement cannot be expressed as a rule-body goal: req_insertion::run (req_insertion.rs:41) weaves requirement forms (Expr::ApplyWithin / ConstructRequirement / RequirementAtSort / VarRef) ONLY into kb.op_bodies, never rule body_nodes. A 'requires(Eq[T])' written in a rule body (e.g. 'something(?x,?y) :- eq(?x,?y), requires(Eq[T])') parses — keywords are soft (grammar.js:23) — as an ordinary Expr::Apply{functor: requires, pos_args:[Eq[T]]} goal with NO requirement semantics: convert_rule_body (convert.rs:1647) has no special case, and at resolution it is just an undefined predicate that fails. Requirements today live only as: the standalone 'requires <Type>' decl -> SortRequiresInfo fact (load.rs:6004), and operation requires/ensures clauses -> OperationInfo reflect fact fields (load.rs:5850). SCOPE: design + implement rule-body requirement goals (conditional rules) — decide the surface syntax/semantics (likely a distinguished goal recognized in convert_rule_body or a type-directed weave), extend req_insertion (or an analog) to process rule body_nodes, and represent the woven form as occurrences consistent with the op-body *Within forms. Builds on the per-rule is_requires_resolved/mark_requires_resolved flags (mod.rs:456) which already exist but are not backed by body-level occurrence synthesis. Surfaced during WI-246 Phase 3c review."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-292"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-322", description: some(value: "collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs:2720) walks only for_each_child on the Expr arm — Globals living in Apply.type_args / ApplyWithin.type_args / Let.type_annotation (the TermId-typed Expr fields that WI-298 made the opener/closer/substitute walkers handle symmetrically) are NOT detected by the caller-var delay pre-check body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes (resolve.rs:2656). PROBLEM: when a builtin delays on a goal whose first positional arg resolves to a var, the pre-check collects unbound vars from that arg and asks 'is any of them a caller var?'. If the arg's structure puts a caller var inside a type_args / type_annotation TermId, the precheck misses it and the rule does NOT propagate delay even though a caller var is genuinely unbound. SYMMETRY: mirror collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered (node_occurrence.rs ~1188) which already handles this via collect_expr_termid_field_vars (node_occurrence.rs ~1215). SCOPE: extend the Expr arm to also walk Apply.type_args / ApplyWithin.type_args / Let.type_annotation, chasing each TermId via the existing collect_unbound_vars term walker (resolve.rs ~2620). LATENT today because builtin-delay first args are predicate applications without type args in the prelude; live once typer/simp populates type_args at a builtin's first-arg position. Code-review finding on WI-298 PR (98a9ea5). ACCEPTANCE: a delayed builtin whose first arg is f[T = ?caller_var](...) triggers rule delay (caller_var detected through the type_args TermId); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T13:11:36Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-378", author: "claude", content: "DECISION (with user, 2026-06-17): do NOT do the STEP 2 repr migration (type_args/type_annotation -> for_each_child occurrence-children). WI-378 is satisfied by gap-1 (delivered 2026-06-04). RATIONALE: gap-1 already eliminated the 4-way type-field lockstep -- map_value_type is the single \"rewrite a type Value\" def with close/open/subst as one-line delegates, collect_value_type its collect twin; nothing can drift over the type spine. The remaining migration would only collapse an already-single, tested side-walk (for_each_child + collect_expr_termid_field_vars -> collect_value_type) and drop 3 debug_asserts that are UNREACHABLE today (for_each_child does not yield type-field children). No live defect. COST that outweighs it: thread kb through the 4 for_each_child walker families OR push var-free ground type-args out of hash-consed Value::Term (losing dedup/O(1)-eq/sharing), plus a new (name,type) child repr that seed_op_type_args relies on, touching load/typer/eval/resolver/DeBruijn. The carrier rule does NOT require it (denoted-containment is the only hard floor; ground MAY stay Term per the CLAUDE.md representation note + types-need-not-be-hash-consed). TERM_CACHE finding (user-raised): cached_term (node_occurrence.rs:2244) memoizes a hash-consed TermId per occurrence, so a Value::Node yields its canonical/dedup'd term on demand -- the dual carrier (Value::Term vs Value::Node; TypeChild::Ground vs TypeChild::Node) is NOT a representational forcing function; no capability gap pushes the migration. IF uniformity is ever wanted (no current driver): the clean path is var-bearing type leaves as TypeChild::Node(Expr::Var) (walkable with NO kb), var-free ground stays Ground(TermId), consumers read the canonical term via the cache -- no hash-consing loss, no kb-threading. RESIDUAL: the lone latent gap (resolve-time delay-check over a Type-spine var, guarded by the WI-322 loud debug_assert in collect_unbound_vars_node) = WI-504; it does NOT depend on this migration. WI-504's WI-378 dependency removed.", at: "2026-06-17T14:35:16Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-378", description: some(value: "Unify rule var-collection (renumbered off origin's parallel WI-377/effect-row collision). Kill the 4-way lockstep over an Expr's embedded type-fields (Apply.type_args / ApplyWithin.type_args / Let.type_annotation, holding Values): collect/close/open/substitute each special-case them; close+open share carrier-agnostic close_value_type/open_value_type but COLLECT re-implemented a bespoke Term-only walk held in manual lockstep ('CRUCIAL: must mirror node_to_debruijn'). STEP 1 DELIVERED (a96a55f, behavior-preserving): collect_value_type/collect_type_args_vars/collect_option_value twins of close_*; collect_expr_termid_field_vars delegates -> structural mirror, not hand-maintained. STEP 2 (follow-on): wire gap 1 (WI-342-P3 Type-occurrence var-walk) so collect/close walk INTO a Type occ, then migrate type_args/type_annotation to occurrence-children -> one carrier-agnostic walk replaces the collect_vars_rec(term-head)/collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered(occ-body) pair; touches the typer + Expr repr; also unblocks denoted value rule heads (WI-373 gap 1). User-chosen 'both sequenced' 2026-06-04. Surfaced reviewing WI-373. Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T14:35:18Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-504", author: "claude", content: "Dependency on WI-378 removed (2026-06-17): WI-378's STEP 2 repr migration was DECLINED (see WI-378 feedback) and WI-378 delivered via gap-1. This residual does NOT require that migration. Narrow fix path: the resolve-time delay pre-check collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs) descends a Value::Node type-arg, but its catch-all arm cannot walk a Type/EffectExpr-kind spine (a TypeChild::Ground(Term::Var) needs kb to see the var, and that walker has no kb). Fix by threading kb into that descent, or by reusing collect_value_type (node_occurrence.rs, which already has kb and descends Type spines via collect_type_node_vars/collect_effect_node_vars) under a subst filter. Currently guarded by a loud debug_assert added in WI-322; latent (no builtin first-arg carries a var-bearing Type-kind Node type-arg today).", at: "2026-06-17T14:35:34Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-505", description: some(value: "Bundle the canonical stage0 domain into the anthill-todo CLI so it is version-locked with the bundled logic, instead of relying on each project's drift-prone anthill-todo/domain.anthill. PROBLEM (observed 2026-06-17): the CLI embeds its LOGIC (anthill_bundle.rs: store.anthill + main.anthill via include_str!) which references anthill.stage0 entities (WorkItem, WorkStatus.PreOpened, Tag, ...), but the ENTITY DEFINITIONS are loaded from the PROJECT's anthill-todo/domain.anthill (collect_anthill_files over the scanned project dir, main.rs:~403-415). The domain the bundled logic depends on is therefore owned per-project and NOT version-locked with the binary. When the grammar or domain changes (e.g. the parser dropped the multi-name `export` clause; the CLI added WorkStatus.PreOpened), every project whose domain.anthill predates the change silently breaks: a stale heimdall (/home/rssh/packages/lantr/heimdall/anthill-todo/domain.anthill) failed to parse on its `export` lines, which cascaded into a wall of `unresolved import anthill.stage0.WorkStatus/WorkItem/...` errors; fixed only by hand-syncing the project copy to the current standard domain. There are also TWO in-repo copies that can diverge: anthill-todo/domain.anthill (this tracker's) and examples/github-todo/domain.anthill (the one `init` writes via include_str! at main.rs:~284). FIX: add the canonical domain to the embedded bundle (anthill_bundle.rs, alongside store/main) so entity defs ship with the binary and cannot drift. Make the project's domain.anthill OPTIONAL: when the bundled domain is present, do NOT also load a project-local domain.anthill (avoid double-definition of anthill.stage0.WorkItem etc.) -- either skip it, or treat its presence as an explicit override with a staleness warning. Stop `init` from writing a domain.anthill that can later drift (write nothing, or a comment stub pointing at the bundled domain). De-duplicate the two in-repo copies into the single bundled source. CONSTRAINTS / GOTCHAS: (1) the synthetic `namespace anthill.stage0` wrap for bare workitems.anthill files (main.rs:~161-178) must still resolve against the bundled domain's scope; (2) existing projects that still ship a domain.anthill must keep working (skip-or-override, not hard error); (3) rules.anthill is a sibling per-project file with the same drift exposure (claimable/blocked/dep_satisfied workflow rules) -- decide whether to bundle it too or note it as a follow-up; (4) keep the crate's own anthill-todo/ self-hosting working (it scans its own dir per main.rs:~190). ACCEPTANCE: a project directory with NO domain.anthill (and one with a deliberately stale/old domain.anthill) loads and runs status/list/next against the bundled domain with no parse/unresolved-import errors; `init` produces a project that survives a future domain change without hand-editing; a regression test loads a domain-less project dir; cargo-test green."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-312", description: some(value: "WI-311 follow-up: field_access/path-node unification (the deferred 'one path node' part of WI-311). WI-311 (merged 7ada265) landed the APPLICATION merge (parameterized_type + instantiation_term -> one `application` node) and changed the bare-reference atom from $.identifier to $.name, but deliberately did NOT do the field_access restructure WI-311 listed as remaining work: 'make a.b ONE path node everywhere — route fn_term names, bare references, and ident-chain projections through the dotted path — and RESTRICT field_access to non-name receivers (?x.y, foo().y); the loader classifies projection-vs-qualified-vs-application'. Instead field_access was left unchanged (object is still $._atom_term; its prec(10) grabs the '.'), so p.x in TERM position parses as field_access(object: name, field: x) while a dotted name in TYPE position is a `name` node — i.e. a.b is NOT one node everywhere. This is FUNCTIONALLY COMPLETE (all WI-311 motivating cases p.x(?x)/g(a.b)/Foo.bar()/qualified-params parse and load; full workspace suite 1243 green) and the loader already classifies (field_access builtin defers + SymbolKind name resolution), so the restructure is NOT needed for correctness — it is purely the grammar-cleanliness payoff: make 'types are terms' uniform for projections/qualified-refs too, matching what the application merge already achieved for applications. TASK: restrict field_access object to non-name receivers (variable_term/paren_expr/fn_term/application/field_access); route bare and dotted ident paths through a single path node in _atom_term and fn_term-name; converter reconstructs projection-vs-qualified-vs-application from the path (the existing convert_term `name` arm already folds a multi-segment name into field_access builtins and convert_name handles application — extend so the field_access NODE is only ever a value-receiver). Corpus rebaseline. SCOPE: grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js) + converter (anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs); cargo green. PAYOFF: grammar cleanliness only, NOT new capability. RELATED: builds on WI-311 (merge 7ada265); the broader 'full type/term conversion' (tuple_type == tuple_literal, etc.) is a further step beyond this one. Also note WI-302's Modify[kb] entity-case (Entity names stay sort_ref, not denoted) is a separate WI-302 follow-up, not this."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-311"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-06-17T15:43:28Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-412", author: "user", content: "OBSOLETE / superseded (2026-06-17), closed with NO code change. (1) Target file rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs no longer exists: the two drifting embedded lists (anthill-cli + anthill-todo) were CONSOLIDATED into one source of truth, anthill-stl/src/stdlib.rs SOURCES, called by both binaries via anthill::stdlib::parse_embedded(). (2) The 7 namespaces flagged missing (kernel/kernel, logic/{minimal,classical,constructive}, realization/{rust_anthill,scala_caps,scala_std}) are ALL present now; anthill-stl/tests/stdlib_drift_test reconciles SOURCES vs the on-disk trees and FAILS LOUDLY on any add/remove (verified green 2026-06-17). (3) The proposed build.rs glob auto-collect (mirroring 841f321) was DELIBERATELY REVERTED: an alphabetical dir-walk loads derived algebra (algebra/lattice) before base types, hijacking +/compare dispatch into infinite recursion (stack-overflowed 'anthill-todo status'). The list is intentionally explicit + dependency-ordered; drift protection now comes from the drift test + include_str! compile-failure + a build-time assert!(!SOURCES.is_empty()), NOT from globbing. Implementing as written would reintroduce the stack overflow. No residual work.", at: "2026-06-17T16:12:31Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-412", description: some(value: "anthill-todo: migrate the HAND-MAINTAINED embedded stdlib list (rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs) to a build.rs AUTO-COLLECT, mirroring anthill-cli (commit 841f321). The list drifts: its header claims 'All .anthill files from stdlib/anthill/' but currently omits 7 on-disk namespaces (kernel/kernel, logic/{minimal,classical,constructive}, realization/{rust_anthill,scala_caps,scala_std}) — low-impact today (none imported by the embedded set) but a latent 'unresolved import at runtime, no compile-time signal' gap. Surfaced in WI-409 where 'combinators' had to be added by hand. Acceptance: anthill-todo embeds every stdlib/anthill/**.anthill via build.rs glob; do NOT hand-edit the generated file; anthill-todo tests green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-06-17T16:12:41Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-419", description: some(value: "entries_cover Strategy-1 requirement forwarding ignores same-unified-variable identity (LATENT, pre-existing; surfaced by WI-418 /code-review). build_dep_projection Strategy 1 (typing.rs ~4258) matches a callee requirement dep against a caller `requires` entry via entries_cover (~4296), then emits `var_ref(__req_<name>)` that forwards the caller's requirement to the callee at eval. entries_cover keys ONLY on (required_sort + per-binding compat) and ACCEPTS when either side is a type-param wildcard (is_type_param_value, ~4327-4329); it does NOT check that the dep's element is the SAME unified logical variable as the caller binding's element. HAZARD: a caller (sort/op) declaring TWO `requires` of the SAME spec sort over DISTINCT element params (e.g. `requires Eq[A], Eq[B]` with A != B) + an ABSTRACT cross-sort callee dep over (say) B: Strategy 1 `position`-matches the FIRST same-spec caller entry (Eq[A]) and forwards `__req` for A — the WRONG dictionary — instead of B's. Eval would then dispatch the callee's deferred spec op through the wrong impl. PRE-EXISTING: entries_cover/Strategy 1 are the live path for same-sort + WI-415 + WI-418; WI-418 only routes MORE abstract cross-sort calls through it. SOUND for every shape currently exercised (each spec sort has a SINGLE covering requirement), so no known code triggers it and no test fails today — this is defensive/correctness-hardening, likely hard to repro without a contrived 2-same-spec-requires sort. FIX DIRECTION: when both sides are type-param wildcards, disambiguate by the element's unification identity — verify the dep's element var resolves (via the call-site subst) to the SAME var as the caller binding's element, rather than accepting any same-spec entry; or thread enough call-site context into build_dep_projection to pick the correct slot when multiple same-spec requires exist. ACCEPTANCE: a 2-same-spec-requires repro (caller requires Eq[A],Eq[B]; cross-sort abstract call needing Eq on B) forwards B's __req not A's; suite green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-06-17T16:56:09Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-071", author: "user", content: "Already implemented incidentally by the WI-302/WI-375 sort_binding generalization: grammar sort_binding choice 2 is now the general _common_type_expr (grammar.js:136-139), convert_sort_binding handles all three spec forms (convert.rs:571-596), and type_expr_to_term maps positional bindings to declaration-order params via type_params_of_sort. Acceptance pinned by tests/include/wi071_positional_sort_binding_test.rs (3 tests, all green). Stdlib already relies on nested positional bracketed bindings (fact PersistentCollection[List[T], T]; Option[Pair[?A, LogicalStream[?A]]]). No remaining code work; delivered as tracker reconciliation.", at: "2026-06-17T18:18:13Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-071", description: some(value: "Grammar: add bare-Type positional SortBinding. Spec (kernel-language.md:481-483) declares three SortBinding forms: Name=Type (named), Type (positional), VariableTerm. The tree-sitter grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:121) only implements Name[=Type] and variable_term. This blocks bracketed-type positional bindings like Effect[Output[?]] or List[Option[Int]], which must be written in named form today (Effect[T = Output[?]]). Fix: extend sort_binding choice 2 from variable_term to a general _type, updating the converter to emit positional bindings. Update existing stdlib opportunistically. Acceptance: 'effects Output[Console]' works for bare names (already parses) AND nested like 'fact Effect[Output[?]]' parses and lowers correctly; existing uses unchanged."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T18:18:15Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-423", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED via option (a) — delocalize the 10 KERNEL_META_SORTS (Sort/Entity/Fact/Rule/Operation/Namespace/Requirement/Description/Constraint/Member) via define_qualified_only in register_prelude (load.rs), exactly mirroring WI-422's functor fix. Chose (a) over the deeper (b) resolve_in_scope_recursive prefer-nearer policy because the gating safety check came back clean: an Explore sweep confirmed NO .anthill source or Rust resolver resolves these names by scope — all reflection facts are emitted/queried via make_name_term()->intern() (a separate intern-map symbol, never scope-resolved), and none are declared in .anthill files. So delocalizing closes the leak with zero capability loss; (b)'s broad core-resolution blast radius is unwarranted. Repro confirmed pre-fix (bare 'Member' in a requires-bearing sort -> 'ambiguous symbol Member [Member, user.Member]') and clean post-fix. Regression test wi423_user_sort_shadowing_kernel_meta_sort_resolves (eval_test.rs) pins both halves: try_load_kb_with(src).is_ok() (no ambiguity) + eval run()->7 (user Member threads through). Full workspace suite 2040 green; /code-review (2 finders, correctness + test-validity/altitude/conventions) clean. This closes the WI-415..423 requires-dispatch cluster.", at: "2026-06-17T18:37:06Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-423", description: some(value: "Loader/resolution: close the requires-induced ambiguity leak for the remaining kernel GLOBAL LOCALS. WI-422 (65da79b) fixed the reported case — the loader-internal reflection FACT FUNCTORS (member/meta/SortAlias) were bare global `locals` via `define()`, and a `requires Spec[T]` link opens a scope path (sort -> spec -> prelude -> _global) that BYPASSES a namespace import alias (which short-circuits only along the ENCLOSING chain) and resurfaces the global symbol as a phantom rival to the user's alias -> `ambiguous symbol` -> hard `unknown functor` cascade. WI-422 moved those 3 functors to the new `SymbolTable::define_qualified_only` (registered in `by_qualified_name` ONLY, never any scope's `locals`). STRUCTURALLY-IDENTICAL LEAK STILL OPEN: `KERNEL_META_SORTS` (Sort/Entity/Fact/Rule/Operation/Namespace/Requirement/Description/Constraint/Member, load.rs ~1365) are STILL bare global `locals` via `define(name,name,Sort,global_raw)` in register_prelude (~1407). TRIGGER: a user sort whose name collides with a kernel meta-sort (e.g. a user `sort Member` or `sort Constraint`), selectively imported into a requires-bearing sort and referenced bare in a nested scope, hits the identical ambiguity. Lower-risk than WI-422 (PascalCase kernel names are rarely user-shadowed; the trigger is more contrived than the real, commonly-imported `List.member` operation case), which is why it was kept out of WI-422 scope. TWO CANDIDATE FIXES, pick one: (a) DELOCALIZE the meta-sorts too — same treatment via `define_qualified_only`. SAFE FOR FACT INDEXING (member facts are keyed by `make_name_term(\"Member\")`, which INTERNS into intern_map, a DIFFERENT symbol than the global-local Sort — verified during WI-422), but FIRST verify no legitimate bare scope-resolution of these meta-sort names exists in stdlib/reflect .anthill or in the Rust loader/typer (grep resolve_in_scope / resolve_name_in_global / remap_* for these names; WI-422 verified this only for the 3 functors, NOT the meta-sorts). If any meta-sort IS legitimately referenced bare as a type, option (a) is unsafe for that one. (b) THE DEEPER / higher-altitude fix — change `resolve_in_scope_recursive` (intern.rs ~300-352) from its current 'collect ALL matches across reachable parents, then flag >1 distinct as Ambiguous' policy to PREFER a nearer match (local/import-alias on the enclosing chain) over a symbol reached only via a `requires`-induced parent link to a farther/global scope. This closes the entire class (functors, meta-sorts, AND any future global symbol) at the resolution policy itself rather than per-symbol, but is a broader behavioral change to core name resolution — needs careful blast-radius review (every ambiguity-warning site) and may legitimately change which symbol wins in other multi-candidate cases. Both /code-review reviewers (WI-422 max-effort pass) independently flagged this; (b) is the principled close but (a) is the low-risk targeted one. ACCEPTANCE: a user sort named the same as a kernel meta-sort (e.g. `sort Member`), selectively imported into a requires-bearing sort and referenced bare in an op body, resolves to the USER's symbol without an ambiguity warning or unresolved cascade; a regression test pins it; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T18:37:08Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-435", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17. Confirmed REACHABLE first: isEmpty(put(empty(),\"a\",1)) on a Map died Err(UnknownOperation{name:\"iterator\"}) while the List control evaluated fine — Iterable combinators worked on entity-valued carriers (List=cons/nil entities) but died on handle-valued carriers (Value::Map) because runtime carrier classification (carrier_of in spec_call_runtime_carrier) only special-cased Value::Stream->LogicalStream and otherwise used value_functor (Entity/Term only). Fix (part A): generalized into runtime_carrier_sort(kb,&Value)->Option<Symbol> next to value_functor — EXHAUSTIVE over Value (no _ arm, so a new variant must declare its carrier), mapping Stream->LogicalStream, Map->Map, Cell->Cell, Closure/OpRef->Function, Int->Int64/Str->String/Bool->Bool/Float->Float/BigInt->BigInt; Entity/Term keep the constructor_parent_sort path byte-identical. Part B (receiver-slot gating) is CLOSED AS A CONSEQUENCE: pre-fix a handle RECEIVER returned None and was SKIPPED by the first-passing carrier_param_receiver_for_values loop, letting a non-receiver carrier-typed arg steal dispatch; now the receiver classifies and wins, matching the typer's carrier_param_receiver (both loops share provision_binds_param_to_carrier — verified no divergence; no current stdlib op has 2+ carrier-typed params with differing carriers in a well-typed program). Regression test wi435_iterable_op_on_map_handle_value_dispatches (eval_test.rs): Map isEmpty dispatches (false) + List control. Suite 2041 green; /code-review (2 finders: dispatch-behavioral-change incl scalar safety + part-B/test-validity) clean — scalar mapping is additive (sort_ops_lookup filters the inherited spec op; real scalar eq dispatches via builtins, unchanged).", at: "2026-06-17T21:58:36Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-435", description: some(value: "Eval: RUNTIME CARRIER CLASSIFICATION for handle values in dynamic spec-op dispatch -- generalize the WI-009 Value::Stream->LogicalStream patch (eval.rs carrier_of) into one runtime_carrier_sort(kb, &Value) -> Option<Symbol> beside value_functor, mapping EVERY runtime handle to its prelude sort: Stream->LogicalStream (done), Map(MapHandle)->Map, Cell->Cell, Closure/OpRef->Function, scalars (Int->Int64, Str->String, Bool->Bool) -- so a body-less spec op receiving any of these dispatches dynamically instead of dying UnknownOperation (the exact WI-385-widening regression class that silently broke 'next' for streams; a spec op consuming a Map value dies the same way today). Keep the mapping next to Value::type_name() so a new Value variant must declare its carrier. ALSO from review: in the WI-424 carrier-param fallback the FIRST passing param wins -- a stream in a NON-receiver slot of a multi-C-typed-param spec op can steal dispatch from the intended receiver; when generalizing, gate carrier classification to the receiver-classified index (mirror the typer's receiver_carrier exactly)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T21:58:38Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-438", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-17. Reflect readers ignored the stored per-target Description index. Confirmed REACHABLE: KB.descriptions(Beta) returned indices [8,9] (global enumerate over ALL Description facts, POLLUTED by the stdlib's own {< >} blocks) instead of the stored per-target [0,1]. Fix (3 touchpoints): (1) reflect/mod.rs DescriptionInfo gains pub index: i64 (the hand-written struct was out of sync with reflect.anthill's declared index: Int64 — the CODEGEN'd reflect.rs already had it, but it's NOT include!'d, only a verification artifact); (2) builtins.rs kb_descriptions drops the global enumerate() counter and reads pos[2] (Description(target,text,index), emit_desc_fact); (3) bridge.rs descriptions() reads pos[2] + populates index (was dropping it). Both guards tightened pos.len()<2 -> <3 (index now required; emit_desc_fact is the sole producer, always 3-arg Int — verified, parse_test asserts exactly 3 args). Regression test kb_descriptions_index_is_per_target_not_global (builtins.rs): Alpha-before-Beta forces a non-[0,1] global index; verified FAILS pre-fix ([8,9]) / PASSES post-fix ([0,1]). Full workspace suite 2042 green; /code-review (2 finders: correctness/removed-behavior incl. guard+borrow-safety + test-validity/conventions/altitude) clean. Surfaced by the bff0e8e review; spec = kernel-language.md §4.1 + proposal 009 Correction.", at: "2026-06-17T22:19:11Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-438", description: some(value: "kb_descriptions index fix: reflect readers ignore the stored Description fact index (Description(target, text, index), 0-based per-target — kb/load.rs emit_desc_fact). anthill-stl/src/reflect/builtins.rs kb_descriptions fills DescriptionInfo.index with a GLOBAL enumeration index over all Description facts — non-contiguous/wrong for target-filtered queries ([3,7] instead of stored [0,1]); bridge.rs descriptions() drops the index entirely though reflect.anthill DescriptionInfo declares index: Int64. Fix: read pos[2] in both readers; add index field to the Rust-side DescriptionInfo struct (reflect/mod.rs). Surfaced by the bff0e8e code review; spec shape documented in kernel-language.md §4.1 + proposal 009 Correction."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-17T22:19:12Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-364", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18 (claude). First concrete MutableCollection carrier = stdlib/anthill/prelude/mutable_list.anthill: nominal 'sort MutableList { entity mutableList(rep: Cell[V=List[T]]) }' providing MutableCollection + Iterable (E={} written), registered in anthill-stl/src/stdlib.rs after cell. Full lifecycle test (new -> insert -> walk via iterator -> clear, + non-aliasing) at tests/include/wi364_mutable_list_test.rs (3 green); full anthill-core 741 green; drift + /code-review clean (removed an unused Int64 import). KEY: the feared runtime substrate was ALREADY DONE (Value::Cell + cell_arena.rs arena, default_modify_handler, WI-314 region masking, WI-368 effect grounding) -- WI-364 reduced to a stdlib carrier + test, NO compiler change. DESIGN: carrier must be a NOMINAL sort (a provision's carrier = its ENCLOSING sort via sort_ref_functor, typing.rs:7841; a bare Cell[List[T]] structural carrier does NOT work). Modify[c] rides Cell's handler; the bodies PATTERN-MATCH the wrapper to bind the inner cell (WI-219 local-elision, the WorkItemStore idiom) -- NOT c.rep field-projection (that hits the WI-506 gap). Idiomatic call forms sidestep 3 discovered dispatch/effect gaps, each filed as a NON-BLOCKING follow-up: WI-506 (declared Modify[c] should cover incurred Modify[c.field] -- field-access propagation, the user-flagged one; only pattern-bound elision works today), WI-507 (bare clear(c) typechecks but eval ArityMismatch 2-got-1 for a carrier-only mutating spec op; dot c.clear() works), WI-508 (nullary MutableCollection.new() can't pin Element/E from expected return type; carrier's own MutableList.new() works). REF: docs/proposals/library/002 Phase 4; proposal 037/027.1; docs/design/cell-runtime.md.", at: "2026-06-18T06:29:07Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-364", description: some(value: "Proposal docs/proposals/library/002-iteration-collection.md Phase 4 -- the first CONCRETE mutable carrier. Phases 1-3 have landed (Iterable declared; Collection renamed PersistentCollection; MutableCollection declared) so the read/persistent half is applied; this is the mutable half. A concrete mutable sequence (a MutableList, or MutableMap from 001-map with Element = Pair[K,V]) provides fact MutableCollection[...] + fact Iterable[...]; wire the arena. MutableCollection.new() carries Modify[result]; insert/clear carry Modify[c] -- mutable_collection.anthill already DECLARES these (they parse); what is missing is the carrier + the runtime. NEEDS real compiler + interpreter work: Modify[result]/Modify[c] effect TRACKING at runtime (proposals 027.1 allocator effects, 037 state model) + a mutable arena resource; running a walk end-to-end additionally uses runtime provider dispatch (WI-281, delivered). The effect-tracking + arena substrate has no standalone WI yet -- if it proves large it should be extracted as a prerequisite WI rather than bundled here. ACCEPTANCE: a full mutable lifecycle (new -> insert -> walk via iterator -> clear) under effect tracking; the carrier provides MutableCollection + Iterable and (once WI-363 lands) passes op-provision completeness. REF: stdlib/anthill/prelude/mutable_collection.anthill; proposals 027.1, 037; docs/proposals/library/002 Phase 4. DEPENDS WI-362 (Iterable/Stream complete -- the mutable carrier iterator returns a Stream)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-362", "WI-368"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T06:29:09Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-364", author: "user", content: "CARRIER SWAPPED 2026-06-18 (2500223, user feedback): MutableList -> MutableStack (a stack is more interesting for stdlib -- pop/top exercise read+mutate, not just append). stdlib/anthill/prelude/mutable_stack.anthill: nominal 'mutableStack(rep: Cell[V=List[T]])' (head=top) providing MutableCollection + Iterable; API new/push/pop(Option,LIFO)/top(read)/iterator + insert(delegates to push)/clear + Iterable size/foldLeft. Test = tests/include/wi364_mutable_stack_test.rs (4 green: push/pop LIFO lifecycle, new->insert->walk->clear collection acceptance with the Bool 'was new' witness, non-aliasing). mutable_list.anthill + its test REMOVED. The 3 follow-up gaps (WI-506/507/508) are carrier-agnostic and apply identically; their illustrative MutableList/MutableList.new() references now read MutableStack/MutableStack.new() (trip-wire = wi364_mutable_stack_test.rs). Full anthill-core 741 + drift green.", at: "2026-06-18T06:53:57Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-506", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18 (claude). Typer fix in kb/typing.rs (+38): at a call site, a Modify on a FIELD-PROJECTION argument (Cell.set(c.rep, ..)) is re-keyed to the projection's HEAD parameter via stable_receiver_path, so a declared Modify[c] covers the incurred Modify[c.rep] (proposal 037 'covers everything reachable from s'). EFFECTS-ONLY (new param_to_arg_head map merged into the effect re-key; return-type re-key via param_to_arg_sym untouched -- a head can't represent .rep). Maps to the ACTUAL arg head SYMBOL (not by name), so soundness holds: Modify[a] still does NOT cover Modify[b.rep] (negative test). Test wi506_modify_field_coverage_test.rs (3: field-proj trip-wire + pattern-bound regression + cross-param soundness); full anthill-core green; /code-review clean (6/6 points, soundness trace-verified). KEY ROOT CAUSE (corrected mid-impl): the place is ALREADY coarsened to head before reaching the boundary, but the projection-arg path never re-keyed the callee Modify-param to the arg head (direct-arg VarRefs do via param_to_arg_sym; projections yield no single sym so were skipped). A first attempt canonicalizing at op_boundary_effects by param NAME passed the test only by COINCIDENCE (Cell.set's param and the test op's param were both 'c') and broke MutableStack (param 's' != Cell.set's 'c') -- the real fix is the call-site arg head re-key. DISCOVERED+filed WI-509: simplifying the MutableStack carrier to field-projection bodies (now typechecking thanks to WI-506) exposes a SEPARATE field-access typing fragility (field_access expected Symbol got String) that perturbs unrelated parse_tests::typing_test fixtures -- WI-506 fix is innocent (isolated by revert). So MutableStack stays pattern-match; WI-506 acceptance met by the typer fix + wi506 fixture. Pre-existing (not a regression): a let-aliased projection head (let x=c; Cell.set(x.rep)) re-keys to Modify[x], same as the direct-arg VarRef path -- no new asymmetry. REF: kb/typing.rs param_to_arg_sym/param_to_arg_head + stable_receiver_path:11726 + declared-effects equality:19717; proposal 037; WI-219 (pattern-bound elision alt); WI-509 (follow-up).", at: "2026-06-18T07:31:03Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-506", description: some(value: "Typer: a declared Modify[c] should COVER an incurred Modify[c.field] (field-access projection) -- proposal 037 §'Effect-row convention' transitivity ('Modify[s] covers everything reachable from s'). Today ONLY the pattern-bound-local path works: WI-219 elides Modify[r] when r is MATCH-bound (external_effects local-resource drop) -- this is how store.anthill and the WI-364 MutableList carrier typecheck (both match the wrapper/state to bind the inner cell). The FIELD-PROJECTION form does NOT: a body Cell.set(c.rep, ...) incurs Modify[c.rep], which op_boundary_effects (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/region.rs:286, the '_' external-keep arm) keeps VERBATIM; the declared-effects check (kb/typing.rs:19663-19694, views_structurally_equal) then compares Modify[c.rep] vs declared Modify[c] -> structurally unequal -> 'undeclared effect: Modify[T=c]' (BOTH sides DISPLAY as Modify[T=c]; the .rep is hidden by the renderer, so the error looks self-contradictory). Surfaced by WI-364 (first mutable carrier): the carrier's insert/clear had to PATTERN-MATCH the wrapper instead of c.rep-projecting. FIX DIRECTION: root a Modify[place] to its place HEAD parameter for boundary + coverage -- receiver_path_head_sym (kb/typing.rs:11778) already extracts s.f.M->s; in op_boundary_effects' Param/'_' arm (or the declared-effects coverage at typing.rs:19684) treat a declared Modify[head] as COVERING an incurred Modify[head.path]. SOUND: mutating a sub-part of c is a mutation of c (037), and the change never UNDER-declares. ACCEPTANCE: an op 'insert(c: Wrap, ..) effects Modify[c] = let _ = Cell.set(c.rep, ..); ..' (field-projection, NO pattern match) typechecks; the pattern-bound form still works; wi219_modify_transitivity + full anthill-core green. REF: region.rs op_boundary_effects + :286; typing.rs:19663-19694 + views_structurally_equal; typing.rs:11778 receiver_path_head_sym; proposal 037 §'Effect-row convention'; WI-219 pattern-bound elision. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T07:31:04Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-507", author: "user", content: "Root cause was TWO distinct bugs behind 'carrier-only clear(c) fails, insert(c,x) works': (1) ABSTRACT requires-threaded path: match_candidate_against_goal (kb/typing.rs) rejected a carrier-only call because the unpinned sibling spec param (Element) arrived as nominal Ref(Sort.Element) and clashed with the impl param T once the concrete carrier pinned it; fix = a type-param wildcard on the per-call side matches an already-bound impl param without constraining it (same leniency the parametric arm + entries_cover already apply). (2) CONCRETE path (the ticket's literal case + flaky 'expected 2 got 1'/'expected 1 got 2'): resolve_cache key omitted op_short_sym but the cached DispatchOutcome resolves the impl op via sort_ops_lookup(impl_sort, op_short_sym), so clear(s)/insert(s,x) on the same carrier shared a goal and poisoned each other's entry (HashMap-order dependent); fix = add op_short_sym to the resolve_cache key (kb/mod.rs + kb/typing.rs). Regression test: wi507_carrier_only_dispatch_test (concrete + abstract carrier-only clear + insert guard). WI-364's wipe switched from the s.clear() dot workaround to bare clear(s). Full workspace green + stable across repeated runs; /code-review (3 adversarial agents) found no defects.", at: "2026-06-18T08:32:23Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-507", description: some(value: "Eval: a BARE-call value-directed spec-op dispatch of a CARRIER-ONLY MUTATING op (MutableCollection.clear(c) -- carrier C is the sole param, returns Unit, effects Modify[c]) TYPECHECKS but FAILS at eval with ArityMismatch{op:'operation call', expected:2, got:1}: the resolved/rewritten op expects 2 args (a threaded requirement dict -- MutableCollection requires Iterable + Modifiable) but eval passes only the receiver. The DOT form 'c.clear()' dispatches CORRECTLY (works end-to-end). Surfaced by WI-364: 'wipe(c) = clear(c)' failed at eval; 'wipe(c) = c.clear()' passed -- so the WI-364 lifecycle test uses the dot form for clear. This is a typer-ACCEPTS-but-eval-FAILS mismatch (latent): the natural bare-call form should eval like the dot form. Contrast: 'insert(c, elem)' (carrier + a VALUE arg, same requires) bare-calls fine at eval; the carrier-only 'clear(c)' does not -- so the bug is specific to a bare value-directed call whose only arg is the carrier. INVESTIGATE the requires-dispatch dict-threading rewrite (kb/req_insertion.rs + dispatch_rewrites, the WI-415..423 concrete-applywithin runtime path) for a bare value-directed call vs the DotApply path -- the dict-arg the typer inserts for the bare call is not supplied at eval (or the impl MutableList.clear is 1-arg and the rewrite mis-threads). ACCEPTANCE: 'operation wipe(c: MutableList[T=Int64]) -> Unit effects Modify[c] = clear(c)' (bare) evaluates identically to the dot form (clears in place); full anthill-core green. REF: WI-364 wi364_mutable_list_test (uses c.clear() workaround); kb/req_insertion.rs; WI-415..423 requires-dispatch cluster. Rust-only (eval/dispatch)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T08:32:36Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-508", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED. A nullary spec op (new() -> C, carrier only in result) got no carrier from value args -> value-directed dispatch returned NoCandidates -> WI-325 abstract-binding check fired. FIX (kb/typing.rs): in check_apply_iter's spec-op dispatch, when outcome==NoCandidates AND the op is nullary (op.params.is_empty()), remap via new resolve_nullary_result_carrier: (a) expected RETURN TYPE names a concrete carrier -> PinNow to its override; (b) no carrier pinned + exactly ONE provider -> use it (information hiding, per user design choice); (c) no pin + 2+ providers -> loud DispatchAmbiguous. requires-covered generic consumers keep the existing Deferred/dict-threaded path. Helpers: impl_sorts_providing_spec (indexed SortProvidesInfo walk, distinct carriers), nullary_carrier_impl_op (carrier override gated on impl_parent_of_op(impl_op) having NO requires so PinNow is safe). Design (user-decided): providers queried fast from KB; unique->info-hiding, 2+->loud error. NOT WI-508: the concrete carrier's own MutableStack.new() element T is ordinary inference (let x = MutableStack.new() valid, T monomorphic, pinned by use). Tests: wi508_nullary_carrier_dispatch_test (abstract new from return type + Maker a/b/c model w/ 2nd unpinned param so case (a) routes through the helper + concrete element-inference guards); WI-364 fresh() switched MutableStack.new()->abstract new(). /code-review (3 agents): fixed 1 PLAUSIBLE latent bug (requires-check keyed on impl_parent_of_op not carrier, for inherited defaulted ops) + test fidelity + unused import. Full workspace green.", at: "2026-06-18T09:28:11Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-508", description: some(value: "Typer/dispatch: a NULLARY spec-op 'new() -> C' (MutableCollection.new -- carrier C only in the RESULT, zero params) does NOT resolve its carrier/Element/E from the EXPECTED RETURN TYPE at a concrete call site. 'fresh() -> MutableList[T=Int64] = new()' errors: 'MutableCollection.new.requires: missing requires MutableCollection[Element=.., E=..]' (the WI-325 abstract-binding check fires because MutableCollection has a provider). Even explicit 'new[C = MutableList[T=Int64]]()' does NOT propagate C to Element/E (the provision MutableCollection[C=MutableList[T], Element=T, E={}] ties them, but the nullary dispatch doesn't derive Element/E from a given C). Workaround in WI-364: call the carrier's OWN concrete 'MutableList.new()' constructor (a generic consumer parameterized over MutableCollection still can't). This is the carrier-only-in-RESULT op dispatch: WI-431 A2 (CpsMonad.pure / zero()->T) delivered the DICT-THREADED eval + value-directed paths, but the TYPER-side pin from the EXPECTED RESULT TYPE at a concrete nullary call site is missing. FIX DIRECTION: when a nullary (or carrier-only-in-result) spec op is called where the expected type is concrete and its sort PROVIDES the spec, bind C from the expected type and DERIVE Element/E via the provision's carrier-derivation (reuse the WI-431 binding), then PinNow. ACCEPTANCE: 'fresh() -> MutableList[T=Int64] = new()' (abstract MutableCollection.new, no explicit type args) typechecks AND evals to a fresh empty MutableList; full anthill-core green. REF: WI-364 (uses MutableList.new() workaround); kb/typing.rs:7278 spec_warrants_abstract_check + WI-325 MissingRequiresForSpecOp; WI-431 instance-facts A2 carrier-only-in-result; carrier-is-dispatch-artifact. Rust-only (typer)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T09:28:14Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-509", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED. Root cause: NOT shared/global state and NOT load order. The typer's ?x.field -> field_access(?x, \"field\") rewrite (DotApply INC-1b) produces a node that does NOT round-trip a RE-type-check: re-typing the stored field_access Apply (a) types it as the generic reflect op field_access(object,field:Symbol)->Term (losing the field type; and the Const(String) name fails field:Symbol), and (b) the WI-506 effect re-key loses the projection head (stable_receiver_path only handled DotApply, not the rewritten field_access Apply). The asymmetry parse_tests-vs-wi_tests: wi_tests does ONE load pass (synthesis path, never re-typed); parse_tests typing_test fixtures re-type-check (type_check_stdlib_no_spurious_errors does an explicit 2nd type_check_sorts over all stdlib sorts; type_check_correct_fact_no_errors's snippet sort_terms exclude stdlib sorts -> mutable_stack.clear falls into the free-op sweep). FIX (kb/typing.rs): make the rewrite IDEMPOTENT under re-type. (1) field_access_projection_type: when check_apply_iter sees field_access(receiver, Const(String)) with a resolvable receiver sort+field, return the FIELD's type (mirrors INC-1b) instead of the generic op; guarded on named_args.is_empty() (review). (2) stable_receiver_path: handle the field_access Apply form (recurse receiver + append interned field name) so the WI-506 effect re-key keeps the head after re-type; signature gained &mut kb for interning. mutable_stack.anthill converted FULLY to field-projection (push/pop/top/iterator/clear) — the acceptance demonstration (carriers can now use s.rep). Regression test wi509_field_projection_body_roundtrips_retype (field-projection carrier + 2nd type_check_sorts(&[]) free-op re-check; verified FAILS without the fix). /code-review (3 agents): all risks REFUTED except the named_args guard (both agents, fixed) + a stale wi364 comment (fixed) + gratuitous clones (removed). Bonus: WI-509 incidentally fixes a previously-broken field-path let-alias. Full workspace green. Lossy TypeError->LoadError remapping (to_load_error flattens context+Value to strings) noted as a separate debuggability cleanup.", at: "2026-06-18T10:36:21Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-509", description: some(value: "A field-PROJECTION operation body in the LOADED stdlib (e.g. a mutable carrier using 'Cell.set(s.rep, ..)' / 'Cell.get(s.rep)' instead of a 'match s case wrap(r)' pattern-match) triggers spurious 'TypeMismatch { entity_name: field_access, field_name: field, expected_type: Symbol, actual_type: String }' errors in OTHER code's field accesses -- observed in parse_tests::typing_test fixtures (test.* snippets) but NOT in wi_tests (e.g. wi364 loads the same carrier clean). Discovered in WI-506: after the typer fix made field-projection mutating ops typecheck, simplifying stdlib/anthill/prelude/mutable_stack.anthill from pattern-match to 's.rep' projection bodies made parse_tests fail ~30 typing_test cases with the above field_access error, while wi364 (wi_tests) stayed green. The WI-506 typer fix itself is INNOCENT (reverting only typing.rs left the failures; reverting only mutable_stack.anthill to pattern-match cleared them) -- the trigger is the field-projection op body in the loaded set. SMELLS like a field-access field-name representation issue (Symbol vs Const(String); cf. WI-490/WI-280 field_name_from_node accepting Const(String) as the canonical post-typer field name) crossed with parse_tests::typing_test global/kb state shared across tests (a load leaves a field name interned as a String that later field_access typing rejects). CONSEQUENCE: mutable carriers must keep the pattern-match idiom (bind the inner cell via 'match', WI-219) rather than field-projection, even though WI-506 now makes field-projection typecheck in isolation -- so the MutableStack carrier was kept pattern-match. REPRO: edit mutable_stack.anthill bodies to project s.rep (drop the 'match s case mutableStack(r)'), build, run parse_tests -- ~30 typing_test failures with field_access Symbol-vs-String. INVESTIGATE: the field_access typer node's field-name carrier (Symbol vs String) + parse_tests::typing_test test isolation / whether a prior stdlib load mutates shared state. ACCEPTANCE: field-projection mutating op bodies can live in stdlib without perturbing unrelated field_access typing; mutable_stack.anthill (or a probe carrier) can use s.rep bodies; parse_tests + wi_tests + full anthill-core green. REF: WI-506; rustland/anthill-core/tests/include/typing_test.rs (via parse_tests + wi_tests); field_access TypeMismatch in kb/typing.rs; WI-490/WI-280 field-name carrier. Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T10:36:25Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-510", description: some(value: "Diagnostics: the TypeError -> LoadError remapping (TypeError::to_load_error, kb/typing.rs ~351 for TypeMismatch and ~487 for Other) is LOSSY and hinders debugging. It flattens the structured TypeErrorContext (EntityField{entity,field} / OperationArgument{op,param} / LetBinding / ... ) and the Value-typed expected/actual into plain display STRINGS (LoadError::TypeMismatch{entity_name:String, field_name:String, expected_type:String, actual_type:String}), and DROPS the variant identity and the CONSTRUCTION SITE. Consequence (hit hard in WI-509): two structurally-different errors render identically (e.g. an EntityField field-arg check and an OperationArgument arg check both surface as 'entity_name=field_access, field_name=field'), and a backtrace captured AT THE CONVERSION reveals nothing because the TypeError is built, pushed into an errors Vec, and remapped later in bulk (type_check_sorts ~18799) -- so you must instrument at CONSTRUCTION, not conversion, to find where an error originates. INVESTIGATE/OPTIONS: (a) carry the originating source location / a lightweight construction marker (or a captured backtrace under a debug cfg/env) on TypeError so the conversion can attribute it; (b) keep LoadError structured (preserve the TypeErrorContext variant + the Value expected/actual) rather than pre-stringifying, stringify only at final render; (c) at minimum, include the TypeError variant name + a distinguishing tag in the rendered message so identical-looking errors are disambiguable. ACCEPTANCE: a field_access (or any) TypeMismatch can be traced to its construction site without hand-instrumenting each candidate; the rendered diagnostic distinguishes EntityField vs OperationArgument origins; full anthill-core green. REF: WI-509 (debugging cost); kb/typing.rs to_load_error + TypeErrorContext::entity_name/field_name; LoadError::TypeMismatch. Rust-only (diagnostics, no semantic change)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-160", description: some(value: "anthill-todo CLI: track build version. Add a `version` subcommand printing semver + git SHA + build date, and a `--version` flag accepted at any subcommand position. Bake the metadata at build time via build.rs (env var ANTHILL_TODO_VERSION = workspace Cargo version; ANTHILL_TODO_SHA = `git rev-parse --short HEAD`; ANTHILL_TODO_BUILD = ISO-8601 UTC). Surface the same string in `--help` footer. Motivation: today there is no way to tell which build of `anthill-todo` is on PATH; a stale `~/.cargo/bin/anthill-todo` (pre-WI-085 grammar fix) emitted spurious parse warnings against the on-disk workitems file and the diagnosis required diffing binary mtimes. Generalises beyond anthill-todo: every CLI built from this workspace (`anthill`, `anthill-todo`, future tools) should embed the same version stamp, ideally via a small shared crate. Acceptance: cargo test green; `anthill-todo --version` prints a non-empty string; `anthill-todo version` matches; CI/regression test asserts the embedded SHA matches `git rev-parse --short HEAD` at build time."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T11:19:36Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-511", author: "claude", content: "SCOPE = the eliminate-the-dual-representation ticket (WI-436 design discussion 2026-06-18); the eq/neq framing is one symptom. TWO INDEPENDENT AXES, both only BRIDGED at the view layer by WI-436, not eliminated. AXIS 1 (Term repr: Ref(c) vs Fn{c}) -- eliminate at the producer: kb.alloc canonicalizes Term::Fn{c,[],[]} to Term::Ref(c) when is_constructor_symbol(c), giving ONE stored TermId. Entity-identity coordinated switch (key on the canonical Ref(c), flipped together): register_entity_of (mod.rs:1478 Term::Fn extraction) + constructor_parent_sort (mod.rs:1500) + is_entity_of (works once keys agree); chicken-and-egg = the identity is built BEFORE c is registered, so build/register it as Ref(c) explicitly. Then the ~3 raw-Term::Fn readers that BYPASS head() (so the view canon does not reach them) each need a Term::Ref arm OR migrate to TermView/head() (the WI-348 boundary migration, cleaner): effect-row walker (typing.rs:11739, match kb.get_term -> Term::Fn empty_row/present/merge), unwrap_list_spine (print.rs:470, nil), eval/pattern.rs:196 (Value::Term(Fn) constructor arm). PAYOFF: once storage is uniform, functor_view_head (the WI-436 view bridge) is DELETED; only the functor_sym readers stay (empty_row is genuinely Ref then) = net LESS code. AXIS 2 (Value carrier: Value::Entity{c} vs Value::Term(Ref(c))) -- this is the eq/neq + SetLiteral carrier-blindness. FIX = make Value::structural_eq carrier-AWARE (route through head()/views_structurally_equal), exactly as eval/pattern.rs ALREADY bridges Entity+Term for matching. Do NOT change the Entity carrier itself -- that would break the Entity-discriminator dispatch (carrier_of / value-directed sort lookup reads Value::Entity.functor DIRECTLY: execute.rs:212/372, subst.rs:373, builtins.rs). CAUTION: views_structurally_equal differs from structural_eq on var/rigid/closure handling -- verify no regression for non-constructor values. NOTE: Entity-discriminator search is UNAFFECTED by either axis (discrim tree is head-based and symmetric; Entity.functor extraction is direct) -- verified, full suite incl github_todo green under WI-436.", at: "2026-06-18T13:00:13Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-436", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18 (5e98878; full workspace 2070 passed / 0 failed; /code-review xhigh, 3 reviewers, 1 finding fixed in-pass, 0 new bugs). Identifies Ref(c) === nullary Fn{c} for CONSTRUCTORS at the VIEW/matching layer (a bridge; single-storage ELIMINATION = WI-511). MECHANISM: TermView::head() canonicalizes a 0-ary registered constructor to ViewHead::Ref(c) across all 5 carrier head-sites (Term::Fn x2, Expr::Apply, Expr::Constructor, Value::Entity) via new functor_view_head, gated on is_constructor_symbol. SOUND + kind-isolated: ops are Value::OpRef (never Term::Ref), sorts/params are not constructors, so the WI-391 Ref=wildcard / Fn=concrete TYPE-dispatch distinction is untouched. THE HARD PART = the meta-world uses 0-ary constructors too (empty_row under EffectExpression, Nothing under TypeExtractor) decomposed STRUCTURALLY via head() -- a naive all-constructors view-flip broke 448 tests. Fix: new ViewHead::functor_sym() reads the symbol off EITHER Ref or Functor, routed through the 4 readers that key on a constructor symbol: resolved_functor_name, explode_incurred_effect_row, value_is_bare_effect_expr, and type_head (restructured to classify by functor SYMBOL first so Nothing is not mis-read as a bare SortRef; Nothing is the ONLY 0-ary TypeExtractor variant). REVIEW FIX (reviewer 1): rules_by_functor indexing (mod.rs assert ~874 + retract ~1414) also routes through functor_sym so a nullary-constructor FACT stays indexed under its symbol, mirroring the discrim tree. VERIFIED SAFE (reviewer 3): codegen never touches head(); printer reads raw Terms (both forms print bare, WI-009 round-trip holds); reify is IMPROVED (a reified Fn{c} now views as Ref(c)); the pre-existing Ref convention (resolve.rs:2250 nullary none = Expr::Ref) confirms Ref is the intended canonical form. The 21-site Functor-head sweep confirmed only these readers see a 0-ary constructor; the rest key on sorts/ops/non-nullary functors (EffectsRuntime is a SORT, List.cons/EffectsRows are non-nullary). TESTS: term_view::wi436_tests (cross-carrier view identity across Term/Entity/occurrence + non-constructor Functor control) + discrim::wi436 (cross-form Fn<->Ref discrim match, both directions). KNOWN BOUNDARY (= WI-511): bridges at the view; storage keeps dual TermIds and the Value::Entity vs Value::Term(Ref) carrier, so Value::structural_eq (backing eq/neq + SetLiteral dedup) stays carrier-blind for 0-ary constructors (pre-existing, latent, unexercised). USER STEER: prefer ELIMINATION over bridging (one representation = less complexity = less risk); WI-511 carries the concrete storage+comparison elimination plan.", at: "2026-06-18T13:00:36Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-436", description: some(value: "Kernel decision: IDENTIFY Ref(c) with the nullary application Fn{c} for CONSTRUCTOR symbols at unification/matching -- the runtime twin of WI-391's extractability criterion and the principled end-state behind TWO shipped local fixes: WI-428's normalize_spec_binding_type (type positions) and WI-009's TermPrinter list literals (cons/nil spines). ROOT DISEASE: a nullary Fn prints BARE (indistinguishable from a Ref), so print->parse does not round-trip; the system survives on the CONVENTION that rule patterns use the bare-ref spelling for enum-like constructors (status: Open) -- but the convention is unenforced and the failure mode is the 9fa0da6 class: facts silently invisible to rules. LIVE INSTANCES (probe-verified in review): the store's replace path persists 'context: none, generates: none, params: none' -- bare nullary constructor writes surviving only by convention; any rule matching none() against them silently fails. DIRECTIONS: (a) unifier/discrim bridge Ref(c) ~ Fn{c} when c is a registered constructor (makes the bare print canonical); (b) loader normalizes bare constructor refs in fact/pattern positions to applications (one-time form churn); (c) printer prints all nullary constructors as name() (breaks every bare-ref pattern -- rejected). Decide with WI-391 (same Ref-vs-nullary-Fn divergence, fact-binding side). Also home for the unwrap_list_spine short-name corruption edge (user cons/nil sorts): a symbol-identity check becomes possible once the identification fixes which symbol is THE list cons."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T13:00:38Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-511", author: "claude", content: "RESUME PLAN (next session) 2026-06-18. STATE: Axis-2 (eq/neq + SetLiteral carrier-aware) DELIVERED commit 17402fc — Value::structural_eq stays carrier-faithful; the eq/neq builtins (new values_equal helper) + SetLiteral dedup route through views_structurally_equal. Prep-pass STARTED commit 92ddcf2 — 2 readers migrated carrier-agnostic, all green, alloc storage flip NOT applied (working tree clean). THE VALIDATED METHODOLOGY (do this): the WI-436 view bridge (functor_view_head) ALREADY makes head() return Ref(c) for a stored Fn{c}, so migrate each raw-Term::Fn-of-a-0-ary-constructor reader to be carrier-agnostic and verify GREEN with storage UNCHANGED (flip off) — the bridge exercises the Ref path now, so green = correct after the flip. NO big-bang. PATTERN readers = read the Pattern enum (NodeKind::Pattern) DIRECTLY (its ctor name is already a Symbol; no pattern_to_term, no Ref/Fn) — DONE for collect_covered_entities (typing.rs, reads branch.pattern directly). FUNCTOR readers = head().functor_sym() (handles Ref + Functor) — DONE for sort_constructor_syms. DIAGNOSTIC LOOP: re-apply the 3 mod.rs edits [alloc: Fn{c,[],[]}->Ref(c) when is_constructor_symbol; register_entity_of: extract functor from Ref|Fn + dual-key entity_parent[Ref(c)] so is_entity_of finds the value form; constructor_parent_sort: match Ref|Fn] -> run anthill-core -> the failures map the remaining raw readers -> migrate them (flip off, green) -> repeat. Beware SPAN MISATTRIBUTION (TermId-keyed span side-table mislabels which match the error is on — use a WI511_DBG eprintln to find the real reader). REMAINING READERS: (1) eval/pattern.rs match_pattern + match_constructor_pattern + match_tuple_pattern + var_pattern_name/extract_var_pattern_sym/constructor_pattern_name -> read the Pattern enum directly (sub-patterns are Rc<NodeOccurrence> inside the enum, thread occurrences through the recursion; callers pattern.rs:139/152/174 recursion, eval.rs:1374 lambda param, 1429/1465 match branches have branch.pattern). ALSO the scrutinee Value::Term arm (pattern.rs:195) -> head() to collapse the hand-written Entity vs Term(Fn) dual-carrier match. (2) typing.rs extend_env_from_pattern (still pattern_to_term'd at the call site ~3805) -> occurrence-native. (3) print.rs unwrap_list_spine (nil) + any others the diagnostic surfaces; NOTE list_to_vec already handles Ref-nil via its _=>break arm. FINAL STEP (trivial once readers migrated): apply the 3 mod.rs edits permanently -> single Ref(c) stored TermId -> then functor_view_head's Term::Fn->Ref canonicalization is dead for stored terms and can be simplified. Most of the original 83 flip-failures were LOAD CASCADES (exhaustiveness, already fixed by the collect_covered_entities migration); residual concentrates in the runtime matcher cluster. See [[wi436-ref-nullary-fn-view-layer]] two-axes model.", at: "2026-06-18T14:10:21Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-511", author: "claude", content: "AXIS-1 STORAGE FLIP DELIVERED + committed 75435e4 (full workspace green, 60 binaries). kb.alloc canonicalizes Term::Fn{c,[],[]} -> Term::Ref(c) when is_constructor_symbol(c): SINGLE storage form, the dual rep WI-436 only bridged is eliminated at term-storage. register_entity_of dual-keys Ref(c); constructor_parent_sort reads either carrier; value-lowering(execute.rs)+make_name_term* route through alloc so 0-ary ctors are uniformly Ref everywhere. eval::match_pattern is OCCURRENCE-NATIVE (reads NodeKind::Pattern enum; Closure.param_pattern+AwaitState::LetBind.pattern now Rc<NodeOccurrence>; 3 eval pattern_to_term bridges + dead extract_var_pattern_sym removed). Diagnostic-loop migrated readers: term_to_param_occurrence(wildcard), effect-row walker(empty_row), collect_positional_arg_value_pats(none), unwrap_list_spine(nil), test walkers. /code-review(high) found 5 LATENT readers, ALL FIXED + regression test: term_ser cons_to_json_array(nil terminator was appended as a stray array element), print.rs write_term/write_type_term(Nothing->'nothing' round-trip), term_pattern_child_as_occ(nested wildcard), IndexedFileStore::retrieve(nullary query invisible), load.rs entity FieldInfo functor. FINDING: functor_view_head bridge CANNOT be deleted (resume plan was wrong) -- occurrence carriers Expr::Apply/Constructor are NOT alloc-canonicalized so head() must still map their 0-ary ctors to Ref; bridge retained+correct. RESIDUAL (flip-SAFE, NOT dual-rep; = WI-348 follow-on, keep WI-511 open): typer extend_env_from_pattern + extract_pattern_type_ann + extract_pattern_var_name still term-based via 3 pattern_to_term bridges (typing.rs 2653/2740/3804); wildcard is a typer no-op so flip-safe; migrating removes those bridges. mod.rs:658 load-order dual-rep (fact refs nullary ctor whose sort loads later -> Fn{c}) is MITIGATED by the retained bridge. Axis-2(eq/neq) was 17402fc.", at: "2026-06-18T15:18:24Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-511", author: "claude", content: "RESIDUAL CLEARED + WI-511 DELIVERED (bfb8c75). Typer pattern helpers (extend_env_from_pattern, extract_pattern_var_name, extract_pattern_type_ann) now read the Pattern enum DIRECTLY; the 3 remaining pattern_to_term reading-bridges (Let/Lambda/match-branch) removed; LetAfterValue.pattern is now Rc<NodeOccurrence>. Code-review confirmed behavior-equivalent (the some/none wrap extract_pattern_type_ann unwrapped was a pure pattern_to_term round-trip artifact; occurrence_to_term(type_ann) yields the identical value). pattern_to_term survives ONLY as the reverse reflection producer (occurrence_to_term's Pattern arm). Net -20 lines, full workspace green 60 binaries. WI-511 complete: dual rep eliminated at term storage (axis-1 flip 75435e4) + Value carrier eq (axis-2 17402fc) + the WI-348 typer pattern-read boundary. Sole intentional retention: functor_view_head view bridge (occurrence carriers Expr::Apply/Constructor are not alloc-canonicalized, so head() must still map their 0-ary ctors to Ref -- correct, not a gap).", at: "2026-06-18T15:54:40Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-511", description: some(value: "eq/neq + SetLiteral dedup are carrier-blind for nullary constructors — the one structural-comparison path NOT unified with WI-436's Ref(c) === nullary-Fn{c} identity. ROOT: Value::structural_eq (eval/value.rs ~180-198) compares Value carriers FAITHFULLY (Entity vs Term, by TermId) and does NOT route through head()/views_structurally_equal, so the eq/neq builtins (kb/resolve.rs ~2432,2443, via normalize_value which only reifies Value::Node) and SetLiteral dedup (eval/eval.rs ~1600) miss the WI-436 identity: a nullary constructor as Value::Entity{c,[],[]} (eval finish_constructor, eval.rs ~1606) vs the same value as Value::Term(Ref(c)) (a fact/answer binding) compare UNEQUAL though they are the same value. PRE-EXISTING (structural_eq was always carrier-faithful; views_structurally_equal was introduced as its cross-carrier generalization) and LATENT — no stdlib/example currently compares a bare nullary constructor (none / a 0-ary enum variant) for equality where the two operands arrive via different construction paths, which is why the suite is green. FIX DIRECTION: route eq/neq (and the SetLiteral dedup) through views_structurally_equal for full Ref===Fn coverage. CAUTION: this is a broader equality-SEMANTICS change, not a drop-in — views_structurally_equal differs from structural_eq in var/rigid/DeBruijn/closure handling, so swapping blindly risks regressing equality for NON-constructor values; needs its own test surface proving (a) nullary-constructor cross-carrier eq now true, (b) no regression for scalars/compounds/vars/closures. Surfaced by the WI-436 /code-review (reviewer 3, xhigh). ACCEPTANCE: a spec that eq/neq-compares a bare nullary constructor across construction paths returns the correct result; SetLiteral dedup collapses cross-carrier-equal nullary constructors; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-436"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T15:54:42Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-503", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18 (49f5e5c). Closed all three residual WI-501 term_ser round-trip gaps. (1) NESTED-OPTION COLLAPSE: serializing some^k(none) k>=1 for an Option[T=Option[U]] field is now a loud SerError::InvalidValue, not a silent round-trip to none() (flattened TOML/JSON cannot represent present-but-empty; self-describing redesign declined for WI-501). USER DECIDED loud-error over accepting the many-to-one collapse: towers ending in a real value (some(some(5))) still round-trip faithfully; only the some^k(none) family would collapse. (2) SHORT-NAME DISPATCH ASYMMETRY: term_to_value + cons_to_json_array detected Option/List by SHORT name while deserialize resolved by QUALIFIED name, so a user entity named some/none/cons/nil in another namespace was mis-flattened (a user cons serialized to []). Fix: new is_prelude(kb,sym,qualified) gates on the qualified prelude name; the 4 prelude qualified names hoisted to module consts (OPTION_SOME/NONE, LIST_CONS/NIL) as single source of truth; pre-existing inline Ref(none) check routed through is_prelude too. (3) POSITIONAL CTOR FALLBACK: build_constructor_term_typed now errors loudly when a multi-field ctor (fields.len>1) gets a non-object scalar/array payload (would build a never-discrim-matching positional Fn); schema-less fields.len==0 positional fallback preserved. TESTS: 3 new regression tests in toml_ser_test (one per gap). Full workspace green (60 binaries). /code-review xhigh multi-agent: correctness [] + removed-behavior [] (qualified-name narrowing confined to a test-only serialize API with no prod caller); acted on the 2 reuse/altitude findings (consts + uniform is_prelude). Declined 3 lower findings with rationale (stdlib path matches build_test_kb convention; manual test term construction faithful for non-nullary ctors; cpp-gen bare-name acceptance is a separate codegen context).", at: "2026-06-18T16:48:21Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-503", description: some(value: "Persistence (term_ser): residual lossy/asymmetric round-trip gaps left by WI-501's type-directed reload (all NARROW / not in the WorkItem schema; surfaced by WI-501 /code-review). (1) NESTED-OPTION COLLAPSE: serialize flattens some(none()) -> inner none -> JSON null -> reload Option+null -> none(), so some(value: none()) (present-but-empty) round-trips to none() (absent) for Option[T=Option[U]] — information loss. (2) SERIALIZE SHORT-NAME DISPATCH ASYMMETRY: term_to_value detects Option/List by SHORT name (name==some/none/cons/nil) while WI-501 made the DESERIALIZE side resolve by QUALIFIED name; a user entity literally named some/none/cons/nil in another namespace is mis-serialized. Harden term_to_value to gate those branches on qualified_name_of(functor)==anthill.prelude.* (the none-Ref serialize check WI-501 added is already qualified). (3) POSITIONAL CTOR FALLBACK (WI-500 class): build_constructor_term_typed _ arm, for a multi-field ctor given a NON-object scalar/array (foreign/hand-authored store only — our serializer never emits this), builds a positional Term::Fn{pos_args} that silently never discrim-matches the named pattern (and drops extra array elems). Make it a loud error when fields.len()>1 and value isn't an object (vs schema-less fields.len()==0 positional fallback, which can't do better). NOTE: gap (1) is inherent to the flattened TOML/JSON format (the tagged/self-describing redesign was declined for WI-501); WI-501 already converted the sibling none-inside-a-list TOML corruption to a LOUD serialize error (json_to_toml null -> Err) vs the old silent null->empty-string. ACCEPTANCE: nested-Option round-trips faithfully OR errors loudly; a user entity named some/cons serializes correctly; foreign multi-field positional payload errors loudly; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T16:48:23Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-504", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18. Fix: resolve-time subst-aware Type/EffectExpr-spine var collector wired into collect_unbound_vars_node's None arm (resolve.rs). New collect_type_node_unbound_vars / collect_effect_node_unbound_vars / collect_type_child_unbound_vars are the resolve-time, subst-aware twins of the loader's collect_type_node_vars / collect_effect_node_vars / collect_type_child (node_occurrence.rs): same arm-for-arm child walk, but TypeChild::Ground chases through the subst-aware collect_unbound_vars (not all-vars collect_vars_rec) and TypeChild::Node recurses through collect_unbound_vars_node (whose None arm re-dispatches a nested Type/EffectExpr spine). The WI-322 debug_assert!(false) guard removed now that the case is handled. NOTE: collect_unbound_vars_node is a &self method, so it already had kb via self — no kb-threading needed (the feedback's threading concern applied to the loader's free-function for_each_child walkers, which retain their asserts and are out of scope). 2 tests added (delay_propagates_on_caller_var_in_type_node_spine = acceptance, NodeKind::Type carrier; collect_type_node_spine_is_subst_aware = direct, proves σ-bound var excluded + EffectExpr/Denoted-Node coverage). Full workspace green (60 binaries, 0 failed). /code-review (xhigh, 2 agents): clean, no findings.", at: "2026-06-18T17:02:33Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-504", description: some(value: "Resolve-time subst-aware var collection for Type/EffectExpr-kind Value::Node type-arg spines in the rule-delay pre-check (WI-322 residual). WI-322 made body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes (resolve.rs) detect caller vars in op type positions (Apply/ApplyWithin.type_args, Let.type_annotation): collect_type_value_unbound_vars routes a Value::Node type-arg spine through collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs:3289). That catches Expr/Denoted leaves subst-aware, but collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs:3192) has a `None => {}` arm (resolve.rs:3228) that SILENTLY skips Type/EffectExpr-kind occurrences (as_expr/as_pattern both None). So a caller var living in a Type-spine sibling of a Node type-arg — e.g. a TypeChild::Ground(Term::Var(Global)) inside a denoted/parameterized type that with_fresh_vars opened from a DeBruijn var — is NOT collected, and a type-dispatching builtin whose first arg is f[T = «Node Type-spine holding ?caller_var»](v) does NOT propagate rule delay (latent UNDER-delay; the exact failure-class WI-322 closed, but for the Type/EffectExpr-kind Node carrier only). The loader load-time twin collect_value_type (node_occurrence.rs:1968) DOES descend such spines via collect_type_or_expr_node_vars (node_occurrence.rs:1987) -> collect_type_node_vars (2018) / collect_effect_node_vars (2047), but those collect ALL vars (no substitution), so they are not directly usable for the resolve-time unbound-only pre-check (and the var must be subst-walked to its final var for the caller-var membership test). SCOPE: provide a subst-aware Type/EffectExpr-spine var collector — the resolve-time twin of collect_type_or_expr_node_vars — reachable from collect_unbound_vars_node`s None arm (or collect_type_value_unbound_vars`s Value::Node arm), so a caller var inside a Type-kind Node type-arg spine is detected (chase Ground TermId children via collect_unbound_vars; resolve Global occurrence vars via the same subst-aware logic). This rides WI-378 step 2 — the kb-threading type-field->child migration that lets collect/close/open walk INTO a Type occurrence; the pending boundary is marked by debug_assert!(false, \"type-field migration must thread kb here\") at node_occurrence.rs:1812/1855/1921, the same wall that blocks this. Once occurrence Type-spine children are walkable with kb threaded, the resolve-time subst filter follows. LATENT today: no builtin first-arg currently carries a var-bearing Type/EffectExpr-kind Node type-arg; WI-322 already covers Value::Term, Denoted-Expr Value::Node, and tuple/named-tuple carriers. ACCEPTANCE: a delayed builtin whose first arg is f[T = «Value::Node Type-spine holding ?caller_var»](v) triggers rule delay (caller var detected through the Type-spine, not silently dropped by the None arm); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T17:02:40Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-321", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18. POLICY DECISION (user-confirmed): cross-file mutual structural recursion is SUPPORTED, not forbidden — it's the standard collect-all-names-then-resolve-bodies technique (cf. SML/Haskell), and the stdlib's Type/EffectExpression already rely on it; forbidding would need a complex DFS cycle detector that false-rejects valid programs. Deliverable = document the load-bearing invariant + pin it (not a detection pass). Changes: (1) scan_definitions doc comment (load.rs) now states 4 sub-passes + the WI-321 INVARIANT (pass 1 defines EVERY name across EVERY file before ANY pass 2; load-bearing for any future single-pass/streaming refactor or import-carries-pass1-info evolution). (2) CLAUDE.md Pipeline updated (was hand-waved '2-pass'; now 4-pass + cross-file-supported note). (3) New pinning test wi321_cross_file_mutual_recursion_test (2 cases: mutual cycle Tree.Node.leaf:Leaf <-> Leaf.parent:Option[Tree] across two files loads+resolves; load-order-independence). (4) New reusable common::try_load_kb_with_files(&[&str]) multi-user-file loader; try_load_kb_with delegates to it (behavior-preserving). Verified: full workspace green (60 binaries, 0 failed); /code-review xhigh — verifier empirically confirmed the test is non-tautological (TREE_SRC alone fails to load) and fixed one doc imprecision (breaking the invariant fires UnresolvedImport/UnresolvedName, not UnresolvedTypeName which WI-429 gates to dotted names). NOT committed yet.", at: "2026-06-18T17:30:20Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-321", description: some(value: "Cross-file mutually-recursive sort/enum declarations: loader robustness + policy. The loader's scan_definitions is a 4-sub-pass walk (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs:225-258): pass1 defines all names across all files; pass2 resolves requires + imports; pass3 registers rule-head Goal functors; pass4 retries deferred predicate imports. This shape ACCIDENTALLY supports cross-file mutual structural dependencies (each file's pass1 ignores the other's content, so both names exist before either file's pass2 runs). Example uncovered during WI-320 (code-review finding #14): effect-expression.anthill imported Type from sort.anthill while sort.anthill (post-WI-320) imported EffectExpression — a mutual cycle whose soundness depended entirely on pass1 being unconditional. SHORT-TERM FIX (WI-320 last commit): colocated EffectExpression into sort.anthill, eliminating that specific cross-file cycle. But the GENERAL question remains: (1) is cross-file mutual structural recursion a SUPPORTED pattern (with documented robustness invariants the loader must preserve), or an INCIDENTAL one (works today, may regress)? (2) Should the loader DETECT cross-file structural cycles and warn / require they be in one file, mirroring how many module systems forbid cross-file mutual recursion (e.g., OCaml's module rec requirement, Rust's per-mod resolution boundary)? (3) Should there be a TEST that pins the invariant (a fixture with a benign cross-file cycle that must keep loading)? (4) Should anthill add a cross_file_recursive annotation or directory-as-module convention to ALLOW the pattern explicitly where intended? RISKS if left unaddressed: (a) a future refactor to a single-pass / streaming loader would re-expose the cycle silently; (b) imports may evolve to carry pass1-needed info (typed-symbol selective imports, qualified-name resolution touching parent files) which deadlocks the cycle; (c) load_incremental (skip-register_prelude path) has the same scan; user code mirroring this pattern across two user files would silently work today but is undocumented. TASK: (a) decide the policy — supported vs incidental, with docs in CLAUDE.md or a comment in scan_definitions; (b) if supported, add a fixture test asserting cross-file mutual structural deps load (e.g., two test files where each entity references the other's Type); (c) if forbidden, add a scan_definitions pass that detects the cycle (DFS over imports + entity field types) and reports a clear error; (d) update brainstorm/proposal docs that hand-wave the 2-pass scan handles cycles with a precise statement of which cycles are actually supported. Surfaced by WI-320 code-review finding #14 (Type vs EffectExpression cycle); the underlying mutual recursion remains (Type/EffectExpression are co-defined data) — colocation hides the cycle but doesnt remove the structural dependency, which any tooling that walks Type field types must still handle."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T17:30:22Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-369", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-18 (not committed). Enforce 'internal' visibility (was parse-only). MECHANISM: SymbolTable.internal_syms HashSet + mark_internal/is_internal/internal_visible_from (walks is_enclosing parent chain from the entry scope to the symbol's declaring scope). record_internal wired at all 4 visibility-bearing definition sites in scan_items_pass1 (Sort/AbstractSort/Entity/Operation + OperationBlock). ENFORCEMENT: (1) name resolution — resolve_in_scope resolves IGNORING internal then POST-FILTERS matched symbols by internal_visible_from(sym, entry_scope) [KEY DESIGN: a per-hop parent.locals filter was UNSOUND — code-review found 2 leaks: transitive (internal reached via a non-enclosing parent's enclosing grandparent) and re-export (internal imported into a descendant then wildcarded out); the post-resolution gate on the matched symbol vs the ENTRY scope fixes both]; (2) by_qualified_name + dotted-probe + multi-segment fallback guarded via internal_visible_from; (3) selective/plain import guarded via forbid_internal_import; (4) field PROJECTION (b.field) — typer ForbiddenInternalField at the DotApply dispatch + field_access_owning_ctor paths, access scope = env.enclosing_sort()'s body scope (kb.alloc(Fn{sort}).raw() == load-time scope_raw via hash-consing). New LoadError::ForbiddenInternalAccess (load-blocking) + TypeError::ForbiddenInternalField. MutableStack carrier 'entity mutableStack(rep)' now 'internal'; its own ops construct+project same-scope (enclosing → clean); external construction/projection blocked. 8 tests (qualified/bare-requires/selective-import construction, projection, same-scope+public-API control, public-sibling selectivity, transitive-leak + re-export-leak regression guards). Full workspace green (60 binaries). /code-review xhigh (3 agents): found the 2 soundness leaks (FIXED) + dead scope_raw_of (REMOVED); regression-safe (filter is a no-op when nothing is internal); free-op projection None-branch is dead-but-defensive (namespace ops get the namespace as enclosing_sort; top-level ops are parse-rejected). Spec §8.6 already described this; impl now matches.", at: "2026-06-18T20:12:55Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-369", description: some(value: "Loader/resolver: ENFORCE internal visibility (currently parse-only). The internal modifier (grammar.js:802 visibility rule; kernel-language.md section 8.6 'hidden from outside the declaring scope', lines 540/1390) is PARSED but NOT enforced: a cross-scope reference to an internal name -- even fully qualified, e.g. a.b.Sort.mkStack -- resolves and loads CLEAN. Verified in WI-364 Phase 0: a MutableStack with internal entity mkStack(rep: Cell[...]) is constructed from a different namespace (anthill.test.mstack.MutableStack.mkStack(...)) with ZERO load errors -- so internal is decorative today. FIX (kb/load.rs + intern.rs scope resolution): record the internal flag on declared symbols (the parse IR carries the visibility modifier) and reject cross-scope resolution of them -- both the scope-walk path (resolve_in_scope) AND by_qualified_name / selective-import -- so an internal name is visible only within its declaring scope (the sort/namespace) and that scope descendants; emit a load-blocking error (UnresolvedName or a dedicated forbidden-access diagnostic) naming the internal symbol. NEEDED to encapsulate stateful carriers: a MutableStack/MutableCollection representation handle (the rep Cell) must be hidden so external code cannot alias it and break invariants (proposal 002 / WI-364). ACCEPTANCE: cross-scope construction/projection of an internal ctor/field errors at load with the name; same-scope use stays clean; default-visible behavior and the standalone export no-op unchanged; stdlib + full anthill-core green. REF: kernel-language.md section 8.6; grammar.js visibility rule; WI-364 Phase 0 finding. Rust-only (resolver; scaland mirrors only if it grows the same check)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-18T20:12:56Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-095", author: "claude", content: "WI-095 review vs current state (2026-06-18). (a) author Monad/etc typeclasses in stdlib -- DRIVER is proposal 047 (effects-as-monads via Filinski reflection), which names the stdlib Monad (pure/flatMap) as its prerequisite (047 sec6: the API monad is the spec both interpreter and codegen honor). FIRST CUT DELIVERED: stdlib/anthill/prelude/monad.anthill -- sort Monad[M[T]] (pure/flatMap/map) + fact Monad[M = Option, ...]; rides the delivered WI-383 (HK carrier fill + injective decomposition) and WI-431 (op-valued instance facts), NO new typer work; full anthill-core suite green (1751 passed, 0 failed). Naming flatMap/map/pure NOT bind/return -- anthill has no do-notation, so the method-call spellings are correct (CpsMonad/F were Scala-specific example names). Remaining for (a): 047's effect-denotation instances (Result/Stream/State) + transformer instance (StateT) + select_monad rank-fold -- these ARE the 047 substrate and build ON this sort; map should become a derived default once value-lambda surface syntax is confirmed. Other WI-095 items re-homed: (b) op-as-value/eta subsumed by WI-431 + WI-442; (c) ?f(?x) Miller-pattern guard = 047 sec8 deferred residue under WI-383 (flexible heads load; guard fires once monad-law rules over concrete instances flow through); (d) arrow effect subtyping ALREADY delivered -- arrow_compatible_view + subtype_effect_rows, contra-param/co-result/co-effect-subsumption, variance-correct (only residual: the open/open lacks arm, sound-but-conservative incompleteness); (e,f) C++ codegen tail remains open -- (f) premise corrected: codegen queries the KB (form-agnostic), the marked/unmarked carrier distinction is a LOADER concern (carrier gets a backing var), not read from source. Net: WI-095 live scope narrows to (a) finish 047 monad instances + (e,f) codegen.", at: "2026-06-18T21:06:03Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-512", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION (mis-framed originally). The non-linear-pattern consistency MACHINERY already exists and works: Substitution::bind_term (subst.rs:100) and bind_value (subst.rs:130) set contradiction=true when a var is bound twice to structurally-unequal values (WI-246), exposed via is_contradiction(). It is honored by the simp_rewrite matcher (simp_rewrite.rs:286). The actual gap is narrow: the SLD resolver (resolve.rs) NEVER consults is_contradiction() on the discrim-query candidate substitutions, so a goal atom with a repeated query var (edge(from:?n,to:?n)) over-matches a fact (edge(a,b)) — the conflict IS recorded in the candidate subst but the resolver counts it as a solution anyway. FIX (reuse existing machinery, not new): in the resolver's consumption of query_view/query_resolved candidates (and/or when merging a candidate subst into the frame subst), drop candidates whose resulting Substitution::is_contradiction() is true. Localized; queries are NOT meant to be linear. Empirically confirmed via WI-023 (edge(from:V,to:V) vs edge(a,b) returned count=1).", at: "2026-06-18T21:12:16Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-023", description: some(value: "Parse/load integration for quantified constraints: extend Constraint IR with ConstraintBody enum (Quantified, Aggregation), update converter for quantified_constraint and aggregation_constraint nodes, update load_constraint to build LogicalQuery term and call add_guard."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T04:01:22Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-515", description: some(value: "Constraint/guard enforcement: var-quantified queries spuriously match synthetic entity field-type DECLARATION facts. The loader asserts a per-entity declaration fact carrying the field TYPES in the slots (per kb_query_test: e.g. Person(name: sort_ref(String), role: sort_ref(String)); confirm exact carrier — appeared as a Value::Node-bound candidate during WI-512 debugging). A CONCRETE query value does not unify with the type slot, so concrete-discriminator constraints (the WI-023 cross-atom tests) correctly exclude it; but a fully-VAR self-referential constraint like  has ?p unify with the (same) type in both slots, so the declaration fact is counted as a match and the constraint is ALWAYS spuriously violated — independent of WI-512's non-linearity fix (which only drops a≠b conflicts). This blocks WI-023 quantified constraints over fully-var self-referential patterns (functional-dependency / self-loop / uniqueness shapes). SCOPE: (1) confirm the exact declaration-fact representation + which sort/domain it is asserted under; (2) exclude these non-DATA facts from constraint/guard enforcement — e.g. tag declaration facts and filter them in the guard's resolve, scope check_all_guards/eval_count_guard queries to the data domain, or stop asserting field-type declarations as same-functor facts. ACCEPTANCE: a fully-var self-referential constraint (no ?p -: edge(from:?p,to:?p)) holds when no DATA fact is a self-loop and is violated only by a real self-loop data fact; cargo-test green. Surfaced isolating WI-512 (the constraint-level self-loop test was confounded by this, so WI-512 was verified at the resolver level instead)."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: nil), status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-515", author: "user", content: "CLARIFY TERM + restore eaten example (a backtick in the original description triggered shell command-substitution and dropped a phrase). \"guard/constraint query\" means: the SLD resolution the guard engine runs to EVALUATE a constraint. A constraint is loaded as a guard (load_constraint -> add_guard registers its LogicalQuery); enforcement (check_all_guards -> eval_count_guard / eval_forall_guard) lowers the constraint condition+body to goals and calls self.resolve(goals). THAT resolve is the query. The full self-referential example dropped from the description is: no ?p -: edge(from: ?p, to: ?p) -- a fully-var self-loop constraint whose enforcement query edge(from: ?p, to: ?p) spuriously matches the synthetic entity field-type declaration fact (both slots the same type, so ?p binds consistently), so the constraint is always violated regardless of the data facts.", at: "2026-06-19T05:55:33Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-512", description: some(value: "Resolver: enforce intra-atom non-linear (repeated-variable) consistency in the discrim-query-as-unifier. A goal f(?x, ?x) over-matches a fact f(a, b): the discrim ViewHead::Var arm (discrim.rs query_node/query_arg_value) and SmallSubst::with_binding (persist_subst.rs) push the query var binding without a conflict check, and resolve_leaf binds each occurrence independently (last-wins), so a repeated query variable within a single atom is not unified. Affects non-linear queries/constraints: self-loop detection (no ?x -: edge(from:?x, to:?x)) and the FunctionalDep guards assumed by WI-020/021. Fix: enforce repeated-variable consistency either at the discrim var-edge binding (reject/merge when a query var is already bound to a different value/path) or via a post-unification consistency pass in resolve_leaf. Surfaced during WI-023 quantified-constraint enforcement."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T05:56:23Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-516", name: "typing")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-517", name: "grammar")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-517", name: "typing")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-516", description: some(value: "Typer effect-tracking bug (graded-effect rows): an effect-set carried as a type/effect parameter is represented INCONSISTENTLY between row-literal position and forced/effects position, blocking graded-monad instance conformance. Surfaced building the stdlib graded DelayMonad/Delay (stdlib/anthill/prelude/delay.anthill, proposal 047). REPRO: Delay.delayFlatMap declared -> Delay[T=B, E={E1,E2}] has a body forcing two sub-computations; the declared {E1,E2} reads the row-vars as a MERGE OF OPEN TAILS (merge[open[tail=E1], open[tail=E2]]), but the body's forced captured effects read as PRESENT LABELS (merge[present[label=E1], present[label=E2], empty_row]); the two do not unify ('type mismatch in delayFlatMap.return: expected Delay[E={merge[open E2, open E1]}], got Delay[E=merge[present E1, present E2, empty]]'). Independent of 'sort E=?' vs 'effects E=?' on the carrier and of bare 'effects Eff' vs braced 'effects {Eff}' on force (all tried). pure/delay/force conform; only the {E1,E2} merge in flatMap fails. ROOT: a param standing for an effect SET is not treated as a row variable (open tail) in effects/@-position -- it becomes a single present label -- inconsistent with how {E1,E2} reads the same vars. Fix likely makes effects/@-position over a row-set-valued param produce an open tail, or makes subtype_effect_rows reconcile present-label vs open-tail for the same var. SECONDARY (related, worked around with let): effects of a NESTED ARGUMENT-position call are dropped -- delayForce(f(delayForce(m))) inferred {E2}, dropping E1 from the inner delayForce(m); 'let a = delayForce(m) ; delayForce(f(a))' correctly accumulates {E1,E2}. So a call's inferred effect omits its argument-evaluation effects (at least inside a lambda body) unless let-bound -- effect under-reporting (soundness-adjacent). ACCEPTANCE: a graded-monad flatMap body forcing two sub-computations conforms to its declared E={E1,E2} return; a nested effectful argument-call effect is reflected without a let; the stdlib Delay instance loads; full anthill-core green. Discovered 2026-06-19 (delay.anthill DelayMonad, proposal 047). Rust typer."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-06-19T07:51:14Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-516", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-19. Two typer fixes unblocked the graded Delay instance: (1) row_tail_var_of (mod.rs) now treats Var::Rigid as a row tail — an effect-set type param is Skolemized during op-body checking, so a performed/forced captured effect surfaces as a bare rigid var that must fold as open(tail), not present(label); this aligns the build side (build_canonical_effects_rows + the arrow-occ build at typing.rs make_*_occ) with the decompose side (row_tail_termid/effects_rows_to_flat_list) which already accept any Var. DeBruijn stays excluded. (2) check_apply_iter Path 2 (arrow-typed VARIABLE application, typing.rs) now unions the argument-evaluation effects with the arrow's own call effect — matching Path 1/Path 3 — fixing the secondary nested-arg drop (delayForce(f(delayForce(m))) lost E1). En route: replaced a debug_assert!(false) WI-348-Phase-C drop in check_constructor_iter's SortAlias alias_info reconstruction with a lossless value_to_term lowering, since the now-conforming Delay E binds to a Value::Node effect-row occurrence. Also fixed a pre-existing main regression: monad.anthill+delay.anthill were missing from the anthill-stl embedded SOURCES list (broke anthill-todo with 'unresolved import anthill.prelude.Monad'). Stdlib Delay instance loads; full workspace green. Docs: kernel-language.md 4.7 corrected (lambda () -> body for nullary thunks; typed binders unparseable, tracked WI-517) + proposal 047 8 status=delivered. Soundness re-verified: typer still loudly rejects a wrong-type body and an unknown-functor call.", at: "2026-06-19T07:51:39Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-514", description: some(value: "Guard occurrence-leaf path hardening (gated on WI-246 occurrence-goal resolution). Today the loader always builds Value::Term guards, so these are latent: (1) check_all_guards' Gated outcome routes through LoadError::Other which is NOT in is_load_blocking, so in the CLI a gated guard would surface as a non-fatal warning and load with the constraint unenforced (contradicts the stated 'surfaced loudly / load-blocking' intent); (2) lower_logical_query's pattern_query non-term branch is debug_assert!(false)+empty, i.e. silent in release; (3) assert_checked silently skips a gated guard at runtime with no diagnostic. When WI-246 makes the resolver evaluate Value::Node occurrence goals (so guards can carry occurrence leaves), make all three loud/blocking. Surfaced by WI-023 code review."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-246"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T08:16:55Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-095", author: "user", content: "EMBED-DRIFT REGRESSION (prereq for WI-514) — already fixed on main by the WI-516 graded-Delay work (origin added both monad+delay to anthill-stl/src/stdlib.rs SOURCES). For the record: WI-095(a) (b74c39d) added stdlib/anthill/prelude/monad.anthill + option.anthill's 'import anthill.prelude.{Monad}' but did NOT register monad in the embedded SOURCES, so every binary failed to load with 'unresolved import anthill.prelude.Monad' and stdlib_drift_test was red. My standalone monad-SOURCES commit was dropped in rebase as redundant.", at: "2026-06-19T08:17:26Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-486", author: "user", content: "CROSS-CARRIER structural_eq gap (prerequisite for sound mixed-carrier eq; surfaced in the WI-514 carrier-neutral discussion). Value::structural_eq (eval/value.rs:180) compares ONLY within a carrier lineage: (Term,Term)->scalar_eq TermId-identity, (Entity,Entity)->recurse, (Node,Node)->occurrence_structural_eq; every CROSS-carrier pair — (Term,Entity), (Term,Node), (Entity,Node) — hits '_ => scalar_eq' and returns FALSE (its own doc punts cross-lineage to TermView). CONSEQUENCE for WI-486: the eq builtin (eq_operands) this WI names is 'structural_eq + Delay', so eq(<term form>, <occurrence/entity form>) of the SAME structure tests UNEQUAL — eq-as-test is UNSOUND across carriers, not just missing the bind. Same bug bites subst.rs bind_value (112/132/137) non-linear consistency (WI-512 contradiction check) and region.rs:170 / load.rs dedup. FIX: views_structurally_equal (term_view.rs:674) already compares correctly across carriers but needs &KnowledgeBase to decode a Value::Term; either thread kb into eq_operands/bind_value/dedup and route through it, or give structural_eq a kb param + delegate. Prerequisite for the WI-514 carrier-neutral guard-lowering port.", at: "2026-06-19T08:17:30Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-191", author: "claude", content: "Design direction 2026-06-19: defer the literal load-time entity synthesis (the WI v1); pursue the reflect-machinery route (the WI v2) instead. Nomenclature drift for future readers: the bundle glue is get_arg / collect_all_args / collect_all_args_acc (main.anthill), NOT the WI's get_binding/collect_all_bindings; Binding(name,value) lives in anthill.cli.parse, specs (OperationSpec/ParamSpec/ParamKind) in anthill.cli.spec. WHAT load-time entity synthesis meant: per command, derive a NEW entity sort from that command's DECLARED ParamSpec list (not from runtime argv) -- e.g. spec_add gives entity AddArgs(description: String, depends: List[String]=[], acceptance: List[ToolPasses]=[ToolPasses('cargo-test')], tag: List[String]=[]); mapping positional/required-flag to a single field, repeatable flag to a List field, bool_flag to Bool, defaults from a new ParamSpec.default_value; cmd_add would then take a: AddArgs and dot-access, and parse_argv would fill an AddArgs instance from argv. WHY it is the costly path (verified by exploration): specs are OPERATIONS (operation spec_add() returns OperationSpec), not declarations/facts, and the Rust loader does not eval operations; there is NO post-load API to inject a sort/entity DECLARATION into the KB -- load is a monolithic pipeline (scan-resolve-witness-typecheck) with no mid-stage injection hook (~500+ lines to add one). Workarounds are all heavy: (i) Interpreter::call on Main.specs at load, then hand-build TermIds + register_sort/register_entity_of per command -- tedious, brushes WI-348; (ii) move specs to fact OperationSpec(...) (the cheapest load-time variant; KB query API exists via rules_by_functor/query) but it still needs Rust to materialize the per-command types AND a two-phase load since the bundle text references AddArgs. Insertion point if ever revisited: main.rs between register_runtime and Main.main. REFLECT-MACHINERY route (preferred): build a generic accessor, do not synthesize types. Building blocks already exist and are WI-348-compliant (no missing Rust): term_field(t:Term,name) returns Option[Term], term_as_string, term_list_items, term_as_entity[E](t:Term) returns Option[E] (Term::Fn to a typed entity Value; already used by cmd_list_tagged/cmd_claim via facts_of), as_term[E], field_access(receiver:Value,field) returns Value (eval-side Entity field read), make_fn. WI-348 boundary: ALLOWED = TermView walking + value-level field reads (term_field/field_access/facts_of/as_term); FORBIDDEN = materializing Value to TermId from logic (reify_to_term retired); the reflect route stays inside this. TWO orthogonal wins to capture: (1) independent of reflect -- parse_argv ALREADY validates required params (check_required) before dispatch, so the case none() -> error branches on REQUIRED args in every cmd_X are dead code; a total arg(args,name) returns String (loud Error if absent, per the repo loud-over-silent principle) collapses each match get_arg none()/some into one 'let id = arg(args, id)'. Big mechanical shrink, no reflect needed. (2) reflect -- typed dotted access still needs the per-command shape to exist; cheapest is to hand-declare the ~15 small args entities in the bundle (far cheaper than load-time synthesis) plus a generic parse_into[E](spec, argv) returns E that builds the typed value from bindings via make_fn + term_as_entity[E], filling defaults from the spec; OR drop static dotting for a reflect accessor field[F](args,name) returns Option[F] (less typed, tiny). OPEN for next session: decide between true typed dotted access (hand-declared args entities + parse_into[E]) vs a generic reflect accessor + the dead-none() cleanup, judged against the WI ~40% shrink target. Ticket stays OPEN.", at: "2026-06-19T08:23:21Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-191", author: "claude", content: "Addendum 2026-06-19 (re: the dot-access macro). Confirmed the CONSUMPTION side, and it sharpens the recommendation rather than changing it: dot-access is NOT a way around declaring the per-command shape -- it is the consumer of it. ?x.field lowers in the converter to a dot_apply(?x, field, []) node (NOT desugared to apply, to avoid re-resolving through lexical scope), then the prelude [simp] rule rewrites it: dot_field: dot_apply(?x,?name,[]) = field_access(?x,?name) :- is_entity(min_sort(?x)), has_field(min_sort(?x), ?name) (proposal 043 sec 6.1-6.3; reflect.anthill:382 dot_apply entity + the field_access builtin at resolve.rs). The guard REQUIRES min_sort(?x) to be a DECLARED entity that HAS the named field, so a.description dispatches only if AddArgs is a real declared sort carrying that field; anonymous tuples are not is_entity, so they do NOT dot-dispatch. UPSHOT for the reflect route: this makes route (2) -- hand-declare the ~15 small args entities -- clearly DOMINANT over the generic field[F](args,name) accessor (route 2 alt). Once the entities exist, a.description is FREE via the existing dot_field rule: no new dispatch machinery, no import. The ONLY remaining work is PRODUCING the typed value: a generic parse_into[E](spec, argv) returns E built from bindings via make_fn + term_as_entity[E], defaults from spec. Bonus: method-call dot (?x.m(args)) also resolves via the default rule find_operation_on_sort(min_sort(?x), name) (043 sec 6.4), so arg-validation methods ON the args sort would dot-dispatch for free too. Net plan crystallizing for next session: (1) total arg(args,name) returns String to kill the dead none() branches (no reflect, independent win); (2) declare the per-command args entities + one generic parse_into[E]; dot reads are already handled by the existing macro. The earlier generic-accessor alternative is dominated and can be dropped.", at: "2026-06-19T08:25:01Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-191", author: "claude", content: "Addendum 2026-06-19 (sort-specific dot-apply). Confirmed the dot-dispatch engine is LIVE, not just proposed: the typer rewrites every Expr::DotApply, and sort-specific [simp] dot rules already fire (typing.rs ~2336-2367 fires a sort-scoped dot rule at a DotApply or falls through to the default dot_field; simp_rewrite.rs is the engine; design doc simp-rewrite-design.md sec 7.1). So WI-191 can lean on the proposal-043 sec 6.3 extensibility lever: write a sort-specific dot rule on the args carrier instead of relying on the default dot_field (which needs declared fields via has_field). THE CRUX is result typing, and it splits the route cleanly. (A) Per-FIELD sort-specific rules with concrete names -- dot_apply(?a, description, []) = arg_str(?a) [simp]; dot_apply(?a, depends, []) = arg_list(?a, 'depends') [simp] -- give correct per-field types (String vs List[String]) because each RHS op has its own return type, BUT that is one rule per field, MORE verbose than just declaring the entity fields, so no win over route 2. (B) ONE GENERIC rule dot_apply(?a, ?name, []) = arg_field(?a, ?name) [simp] on the carrier is maximally DRY (no per-command anything; parse_argv emits a single carrier value), BUT arg_field has a SINGLE return type, so a.description:String and a.depends:List[String] cannot both hold -- the typing wall. Resolving (B) needs the result type sourced from OUTSIDE the runtime value: either a type-indexed arg_field[F] inferred from the EXPECTED type at each use site (bidirectional, fragile), or SPEC/TYPE-DIRECTED dot typing where the typer consults the param's declared kind/type for ?name at the dot site (the elegant endgame = the WI v2, real new typer work; note ParamSpec today carries NO type field, only kind, so it would need ParamSpec.type or a kind-to-type derivation). NET of the whole analysis: cheapest CORRECT landing is route 2 (declare per-command args entities + a generic parse_into[E]; the default dot_field rule handles reads, correctly typed, zero new dispatch rules). Route B (generic carrier + sort-specific dot rule + spec-directed result type) is the genuinely DRY endgame but its value rests on solving result-type sourcing -- that is the WI-191 v2 research item. RECOMMEND for the build session: ship route 2 first plus the dead-none() arg(args,name) returns String cleanup (independent win); keep Route B as v2 once spec-directed dot typing is scoped. Ticket stays OPEN.", at: "2026-06-19T08:31:24Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-191", description: some(value: "CLI spec → typed args. Today every cmd_X operation receives `bindings: List[Binding]` and re-extracts each parameter via `get_binding(bindings, \"name\")` + nested Option matches + (for repeatable flags) `collect_all_bindings`. The OperationSpec already declares param names + kinds + types — the typed args entity can be derived. Surface: `spec_add` declares params; the loader emits a synthetic entity `AddArgs(description: String, depends: List[String] = [], acceptance: List[ToolPasses] = [ToolPasses(\"cargo-test\")])`; cmd_add is rewritten to take `a: AddArgs` and use `a.description` / `a.depends` directly. parse_argv elaborates argv into AddArgs instead of List[Binding]; positional / flag / bool_flag kinds map to single-value / list-or-single / Bool fields respectively. Default values live on the spec param declaration. Work: (a) extend ParamSpec with `default_value: Option[Term]` and a derived-args-entity flag; (b) loader: for each spec, synthesize an entity declaration matching the param shape; (c) parse_argv reshape: walk argv producing the synthetic-entity Value rather than List[Binding]; (d) bundle ports — cmd_X bodies switch from get_binding cascades to dotted field access; (e) tests: parser produces typed args matching declared param types; missing required positional becomes a typed error not a `none()` extraction. Acceptance: every existing cmd_X drops its get_binding / collect_all_bindings glue; cargo test green; bundle bytes shrink by an estimated ~40%. Independent of WI-189 in v1 (typed args are derived from spec at load time, not via runtime ↓ over a Bindings term — that is a possible v2 unification once brackets land)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-292"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-486", author: "user", content: "SCOPE NARROWED (2026-06-19, agreed w/ user): WI-486 = the cross-carrier structural_eq SOUNDNESS fix only (WI-518 prerequisite a). The eq-binds-unbound DECISION (original title) split into its own WI (not a WI-518 prereq; relates WI-483). PLAN: remove the carrier-blind Value::structural_eq hazard — route every cross-carrier-EXPOSED caller (subst.rs bind_value/bind_term contradiction, region.rs/load.rs/typing.rs dedup, eval/builtins.rs Eq.eq/neq) through the carrier-aware views_structurally_equal (term_view.rs:668), threading &KnowledgeBase into the two subst bind methods. NOTE: WI-511 already did this for the resolver eq builtin (eq_operands->values_equal->views_structurally_equal). Keep a kb-free SAME-CARRIER-only primitive (renamed loud) for the 2 genuinely-same-carrier internal recursions: occurrence_structural_eq's NamedTuple fields (node_occurrence.rs:2198, fields can be Value::Entity) + the Value/var recursion.", at: "2026-06-19T09:27:06Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-520", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION on reachability: Expr::Instantiation is NOT vestigial/superseded — it is a REFLECT-Expr / code-as-data form (WI-296). Per open_debruijn_node doc (node_occurrence.rs:1084): rule body atoms are usually Apply/Constructor, BUT 'reflection / typing rules match expression structure as data', so a body atom can carry Instantiation/HoApply/Match/If/Let/Lambda materialized as reflect-Expr data. So the gap IS reachable when reflection/typing rules compare two instantiation-shaped expression VALUES (var bound twice to equal Instantiation data -> false contradiction; Eq.eq over reflected code). Normal predicate/constructor atoms still use Apply (Term::Fn->Expr::Apply in build_body_atom_occurrence; source Name[T=..] -> application per WI-311), so occ_head's Opaque is correct for NORMAL matching but lossy for reflect-data EQUALITY. This makes fix-option (b) (equality-specific faithful Node head / walk as_expr() directly, separate from the matching head occ_head) the right approach — reflection is exactly where 'compare two code values structurally' is the intent. Pre-existing for eq since WI-511.", at: "2026-06-19T10:44:31Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-520", author: "user", content: "FIXED (Instantiation/Bottom part) in the WI-486 change, 2026-06-19. ROOT CAUSE was sharper than first filed: occ_head VIOLATED the WI-342 occ_head<->term-twin invariant — occurrence_to_term already materializes Expr::Constructor AND Expr::Instantiation identically via occ_build_fn -> Term::Fn{name,..} (node_occurrence.rs:2200-2203), and Expr::Bottom -> Term::Bottom (2232), so their term twins read ViewHead::Functor{name}/ViewHead::Bottom — but occ_head's '_ => Opaque' catch-all swallowed both, so an Instantiation occurrence couldn't even match its OWN materialized term. FIX: occ_head + occ_pos_child/occ_named_child/occ_named_keys now read Instantiation exactly like Constructor, and Bottom as ViewHead::Bottom (term_view.rs). This (a) repairs the matching invariant and (b) closes the views/bind/eq equality gap for these forms. SIDE EFFECT: retroactively makes the occurrence_structural_eq deletion fully sound — views now covers the SAME set occ_eq did (the 2 forms that differed are handled). Tests: wi520_tests (instantiation_reads_like_its_term_twin_and_compares_structurally + bottom_occurrence_reads_as_bottom_not_opaque); full anthill-core 1770/0 (matching change clean) + lib 311/0. RESIDUAL (NOT this WI's scope, pre-existing in BOTH old occ_eq and new code): the genuinely headless control-flow reflect forms (Match/If/Let/Lambda/HoApply) stay Opaque->unequal; occ_eq also returned false for them. Faithful equality for those needs synthetic heads — separate/low-priority.", at: "2026-06-19T10:56:28Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-520", description: some(value: "views_structurally_equal / occ_head treat Expr::Instantiation and Expr::Bottom occurrences as Opaque -> two STRUCTURALLY-EQUAL Instantiation/Bottom Value::Node values compare UNEQUAL. occ_head (term_view.rs) maps only Apply/Constructor/Const/Ref/Ident/Var(Global)/DotApply (+ type/effect nodes) to real heads; everything else (Instantiation, Bottom, HoApply, Match, If, Let, Lambda, ListLit, ...) -> _ => Opaque -> views head-match _ => false. CONSEQUENCE: a var bound twice to equal Instantiation/Bottom occurrences gets a FALSE contradiction (WI-512 drops the substitution -> lost solution); Eq.eq(inst, inst) returns false. PRE-EXISTING for the eq/neq builtin since WI-511 (values_equal->views); WI-486 extended views to bind_value/resolved_labels_equal/merge_effects so they now share the gap (consistently). The OLD occurrence_structural_eq (removed in WI-486) handled Bottom=>true and Instantiation=>structural; it was production-dead+inconsistent-with-eq so removed rather than kept as a parallel comparator. FIX OPTIONS (decide): (a) make occ_head read Instantiation as a Functor (like Constructor) — but assess rule-LHS MATCHING impact first (occ_head is dual-purpose index+equality; mod.rs:399 notes it deliberately does NOT mirror the whole Expr enum); (b) give views an equality-specific Node head distinct from the match head; (c) confirm these occurrences never reach a structural-equality compare and document as unreachable. Reachability is LOW (Instantiation largely superseded by Apply per WI-311; Bottom is an error placeholder) — untested today (full suite green). SCOPE: term_view occ_head / views_structurally_equal, Rust-only. RELATES: WI-486, WI-511, WI-512."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T10:56:32Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-486", description: some(value: "Decide + implement eq-binds-unbound-operand (eq test->unify) for computational rule bodies. WI-482 made a dispatched rule-body field_access EVALUATE at SLD (eq(7, ?p.x) succeeds once ?p.x reduces), but the acceptance's literal 'eq(?v, ?p.x) binds ?v' is NOT delivered: (1) the resolver's eq builtin (builtin_eq/eq_operands) is a TEST — structural_eq + Delay on a flex operand, never SuccessWithBindings, so an unbound ?v delays not binds; (2) the caller-var delay pre-check (body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes) delays the whole rule BEFORE the body runs when a builtin's first arg is an unbound caller var, so an unbound-var query residualizes. DECISION NEEDED (stop-and-ask): should eq(?v, expr) in a rule body UNIFY (bind an unbound flex operand to the other evaluated operand) + relax the caller-var pre-check, OR stay a pure Bool test (bind via an earlier goal / a future let form)? Either touches core SLD/NAF semantics. Relates to WI-483. Acceptance: TBD per decision; cargo-test green. SCOPE: resolver, Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-482"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T10:56:36Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-517", description: some(value: "Grammar: support type-annotated lambda binders (lambda (x: T) -> ..., lambda (acc: A, elem: B) -> ...). The parser currently REJECTS type annotations in lambda patterns: grammar.js _pattern = pattern_constructor/tuple/literal/wildcard/var has no 'name: Type' form, and pattern_tuple requires >=2 elements, so even a single typed binder '(u: Unit)' fails to parse ('syntax error near x: Int64'). kernel-language.md 4.7 DOCUMENTED these forms (lambda (u: Unit) -> body as the nullary-thunk recommendation; lambda (acc: A, elem: B) -> add(acc, elem) as typed tuple destructuring) but they were unparseable; the docs were corrected to match the grammar under WI-516 (nullary thunk = 'lambda () -> body'; lambda tuple binders untyped, types inferred from the expected arrow type). This WI restores the doc-intended FEATURE: allow optional ': Type' annotations on lambda binders. EMPIRICAL STATE (probed 2026-06-19): 'lambda x -> e' OK, 'lambda () -> e' OK (nullary thunk), 'lambda (a, b) -> e' OK (untyped tuple), 'lambda (x: T) -> e' PARSE ERROR, 'lambda (a: A, b: B) -> e' PARSE ERROR. SCOPE: tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js (extend the lambda param pattern to accept typed binders -- a dedicated typed-binder pattern, or allow field_decl as a tuple element), regenerate parser (parser.c is gitignored, build regens), parse/convert.rs lowering to carry each annotation into the lambda param's type so it constrains inference, corpus tests (tree-sitter-anthill/test/corpus/expressions.txt) + a typer test that an annotated binder type-checks and conflicts LOUDLY on a body/annotation mismatch. Motivation: annotations let a lambda be written without an expected-type context (e.g. a bare 'let f = lambda (x: Int64) -> x') and document intent in foldLeft-style callbacks. Discovered while building the WI-516 graded Delay instance."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T16:11:09Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-513", author: "user", content: "WI-518 (carrier-neutral guard lowering) changed the shape this WI targets: lower_logical_query now returns Vec<Value> (not Result<Vec<TermId>,GuardGated>), and the silent fall-through the unknown-ctor case lands in is now lower_logical_query's '_ => vec![lq.clone()]' plus evaluate_guard's catch-all '_ => true' and bare-leaf '=> true' (value_goal_term/leaf_goal were removed). WI-518 code review (2 angles) surfaced that the gap now ALSO covers OCCURRENCE leaves whose TermView head is non-resolvable — ViewHead::Bottom (Expr::Bottom) or ViewHead::Opaque (Lambda/If/Let/Within control-flow, Rigid/DeBruijn-var occurrences; term_view.rs occ_head ~lines 287/302). Such a leaf matches nothing in resolve_goals -> 0 solutions -> a no_q/lone_q (min==0) silently Holds, loading the KB with the invariant unenforced and no diagnostic (CLAUDE.md 'loud error over silent skip'). The deleted WI-514 GuardGated/ConstraintGated path used to make this load-blocking. Cannot arise from the loader today (it builds only Value::Term guards, and constraint leaves are always relational Constructor/Apply patterns, never opaque), so it is a latent/dormant gap — but the consolidation onto execute.rs::lower_query should reject a non-goal-shaped (opaque/Bottom-headed) leaf uniformly for BOTH carriers, not just unknown term ctors.", at: "2026-06-19T16:08:13Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-518", description: some(value: "Port the guard lowering from Vec<TermId> to carrier-neutral Vec<Value>, so occurrence (Value::Node) guard leaves RESOLVE instead of being gated. WHAT: change lower_logical_query (kb/mod.rs) to return Vec<Value> instead of Vec<TermId>; pass each LogicalQuery leaf through as a Value (Term OR Node) rather than extracting a TermId via value_goal_term/leaf_goal; build the not(goal) wrapper (negation arm + eval_forall_guard) as Value::Entity{functor: not, pos:[goal]} instead of self.alloc(Term::Fn{not}); have eval_count_guard/eval_forall_guard/eval_negation_guard feed resolve_goals(Vec<Value>) / resolve_lazy_goals instead of the term-based resolve(&[TermId]). WHY NOW: guard STORAGE (Guard.query) is already carrier-agnostic Value via TermView, and the resolver CORE is already Vec<Value> (resolve_lazy_goals canonical; Frame.goals: Vec<Value>; candidate match via query_view/match_view; Value::Node goals reify on demand via reify_goal_value at term/identity boundaries only). The Vec<TermId> in lower_logical_query is a guard-engine-local LEGACY bottleneck from WI-023 (pre carrier-agnostic resolver) and is the SOLE reason occurrence guard leaves must be gated (WI-514). EFFECT: once occurrence guard goals resolve, WI-514's gating dissolves — GuardGated / LoadError::ConstraintGated / the assert_checked panic become unreachable and should be removed. PREREQUISITES for SOUNDNESS: (a) WI-486 cross-carrier Value::structural_eq (Term vs structurally-equal Node/Entity must compare EQUAL); (b) the WI-246/WI-482 occurrence-goal SLD-eval cluster (match path works; builtin eval over occurrences partial — WI-486 eq-bind, WI-487 method-fold). APPROACH: spike FIRST — build an occurrence self-loop constraint (no ?p -: edge(from:?p,to:?p)) with denoted/Value::Node leaves, lower via the new Vec<Value> path, feed resolve_goals, confirm it resolves end-to-end (matches a real self-loop data fact, excludes non-self-loops). If clean, port + remove the gate; else scope the gaps. ACCEPTANCE: lower_logical_query returns Vec<Value>; an occurrence-leaf guard resolves through resolve_goals (no GuardGated); WI-514 gating removed or provably unreachable; full cargo-test green incl. WI-023 + wi514_guard_gating_tests (gated-shape tests updated to assert resolution). DEPENDS: WI-486. RELATES: WI-514, WI-246/WI-482/WI-487. SCOPE: resolver + guard engine, Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-486"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude-opus", at: "2026-06-19T16:08:31Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-395", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-19. unclaim/preopen/promote already existed (WI-310 + follow-up); the remaining scope was the GENERAL correction route: 'update --status <Status> [--reason R]' (case-insensitive) sets ANY WorkStatus in one atomic replace, stamping agent+now like claim/deliver (Claimed/Delivered), now only (Verified), or nothing (Open/PreOpened/Draft, clearing the claimant); Rejected/ProposalRejected/Stale carry (--reason, now) and REQUIRE --reason. id/depends_on/tags preserved. Loud errors (exit 2, no write) on unknown status, missing --reason, and (per /code-review) a stray --reason on a non-reason/absent status. Classification centralized in status_for -> UpdateStatus result sort (status_ok/needs_reason/reason_unused/unknown) — no string-fallback, no dup. GOTCHA: a locally-defined sort field typed WorkStatus needs 'import anthill.stage0.{WorkStatus}' (the type), not just its constructors — unresolved field type is only a WARNING but silently broke the store atomic replace (append-without-retract). Files: rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill + tests/cmd_update_status_test.rs (11 tests). Full workspace green (2122).", at: "2026-06-19T16:47:00Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-395", description: some(value: "anthill-todo CLI: let `update` CHANGE a work item's status (or add an `unclaim`/`reopen` subcommand). Today the only status transitions are claim -> deliver -> verify; there is NO way to revert Claimed -> Open (un-claim) or otherwise correct a status, and `update` explicitly PRESERVES status (only edits description/acceptance). Surfaced 2026-06-05 resequencing WI-374: it was Claimed, then deferred behind WI-376, leaving it Claimed-but-blocked with no CLI way to reopen -> had to hand-edit anthill-todo/workitems.anthill (status: Claimed(...) -> Open). FIX: add `update --status <Open|Claimed|...>` and/or an `unclaim`/`reopen` command; preserve id/depends_on/tags; set/clear agent+timestamp consistently with claim/deliver. Bundle lives in rustland/anthill-todo (anthill bundle + src/main.rs shim)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-19T16:47:08Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-002", description: some(value: "implement rust embedding. Design: see docs/proposals/029-rust-mapping-split.md (split by direction-of-truth into bootstrap + anthill-rust-gen + rust-anthill-gen workspace). Mapping spec: docs/rust-forward-mapping.md."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: PreOpened)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-513", description: some(value: "Guard-eval completeness: lower_logical_query (kb/mod.rs) is a partial re-implementation of execute.rs::lower_query. It handles only pattern_query/conjunction/empty_query/negation and dispatches by resolve_sym(functor).to_string() string-compare; unknown LogicalQuery constructors (disjunction, sort_query, guarded, projected, limited, and the aggregation/quantifier ctors) silently fall through to '_ => value_goal_term(lq)' (treated as one opaque goal) instead of a loud not-yet-supported error. Also the multi-goal 'negation' branch returns inner goals UN-negated (dormant today). Consolidate onto the existing, more complete + loud execute.rs::lower_query (or share a single lowerer), comparing interned LogicalQuerySymbols instead of allocating a String per node. Surfaced by WI-023 code review."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude-opus", at: "2026-06-19T17:57:14Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-040", author: "user", content: "Reframed 2026-06-19 (from \"eliminate global imports\"). Since filing, WI-476 deleted the resolve_by_short_name fallback and chose global-import-into-_global for the kernel vocab, paying for it with a collision blocklist. This narrows WI-040 to the principled half (Part A: converter provenance, kills the blocklist) and splits out two siblings: Part B (type-directed cons/nil) is ALREADY direct via build_list_with_tail->resolve_symbol and typer make_sort_ref_by_name, so nothing to do; Part C (bare user-written names) is the Prelude decision, filed separately. The original feedback \"build cons chains directly in the loader\" has the wrong shape post-WI-007/285/393: collection literals are type-dependent, so the converter keeps a neutral carrier and a type-directed consumer lowers it.", at: "2026-06-19T19:49:33Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-040", author: "user", content: "Scala mirror (design-doc open question 2): scaland mirrors the loader, but per the dual-impl notes its converter is largely dead and it has no native typer / does not load operations. So WI-040 likely needs NO scaland change — but VERIFY, do not assume: check whether scalands desugaring/load path global-imports kernel vocab the way rustland does; if it does, apply the same node-keyed provenance there; if its converter is a no-op for this, record that and move on. Do this within WI-040, not as a separate ticket.", at: "2026-06-20T08:17:05Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-040", author: "user", content: "DERISK (claude 2026-06-20, read-only): the design doc over-specifies. There are TWO loader paths handling kernel vocab, with DIFFERENT current mechanisms. (1) OP-BODY path build_load/LoadBuildFrame: the synthesized Expr/Pattern frames (MatchExpr/IfExpr/LetExpr/Lambda/Pattern*/DotApply) are built from ExprBuilderSyms (load.rs ~4785), a struct populated by DIRECT kb.resolve_symbol(\"anthill.reflect.Expr.match_expr\") — i.e. it ALREADY does provenance, frame-structurally (the frame variant says \"synthesized\"), and does NOT use the _global imports. NOTHING TO DO here; the design doc claim \"the occurrence path needs the same node-keyed guard\" is WRONG. (2) RULE/FACT TERM path convert_term_with_expected (~5334, remap_symbol at ~5425): resolves synthesized field_access (x.f), dot_apply, and the literal carriers as generic Term::Fn via remap_symbol -> _global import. THIS is the only path needing node-keyed provenance (name alone cannot distinguish synthesized field_access from a user identifier). So WI-040 minimal scope = node-keyed provenance for the convert_term synthesized subset (field_access/dot_apply/carriers), MIRRORING what ExprBuilderSyms already does structurally for op-bodies — possibly reuse the same resolved-symbol cache. The Expr/Pattern CONSTRUCTOR names in KERNEL_VOCAB are defined in reflect.anthill self-scope with no stdlib rule naming them bare (grep), so deleting their _global import is likely safe — but CONFIRM against the reflect.typing_pass reflection rules first. NEXT: update the design doc Production/Consumption sections to the two-path model before coding.", at: "2026-06-20T08:21:18Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-519", author: "user", content: "DECIDED 2026-06-19 (design; not yet impl; STOP-AND-ASK satisfied). NOT 'make eq bind'. Resolution = a language-level test/unify split: '=' stays the equality TEST (prelude Eq op, dispatched, -> Bool, never binds, NAF-safe); NEW '<=>' = unify (kernel resolver primitive anthill.kernel.unify, beside push_choice/prop-033; structural-only, never dispatches, binds either side, symmetric; derives a computed operand via reduce_operand then unifies). Deep reason vs auto-bind: binding is a resolver substitution-effect a layer below a dispatched prelude op (auto-bind=layer violation). Radius-3 migration: every is_equation rule head (=->'<=>') incl. prelude lt=gt-flip/neq=not(eq)/[simp]/[unfold]; classification-driven so contracts (ensures eq), constraints, body guards stay '='. '<=>' symmetric, firing direction from the [simp] tag (citable both ways via using). ALSO add let ?v=expr / ':=' as directed sugar over ?v <=> expr (one primitive, two surfaces). NAF: static allowedness for '<=>' (var under not bound positively first -> load-time loud error) + undischarged-residual honesty (undischarged =/<=> must NOT count as a solution -> the original WI-519 '1 solution was a residual' bug). Lexing: '<=>' greedy before '<=' in tree-sitter+fastparse; scaland mirrors grammar+loader (no typer). Next artifact = proposal 049. Decision detail in memory project_wi519_eq_unify_split.", at: "2026-06-19T19:58:24Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-040", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20. Reserved-name direct resolution (simplest design-doc approach), NOT node-keyed provenance — no ParsedFile change, no converter side-table. CHANGES (load.rs): (1) deleted register_kernel_vocab_imports+call; KERNEL_VOCAB_QUALIFIED now backs kernel_vocab_qualified(name)->Option<&str> short->qualified lookup; added the 3 literal carriers to the list. (2) remap_name_str NotFound branch resolves reserved vocab directly via that lookup (FALLBACK precedence: only past scope resolution, user names win; before forbid_if_internal/bare-intern). (3) removed carrier _global add_import (define kept — registers in by_qualified_name); dropped unused let bindings. (4) deleted the collision-blocklist comment (kind/fields/rules/kb/constructor/not are NOT converter-synthesized per grep, never in the list, stay explicit-import; nothing left in _global to guard). CODE REVIEW (3 agents xhigh): found a REAL regression — query path (resolve_name_in_kb_opt via convert_query_term) lacked the fallback, so a bare reserved name in a query silently bare-interned post-removal; FIXED with the same fallback there (uniform reserved semantics; narrow, does not reopen WI-476 query strictness). Dismissed: None-fall-through matches prior behavior; missing qualified_visible() is a justified asymmetry (reserved vocab all public, never internal). TESTS: wi040_reserved_vocab_test.rs (bare field_access + ListLiteral query resolve to qualified reflect home; precedence invariant documented). Full workspace GREEN 2124 (+2). Scala mirror NOT touched/verified (scaland has no native typer) — flag if diverges. WI-521 owns residual _global user-facing names.", at: "2026-06-20T09:14:42Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-040", description: some(value: "Resolve converter-synthesized kernel vocab DIRECTLY to its reserved qualified namespace, eliminating the _global imports + collision blocklist. The synthesized vocab already lives in reserved homes: anthill.reflect.* (Expr/Pattern ctors, field_access, dot_apply, occurrence_*), anthill.prelude.List.* (cons/nil), anthill.kernel.*. APPROACH (reserved-name, NOT node-keyed provenance — see docs/design/kernel-vocab-provenance.md \"Primary approach 2026-06-20\"): path 1 (op-body build_load) ALREADY resolves these direct via ExprBuilderSyms (load.rs ~4785, kb.resolve_symbol(FQN)); generalize that to path 2 (convert_term_with_expected ~5334/5425) — for the names convert_term itself synthesizes (field_access from x.f, dot_apply, the literal carriers ListLiteral/SetLiteral/TupleLiteral) resolve via a direct name->qualified map instead of remap_symbol. Then DELETE register_kernel_vocab_imports/KERNEL_VOCAB_QUALIFIED, the carrier _global imports (~2404-2406), and the blocklist (kind/fields/rules/kb/constructor exclusion ~765-770). No ParsedFile change, no converter side-table. Safe because the converter-synthesized names are kernel-owned (non-shadowable, accepted) and the user-definable blocklist names are NOT synthesized (grep: convert.rs never interns kind/fields/etc.; they stay explicit-import). CONFIRM before deleting: no reflect.typing_pass rule names the Expr/Pattern ctors bare via the _global import. OUT OF SCOPE: cons/nil already direct via build_list/typer (Part B); user-facing names incl. operator targets -> Prelude (WI-521). Node-keyed provenance kept in the doc only as a fallback escape hatch (unused by the current vocab)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T09:14:44Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-527", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 7 (docs). Update docs/kernel-language.md (Eq/Ordered/Numeric examples, rule-semantics section) and proposal 043 (lhs = rhs becomes lhs <=> rhs) to reflect the `=` test vs `<=>` unify split."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-523", "WI-526"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-528", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 8 (scaland mirror). Mirror in scaland: grammar (`<=>` + `let`, greedy lex before `<=`) + loader (`<=>`/unify recognition, `let` desugar, the = to <=> migration). No typer (scaland has none). Verify with sbt test."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-522", "WI-526"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-519", author: "claude", content: "Implementation mapping (proposal 049 sequence, 2026-06-20): this ticket = 049 build step 1, the residual-honesty fix [R] — an undischarged flex `=`/`<=>`/goal must stop counting as a solution (Solution.residual / NAF-groundness), without breaking legit delay-and-rotate. Decision-free, independent of `<=>`, lands first. Rest of 049 filed: WI-522 grammar -> WI-523 kernel unify -> {WI-524 let, WI-525 NAF, WI-526 migration, WI-527 docs} -> WI-528 scaland. Typed half parked: WI-502 design / WI-292 impl.", at: "2026-06-20T09:38:37Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-521", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20. Reused the WI-040 fallback mechanism (user decision), NOT a literal import edge. Added PRELUDE_QUALIFIED list + prelude_qualified() helper; combined with kernel_vocab_qualified into ONE pub(crate) implicit_qualified(name) — the single lowest-precedence fallback source. Removed ALL flat add_import(_global,...) of user-facing names: cons/nil/some/none, arithmetic/comparison (eq/neq/gt/lt/gte/lte/add/sub/mul/to_bigint/to_int), logic operators not/or, push_choice, and the *Info reflection sorts. Wired implicit_qualified into THREE resolution entry points: remap_name_str (loader), resolve_name_in_kb_opt (query patterns), KnowledgeBase::resolve_name_in_global (mod.rs, the anthill-stl reflect bridge). KEY PROPERTY: prelude/reflection names now resolve at LOWEST precedence — a user local/import ALWAYS wins and the name can never go AMBIGUOUS against a user name (the WI-476 blocklist footgun is gone). SURPRISES (caught by suite, not assumptions): (1) push_choice IS named bare outside kernel.anthill (push_choice_test) -> added to fallback (it is a global language primitive, per the old \"globally visible\" comment); (2) the *Info sorts are queried bare by the reflect BRIDGE via resolve_name_in_global — a THIRD resolution path I had to wire — so *Info went into the fallback too (a reflection vocabulary), not explicit-import-only as first attempted. `not`->reflect.not conflation kept INTACT (deferred, own ticket). TESTS: wi521_prelude_test.rs (user eq shadows prelude WITHOUT ambiguity; bare add/eq resolve without import). CODE REVIEW (2 agents): both clean []. No short-name dups across the two lists. Full workspace GREEN 2126 (+2).", at: "2026-06-20T10:00:07Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-521", description: some(value: "Build a real, named, shadowable anthill.prelude module, implicitly imported into every namespace via a genuine import edge, REPLACING the entire flat add_import(_global,...) injection (load.rs ~2393-2436 AND the kernel-builtin block ~2408-2417). This WI owns the fate of EVERY name still flat-injected into _global after WI-040 removes the converter-vocab (which moves to node-keyed provenance). Each residual name either joins the Prelude or becomes an explicit stdlib import. Inventory: (1) bare constructors cons/nil/some/none; (2) math/comparison operator targets add/sub/mul/eq/neq/lt/gt/gte/lte (pratt.rs ~50-58 infix desugaring of +/-/*/=/!=/<); (3) LOGIC operator targets not (!/word not), neg (prefix -), or (|/word or) — these are pratt prefix/infix ops too, but point at KERNEL/reflect primitives (reflect.not = NAF, kernel.or = disjunction), not Prelude math; (4) push_choice (anthill.kernel, NOT surface-emitted — named bare by the stdlib `or` rule body: or(?a,?b):-push_choice(?a,?b)); (5) the *Info / *Literal reflection-result sorts (SortInfo/FieldInfo/OperationInfo/EntityInfo/..., named bare by reflection/generated code). DECIDED 2026-06-19: math operators resolve via the Prelude, NOT provenance (Haskell model: 1+2 is Prelude-dependent; one source for every user-nameable name; a local eq shadows Prelude eq; Numeric.add still dispatches to user instances under +). DECISION STILL OPEN within this WI: the `not` CONFLATION — `!x` boolean negation (should be Bool.not, a dispatched spec op) vs `not(goal)` negation-as-failure (reflect.not, a logic primitive) currently BOTH desugar to the single functor `not` -> reflect.not; decide whether to split them. Sequenced after WI-040 (so _global then holds ONLY these user-facing/residual names, nothing kernel-internal). See docs/design/kernel-vocab-provenance.md section C."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-040"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T10:00:09Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-524", author: "claude", content: "SUBSUMED by WI-522 (delivered 2026-06-20). The `let ?v = expr` -> `unify(?v, expr)` desugar landed in the PARSE layer (parse/convert.rs convert_let_binding), NOT the loader — because that is exactly where every operator desugars (pratt.rs lowers `<=>` and all infix ops in parse/). Grammar `let_binding` + shared `_goal` rule; converter lowers body `let` to unify and rejects `let` in rule heads (loud). Verified: parse_test let/<=>->unify + corpus tests + full anthill-core suite green. No separate loader work needed; closing as Delivered.", at: "2026-06-20T10:31:51Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-525", author: "claude", content: "Scope note from WI-522 code-review (2026-06-20): the grammar now lets `<=>`/`let` (binding) parse in ensures/requires/constraint bodies too (they all share rule_body). Proposal 049 mandates contracts TEST (`=`), never bind. WI-525 static-allowedness should also reject a BINDING `<=>`/`let` in a postcondition/constraint position (not just under `not`), or confirm the residual-honesty backstop covers it.", at: "2026-06-20T10:31:55Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-524", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 4 (let sugar). Desugar `let ?v = expr` to `?v <=> expr` in the loader (one primitive, directed surface). `:=` is RESERVED for Cell.set, not a let surface (proposal 037). Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-522", "WI-523"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T10:31:59Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-522", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 2 (grammar). Add `<=>` (kernel unify) and `let ?v = expr` to the grammar: tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js + scaland fastparse. `<=>` lexed greedy-longest BEFORE `<=` (lte) so `a <= b` is lte and `a <=> b` is unify. Corpus tests (tree-sitter test/corpus) + rustland parse tests. Implements proposal 049; no deps."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T10:32:02Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-523", author: "claude", content: "Handoff pointers (from WI-522 delivery 2026-06-20). READ FIRST: proposal 049 sections \"<=> as anthill.kernel.unify\" (the 7-step lazy semantics) + \"Two faces of one search\". The parser ALREADY emits `unify(a, b)` terms (pratt.rs maps `<=>` -> functor unify; convert.rs convert_let_binding lowers `let ?v=e` -> unify(?v,e)). WI-523 makes `unify` RESOLVE. CODE MAP (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/): (1) builtin dispatch = execute_builtin (resolve.rs ~1627) by BuiltinTag; add a Unify tag + bind anthill.kernel.unify in register_standard_builtins. (2) Mirror builtin_eq / eq_operands (resolve.rs ~2442/2478) but BIND not test: eq calls values_equal = views_structurally_equal (resolve.rs:2470, a TEST); unify must return SuccessWithBindings via finish_result + ResultTarget::Bind (resolve.rs:2600). (3) per-node head-normalize = reduce_operand (resolve.rs:3075 = reduce_dot_value + reduce_op_value, head-directed only); is_unreduced_op_call -> Delay. (4) RELAX caller-var pre-check for `<=>`: body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes (resolve.rs:3134) must NOT pre-residualize a bare-var first operand. (5) unify-as-search precedent: match_view/match_term (mod.rs:2008) = single-pattern discrim search -> Option<Substitution> (one-sided MATCH; `<=>` = two-sided generalization). (6) `<=>`-equation recognition: is_equation / eq_functor / apply_eq_rules (resolve.rs:1506) + typer try_fire (simp_rewrite.rs:271, rules_by_functor scan) must treat `<=>`-headed empty-body rules as equations. (7) reflect.unify face: reflect Substitution sort (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:561, apply/compose/lookup) + Term bridge; add operation unify(a:Term,b:Term,kb)->Option[Substitution] wrapping builtin_unify (return sigma as data). OPEN: occurs-check (confirm Substitution::bind occurs-checks, else add). NAF allowedness = WI-525. scaland mirror = WI-528. Test via rustland/scripts/test.sh.", at: "2026-06-20T10:40:11Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-523", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20 (commit 121447d). builtin_unify (lazy, occurs-checked, rigid/DeBruijn-reflexive) + kernel decl + caller-var relax + is_equation/unify_functor/apply_eq_rules/try_fire recognition + reflect.unify data face. 11 tests, anthill-core full suite green. Rust-only.", at: "2026-06-20T12:01:37Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-523", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 3 (kernel unify). Add `anthill.kernel.unify` decl + a lazy `builtin_unify` in the resolver: head-normalize each operand ON REACH via reduce_operand (NOT an eager derive-then-unify pass), fail-fast on functor/arity mismatch (no child reduction), bind-and-stop on a flex var with OCCURS-CHECK (`?v <=> f(?v)` is a loud failure), recurse on functor match binding sub-vars on either side; return SuccessWithBindings. Relax the caller-var pre-check (body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes) for `<=>`. Teach is_equation / eq_functor / apply_eq_rules + typer try_fire to recognize `<=>`-headed empty-body rules as equations (type-INDEPENDENT recognition; selection stays discrim-indexed via query). Also expose the term-level `reflect.unify(a: Term, b: Term, kb) -> Option[Substitution]` face (thin wrapper returning the substitution from builtin_unify as data, for reflection and the WI-010 self-hosted typer). Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-522"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T12:01:42Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-526", author: "user", content: "HANDOFF from WI-523: recognition machinery is ready (is_equation/apply_eq_rules/try_fire accept unify; selection queries both eq+unify functors). BUT a source-level `<=>`-headed equation only indexes under anthill.kernel.unify if its head functor RESOLVES there. scan_rule_goal mints a fresh <ns>.unify Goal shadow for an unimported `unify` head (resolve_in_scope NotFound), hiding the equation. So migrated equations must reach canonical unify in scope — author them where `unify` is imported/reachable (the same way stdlib `=` equations sit in scopes where `eq` is reachable). DO NOT fix via a global scan_rule_goal skip for reserved names: I tried (skip fresh-Goal when implicit_qualified name exists) and it was (a) a regression — user predicate rules with reserved-name heads silently route to the kernel/prelude symbol (builtin shadows the user body; `or` merges with kernel disjunction), and (b) FLAKY — the by_qualified_name existence check at scan time gave non-deterministic results in the full test binary (passed isolation, failed full-binary intermittently; root cause undiagnosed). Prefer explicit import, or a load-time LOUD diagnostic on reserved-name head collision. Also note: apply_eq_rules (resolver path) does NOT open a rule's DeBruijn vars, so a variable-RHS equation leaves vars unthreaded there — the typer try_fire path opens them correctly (pre-existing, shared with `=`).", at: "2026-06-20T12:02:07Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-525", author: "user", content: "CODE-MAP HANDOFF (prepared 2026-06-20, post WI-523). Dep WI-523 DELIVERED. Design = proposal 049 'NAF discipline for <=>': PRIMARY = static load-time allowedness; backstop = residual-honesty (WI-519, still Open, but PRIMARY is independent). NO existing static NAF check today (only runtime step_naf groundness, resolve.rs ~1032); ZERO <=> goals under not in-tree yet (WI-526 migrates) so the check fires on nothing now = forward-scaffolding, low regression risk.\nTWO PARTS: (A) a var in a <=> (unify) goal UNDER not(...) must be bound by an earlier positive goal -> loud LoadError. (B) a binding <=>/let (lowers to unify(?v,e)) in an ensures/requires/constraint body -> loud LoadError (contracts TEST via =, never bind). [B RECOMMENDED 'know errors early'; WI-519 backstop is the fallback if deferred.]\nRECOMMENDED APPROACH - operate on the BUILT occurrence body (resolved functors), NOT parse-time names: Hook load_rule (load.rs:9512); after the body loop ~9549 builds body_nodes: Vec<Rc<NodeOccurrence>> (each via build_body_atom_occurrence:6889, which remaps unify->anthill.kernel.unify, not->anthill.reflect.not). Classify each node via kb.get_builtin_view(node) (mod.rs:3908) -> Some(BuiltinTag::Not)/Some(Unify) (same classifier the resolver uses).\nPART A algo: scan body_nodes L->R with bound:HashSet<VarId>. Positive goal -> add its vars (collect_occurrence_global_vars, node_occurrence.rs:1830). A Not goal -> recurse under its pos_arg(0) occurrence to find EVERY nested Unify (a not may wrap a compound), collect each unify's global vars, require subset of bound else error. Do NOT add the not's vars to bound.\nSEMANTICS NUANCE: proposal says 'EARLIER positive goal' (strict L->R). But anthill ROTATES/delays goals so a var bound by a LATER positive goal may still bind before the not runs -> order-independent range-restriction (var in SOME positive goal) is the looser classic alt. Moot today; pick strict-L->R per the proposal, revisit in WI-526 if a migrated rule false-positives.\nPART B locations: Operation requires/ensures = ir.rs Operation.requires/ensures: Vec<Vec<TermId>> (~384/385), load_operation (~9744; convert ~9940-9941). Constraint = ir.rs Constraint.body: ConstraintBody (~440; enum ~449 Denial/Quantified/Patterns/Aggregation), load_constraint (~10153). Check: any Unify-classified goal in those bodies -> error (let covered since it lowers to unify).\nPLUMBING: LoadError enum (load.rs:122) add UnsafeNegatedUnify{var_name,span}+BindingInContract{position,span}; format_with_source (:334) add Display arms; is_load_blocking (:452) mark both blocking. Tests: tests/include/parse_test.rs pattern (load->expect_err->filter matches! on variant); add wi525 cases (negated-unify-unbound->error; bound-first->ok; let/unify in ensures->error). Acceptance cargo-test. Rust-only (scaland has no typer/this-check).", at: "2026-06-20T12:12:39Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-525", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20 (uncommitted). Static NAF/contract discipline for <=> in rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs. Part A (check_negated_unify_allowedness, hooked in load_rule after body_nodes built): scans built occurrence body L->R; a unify under not(...) whose vars aren't bound by an EARLIER positive goal -> LoadError::UnsafeNegatedUnify. Classifies via kb.get_builtin_view (canonical anthill.kernel.unify / anthill.reflect.not, NOT parse spelling); collect_negated_unify_violations DFS-walks the not subtree (nested not transparent, finds every nested unify). Part B (reject_binding_unify_in_contract; load_operation requires/ensures + load_constraint via collect_constraint_body_goal_tids): a top-level unify goal in a contract -> LoadError::BindingInContract (let covered, lowers to unify). Both variants: Display + format_with_source + is_load_blocking. DESIGN NOTE: NO anonymous-var exemption -- every var counts incl. ? and ?_ (both intern to '_', indistinguishable by name; and anthill NAF requires a ground inner goal per step_naf, so any unbound var flounders). This matches the handoff algo ('require subset of bound') exactly. Strict L->R per proposal; head vars do NOT seed bound (Datalog safety) -> WI-526 revisit if migration false-positives. /code-review (max): 1 confirmed bug found (named ?_ wrongly exempted) + FIXED by removing exemption; other notes accepted by-design. 10 tests in tests/include/wi525_naf_allowedness_test.rs; full anthill-core 1804/0/3 green.", at: "2026-06-20T12:55:03Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-525", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 5 (NAF allowedness). Static load-time check for `<=>` under negation: a variable in a `<=>` under `not` must be bound by an earlier positive goal, else a loud load-time error (know errors early). Backstop is the undischarged-residual honesty (WI-519). Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-523"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T12:55:06Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-529", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED (commits 8cc3897 + review-fix 908579a; full workspace green, merged with proposal-049 WI-522/523/525). MECHANISM (op-body vs resolver): op body EVALUATED -> not/or/and = dispatched Bool VALUE ops (eval builtins); rule body RESOLVED -> not/or stay reflect.not NAF / kernel.or disjunction (no eval builtin, so a Bool op can never be an SLD goal — why neq/NAF/disjunction MUST stay primitives). Loader.in_op_body_value (convert_expr_term, entry debug_assert) + POST-RESOLUTION redirect in remap_name_str (reflect.not->Bool.not, kernel.or->Bool.or AFTER resolution, so it beats an explicit import anthill.reflect.{not} Found-shadow; user own not/or = different symbol, untouched). Bool.and + Numeric.neg in PRELUDE_QUALIFIED. numeric.anthill: Numeric.neg + neg_def; numeric_neg eval builtin. Repaired pre-existing broken op-body and/not (cli/parse.anthill, lf1). TEST wi529_boolean_operator_split_test.rs (4). REVIEW (high; 3 finders+verify): import-shadow CONFIRMED+FIXED via the redirect; rest refuted/hardening. DEFERRED: prefix `-x` on NON-literals — `-` in tree-sitter _prefix_op COLLIDES with negative-literal lexing (/-?[0-9]+/), broke eq(state.seq,-1) in lf1, generate did NOT flag it -> REVERTED; use neg(x) + negative literals; a real `-x` op needs unifying with negative-literal lexing (broad blast radius), separate grammar task. GOTCHA: grammar.js change leaves a stale tree-sitter rlib in workspace cargo test -> cargo clean -p tree-sitter-anthill. scaland NOT mirrored.", at: "2026-06-20T13:02:42Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-529", description: some(value: "Split the boolean-operator / logic-primitive conflation (not/or/and) + route prefix-neg; deferred from WI-521. DECISION + detail in docs/design/kernel-vocab-provenance.md section C.1 — no new proposal (boolean-family analogue of proposal 049 (= vs <=>): dispatched value op vs resolver primitive). Bool.not/and/or ALREADY EXIST (bool.anthill + bool_not/and/or builtins) so MOST is RESOLUTION ROUTING. DISAMBIGUATE BY SYNTACTIC POSITION: op-body value -> Bool.X; rule-body goal -> resolver primitive. (1) not -> Bool.not vs reflect.not (NAF); (2) or -> Bool.or vs kernel.or (disjunction); (3) and -> Bool.and (goal conjunction is the comma); (4) neg (prefix -) -> Numeric.neg. ONLY NEW STDLIB: Numeric.neg op + default neg(?a)=sub(zero-val,?a). See WI-521 feedback + design doc C.1."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T13:02:44Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-238", description: some(value: "WI-238 DECISION: resolved as option (B) — KEEP the WI-243 NodeOccurrence-synthesis substrate. A real production consumer materialized after this ticket was filed, so the keep/drop question is settled in favor of keep and no code change is required by this ticket. Background: at filing time the substrate (NodeOccurrence::synthesized_expr, PassId, OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized, kb.register_pass) had exactly one caller — its own unit test — and the originally-intended consumer was moot. That original motivation was to wrap each req_insertion-emitted Term::Fn with a Synthesized origin so an unbound-var-in-requirement eval error could point at a source span; post WI-247/248/251 the eval instead reads real Apply NodeOccurrences from kb.op_bodies (with their own spans) and synthesizes the requirements channel at runtime via expand_dispatching_dict, never touching the emitter output, which now lives only in the test-only kb.dispatch_rewrites / dispatch_origin side-tables (the interpreter never reads it). What changed: the typer-phase [simp] rewriting engine (kb/simp_rewrite.rs; WI-277 / WI-278 / WI-283; proposal 043) became a full production consumer of the substrate. It calls kb.register_pass(anthill.kb.passes.simp_rewrite) to obtain a PassId and builds every rewritten RHS via NodeOccurrence::synthesized_expr carrying OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized { from, by }, so when a [simp] equation fires LHS->RHS over an operation body the synthesized RHS inherits the redex source span plus provenance. The substrate is additionally consumed across kb/typing.rs and kb/node_occurrence.rs. Consequences: option (A) drop is off the table — deleting synthesized_expr / OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized / register_pass / PassId now breaks the typer. Option (C) speculative req_insertion emitter migration is NOT done and stays out of scope: still no consumer, and dispatch_origin remains test-only (consumers wi204 / wi218 / wi222 / wi227 / wi231 / wi237 only). The consumer the substrate found is essentially the (B) outcome this ticket predicted (a pass that lifts forms into more primitive Expr with synthesized origin), realized as the [simp] equational rewriter rather than a let/match lift. Acceptance met: decision recorded (B); workspace cargo-test green independent of this ticket (the substrate ships with its [simp] consumer); description updated to match what shipped. Closed as Delivered."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-243"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T13:18:04Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-530", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20 (uncommitted), prerequisite of WI-526. Root-cause fix: scan_rule_goal (load.rs ~1338) no longer mints a per-namespace <ns>.eq / <ns>.unify Goal shadow for an equation-connective head (the =/<=> desugar) when eq/unify is not lexically in scope. Guard: skip define when (functor=='eq'||'unify') && implicit_qualified(name).is_some(). NARROW (only these two connectives -> a user predicate rule with any other reserved head like or/not still gets its Goal symbol; no WI-523 broad-skip reroute regression) and DETERMINISTIC (static implicit_qualified const, not the load-order-dependent by_qualified_name check that made the WI-523 attempt flaky). Effect: <=>/= equation heads resolve to canonical anthill.kernel.unify / anthill.prelude.Eq.eq via remap_name_str's implicit-prelude fallback -> no import needed. Empirically confirmed strange-import premise (5/8 prelude files minted unify shadows without import; eq.anthill neq would have regressed). BEHAVIOR CHANGE: activates previously-dormant (shadowed) equations in Pair/String/Int64/Float -> all strictly orienting (verified no loop); Set/List/Map non-orienting laws are requires-guarded so apply_eq_rules skips them. Full anthill-core 1805/0/3 green; independent max-effort review found NO bugs. Diagnostic: wi526_equational_migration_test asserts no <ns>.unify shadows.", at: "2026-06-20T13:43:28Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-530", description: some(value: "scan_rule_goal mints a per-namespace Goal shadow (<ns>.eq / <ns>.unify) for an equation-connective rule head (the =/<=> desugar) when eq/unify is not lexically in scope, because resolve_in_scope does not consult the implicit prelude (PRELUDE_QUALIFIED) where eq/unify live. This silently hides the equation from apply_eq_rules (which selects under the canonical functor), and means a <=> equation needs an explicit 'import anthill.kernel.{unify}' to work — strange/unintuitive since unify resolves canonically in expression position. Empirically (WI-526): 5/8 prelude files (Pair, Eq, String, Int64, Float) mint a unify shadow without the import; eq.anthill's neq even REGRESSES from canonical eq to a unify shadow under <=>. FIX: in scan_rule_goal, skip minting the shadow for eq/unify connective heads that resolve via the STATIC implicit prelude (implicit_qualified) — narrow (only eq/unify, so user predicate rules with other reserved-name heads like or/not still get their Goal symbol => no WI-523-style reroute regression) and deterministic (static const check, not the load-order-dependent by_qualified_name existence check that made the WI-523 broad attempt flaky). NOTE behavior change: activates previously-dormant (shadowed) equations in files where eq/unify was not reachable; verify full suite. Unblocks an import-free WI-526."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T13:43:31Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-526", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20 (uncommitted), depends on WI-530 (delivered). Radius-3 migration: 40 empty-body equational rule heads =->><=> across 8 prelude files (eq, pair, set, string, map, int64, float, list), IMPORT-FREE (WI-530 makes <=> heads resolve to canonical anthill.kernel.unify). Classification-driven: guarded equations (field.anthill, list:127, map:48, logical_stream, stream head/tail/isEmpty), body-position = goals, contracts (ensures eq), and constraints all KEPT =. is_equational_head (load.rs ~4180) extended to recognize 'unify' so a migrated <=> equation stays cite-required/unindexed like its = predecessor (WI-139). Out of scope (per ticket): type-GUARDED resolver firing of requires-guarded rules = WI-292. wi526 diagnostic test (no shadow minted). Full anthill-core 1805/0/3 green; independent review verified migration complete+correct both directions and no non-termination (activated Pair/String/Int64/Float equations are orienting; Set commutativity is requires-guarded -> apply_eq_rules skips).", at: "2026-06-20T13:43:34Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-526", description: some(value: "Proposal 049 build step 6 (radius-3 migration). Migrate every is_equation rule head from `=` to `<=>` across prelude/stdlib (classification-driven: oriented rewrites + [simp]/[unfold] equations migrate; contracts (ensures eq), constraints, body guard tests STAY `=`). Needs the engine to recognize `<=>`-headed equations (WI-523). Resolver-side type-GUARDED firing of requires-guarded rules is OUT OF SCOPE (WI-292)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-523", "WI-530"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T13:43:37Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-077", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED: added anthill-core/tests/include/wi077_long_stream_stress_test.rs (registered in wi_tests.rs). Two tests drive the StreamSource::Resolver arena path at N=1000. (1) wi077_resolver_long_stream_surfaces_all_n_solutions: 1000 facts item(group:0, key:0..999), query item(group:0, key:?k) -> asserts count==N (declaration fact excluded because literal Int head can't unify with sort_ref(Int64), per kb_query_test pattern), stream_arena_live_count returns to 0 after handle drop, subst_arena_live_count stays 0 (per-yield Value::Substitution freed each iteration => no O(N) blowup). (2) wi077_mplus_over_long_branches_surfaces_all_solutions (WI-075 gate): MPlus over two 1000-fact resolver branches -> count==2N, all arena slots reclaimed via cascade. Full anthill-core suite green (810 passed/0 failed). /code-review max-effort: 0 correctness bugs (count, refcount traces, subst reclaim, declaration-fact exclusion, non-vacuity all independently verified); 1 cleanup applied (raw-string header instead of \\x20 escapes). Tests run in 0.38s -> perf does not blow up.", at: "2026-06-20T16:56:43Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-077", description: some(value: "Long-stream stress test for execute_logical_query / SearchStream: build a KB with N (>=1000) matching facts (or a recursive rule yielding N solutions), wrap the resulting SearchStream as StreamSource::Resolver, drive splitFirst to exhaustion, and assert (a) all N solutions surface, (b) stream arena slot is reclaimed (stream_arena_live_count returns to 0), (c) memory/perf does not blow up. Current coverage tops out at 3 solutions on Resolver streams (eval_m4_test.rs); infinite-stream tests only exercise StreamSource::Native, not the resolver path. Should also gate disjunction work (WI-075) so the same harness can verify MPlus over long branches."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: []), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T16:56:49Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-531", author: "user", content: "DESIGN REFINED (user, 2026-06-20): execute is ALREADY 'operation execute(kb, query) -> Stream[T = Substitution, E = Error]' (reflect.anthill:284-285) — the Error channel is the residual's home. So do NOT change the stream element type (it stays Stream[Substitution] of DEFINITE answers, per the existing API). Instead: a floundered solution RAISES Error (via the existing E=Error effect, WI-073) carrying the residual goals as data, rather than silently delivering/dropping it (eval/mod.rs:850 PumpResolver currently drops sol.residual). This is verdict-honest (floundered != a substitution answer), data-faithful (residual inspectable via the Error handler => reflect still describes core), uses the existing effect (no signature change), and is 'loud error over silent skip'. Streams compose: yield N definite substitutions, then raise Error on the floundered branch. SUPERSEDES the earlier 'stream of (subst,residual) pairs' shape — residual rides in the Error, not on every element. Likely needs an Error variant like Floundered(residual: List[Term|NodeOccurrence]). The rigid-var alternative is rejected: floundering is a trichotomy (success/fail/undecided); a substitution only encodes success-with-bindings, and rigidity (a var's unify-behavior, value-like) can't carry 'goal pending' — it collapses undecided into success (masquerade) or fail (wrong verdict, e.g. eq of distinct rigids), which is the very core/reflect divergence to avoid.", at: "2026-06-20T17:26:01Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-531", author: "user", content: "CORRECTION (user, 2026-06-20) — RETRACTS the flounder-as-Error refinement above. Undecided is NOT a runtime Error; it is a THIRD logical outcome carried as residual DATA. (1) The core already represents it as data (resolve() -> Solution.residual, never raises) — raising Error in reflect would re-diverge reflect from core. (2) E=Error on execute is for genuine Error.raise from op bodies; floundering is 'couldn't decide', conflating them is wrong. (3) DECISIVE: the WI-010 self-hosted typer (reflect's reason to exist) must COLLECT residual constraints as data to solve them; if undecided aborted as an error, inference couldn't run. So WI-531 = expose residual as DATA: the streamed answer carries (subst, residual) — i.e. execute's element type becomes a Solution-like sort (subst + residual), NOT bare Substitution; E=Error reserved for genuine errors. Each consumer then DECIDES (prover: residual=not-proved; typer: residual=pending constraints). This is bigger than flounder-as-Error (changes the stream element type / public KB.execute result) but is the faithful, typer-enabling design.", at: "2026-06-20T17:31:49Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-531", author: "user", content: "DECISION (user, 2026-06-20): the honest result type is Either INSIDE the stream — Stream[Either[Undecided, Substitution]] (equivalently Stream[T = Solution] where Solution = definite(subst) | undecided(subst, residual)), NOT Either[Undecided, Stream[Substitution]] (Either outside). Reason: Either-outside forces EAGER flounder-detection (you must know if any branch flounders before choosing Left/Right) which defeats the lazy Stream and collapses the 'one definite + one floundered' case. Either-inside is lazy and exactly faithful to core's Vec<Solution> (a Solution IS Either[Undecided(residual), Substitution] with Right = empty-residual). Each pull yields a definite Substitution OR an Undecided carrying (partial subst, residual goals). Undecided is the Left DATA case in the answer stream, NOT the E=Error channel (E=Error stays for genuine Error.raise). 'There is no stream of residuals' — the residual is per-stuck-branch; the stream is of definite-or-undecided ANSWERS. Final naming/shape (named Solution sort vs Either) is impl detail for WI-531.", at: "2026-06-20T17:40:12Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-519", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-20 (uncommitted) — residual honesty at the CORE decision boundaries. Resolver (resolve.rs): NEW ResolveConfig.definite_only (default false) + Solution::is_definite() (==residual.is_empty()); resolve_lazy_goals threads definite_only into the SearchStream config; the THREE residualize-yield sites (step_init delay-exhausted, step_init builtin-Delay single-goal, step_naf non-ground single-goal) POP+Continue (skip record+yield) when definite_only, so a floundered residual never counts toward max_solutions or masquerades as success. step_naf GROUND branch rewritten from is_some() to a THREE-WAY: pull inner (sub_config definite_only=false, max_solutions=0) until a DEFINITE solution (-> P holds -> not(P) FAILS) or exhaustion tracking inner_floundered; definite->fail, floundered->residualize not(P) (undecided propagates, skip if outer definite_only), none->succeed. Consumers set definite_only=true: prove.rs dispatch_sld (Proved only on a definite solution; floundered body falls through to existing Verdict::Unknown), and mod.rs 3 constraint guards (count/forall/negation). main.rs interactive query keeps definite_only=false (still DISPLAYS residual). Default-false keeps the residual mechanism + all residual-inspection tests (wi483, resolve.rs units, region.rs) intact. 3 tests wi519_residual_honesty_test.rs (floundered->residual-not-definite + skipped under definite_only; definite survives; NAF three-way). FULL WORKSPACE SUITE exit 0 (wi_tests 812/0/3); no regressions in NAF/constraint/prove. KEY ANALYSIS (delay-fallback, resolve.rs:1213): skipping record_solution_in_ancestors under definite_only makes child_solutions stay 0 so the fallback fires more, but each fallback replaces the ChoicePoint with an Init frame bounded by consecutive_delays -> NO infinite loop; legitimate delay-and-rotate preserved (definite_only only skips the FINAL give-up residualize, not the rotation phase). /code-review agent was unproductive (stuck on its own scratch probe, stopped) -> reviewed manually, no bugs. REFLECT data-faithfulness (undecided as Stream[Either[Undecided,Substitution]] data, NOT error) = separate WI-531.", at: "2026-06-20T18:22:14Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-519", description: some(value: "eq-binds-unbound-operand: decide + implement whether eq(?v, expr) in a computational rule body should UNIFY (bind an unbound flex operand to the other evaluated operand) + relax the body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes caller-var pre-check, OR stay a pure Bool test (bind via an earlier producer goal / a future let form). WI-482 made dispatched field_access EVALUATE (eq(7, ?p.x) succeeds once ?p.x reduces) but eq(?v, ?p.x) does NOT bind ?v: (1) resolver eq builtin (builtin_eq/eq_operands) is a TEST (structural_eq + Delay on a flex operand, never SuccessWithBindings) so an unbound ?v delays not binds; (2) the caller-var delay pre-check delays the whole rule BEFORE the body runs when a builtin first arg is an unbound caller var. Either direction touches core SLD/NAF semantics. STOP-AND-ASK before implementing. Split out of WI-486 (which became the cross-carrier structural_eq soundness fix). RELATES: WI-483, WI-486. SCOPE: resolver, Rust-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-482"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-20T18:22:19Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-084", author: "user", content: "Proposal 039 phases 1-3 DELIVERED (const grammar+loader SymbolKind::Const, fold-free typing via check_bare_ref, lazy eval-fold force_const with const_cache Forcing-sentinel + isolated-stack fold under step_cap + host reflect-builtin path, load-time conservative purity gate check_const_purity). Headline adoption: lf1 Emitter 'entity BROADCAST_CHANNEL' -> 'const BROADCAST_CHANNEL: Int64 = -1' (cpp-gen + smt-gen safety proof green; full suite 2184). REMAINING (keep open): motor velocity-mode +infinity BLOCKED (no infinity value; const codegen deferred); safety_common D_MIN/D_MAX is proposal's 'soft' fact-query case (deferred). Deferred limits: dup-const-name silent last-write-wins, no Const reflection member-fact, const codegen.", at: "2026-06-21T06:20:47Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-084", description: some(value: "Term-level named constants in anthill. Currently the language has primitive literals and entities but no way to declare a named constant of a primitive type. Workarounds (entity-as-constant + side fact, unit-sort with coercion) are clunky. Proposed shape: 'const NAME: Type = literal_expr' at namespace or sort scope, identifier-resolvable everywhere a term is expected. Drives: webots binding sentinels (CHANNEL_BROADCAST = -1, infinity-as-velocity-mode), magic numbers in the safety proof's KinematicAssumptions / DistanceBounds. Should compose with the proposal-026 expression evaluator so constant expressions can be folded at load time."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T06:48:25Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-531", author: "user", content: "DECISION FINAL (user, 2026-06-21): element type is a NAMED Solution sort, not generic Either — resolving the 'named Solution vs Either' impl-detail the 2026-06-20 decision left open. Shape: sort Solution { entity definite(subst: Substitution); entity undecided(subst: Substitution, residual: List[Term]) }. execute: Stream[T = Solution, E = Error] effects Error. KEY: keep BOTH channels for their proper meanings — undecided (couldn't-decide, floundered) is the DATA case in the stream (definite|undecided); E=Error stays RESERVED for genuine errors only (invalid query, depth limit, Error.raise from op bodies). Rationale recap (chosen over Substitution+Error[NotDecidable] effect): reflect must faithfully describe core, and core's Solution{subst,residual} never raises on flounder (resolve.rs:246, is_definite()==residual.is_empty()) — an execute that raised would re-diverge reflect from core; the WI-010 self-hosted typer must COLLECT residual as pending-constraint data; Either-INSIDE the stream stays lazy/per-branch (interleaves one-definite + one-floundered). The typed Error[NotDecidable] steelman reifies (047 Error↦Result) to exactly this Stream[Solution], so it buys nothing but forcing every caller to reify at the boundary that exists to reify. 3 deliverables: (1) element type Substitution→Solution (undecided arm carries partial subst + residual goals, NOT a bare marker); (2) stop dropping sol.residual at eval/mod.rs:850 PumpResolver, thread through kb_execute (builtins.rs:724) + logical_stream.splitFirst (665-701); (3) fix reflect.anthill:283 comment which currently documents the rejected 'residual captured by E=Error' design.", at: "2026-06-21T05:16:26Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-531", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-21 (uncommitted; agent claude). execute now -> Stream[T = Solution, E = Error] with enum Solution { definite(subst: Substitution) | undecided(subst: Substitution, residual: List[T = Term]) } (reflect.anthill) — the named-sort form of the 2026-06-20 Either-inside decision. Producer = ONE choke point Interpreter::make_solution_value (eval/mod.rs) feeding stream_split_first's resolver branch (the site that was dropping sol.residual). Residual is CARRIER-FAITHFUL: goals stay as their Value (a Value::Node keeps occurrence/span per WI-348 — deliberately NOT reified, which would drop span), surfaced as List[Term]. Field order DECLARED (subst, residual) via sort_named_canonical, not alphabetical, so positional patterns bind right (first non-alphabetical entity). E=Error reserved for genuine errors. Consumers migrated: tests kb_query/wi182/wi077 + NEW wi531_solution_residual_test (proves the undecided arm carries a non-empty residual via a Person(...) :- eq(?a,?b) flounder); anthill-stl split_first_yields_solution_values unit test; anthill-todo bundle main.anthill walk_solutions — made VERDICT-HONEST (skips undecided claimable; exhaustive match forces both arms; golden parity byte-unchanged since claimable is ground). Full workspace 2161 passed / 0 failed / 11 ignored. /code-review (4 finder agents + verify + sweep): applied 3 fixes (verdict-honest walk_solutions; functor-resolve-before-alloc leak-proofing; explicit residual-carrier docs); refuted the arena-leak finding; FILED WI-534 for the host bridge (anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs) which is a SECOND execute realization still dropping residual (distinct subsystem, no test break). Remaining follow-ups: WI-527 (docs), WI-528 (scaland), WI-534 (bridge). NOT committed (awaiting user).", at: "2026-06-21T07:30:51Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-531", description: some(value: "Reflect faithfully mirrors core query semantics: a reflect query result must carry (subst, residual) exactly like the core Solution, so reflect is a faithful DESCRIPTION of the core (the WI-010 self-hosted typer runs on reflect, so any gap = reflect lies about core). Today eval/mod.rs:850 (stream_split_first / PumpResolver) wraps sol.subst as Value::Substitution and SILENTLY DROPS sol.residual; consumers KB.execute (builtins.rs:724 kb_execute), LogicalStream.splitFirst (665-701 logical_stream_split_first). WI-519 makes the VERDICT honest at the reflect boundary (a floundered residual is not delivered as a definite answer); THIS WI adds the DATA: the reflect query result exposes the residual goals (the pending/undischarged goals) so anthill code can inspect WHICH goals floundered, matching what Rust consumers see from resolve(). Likely shape: a result sort carrying (substitution, residual: List[Term|NodeOccurrence]) OR a stream of (subst, residual) pairs; update stdlib reflect query result sort (reflect.anthill Substitution/query area) + eval PumpResolver + kb_execute/logical_stream. DESIGN NOTE (considered + rejected alt, user 2026-06-20): representing floundering by rigidifying the unfilled vars (Var::Rigid) instead of carrying the residual is NOT equivalent — it loses the pending CONSTRAINT (gt(?x,3)/not(p(?x))/nonvar collapse to 'opaque var'), conflates a floundered answer with a universally-quantified DEFINITE answer (re-introducing the masquerade), and skolemizing free vars to DECIDE a goal is unsound. Residual = first-class 'goal is pending' marker, strictly more expressive. Rust-only + stdlib."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-519"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T07:30:55Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-534", author: "user", content: "BLOCKED on WI-535 (user, 2026-06-21). Implementation began but stopped: the host bridge is PRE-TermView-migration (rust-gen written before WI-348/470/477), so 'pub type Term = TermId' (reflect/mod.rs:10) and the whole bridge reifies every term — carrying the residual as a carrier-faithful TermView would be the lone TermView spot in an all-TermId bridge, and reifying it to TermId re-introduces the exact occurrence/span loss WI-531 avoided. So WI-534 (stream Solution with a faithful residual) now DEPENDS on WI-535 (migrate the bridge + rust-gen to TermView). Releasing the claim until WI-535 lands.", at: "2026-06-21T08:21:51Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-534", description: some(value: "WI-531 follow-up: migrate the host-side reflect bridge (anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs) to stream Solution, mirroring the interpreter path. KbBridge::execute + SearchStreamAdapter (bridge.rs:358-374, ~711) is a SECOND realization of reflect.KB.execute — the host-language/codegen trait (reflect/mod.rs:50) that generated Rust implements, distinct from the interpreter's kb_execute. It still yields the bare substitution: SubstBridge::from_core(solution.subst) at bridge.rs:365/401/422 SILENTLY DROPS solution.residual, and its element type is Stream<SubstBridge, Error> (= Stream[Substitution]), now inconsistent with the spec's Stream[T = Solution] (reflect.anthill, WI-531). This is the same residual-drop + verdict-dishonesty WI-531 fixed on the interpreter side, still live on the host/codegen path (self-consistent within anthill-stl, so no test break today — its 5 tests at bridge.rs:837-909 pin the old Vec<SubstBridge> shape). NEEDS: a SolutionBridge (definite|undecided carrying SubstBridge + residual) or equivalent, SearchStreamAdapter yielding it, and updating those 5 bridge tests (execute_sort_query_finds_operations/_nonexistent_is_empty/_empty_query/_pattern_query/_limited_query). Found by /code-review cross-file tracer during WI-531. Rust-only (anthill-stl). RELATED stale doc artifacts (fold into WI-527 docs, NOT here): generated/reflect.rs:33, docs/proposals/026.1, docs/proposals/011, docs/rust-forward-mapping.md still show Stream[Substitution]."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-531", "WI-535"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Open)
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-532", description: some(value: "Float infinity as a host-supplied term-level constant. anthill currently has NO way to WRITE IEEE +infinity as a Float — it appears only in float.anthill comments (floor/ceil docs). Add 'const infinity: Float' (bodyless, host-supplied) to the prelude (float.anthill), backed by a registered reflect builtin in anthill-stl returning Value::Float(f64::INFINITY); reuses the WI-084 host-const value-source path (force_const reads a registered builtin for a SymbolKind::Const). Consider negative_infinity / nan siblings and an is_finite/is_nan predicate. Built on WI-084 (term-level const, delivered in main). Driver: lf1 webots motor velocity-mode sentinel — 'const VELOCITY_MODE_POSITION: Float = infinity' for Motor.set_position(+inf) — which ALSO needs the const-codegen WI before it reaches generated C++. Generally useful beyond motors (saturation bounds, unbounded ranges)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T07:04:45Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-533", description: some(value: "Codegen for term-level constants (SymbolKind::Const, proposal 039). WI-084 phase 1 left 'Item::Const' a no-op in codegen (codegen/rust.rs emit_items has an explicit 'later phase' arm; cpp-gen likewise does not emit it). Emit a const as a target-language constant: Rust 'pub const NAME: T = <value>;', C++ 'inline constexpr T NAME = <value>;'. Needs: fold the const value (or lower its symbolic body) to a target literal/expression, and place it in the correct scope (namespace-level const -> module/namespace; sort-body const -> the carrier's struct/class). Built on WI-084 (term-level const + fold path, delivered in main). Drivers: lf1 webots sentinels reaching generated C++ (BROADCAST_CHANNEL; motor velocity-mode infinity once the Float-infinity WI lands). Acceptance: a const in an example sort emits a compilable C++/Rust constant (golden/integration test)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T07:59:27Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-536", description: some(value: "WI-533 follow-up: carrier-bound sorts term-level consts do not reach generated C++ via the cpp PROJECT pipeline. WI-533 delivered const-DECLARATION codegen — non-carrier-bound sort-body consts emit as struct static constexpr members, namespace consts as inline constexpr, and the standalone emit_traits_struct API emits consts for ANY sort (the WI-533 acceptance test lf1_emitter_emits_broadcast_channel_const uses exactly this path). BUT classify_namespace (anthill-cpp-gen/src/lib.rs) EXCLUDES carrier-bound sorts from the namespace/project header (a carrier-bound sort already maps to a host type, so emitting a fresh struct would shadow it), so a const declared INSIDE a carrier-bound sort (lf1 Emitter.BROADCAST_CHANNEL, or a future Motor.VELOCITY_MODE_POSITION = infinity) never reaches the header that codegen cpp-project writes. Consequence: the lf1 motor velocity-mode sentinel does NOT flow end-to-end to generated C++ through the project pipeline, even though WI-532 (infinity value) and WI-533 (const codegen) are both delivered. Also: a const REFERENCE in an operation body lowers (lower_node Ref branch) to the bare short name (e.g. BROADCAST_CHANNEL), which will not resolve in C++ unless the const is emitted somewhere reachable. DESIGN (pick one, realization-layer concern): (a) inline a const reference to its folded value at the use site (BROADCAST_CHANNEL to -1; infinity to numeric_limits double infinity) — simplest, loses the named constant; (b) emit a carrier-bound sorts consts as free inline constexpr at namespace scope via a non-shadowing companion; (c) map a const reference to the carrier static member via a realization mapping (BROADCAST_CHANNEL to webots Emitter CHANNEL_BROADCAST). RELATED minor gap (fold in or note): a SUM/entity sort that ALSO carries a const drops it in cpp-gen (emit_sum_in emits a std variant alias with no place for a static const; rust.rs already emits it via enum+impl). Driver: lf1 motor velocity-mode sentinel reaching generated C++ via codegen cpp-project. Acceptance: a const in a carrier-bound example sort reaches generated C++ through the project pipeline with references resolving (golden/integration test). Rust-only (anthill-cpp-gen + realization). Built on WI-533 (delivered) + WI-532."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-533"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T09:47:20Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-478", description: some(value: "Proposal 048 Phase 1 — guarded effect-row elements (grammar + representation). Admit an optional trailing ':- guard' on effect-row elements per 048 'Grammar delta': add guarded_effect (bare 'E :- term') and paren_guarded_effect ('( E :- rule_body )') productions on the effect_row node (builds on WI-375 effect_row); the mandatory ':-' preserves the '(' fail-fast typo protection. Loader stores the guard as a new EffectExpression.guarded(label: Type, guard: List[anthill.reflect.Term]) element in stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill (bare 'E :- p' -> [p]; '( E :- p, q )' -> [p,q]; present(label) == guarded(label, [])), materializing to occurrence goals via term_body_to_nodes at use; decompose_effect_row gains a 'guarded' arm. Guard is List[Term] today (EffectExpression rides a hash-consed arrow, WI-251; Positioned bridges local-binder goals). NO discharge here — that is WI-067. Semantics fixed in 048: the row stays closed over labels, a guard is evaluated open-world (resolves to {} or present, never an enforcing absence)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T12:20:53Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-067", name: "p048")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "user", content: "Design written 2026-06-21: proposal 050 (local-interpretation / flow-sensitive logical env Γ) + 025 §'In-body and control-flow proofs' + 048 §'Typer delta'. Discharge = TWO TIERS over Γ at the call site: (1) trivial flow — constructively refute σ(G) from Γ + ground eval + KB on the SLD resolver under step_cap with floundering prevention; (2) fallback — in-body proof (025), context seeded with Γ. Soundness: drop only on positive proof of ¬G (048 §'constructive refutation'). PREREQUISITE = proposal 050: typer scout shows TypingEnv threads only type bindings (no fact channel), if does NOT fork branch envs, match guards are unvisited, and the typer never calls kb.resolve during body checking; BUT the per-arm env fork/join substrate already exists (match extend_env_from_pattern). Net-new = fact channel on TypingEnv + if-fork narrowing + match-guard typing + resolver bridge. Recommend filing 050-impl as its own WI before WI-067.", at: "2026-06-21T13:10:39Z")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-537", name: "p048")
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-538", name: "p048")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-539", description: some(value: "Proposal 050 \"operation call\" modification rule + 025 §\"Proof for operation contracts\" — call-site operation contracts (requires/ensures) over Γ. A SIBLING consumer of WI-537 (the 050 substrate); NOT on WI-067's critical path (effect discharge rides branch conditions and Γ, not contracts) and therefore does NOT block WI-067 — filed because it is part of proposal 050 and the main thing that richly POPULATES Γ. At a call y = callee(args), build σ (callee params ↦ actual args, result ↦ y), then: (1) requires IS CHECKED — the callee's precondition σ(requires) must follow from Γ_in, discharged by the SAME resolver query (and, failing the trivial flow, the same in-body-proof fallback) used for a guarded effect; an undischarged precondition is an obligation/error, never a silent pass. (2) ensures IS ASSUMED — Γ_out = Γ_in ∪ { σ(ensures) }: the callee's postcondition (result ↦ y) becomes a known fact for the code after the call. This is how contract knowledge flows: an op that \"ensures neq(result,0)\" lets a later div(_, y) refute its eq(y,0) guard straight from Γ with no branch test written; ensures facts are in practice the main populator of Γ beyond branch conditions and bindings. Plus 025 §\"Proof for operation contracts\": a proof targeting the implicit contract rule via the <operation>.<clause> naming convention (e.g. push.ensures). DISTINCT FROM WI-347 (DELIVERED), which checks OVERRIDE refinement (a providing sort's op vs the spec op — precondition no stronger, postcondition no weaker); THIS is CALL-SITE checking, which is unimplemented — op requires_clause/ensures_clause exist in the IR (OperationInfo.requires/ensures) but are unused across stdlib/examples and never checked at a call. Depends on WI-537 (needs Γ + the resolver bridge). Acceptance: cargo-test green; a test shows a callee's requires checked against Γ at a call site (error when undischarged, pass when Γ entails it) and its ensures available as a Γ fact after the call."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-537"]), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-539", name: "p048")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "user", content: "Prerequisites filed 2026-06-21 (user chose the 3-WI decomposition). WI-067 now depends on WI-537 + WI-538 (in addition to existing WI-066, WI-478). Map: WI-537 = proposal 050 Γ substrate + resolver bridge (fact channel on TypingEnv, if-fork cond/¬cond narrowing, match-guard typing + earlier-arm negation, refute(goal,Γ) over Γ∪KB under step_cap with floundering prevention) — BLOCKS WI-067, enables Tier-1 flow discharge. WI-538 = proposal 025 §\"In-body and control-flow proofs\" (proof in body/branch, ProofContext seeded from Γ, scope-chain lemma citation, verified conclusion fed back into Γ) — BLOCKS WI-067, is the Tier-2 fallback this WI dispatches to. WI-539 = proposal 050 op-call contracts (requires/ensures via Γ) — SIBLING consumer of WI-537, NOT a blocker (effect discharge rides branch conditions, not contracts). WI-067 itself remains the 048 §\"Typer delta\" = the two-tier discharge GLUE: build σ (callee params ↦ args), Tier-1 constructively refute σ(G) from Γ + ground eval + KB, else Tier-2 look for an in-body proof targeting the obligation; drop the guarded element only on a positive proof of ¬G (never NAF), else conservatively present / propagate upward with σ. Build order: WI-537 → (WI-538, WI-539 in parallel) → WI-067 → WI-479 (migrate primitives). \"Newly added changes in proposal 48\" = this Typer-delta section itself (no separate ticket; grammar prereq WI-478 already delivered).", at: "2026-06-21T14:19:03Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-537", author: "user", content: "Design correction (user): type deduction is NOT logical deduction, so the local-interpretation environment Gamma is its OWN abstraction, NOT a field on TypingEnv. TypingEnv = a set of types (the type-deduction context: var/DeBruijn to Type, resources). Gamma = local LOGICAL storage: the facts that hold at a program point, proved/refuted by the SLD resolver. Keep them separate -- REVERT the facts: Rc<Vec<Value>> field on TypingEnv. Represent Gamma as a discrimination-tree-indexed fact store (the same structure the KB uses for facts) -- the WI indexed-store option. ENABLER (already in working tree): ViewHead::Var(VarId) becomes Var(Var) plus DiscrimKey::RigidVar(VarId), so the discrim tree indexes/matches Rigid (skolemized op-param) vars as CONSTANTS by id, not Opaque -- the logical store can then hold facts over op parameters (a guard neq(b,0) over rigid b). Opaque-headed facts (control-flow / elaborated if-conditions) are excluded from the index LOSSLESSLY: an Opaque head can never unify with a clean goal-shaped membership query, and insert_pattern rightly panics on Opaque (the rule-head invariant), so the Gamma store SKIPS Opaque facts instead of weakening that invariant. Bridge unchanged in spirit: Tier-1 = discrim-tree membership over Gamma (post-checked by not-is_contradiction, mirroring match_view); Tier-2 = KB resolve under definite_only (the floundering guard).", at: "2026-06-21T16:33:44Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-537", author: "user", content: "Threading shape (user): instead of threading TypingEnv, thread an Env carrier that CONTAINS both TypingEnv (type deduction) and FlowEnv (the flow-sensitive logical storage Gamma, discrim-tree-backed) -- or something like this. So: Env { types: Rc<TypingEnv>, flow: FlowEnv }; FlowEnv { facts: Rc<SubstTree<Value>> } is the logical store (empty/assume/membership, COW via Rc::make_mut -> SubstTree gains Clone, doc-noted shallow-only). Env threaded by value (cheap: two Rc bumps), Deref<Target=TypingEnv> so existing type-deduction method calls are untouched; fork at if narrows env.flow only (types shared via Rc::clone). Bridge prove_from_gamma/refute_guard take &FlowEnv (pure logical deduction, no types). Revert facts field off TypingEnv. Blast radius ~34 env signatures in typing.rs + region.rs + typer tests.", at: "2026-06-21T16:36:41Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-537", author: "user", content: "DECISION (user-confirmed): do NOT duplicate SLD. The SLD resolver already consults frame-scoped local hypotheses (Frame.assumed_facts, WI-108) as Candidate::Assumption inside the normal search (resolve.rs:789-805). Gamma rides that. Realization = TREE OVERLAY on the resolver Frame: add gamma: Rc<SubstTree<Value>> to Frame, seeded once at resolve start, inherited by child frames via Rc::clone (immutable, no push/pop unlike assumed_facts), consulted at the EXISTING candidate step via query_resolved_value -> Candidate::Assumption. FlowEnv stays tree-only and BECOMES that overlay backing (the Vec<TermId> assumed_facts linear scan is the thing the tree replaces for Gamma). Bridge prove_from_gamma collapses to one kb.resolve over KB-union-Gamma under definite_only; the standalone FlowEnv::proves_directly membership matcher is DELETED (it was the start of the SLD duplication). The ViewHead->RigidVar refactor is what lets that overlay tree hold Gamma facts over rigid op-params. Carrier-faithful (Value::Node if-conditions) via query_resolved_value.", at: "2026-06-21T16:54:31Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-537", author: "user", content: "DEFERRED design fork (decide AFTER first design lands): (1st, building now) Gamma as a tree OVERLAY queried at the candidate step alongside the existing Vec assumed_facts, both feeding Candidate::Assumption. (2nd, later) a LAYERED SubstTree with a parent link: query falls through local->enclosing, insert hits only the local layer. Two distinct uses of layering: (a) Gamma OWN lexical nesting (proposal 050 each scope extends enclosing) -- a thin per-scope layer over the enclosing Gamma tree shared by Rc, avoiding the O(Gamma) Rc::make_mut whole-tree clone per fork; FlowEnv-local, no KB churn. (b) uniting local+global (Gamma + KB index) in ONE tree -- BLOCKED by leaf mismatch: KB index is SubstTree<RuleId>, Gamma facts are Value; needs SubstTree<FactRef{Rule|Local}> refactor + the KB candidate path also does eq/simp/cache, so out of WI-537 scope. User leans: maybe just the existing assumptions mechanism is better than the layered tree -- revisit once the overlay is proven.", at: "2026-06-21T16:59:26Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-540", description: some(value: "Make the reflect KB bridge GENERATED-AND-USED (renumbered from the locally-filed WI-536; main concurrently took WI-536 for a cpp-gen const item). KbBridge/SubstBridge implement the codegen-emitted KB/Substitution traits so the compiler enforces bridge==spec. Codegen gained (flag-gated): boxed_trait_objects (Box<dyn>/&dyn/where Self:Sized), emit_only (scope generation to the KB-bridge subset), has_trait_object_field (derive-skip). Distinct opaque reflect Term/Symbol (ReflectTerm/ReflectSymbol, private fields; Value/TermId never in a reflect signature; bridge converts at the boundary). execute->Stream[Solution] carrier-faithful definite/undecided (absorbs WI-534). DELIVERED 2026-06-21 (branch reflect-generated-bridge); full suite 2189/0. Foundation follow-ups tracked as the next WI. See [[project_wi536_generated_bridge]]."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T14:49:13Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-535", description: some(value: "Migrate the host reflect bridge (anthill-stl/src/reflect/mod.rs + bridge.rs) and the anthill-rust-gen contracts from TermId to TermView (carrier-faithful). The bridge + rust-gen were written BEFORE the TermView/carrier-faithful migration (WI-348/470/477), so 'pub type Term = anthill_core::kb::term::TermId' (reflect/mod.rs:10) and the whole bridge reifies every term to a bare TermId — it is NOT carrier-faithful at ANY point (a Value::Node loses its occurrence identity/span). SCOPE: the host Term representation across the KB trait (reify/reflect/nonvar/ground/apply_core_subst), TermRepr, SortInfo/OperationInfo/FieldInfo, Substitution::apply + SubstBridge, AND the anthill-rust-gen codegen that emits/consumes these (generated-code contract changes). TermView is a TRAIT (impl for TermId/Value/Rc<NodeOccurrence>/ViewItem/ReflectedExpr, term_view.rs:902/953/1078/1108), so pick a concrete carrier for the host Term (Box<dyn TermView> or a view enum). Stage if possible: bridge-internal first, then the generated-code surface. Rust-only (anthill-stl + anthill-rust-gen). This is the FOUNDATION WI-534 needs: streaming a Solution with a carrier-faithful residual (Value/Node-preserving) is incoherent while the rest of the bridge speaks bare TermId and would force a lossy reify. Found during WI-534 — the bridge is pre-migration legacy."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T14:49:17Z"))
