fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-542", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). Gave the prelude Type stub a Value carrier (was a bare unit — facts_of couldn't name the entity); facts_of extracts the functor via a host twin of core value_functor (Fn/Ref/Entity, lock-step with core) and enumerates rules_by_functor heads carrier-faithfully — exact parity with interpreter kb_facts_of incl. the synthetic-entity-declaration contract. Non-entity Type now PANICS loudly (not silent vec![]; code-review fix, mirrors the interpreter type error). Type::new is #[cfg(test)] (only test callers today). 3 bridge unit tests. anthill-stl 25/0.", at: "2026-06-21T16:35:43Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-543", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). Added entity BigIntLiteral(value: BigInt) to reflect.anthill LiteralRepr; codegen map_primitive_type BigInt->num_bigint::BigInt; routed BigInt through BigIntLiteral in BOTH realizations — bridge (literal_to_repr + reflect) and interpreter (reify_term_to_value + reflect-direction + ReflectSyms.bigint_lit). IntLiteral is now Int64-only (no more lossy BigInt->StringLiteral, no BigInt-in-IntLiteral). Round-trip bridge test. Scaland inert (no LiteralRepr matches; already maps BigInt). Full suite was 2218/0 with these changes.", at: "2026-06-21T16:35:49Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-542", description: some(value: "Reflect KB bridge parity: implement KB.facts_of (WI-541 gap 3a). Today bridge.rs panics loudly (\"KB.facts_of not yet implemented\"). The interpreter realization (eval/builtins.rs kb_facts_of) is the model: resolve the entity reference to its functor symbol (value_functor), rules_by_functor, then rule_head_value per rule (carrier-agnostic — a value-fact head returns its Value directly). Bridge returns List[Term] = ReflectTerm wrapping each head Value (carrier-faithful, mirrors WI-535). The bridge's facts_of takes sort: Type; thread Type->functor symbol. Acceptance: facts_of returns the WorkItem/OperationInfo fact heads (incl. value-fact heads) for a loaded source; unit test in bridge.rs; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T16:35:54Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-543", description: some(value: "Reflect: add first-class BigIntLiteral to LiteralRepr (WI-541 gap 4). reflect.anthill's LiteralRepr enum (IntLiteral/FloatLiteral/StringLiteral/BoolLiteral) has no BigInt case, so the bridge's literal_to_repr lowers a core Literal::BigInt to its decimal StringLiteral — lossy/ambiguous (a BigInt is indistinguishable from a real string). Add entity BigIntLiteral(value: BigInt) to LiteralRepr; regen (anthill-stl build.rs emits LiteralRepr in the emit_only subset); map Literal::BigInt -> LiteralRepr::BigIntLiteral in bridge.rs literal_to_repr, and the reverse in KB.reflect (BigIntLiteral -> Literal::BigInt). Check whether the interpreter (builtins.rs reify/reflect, if any LiteralRepr handling) needs the new arm. Acceptance: a BigInt literal round-trips through reify/reflect as BigInt (not String); cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T16:36:00Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-547", name: "wi541")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-544", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). Added operation bindings(s: Substitution) -> List[Pair[Term,Term]] to reflect.anthill (the dual of lookup — variable rides as a var Term so identity is recoverable across the &dyn Substitution boundary). Rewrote SubstBridge::compose to the FULL union: first-half apply s2 to self's range, second-half merge s2's standalone bindings via bindings()+vid_of, keyed by VarId (self wins on overlap) — mirrors interpreter subst_compose. Implemented bindings in BOTH realizations: bridge SubstBridge::bindings + interpreter subst_bindings (ReflectSyms.pair/f_fst/f_snd). 2 new tests (bridge compose union + interpreter bindings); parity confirmed by code-review. anthill-stl 27/0, full suite 2220/0. code-review surfaced a PRE-EXISTING shared limitation (compose first-half doesn't chase a bare Value::Var binding through s2, same in interpreter) -> loud-documented in compose + filed WI-547.", at: "2026-06-21T17:43:30Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-544", description: some(value: "Reflect Substitution.compose full union via a binding-enumeration op (WI-541 gap 1). bridge.rs SubstBridge::compose is PARTIAL: through a &dyn Substitution it applies s2 to self's range but cannot merge s2's STANDALONE bindings (the spec trait exposes only apply/compose/lookup — no way to enumerate s2's bindings). The interpreter (anthill-stl builtins.rs subst_compose) does the full union because it holds concrete s2.bindings. Fix: add a binding-enumeration operation to sort Substitution in reflect.anthill (e.g. operation bindings(s: Substitution) -> List[T = pair-of-name-and-Term], or an entries form), regen, implement it in the bridge (SubstBridge has concrete inner) AND in the interpreter builtin, then complete compose's second half (extend with s2's bindings for vars absent in self). Acceptance: compose(s1,s2) merges s2's standalone bindings; unit test; cargo-test green. Note compose is currently unused by the bridge — this is parity/correctness, low live impact."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T17:43:33Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-548", name: "wi541")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-545", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). Bridge operations() now surfaces an op's requires/ensures contract clauses. INVESTIGATION found the WI's plan carrier (Rc<NodeOccurrence>) WRONG: op contracts are stored as Vec<Vec<TermId>> goal terms (IR), surfaced by the loader as Value::Term clause lists in the OperationInfo fact — NOT positioned occurrences. So carrier-bound NodeOccurrence to a Value-carrying opaque newtype ReflectNodeOccurrence(Value) (mod.rs, mirrors ReflectTerm) via build.rs carrier_bindings (NodeOccurrence is DECLARED in reflect.anthill so the codegen carrier-alias fires — no prelude-stub trick needed, unlike Type/WI-542). Bridge reads requires/ensures the SAME way as effects (field + collect_list_terms) and wraps each clause via a nocc helper. NO op_info.rs/lookup_operation_info needed. Multi-goal clauses ride as one conjunction(...) term = 1:1 faithful. code-review CLEAN (confirmed no trait method needs Rc<NodeOccurrence>; only OperationInfo.requires/ensures field types use it). 1 new bridge test (op with requires/ensures → non-empty). anthill-stl 28/0, full suite 2221/0. PARITY GAP filed WI-548: interpreter kb_operations still omits requires/ensures+meta (builds 4-field OperationInfo). Pre-existing value-fact-head skip (denoted-effect ops) inherited+documented, not introduced.", at: "2026-06-21T20:43:00Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-545", description: some(value: "Reflect bridge: surface OperationInfo.requires/ensures via a ReflectNodeOccurrence carrier (WI-541 gap 2). bridge.rs KB.operations currently reports requires/ensures EMPTY (loud-documented Foundation limitation): the spec types them List[NodeOccurrence] (real pre/postcondition occurrences the loader stores and the typer reads via load.rs OperationInfo.requires), but the host NodeOccurrence is an empty opaque unit struct, uncarrier-bound. Fix: carrier-bind NodeOccurrence to an opaque newtype ReflectNodeOccurrence(Rc<NodeOccurrence>) in reflect/mod.rs (same pattern as ReflectTerm), add it to build.rs carrier_bindings, and have the bridge read the loader-stored clause occurrences for the operation and wrap them. Investigate how the KB exposes an op's requires/ensures occurrences (op symbol -> stored occurrences; cf. occurrences_of / operation_body side-tables) — may need a KB accessor. Riskiest gap (new carrier + codegen + loader access). Acceptance: operations() returns non-empty requires/ensures for an op with contracts; unit test; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-21T20:43:03Z"))
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-549", name: "wi541")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-546", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). assert + kb() done; add_guard SPLIT to WI-549 (needs a reflect-LogicalQuery-enum -> structured guard-Value reifier, ~18 variants, distinct from query_to_goals which flattens). assert: forwards to kb.assert_checked (Option<RuleId> = the spec's 'violated constraint -> none'); fact head via expect_term (loud on non-Term); fact's sort derived from the head via a NEW pub kb.fact_trigger_sort (wraps the private view_to_trigger_sort) so the asserted fact and a registered guard agree on the sort key (both use constructor_parent_sort) — the  arg is the fallback when the head names no sort; sort=domain for runtime facts. kb(): DECISION = documented panic (no ambient host KB; build a KbBridge from a KnowledgeBase). 2 tests: happy-path (assert+facts_of, prelude-only) + rejection (full-stdlib helper load_source_bridge_with_stdlib + the proven wi023  2-cycle constraint; assert edge(b->a) completes the cycle -> None). code-review CLEAN (empirically verified the rejection isn't a false positive: guard_count=1, non-violating edge->Some, violating->None). GOTCHAS: a plain  denial constraint is INERT (WI-023; only quantified/negation guards enforced); guard registration needs reflect stdlib loaded; the synthetic entity-declaration head matches all-var constraint patterns at load (use ground constants like wi023). anthill-stl 30/0, full suite 2223/0.", at: "2026-06-22T03:28:45Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-546", description: some(value: "Reflect bridge: implement KB.assert / KB.add_guard; decide KB.kb() disposition (WI-541 gap 3bc). bridge.rs panics loudly for all three. assert(term, sort) -> Option[FactId] and add_guard(guard) -> ConstraintId mutate the KB (effects Modify[kb]); implement via the existing KnowledgeBase APIs (assert_fact / add_guard_labeled, cf. load.rs and kb/mod.rs call sites) — assert returns the RuleId-as-FactId, runs constraint checks (none on violation); add_guard lowers the LogicalQuery to goals (reuse query_to_goals) and registers it. kb() is the ambient-KB accessor (zero-arg, no self, returns KB) — genuinely not host-constructible from a static fn; decide: leave a documented panic (the host builds a KbBridge from a KnowledgeBase directly, never via kb()), or restructure. Acceptance: assert adds a fact and a follow-up facts_of/execute sees it; add_guard registers a constraint that rejects a violating assert; unit tests; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-22T03:28:49Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-547", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (uncommitted, branch main). Fixed the bug at the right depth: core reify_value (kb/mod.rs) now CHASES a BOUND bare Value::Var through the substitution (recursively, for non-path-compressed z->w->v chains) — the single-point fix for the bridge SubstBridge::compose AND apply. Interpreter subst_compose (anthill-stl builtins.rs) got the matching Value::Var arm (was: Value::Term->apply_subst, other->clone — the clone dropped bare vars). An UNBOUND var still passes through (resolver goal boundaries at resolve.rs 797/1135 rely on a free value-level var staying free, so resolution is unaffected — confirmed: ripple-check full suite green). code-review (2 findings, BOTH fixed): (1) added a SELF-BINDING cycle guard — compose can synthesize z->z from {z->w} composed {w->z}, and a later apply would recurse forever; guard returns the var unchanged, mirroring walk_view/reify/occurs_in_value; (2) use subst.resolve_as_value (parent-chain aware) instead of bindings.get (local-map only) for parity with reify/walk_view. 3 tests: core reify_value chase+self-binding-guard+unbound; bridge compose_chases_bare_value_var; interpreter subst_compose_chases_bare_value_var. A genuine 2-cycle is unsound (occurs-check) and out of scope, same as the sibling chasers. full suite 2226/0.", at: "2026-06-22T05:11:46Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-547", description: some(value: "Substitution.compose first-half does not chase a BARE Value::Var binding through s2 (shared by BOTH realizations). compose's first half re-applies s2 to self's range via apply/reify_value (and the interpreter subst_compose via apply_subst), which substitute vars carried INSIDE a Value::Term/Value::Node but pass a bare Value::Var through unchanged (reify_value: 'other => other.clone()', kb/mod.rs ~2391; subst_compose: 'other => other.clone()', anthill-stl builtins.rs). So a self-binding z ↦ Value::Var(w) is left dangling instead of resolved to s2(w). Probe (surfaced in WI-544 code-review): s1={z↦Value::Var(w)}, s2={z↦7, w↦9}; compose yields z↦w (unresolved) + w↦9, not z↦9. resolve.rs (unify_flex_var/chase_value) CAN produce Value::Var bound children, so it may reach a stored subst. NOT a WI-544 regression — pre-existing, shared, and bridge::compose has no live caller yet; loud-documented in bridge.rs compose. INVESTIGATE: (a) whether bare Value::Var values actually reach a subst that compose runs on, or whether the carrier model guarantees Value::Term in subst range (if so, this is a non-issue + assert/doc); (b) if real, the fix likely belongs in core reify_value (substitute a bare Value::Var via subst lookup) so BOTH compose realizations + every apply caller benefit — assess ripple before changing. Acceptance: either a test+assert pinning 'subst range is always Value::Term (no bare Var)', or reify_value substitutes bare Value::Var and a compose test shows z↦9; cargo-test green."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-22T05:11:51Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-537", description: some(value: "Proposal 050 Phase 1 — local-interpretation Γ substrate + resolver bridge (the prerequisite for WI-067 Tier-1 discharge). Proposal 050 (docs/proposals/050-local-interpretation.md) defines Γ, the flow-sensitive logical environment: the static sibling of the 026 evaluator — the same forward walk over a body's ExprOccurrence IR, computing the set of facts true at each program point instead of runtime Values; flow-sensitive (each occurrence has its own Γ) and constructive (a fact enters Γ only from a seed, binding, or branch that established it). Runs as part of the typing pass. Net-new in rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs (050 §Implementation; the fork/join substrate already exists — match forks a per-arm env via extend_env_from_pattern and joins at MatchFinal, if clones the env for both branches): (1) FACT CHANNEL on TypingEnv — facts: Rc<Vec<Value>> (or a normalized/indexed store) beside var_bindings, carrying goal/atom Values in the same vocabulary a rule body or 048 guard speaks; seed Γ0 at body entry = the op's requires-clause facts + signature facts (param sorts, result typing) + in-scope KB facts. (2) IF-FORK NARROWING — fork the env at Expr::If, extend then with cond and else with ¬cond (today both branches share one env and the typed-to-Bool condition is discarded); ¬cond per open-Q C (structural neq vs reified not). (3) MATCH-GUARD TYPING + THREADING — type-check the arm guard (parsed today but never visited) and add its predicate + the pattern fact + earlier-arm negations to the arm Γ. (4) RESOLVER BRIDGE — a refute(goal, Γ)/discharge helper running goal against Γ ∪ KB on the existing SLD resolver under step_cap, soundness guarded by FLOUNDERING PREVENTION (a goal over unknown runtime params DELAYS rather than succeeds — the open-world reading; 048 §\"Discharge is constructive refutation, not NAF\"). The typer does not call kb.resolve during body checking today — this bridge is the load-bearing new mechanism. Plus: binding rule (let x = e adds x ≡ e), sequencing accumulation, join = meet (intersection — only facts true on every incoming path survive), and lexical NESTING (each scope's Γ extends its enclosing scope's). One substrate, reused by all three consumers. OUT OF SCOPE: effect discharge (= WI-067), the op-call requires/ensures Hoare rule (= the contracts sibling WI), in-body proofs (= the 025 WI). See 050 open questions A–E. Acceptance: cargo-test green; a test shows Γ carries neq(b,0) inside the then-branch of \"if neq(b,0)\" and refute() proves it from Γ, while a symbolic neq(b,0) stays undischarged via floundering."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-22T19:19:37Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "user", content: "WI-537 (delivered) added the match-arm Γ narrowing (proposal-050 match rule producer): per-arm eq(scrutinee, value(p)) + neq(scrutinee, value(pj)) for earlier GROUND/UNGUARDED arms — the canonical 'case 0 -> neq(s,0)' discharge case. Live Γ producers now: if-then(cond), if-else(¬cond), match-guard predicate, match ground-pattern facts/negations; prove_from_gamma/refute_guard is the bridge. TWO Γ-producer pieces DEFERRED here for WI-067 (need the binder's logical representation, co-designed with the discharge consumer): (1) let x=e -> x≡e binding fact — a let/lambda binder ref is Expr::VarRef -> ViewHead::Opaque, so NO indexable Γ form exists today (Term::Ref is canonical only for CONSTRUCTOR refs); plus rebind-staleness (let x=0; let x=1) needs a Γ retract, the analog of the type-level clear_receiver_alias. (2) binder & constructor-with-binder pattern facts + their 'not-any' negation (¬∃x. s=some(x)) — need a reified form (050 open Q C); the existential eq(s,some(?fresh)) is inert under the identity-aware Γ match (views_structurally_equal).", at: "2026-06-22T19:19:39Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-550", author: "user", content: "Preferred approach (user): create FRESH UNIQUE SYMBOLS for local vars (alpha-rename each let/lambda/match binder at scope entry to a gensym) and carry that symbol in var_ref(name: Symbol). This is cleaner than a separate Var-identity layer: var_ref already keys by Symbol, and the WI-537 view/lowering (var_ref → Functor{var_ref, name: Ref(sym)}) already mirrors the reflect form — so swapping the source name for a per-binding unique symbol makes Γ shadowing-correct (let x=0; let x=1 → distinct symbols → no collision) with NO new view/term/discrim machinery, just alpha-conversion at binder introduction. Localizes the change to where binders are introduced + references resolved.", at: "2026-06-23T06:26:44Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-550", description: some(value: "Open let/lambda/match binders to shadowing-correct logical IDENTITY, then re-enable the deferred proposal-050 binder Γ facts. The WI-537 occ_head fix (Expr::VarRef → ViewHead::Ident(name), term_view.rs) made binder references INDEXABLE BY NAME — enough for the match/if scrutinee narrowing (a scrutinee is not rebound within its match). But the deferred proposal-050 producers need shadowing-correct binder IDENTITY, which name-keying does NOT give: 'let x = 0; let x = 1' would collide (both key Ident(x)). Fix: open let/lambda/match-arm binders to DISTINCT Var identities on scope entry (the way rules open DeBruijn → fresh Global) and rewrite VarRef references to them — OR add a Γ-retract on rebind (the logical analog of the typer's type-level clear_receiver_alias). Then re-enable, soundly: (1) the let x=e → x≡e binding fact (pure/effect-free values only); (2) constructor pattern-binder facts eq(scrutinee, ctor(binders...)) for case some(x), plus the 'not-any' earlier-arm negation ¬∃v. s=ctor(v) (050 open Q C reified form). Unblocked by the WI-537 occ_head fix; consumer is WI-067 (effect discharge) / WI-538 (in-body proofs)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-537"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-23T08:52:58Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-550", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED parts 1+2a+2b (full suite 2243/0). (1) Alpha-rename: each let/lambda/match binder gets a FRESH per-site Symbol (intern_unique) — distinct identity, display name preserved as 'x' — so shadowing binders no longer collide in Γ; the pattern occurrence and body references share one identity per site via a parse-id-keyed binder_sym get-or-mint map (load.rs). load_op_body_var now resolves a '?x' naming a local binder to that gensym (fixed 3 dot-dispatch regressions). (2a) let x=e => Γ∪{x≡e} (pure values only) via binding_gamma_fact. (2b) constructor-binder positive fact eq(s, some(var_ref(x))) via pattern_match_value(admit_binders=true), kept distinct from the ground-only value used for later-arm negations; the bare 'case x' alias eq(s,x) is included (bridges an earlier arm's neq(s,0) to a guard over x). Γ stays write-only (refute_guard has 0 call sites) so additive. DEFERRED: part 2c the 'not-any' reified negation ¬∃v.s=some(v) (050 open-Q-C) -> recorded on WI-067 (the discharge consumer) to co-design when Γ gets a reader. KNOWN LIMITATION (sound): a '?x'-spelled binder ref lowers to Var::Global(gensym) while bare 'x' lowers to var_ref(gensym), so only the bare-'x' form discharges against the var_ref-keyed facts (incompleteness, not unsoundness).", at: "2026-06-23T08:53:22Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "claude", content: "Proposal-050 'not-any' earlier-arm negation deferred here from WI-550 (DELIVERED): a match arm 'case some(x)' should narrow LATER arms with ¬∃v. s=some(v) (050 open question C, reified form). WI-550 delivered the binder POSITIVE facts (eq(s,some(x))) but NOT this negation: a naive not(eq(s,some(?))) is redundant when s is ground (the later arm's own eq fact already says it) and FLOUNDERS when s is symbolic under the resolver's definite_only guard, so it needs genuine reified-existential-over-constructors resolver support AND a reader (this discharge consumer) to validate the polarity. Co-design it when wiring refute_guard/prove_from_gamma into effect discharge — match_arm_gamma_facts (typing.rs) is the producer to extend.", at: "2026-06-23T08:53:24Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-538", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED (commit 2b8abe1, full suite 2248/0). The in-body/control-flow proof CONSTRUCT + Tier-A discharge. Design settled with owner: it is the SAME proof construct in statement position (new proof_statement node in _expr_body, trailing continuation), reusing target/by-strategy/using verbatim + ONE optional 'conclude <goal>' clause; top-level proof_declaration untouched — NOT a new proof kind. Two forms: short (proof <rule> by <strategy> end, goal = target rule head — impl treats it as a 0-ary atom, so fires only for 0-ary rules; N-ary head reconstruction is a follow-on) and conclude (proof <handle> by <strategy> conclude <P> end, inline goal over a local param — the guard-discharge case with no rule to name). Pipeline: proof_stmt parse term (ParseAux::ProofStmt metadata) -> Expr::Proof{target,strategy,using,conclude,body} occurrence (load.rs LoadBuildFrame::ProofStmt) -> typer Tier-A: prove_from_gamma(Γ, goal); on success assume(goal) into Γ for the continuation (the 050 in-body-proof modification rule). Type is the continuation's; eval/cpp-gen lower a proof to its body (type-level no-op). /code-review (4 finders, max effort) caught 5 REAL wildcard-reader bugs the new Expr::Proof fell into: simp_rewrite::reassemble (CONFIRMED miscompile — dropped a [simp] rewrite inside a proof body; regression test added) + is_rewritable, flow_derive::analyze (tail-flow soundness drop) + find_accumulators, cpp-gen node_references_name, const_node_is_pure — all fixed (proof is type-transparent, recurse into conclude?/body). DEFERRED (all gated on the prove-pass gate, a design follow-on): Tier-B recording (external by-z3 is CONSERVATIVE now — contributes nothing, sound — until the Γ-snapshot+ProofRecord+gate land; provisional-assume without the gate is unsound); using-as-hypotheses (redundant for Tier-A since the resolver already sees in-scope KB rules; load-bearing only as z3 assumptions in Tier-B). NOTE: the Tier-A discharge OUTCOME is not observable end-to-end yet — the typer's Γ is write-only until its consumer WI-067 (effect discharge) wires a reader; the discharge logic itself is unit-tested via prove_from_gamma. Design doc docs/design/local-proof.md updated (Syntax + Scope sections).", at: "2026-06-23T21:08:16Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "claude", content: "WI-538 DELIVERED (2b8abe1) the in-body proof construct + Tier-A discharge (prove_from_gamma + Γ-feedback). WI-067 is the consumer that makes the Tier-A discharge observable: the typer's Γ stays WRITE-ONLY (refute_guard has 0 callers) until WI-067 wires a guard-discharge reader over Γ. The Tier-2 in-body-proof fallback the 048 typer-delta dispatches to is now buildable: at an un-refuted guard, find an Expr::Proof targeting the obligation and check it against the same Γ (the proof already does prove_from_gamma internally). Also rides here: (a) Tier-B recording for external in-body proofs (Γ-snapshot onto a ProofRecord + the prove-pass gate — currently conservative/no-op, provisional-assume is unsound without the gate); (b) using-as-hypotheses (the cited lemmas are carried on Expr::Proof.using but not yet spliced into the discharge context — redundant for Tier-A/SLD, load-bearing as z3 assumptions in Tier-B).", at: "2026-06-23T21:08:38Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-538", description: some(value: "Proposal 025 §\"In-body and control-flow proofs\" — the NEW slice of 025 (the base proof machinery prove.rs/check.rs/witness.rs already exists; this adds proofs INSIDE bodies). A proof may appear inside an operation body or a control-flow branch (if-arm/match-arm), not only as a top-level companion to a rule, discharging an obligation that arises at that program point — the motivating case is a 048 guarded-effect guard the typer's Tier-1 automatic flow could not refute. Pieces: (1) parse/load a proof declaration in body+branch position (proof is already valid at sort/namespace scope — extend to body+branch scopes); (2) its ProofContext is SEEDED with the local-interpretation env Γ (WI-537, the 050 substrate) at that point — every fact narrowed by enclosing bindings + branch conditions is already assume'd, so a proof in the then-branch of \"if neq(b,0)\" starts with neq(b,0) in context for free and only has to bridge from there; (3) PROOF REFERENCES FOLLOW LEXICAL SCOPE — a guided in-body proof cites lemmas (a \":- name, …\" body) from its whole scope chain: earlier sibling proofs in the same body/branch, proofs in any enclosing branch/body, up to the top-level proofs attached to rules at sort/namespace scope (the proof-side mirror of Γ's nesting — one lexical visibility exposed two ways, as Γ facts and as citable lemmas); a proof in the else branch sees neither the facts nor the proofs that exist only in the then branch; (4) BIDIRECTIONAL WITH Γ — once a proof of P is verified, P is ADDED to Γ for the code after it (the 050 in-body-proof modification rule), symmetric to a call's ensures, so a proved lemma feeds later discharge / requires-checks / sibling proofs; an unverified proof contributes nothing and stands as an obligation (never a speculative fact). This is the Tier-2 fallback WI-067 dispatches to when Tier-1 cannot refute a guard (048 §\"Typer delta\"); a failing or absent proof leaves the effect conservatively present, never silently dropped. SCOPE NOTE: the Tier-2 dispatch glue in WI-067 (find an in-body proof targeting the obligation, check it against the same Γ) lives in WI-067; this WI delivers the construct it dispatches to. Depends on WI-537 (needs Γ). Acceptance: cargo-test green; a test shows a proof inside an op body verifying from a Γ-seeded premise, with its conclusion then available as a Γ fact for downstream code."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-537"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-23T21:08:40Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-548", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED. Interpreter kb_operations now surfaces requires/ensures/meta, matching the host bridge operations() (WI-545). Made op_info::clause_list_field pub (mirrors already-pub effects_of_head); added f_ensures/f_meta to ReflectSyms; kb_operations reads requires/ensures via clause_list_field (carrier-faithful — handles value-fact heads too, broader than the bridge which skips them) and meta via head_field_term (default bare meta ref when absent, mirroring bridge). Each clause placed directly as a carrier-agnostic Value (interpreter is dynamically typed, NodeOccurrence nominal). 1 new test (op with requires/ensures+meta -> all 3 fields populated). anthill-stl 33/0, full workspace suite exit 0 (green). code-review clean (no findings).", at: "2026-06-23T20:41:05Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-548", description: some(value: "Interpreter kb_operations parity: surface OperationInfo.requires/ensures (and meta) (WI-545 follow-up). The host bridge operations() now surfaces an op's requires/ensures contract clauses (WI-545), but the interpreter realization anthill-stl/src/reflect/builtins.rs kb_operations builds a PARTIAL OperationInfo Value with only 4 named fields (name/params/return_type/effects) — it omits requires, ensures AND meta entirely. So the two reflect realizations of KB.operations now diverge (bridge surfaces contracts+meta; interpreter omits them). Fix: have kb_operations read the requires/ensures clause lists (e.g. via op_info::clause_list_field — currently private, make pub — or lookup_operation_info) and the meta term from the OperationInfo head, build them as List values, and add the f_ensures ReflectSyms field (f_requires already exists). Each clause is a carrier-agnostic Value (Value::Term goal / conjunction, occasionally Value::Node) placed directly — the interpreter is dynamically typed so 'NodeOccurrence' is nominal. Acceptance: kb_operations on an op with requires/ensures returns an OperationInfo whose requires/ensures/meta fields are populated, matching the bridge; cargo-test green. Note: requires includes the loader's synthetic EffectsRuntime[Effects=E] clause (WI-320); ensures is user-only."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-23T20:41:08Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-549", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED. Bridge KB.add_guard implemented: reify_logical_query converts the generated LogicalQuery enum into a carrier-faithful Value::Entity over anthill.reflect.LogicalQuery.* ctors (mirrors interpreter eval-side builders + WI-513 carrier-agnostic lower_query_with/collect_trigger_sorts read it via TermView like the loader's hash-consed form), then kb.add_guard_labeled(value, None). Reify is total over all 18 variants; quantifiers (forall/some/one/lone/no) delegate to reify_quantifier (var=Symbol ref, inert to eval), conjunction/disjunction to reify_binary, sort_name=Value::Str (matches both readers), pattern term rides verbatim (Node-faithful). lq_ctor/reify_string_list panic loudly if reflect/prelude stdlib absent. code-review (xhigh, 2 finders) caught 1 REAL bug: add_guard accepted aggregation variants (count_q/sum_q/min_q/max_q) which the engine can't lower -> a DELAYED misleading panic at the next matching assert (assert_checked assumes load-time check_all_guards ran, which never does on the bridge path; loader avoids it via build_logical_query->None for Aggregation). FIX: reject aggregations loudly+early at reify (not boolean constraints). 3 tests: negation-rejects-violating-assert, no_q-rejects-2-cycle (quantifier path, shared ?x), aggregation-rejected-early (#[should_panic]). anthill-stl 36/0, full workspace suite exit 0 green.", at: "2026-06-23T22:22:37Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-549", description: some(value: "Reflect bridge: implement KB.add_guard via a LogicalQuery-enum -> structured guard-Value reifier (split from WI-546). bridge.rs add_guard still panics (WI-549). It must convert the generated reflect LogicalQuery ENUM (negation/conjunction/pattern_query/sort_query/forall_q/no_q/... ~18 variants) into a KB Value built from the anthill.reflect.LogicalQuery.* constructors, so the KB's add_guard_labeled + collect_trigger_sorts (which walk pattern_query/negation/quantifier nodes via LogicalQuerySymbols) + evaluate_guard recognize it. This is DISTINCT from the bridge's query_to_goals, which FLATTENS a LogicalQuery to resolver goals (unwrapping pattern_query) — wrong for guards. Key facts (from WI-546 investigation): only QUANTIFIED/negation guards are enforced (a bare pattern_query/conjunction vacuously holds, evaluate_guard kb/mod.rs); guard registration needs the reflect stdlib loaded (LogicalQuerySymbols); ConstraintId is a generated unit struct so add_guard just returns ConstraintId. Scope: a reflect-LogicalQuery -> Value reifier in bridge.rs (resolve the LogicalQuery.* ctor syms once), then kb.add_guard_labeled(value, None). Acceptance: bridge.add_guard(negation/no_q over a pattern) registers a guard whose subsequent violating bridge.assert returns None; unit test; cargo-test green. WI-546 already delivered assert + kb() and proved the assert<->guard path via a source constraint."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: nil), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-23T22:22:40Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED (commit 018a646 + merge cd6a908; full workspace suite green). WI-067 effect discharge = the two-tier glue, realized as ONE Γ query at each call site (the architecture collapses Tier-1/Tier-2 into the single Γ-refutation). MECHANISM (check_apply_iter, typing.rs): for each guarded atom L:-G of the callee's row, build σ (callee param ↦ actual-arg term via try_occurrence_to_term), refute σ(G) via the WI-537 refute_guard/prove_from_gamma bridge, DROP the label on a positive proof of ¬G else conservatively present; filters substituted_op_effects (the source, so downstream re-merges stay clean), gated on op_has_guarded (zero-cost off the partial ops). ALL discharge sources via one Γ query: literal divisor (ground eval), if-narrowing + earlier-match-arm narrowing (Γ facts), AND a preceding in-body 'by derivation' proof (WI-538 already assume()s its conclude into Γ, so Tier-1's Γ-refutation IS the Tier-2 dispatch — for by-derivation a proof derives exactly what Tier-1 derives, so no separate proof-search is buildable/meaningful until WI-538's deferred using-as-hypotheses / Tier-B(z3) follow-ons land). Symbolic divisor + literal-zero correctly KEEP. 6 load-level tests (wi067_guard_discharge_test). SUBSTRATE FIX (flag for review): the Γ substrate was WRITE-ONLY (WI-537/538/550), so the open-world-parameter floundering the proposals SPECIFY (048 §'constructive refutation', 050 §'Querying Γ') was never exercised — and was BROKEN: a param/binder reference is a ground term (Ref(b) from the effect-rekey; var_ref(b) from binder_ref_value), so neq(b,0)=not(eq(b,0)) over a symbolic param WRONGLY SUCCEEDED (NAF over a 'ground' constant), unsoundly dropping real effects. Fixed in the resolver, SCOPED to the Γ-query context (gamma overlay = ONLY prove_from_gamma sets it): a var_ref(name) binder twin inside a builtin/not goal forces a DELAY (flounder); a bare Ref (sort/op/const/constructor) stays a closed datum so a reflective builtin a proof chases still DECIDES. The discharge normalizes a guard's binder Ref(b) → its canonical var_ref(b) twin (ONE producer: KnowledgeBase::make_var_ref_term, shared with occurrence_to_term) so it unifies with the Γ fact binder_ref_value mints. This realizes SPECIFIED semantics (not a new design), scoped + verified — but it is a core-resolver change, flagging prominently. ALTITUDE NOTE: the root cause is the dual binder representation (effect-rekey emits Ref, Γ emits var_ref); a deeper single fix (one canonical binder shape, or the effect-rekey emitting var_ref) would drop both the normalize pass and the resolver's var_ref recognition — deferred as a larger refactor.", at: "2026-06-23T23:12:40Z")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "claude", content: "/code-review (8 angles / 6 finders, high effort) caught + FIXED before commit: (1) SOUNDNESS — drop_refuted_guarded_labels removed ALL same-label present entries on a refuted guard, unsoundly losing a same-label UNCONDITIONAL effect ({Boom, Boom:-eq(b,0)}) — now removes one per refuted atom + regression test; (2) REGRESSION — the open-world gate first flagged ANY non-constructor Ref (sorts/ops/consts), which would force-delay reflective builtins a WI-538 proof / future requires-check chases (latent, uncovered) — narrowed to the var_ref binder form only (proof goals' bare sort/op Refs stay decidable); (3) op_has_guarded scanned with an EMPTY subst, missing a guarded atom behind a subst-bound row-tail var — now the real subst; (4) the var_ref double-wrap guard matched by SHORT name — now the canonical symbol; (5) the var_ref term was built in 3 places — one make_var_ref_term producer (WI-537 doc: the binder shape must have one home). DEFERRED (sound conservative misses, NOT soundness bugs): (a) a DENOTED-label (Modify[c]) guarded effect rides its guard as a Value::Entity cons list that guarded_atom_refuted does not yet read (returns false = keep) — the partial primitives (div/mod/rem, Field.div) use GROUND labels (Error[DivisionByZero]), whose guard is a Term list and discharges; value-parameterized guarded effects are the follow-on (op_info::value_list_to_vec is the carrier-agnostic reader to reuse). (b) a guard over a NAMED const (eq(b, ZERO)) gets the const wrapped by normalize → flounders rather than folding (precision, not soundness; literal 0 is Const not Ref so eq(b,0) is unaffected). (c) op_has_guarded does a per-call collect_guarded_atoms walk — acceptable (no measurable suite-time regression), a precomputed OpInfoRecord.has_guarded flag is the optimization if it ever shows. UNBLOCKS WI-479 (migrate Int64.div/mod/rem/divExact + Field.div/recip to 'Error[DivisionByZero] :- eq(b,0)').", at: "2026-06-23T23:13:00Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-067", description: some(value: "Discharge Error-effects from local proofs. When Int.div / Field.div declare Error[DivisionByZero] unconditionally, callers must propagate the effect everywhere — even where b≠0 is locally obvious (pattern match arm after case 0, explicit if neq(b, 0) guard, or a refinement-typed non-zero Int). Design + implement a mechanism to elide the effect at call sites where the partiality-triggering condition is statically ruled out. Three candidate mechanisms, not mutually exclusive: (1) flow-sensitive typer that narrows value facts inside if/match branches; (2) refinement types, e.g., NonZero Int with a require clause; (3) pattern-match refinement, same as (1) applied to match arms. Unrelated to proposal 023 (KB guards — that's about assert-time fact integrity). Needs its own proposal; this WI is the placeholder."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-066", "WI-478", "WI-537", "WI-538"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-23T23:13:01Z"))
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-551", description: some(value: "Consolidate the two reflect realizations + generate the Stream trait (WI-541 gap 5, optional/non-blocking). There are TWO independent hand-written realizations of the reflect KB introspection surface: the interpreter eval-time path (anthill-stl/src/reflect/builtins.rs, Value-based, registered as anthill.reflect.KB.* builtins) and the host-Rust bridge (anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs, KbBridge impl of the GENERATED trait KB). Both independently walk KB facts, extract named args, and collect cons-lists for the SAME operations (sorts/operations/constructors/fields/facts_of/reify/reflect/assert/add_guard) — builtins.rs's own header comment flags 'consolidating the two paths is tracked separately'. They have already drifted and been re-synced per-op (WI-548 kb_operations parity, WI-545 requires/ensures, WI-543 BigIntLiteral) — the recurring parity tax this WI removes. Scope: (a) factor the shared fact-walking / named-arg / cons-list / LogicalQuery-reify / OperationInfo-read logic into ONE carrier-agnostic core (the op_info funnel + TermView are the existing substrate; both realizations already read carrier-faithfully), so the interpreter builtin and the bridge method call the same helper; (b) generate the Stream trait from reflect.anthill (currently the one reflect trait NOT codegen-emitted — KB/Substitution already are via WI-540) and wire SearchStreamAdapter to it; (c) ideally drive the interpreter builtins THROUGH a KbBridge (or shared core) so there is a single source of truth. Acceptance: one shared implementation per reflect op (no parallel re-walk in builtins.rs vs bridge.rs); Stream trait generated + a drift-guard like bridge_implements_generated_reflect_interface; cargo-test green; the per-op parity tests (wi348/wi545/wi548) still pass against the unified path."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540"]), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-551", name: "wi541")
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-541", author: "user", content: "DELIVERED (substantially-complete, tracking-only flip — no new code in this WI). All NON-optional gaps done via the split-out per-gap WIs: gap 1 (compose full union) = WI-544 + WI-547 (chase bare Value::Var); gap 2 (OperationInfo.requires/ensures carrier) = WI-545 (ReflectNodeOccurrence) + WI-548 (interpreter kb_operations parity); gap 3 (loud-panic stubs kb()/facts_of/assert/add_guard) = WI-542 (facts_of) + WI-546 (assert+kb()) + WI-549 (add_guard via LogicalQuery->guard-Value reifier); gap 4 (BigIntLiteral) = WI-543. Acceptance (cargo-test green) holds — full workspace suite exit 0. Gap 5 (OPTIONAL, non-blocking: generate Stream trait + consolidate the two parallel reflect realizations builtins.rs<->KbBridge) was never in WI-541's depends_on and is now filed as standalone WI-551. NOTE: WI-541 depends_on listed only 540/542-546; the actual delivery also required 547/548/549 (split out later from 544/545/546).", at: "2026-06-24T04:28:59Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-541", description: some(value: "WI-540 Foundation follow-ups: complete the generated-and-used reflect KB bridge. Each gap is loud-documented in anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs. (1) Substitution.compose is PARTIAL through a trait object — a &dyn Substitution cannot enumerate s2's bindings, so it applies s2 to self's range but cannot merge s2's standalone bindings; needs a binding-enumeration op on the spec's Substitution trait, then a full union impl. (2) OperationInfo.requires/ensures are produced EMPTY: the host NodeOccurrence is currently an empty opaque unit struct (uncarrier-bound), so carrier-bind it to a ReflectNodeOccurrence(Rc<NodeOccurrence>) opaque newtype (same pattern as ReflectTerm) and have the bridge wrap the stored clause Values. (3) Implement the loud-panic stubs kb()/facts_of/assert/add_guard. (4) Add a first-class BigIntLiteral to reflect.anthill LiteralRepr (currently BigInt lowers to its decimal StringLiteral). (5) Optional: generate the Stream trait + consolidate the interpreter (builtins.rs) and host (KbBridge) reflect realizations. Non-blocking (bridge compiles, suite green). See [[project_wi536_generated_bridge]]."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-540", "WI-542", "WI-543", "WI-544", "WI-545", "WI-546"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-24T04:29:03Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-067", author: "claude", content: "FOLLOW-UP (commit c26b350): the deferred denoted-label discharge gap is CLOSED. A guarded effect with a value-parameterized LABEL (Modify[c] :- eq(b,0)) rides the occurrence carrier and stores its guard as a Value::Entity cons spine (build_value_list), which guarded_atom_refuted fell through (_ => false) — so a conditional Modify loaded + was conservatively present but NEVER discharged, even at a literal-refutable call (confirmed: 'undeclared effect: Modify[T = c]' at maybe_modify(c, 5)). This was an incompleteness, not exotic — Modify is first-class and WI-478 built the Node-carrier representation FOR it. FIX: guarded_atom_refuted now reads the guard list CARRIER-AGNOSTICALLY (the goal heads are Value::Term regardless of wrapper; the Entity spine is read via op_info::value_list_to_vec, now pub(crate)); each conjunct re-enters the same σ + normalize_param_refs_to_var_ref + refute_guard path. Literal-refutable denoted guard now DROPS; symbolic KEEPS (same floundering floor). Test denoted_modify_label_guard_discharges_and_keeps (both branches); focused soundness review clean (no over-discharge — Entity goals are Value::Term, same path); full suite green. REMAINING deferred: only the named-const-in-guard precision gap (eq(b, ZERO) wraps ZERO via normalize → flounders rather than folds; sound, literal 0 is Const not Ref so eq(b,0) unaffected).", at: "2026-06-24T04:30:46Z")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-552", description: some(value: "Canonicalize binder/parameter references to var_ref(name); retire the WI-067 discharge normalize pass. SURFACED BY WI-067 (effect discharge): a reference to a LOCAL binder / operation parameter has TWO representations that do not unify — var_ref(name) (the canonical form, minted by binder_ref_value for Γ facts + occurrence_to_term / Expr::VarRef, settled by WI-550) vs bare Ref(sym) (minted by the effect-rekey substitute_ref_syms, the Modify[c] -> Modify[s] rename, which never got the var_ref memo). So a guard eq(b,0), after the rekey rewrites b to the caller binder, is eq(Ref(caller_b),0) while Γ holds neq(var_ref(caller_b),0) — they do not unify. WI-067 papers over this with TWO consumer-side patches: (1) normalize_param_refs_to_var_ref (rewrite the guard's Ref -> var_ref at discharge time) and (2) the resolver's value_has_open_world_ref recognizing var_ref-ONLY as the open-world binder (a bare Ref must stay decidable so a reflective builtin a proof chases — scope/is_entity_of — still resolves). Three sync points for one concept; binder_ref_value's own doc-contract ('if the canonical binder form ever moves, both producers move with it') is ALREADY VIOLATED by the rekey. ROOT CAUSE: bare Ref(sym) is OVERLOADED — it means both 'a global (sort/op/const/constructor — closed, decide)' and 'a local binder (open-world, flounder)'; var_ref is precisely the disambiguator and one producer just does not emit it. REFACTOR: make var_ref(name) the SINGLE canonical form for a local binder/param everywhere, Ref(sym) reserved for globals. Concretely substitute_ref_syms emits var_ref(arg) (not Ref(arg)) when it rewrites a param to a binder argument — and its targets ARE binder refs (it is fed by extract_var_ref_sym_node), so this is semantically exact, not a hack. Then guards carry var_ref natively, unify with Γ with NO normalize pass, and the resolver's open-world rule becomes a principled 'var_ref => open-world' instead of 'gated on the gamma overlay + relies on a pre-normalize having run'. CATCH (blast radius — why deferred not done): the Modify[.] resource readers — effect-region masking (WI-351/353 keep/flow), eval, cpp-gen, the effect-row printer/canonicalizer — currently read the resource as a bare Ref(s); if the rekey emits var_ref(s) for LABELS too (a blind whole-value rekey cannot tell guard-position from label-position) each must learn var_ref. Smaller alternative: var_ref-ify ONLY the guard sub-term at the producer (teach substitute_ref_syms guard-vs-label position-awareness) — net-even with the current normalize-at-consumer, so the real win is the full label+guard canonicalization. BENEFIT: retire normalize_param_refs_to_var_ref; collapse three sync points to one (KnowledgeBase::make_var_ref_term + binder_ref_value); the resolver's open-world floundering becomes principled instead of gamma-gated-plus-pre-normalized; restores binder_ref_value's one-canonical-form contract. NON-BLOCKING: the current WI-067 fix is sound and gamma-scoped so it cannot leak into non-discharge resolution — this is altitude/maintainability, not a correctness fix. TRIGGER: WI-539 (call-site requires/ensures over Γ) is the same-shaped SECOND consumer (its preconditions are the same guard shape) — doing this before/with WI-539 avoids adding a fourth patch. Acceptance: cargo-test green; normalize_param_refs_to_var_ref removed and the resolver open-world recognition principled (var_ref = open-world, no gamma-pre-normalize dependency), WI-067's discharge tests still green."), acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test")], depends_on: some(value: []), status: Open)
fact Tag(workitem: "WI-552", name: "p048")
fact WorkItem(id: "WI-479", description: some(value: "Proposal 048 Phase 3 — migrate partial primitives to guarded Error[DivisionByZero]. Change Int64.div/mod/rem/divExact (and Field.div/recip) from unconditional 'effects Error[DivisionByZero]' (WI-066) to '{ Error[DivisionByZero] :- eq(b, 0) }'; update the WI-066 tests so a literal-divisor call (div(a,5)) and a guarded-branch call (if neq(b,0) then div(a,b)) now type PURE, while div(a,b) with unknown b still carries the effect. Decide open question C: keep the existing 'constraint div_nonzero_primary: neq(?b,0) :- div(?_,?b)' as an integrity guard and DECLARE the positive guard on the op (do not derive it from the constraint — neq is not(eq)=NAF). Depends on WI-067 (discharge) which already requires WI-478 (grammar/representation)."), context: none, acceptance: [ToolPasses(tool: "cargo-test", params: none)], depends_on: some(value: ["WI-067"]), generates: none, requires_capability: none, status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-06-24T04:55:20Z"))
fact Feedback(workitem: "WI-479", author: "claude", content: "DELIVERED 2026-06-24 (commit 37cf9af). Migrated Int64.div/mod/rem/divExact + Field.div/recip from unconditional 'effects Error[DivisionByZero]' to guarded '{ Error[DivisionByZero] :- eq(b,0) }' (recip guards eq(a,0), its sole param). WI-067 discharge applies unchanged to the stdlib ops: literal non-zero divisor (div(n,2)) and 'if neq(d,0) then div(n,d)' narrowing now type PURE; symbolic divisor + literal-zero (div(n,0), eq(0,0) holds) keep the effect; declaring it over a symbolic divisor still loads (over-declaration is allowed — the effect check is one-directional incurred-subset-declared, no reverse check). Open-question-C: DECLARED the positive guard on each op; kept div_nonzero_primary/div_nonzero/rem_nonzero/mod_positive constraints unchanged as integrity guards (NOT derived — neq=not(eq)=NAF would route discharge through the polarity hazard). mod's effect guard eq(b,0) is correct (DivisionByZero fires at b=0) even though mod_positive is stricter (b>0) — separate concerns. Rewrote wi066_division_effect_test.rs (6 tests). Full workspace suite green (63 binaries). /code-review (3 finders, max effort) returned [] — verified guard params correct, sound (drop only on constructive refutation), literal-0 error is genuinely undeclared-effect not a constraint violation (op bodies emit no div(...) fact). Field has no concrete instance so Field.div/recip validated only by stdlib load. Phase 4 (head/nth/... partial ops) remains future work.", at: "2026-06-24T04:55:21Z")
